<html><head><title>Whisky and wry</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="3gr5.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>American humour</b></p>
<h2>Whisky and wry</h2><ul><li><a href="3ex38.html">J<font size=-1>AMES </font>T<font size=-1>HURBER</font></a>: H<font size=-1>IS</font> L<font size=-1>IFE</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> T<font size=-1>IMES</font>&nbsp; By Harrison Kinney.<br>
</ul>

<p>JAMES THURBER left his own monument. He created it between 1927 and 1947 in the pages of the <i>New Yorker</i>. Anyone attempting to build another is inevitably reduced to the status of the Late Arrival or the Also Ran (alongside such other small burrowing Thurber creatures as the Hopeless Quandary and the White Lie). Thurber understood Thurber as nobody else did, and wrote about himself with reckless transparency. His readers did not doubt that the Thurber male, endlessly hen-pecked, baffled by modern machinery, finding fierce courage only in liquor, was Thurber himself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He was born in 1894, "on a night of wild portent and high wind", in Columbus, Ohio. His fate was sealed seven years later, when his brother half-blinded him with a toy bow and arrow. Like a near-contemporary, James Joyce, Thurber found escape from his trauma by becoming a bookish child, immersed in fantasies and word games; in middle age, tall and angular and with glasses "as thick as binoculars", he also came to resemble Joyce physically. By 1953, almost totally blind, he delighted in having parts of "Finnegans Wake" read out to him by his secretary.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For most of his career, however, near-blindness gave Thurber his comic inspiration. At parties, he knocked over fruit bowls and lampshades; in hotels, he wandered into wrong rooms; when writing, he would dip his pen into his scotch. Behind the driving wheel, "flecks of dust and streaks of bug blood on the windshield look to me often like old admirals in uniform, or crippled apple women, or the front ends of barges and I whirl out of their way, thus going into ditches and fields and up on front lawns, endangering the life of authentic admirals and apple women who may be out on the roads for a breath of air before retiring." Undoing a woman's girdle "is likely to lead to a grave and determined effort, in which the gentleman goes about the process much as if he were trying to fix a gasoline engine." Out of this murky and fumbling world came "Villanelle of Horatio Street, Manhattan", his first published piece for the <i>New Yorker</i>, which concluded:
<ul><font size=-1>If your eyes lift up to greet<br>The stars you fall on, sure as hell,<br>Rusted bed-springs in the street,<br>All in a clutter at your feet.</font></ul>
His handicap had another outcome, too. According to his biographer (who does an exhaustive and fairly convincing job of proving it), Thurber developed a savage dislike of the weaker side of himself, all that seemed to him feminine and dependent; and this led on to savagery against "the weaker sex" in general. His drawings seem to make the point. The women in Thurber's cartoons are either daisy-plucking airheads or emasculating harridans, giants before whom the timid Thurber male cowers and flees away. Only his loyal and equally nonplussed dog offers him comfort against them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thurber's series of articles, "The War Between Men and Women", drew heavily on his miserable first marriage, in which much of his time was spent in enforced separation in the Algonquin Hotel surrounded by unlaundered shirts. But it continued even during his happy second marriage to a woman who understood, encouraged and humoured him. He once explained that what made the male fear the female was "the look one woman gives another when observing what she is wearing." This fear apparently never left him, just as he never lost his terrifying irascibility when drunk, or his contrition the morning after.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thurber was not a political animal. Indeed, the early <i>New Yorker</i> was determinedly frivolous, its staff--on the evidence of these pages--spending most of their time half-legless in speakeasies. In 1933, his blithe advice for dealing with what he called "The Inflation" began: "Don't shout over the phone." In 1936, during the terrible dust storms, he joked to a friend "My God, this nation is rapidly being covered by sand!" Only the rise of fascism and later McCarthyism kindled a political conscience in him. In 1950, in an essay entitled "Look Out for the Thing", he tackled anti-communist hysteria head on:
<ul><font size=-1>The Thing can blacken a man at a distance of 10,000 miles, by using one or another of its many stings: the thundering charge, the sweeping generalisation, the bold assumption, the mysterious record, the secret testimony, the overheard insinuation, the patriotic gesture, the enormous lie, the fearful warning ... Do not attempt to take the Thing single-handed. It is armed and dangerous, what is worse, it has a lot of friends.</font></ul>
Thurber also has a lot of friends: people who have warmed over time to the cuddly man in a derby, writhing in an armchair, whom they have taken him to be. This book, sadly, will not win him any more.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Harrison Kinney plainly dotes on his subject, but his doting proves fatal. For all his diligence and hard work, he does not understand that Thurber's stories are ruined by paraphrasing, as a fine tune by a crass arrangement. Nor does he understand that much of his analysis is, in the end, irrelevant. Dealing with the famous brawl in "The Dog that Bit People", in which the dog's owner ends up on the table among the silverware while the dog sails across the room, Mr Kinney brings in Thurber's brother to say exactly who bit whom first, and whether the dog would have bitten anyone at all, or "maybe just snarled and snapped". At such times the reader would like to bury his teeth deep into Mr Kinney's leg, and worry him to death.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
