<html><head><title>Go directly to jail</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="4gr1.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<h1>Go directly to jail</h1>


<p><b>Prisons fail to inflict fair, effective punishment at reasonable cost. Penal reform seems not to work either. Can the circle be broken?</b></p><ul><li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> O<font size=-1>XFORD</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> P<font size=-1>RISONS</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> P<font size=-1>RACTICE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> P<font size=-1>UNISHMENT</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> W<font size=-1>ESTERN</font> S<font size=-1>OCIETY</font>&nbsp; Edited by Norval Morris and David Rothman.<br>
<li><a href="4ex76.html"></i>W<font size=-1>ESTERN</font> E<font size=-1>UROPEAN</font> P<font size=-1>ENAL</font> S<font size=-1>YSTEMS</font></a>&nbsp; Edited by Vincenzo Ruggiero, Mick Ryan and Joe Sim.<br>
<li><a href="4ex77.html"></i>A R<font size=-1>EADER</font> <font size=-1>ON</font> P<font size=-1>UNISHMENT</font></a>&nbsp; Edited by Antony Duff and David Garland.<br>
<li><a href="4ex78.html">P<font size=-1>UNISHMENT</font></a>: A P<font size=-1>HILOSOPHY AND </font>P<font size=-1>UBLIC </font>A<font size=-1>FFAIRS </font>R<font size=-1>EADER</font>&nbsp; Edited by John Simmons, Marshall Cohen, Joshua Cohen and Charles Beitz.<br>
<li><a href="4ex79.html">G<font size=-1>UILTY</font></a>&nbsp; By Harold Rothwax.<br>
<li></i>I<font size=-1>N</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> N<font size=-1>AME</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> L<font size=-1>AW</font></a>&nbsp; By David Rose.<br>
</ul><ul></ul>

<p>EVERY new society, wrote Nathaniel Hawthorne in one of his cheerier moods, is soon in need of a graveyard and a prison. The glum tale of western punishment, as told in the excellent "Oxford History of Prisons", a set of essays by social historians and penal experts, would seem to bear him out: prisons are wasteful, unjust--and indispensable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Penal reform and counter-reform have followed each other through recent times in a melancholy cycle. Enlightenment reformers devised the modern prison and swifter execution as humane alternatives to branding, maiming or brutally prolonged death. Anyone wanting a refresher course in ancient and medieval pain-infliction can get it from this illustrated volume. It includes the Roman <i>culleus</i> (a drowning sack for kin murderers filled also with monkey, dog and snake) and ingenious later torments. Though the book will do nicely as a coffee-table Chamber of Horrors, it is serious history with a clear, pertinent thread.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Jails were once just for civil debtors, for those sent to trial and for felons awaiting execution. From the 18th century semi-solitary confinement replaced the whip, the wheel and the pillory as the public theatre of bodily pain gave way to a shut-away world of internal banishment. That new world did not look like progress for long. By early this century prison itself--not to mention execution of any kind--had come to seem barbarous. Efforts were made to lighten sentences, to limit or end the death penalty, to empty jails and generally to lessen the cruelty of the criminal-justice system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now, as if by Hawthorne's law, penal fashion in America and much of Europe has swung hard the other way. Norval Morris, an eloquent advocate of alternatives to prison, ends the "Oxford History of Prisons" with a particularly depressing essay on contemporary America, where the number of prisoners has more than doubled since 1980. It is now over 1m and disproportionately many are black. All but 13 states have brought back the death penalty since 1976, when the Supreme Court, after a four-year suspension, deemed it constitutional again. Prisoners on death row are being gassed, poisoned, electrocuted or shot at a rate of 30-40 a year. In Alabama, chain gangs are back.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No nation in Europe now punishes on this scale or with such ferocity. The gallows, the firing squad and the guillotine have disappeared, as have the penal colony and the stone quarry. Yet, under pressure from lawmakers and prosecutors, who seem to believe that this is what the public wants, European courts have been passing longer sentences, with less easy parole. German judges, who doggedly question the point of long sentences, are an exception. Italy's authorities are trying to reduce the country's inmate population but more than anything because there is no room left in its prisons--or public money for new ones.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This harsher European climate is looked into in "Western European Penal Systems", a dry though useful set of nine country studies. Its editors could have been less timid about spotting common trends. They themselves say that national patterns of criminal justice are blending as travel increases and economies mesh. They point to the high number of foreigners (many of them illegal immigrants) in Europe's jails--perhaps 25% of France's 52,000 prisoners. History recurs. As the Oxford prison history notes, Europe has always put away immigrants and people with the wrong colour or beliefs more readily than others.</p>
<p><b>Neither fair, effective nor affordable?</b><br>The crime rate is a poorly understood and sensitive variable. Readers of these books are wisely and repeatedly warned that it can go down as well as up. In the 1980s America's crime rate first fell and then rose. It now seems to be falling again, but the prison population rises inexorably. Attempts in Europe to show a link between harsh penalties and less crime (or vice versa) have also faltered. The prison population went up in post-war England and Wales, down in the post-war Netherlands, while crime rose in both places. Nor, if prisons are failing at their job, are they failing cheaply. America is spending $25 billion a year on them and many European countries are investing expensively in new ones.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But what is prison's job? A generation ago most people would probably have said it was to deter or prevent crime and to rehabilitate criminals. Nowadays a likelier reply is that it gives the wicked their deserts. Is it sensible to expect prison to do all that? Can punishment be effective for society as well as fair to villains and victims?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"A Reader on Punishment" edited by Antony Duff, a philosopher, and David Garland, a criminologist, is a collection of 14 recent essays or book-chapters on the whys, whos and hows of punishment that it would be hard to better. Its scope is both philosophical and practical, English and American. It questions the fashionable "futility thesis" that neither prison nor penal reform work. Interesting alternatives to prison--supervision (perhaps electronically monitored), community service, heavy fines--are seriously and intelligently canvassed. Its bolder contributors ask why the criminal law or the state's monopoly on criminal justice should be kept at all.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Historically, the criminal law emerged as central authorities took over the exaction of compensation and infliction of punishment from church courts, feuding clans and vigilante posses. Herman Bianchi's contribution explores replacing criminal penalties with debt liability, leaving prison as a "sanctuary" for perpetrators of heinous deeds. You could go further. It is possible to imagine a system without state-controlled criminal justice in which people could buy the private security and victim insurance they wanted. The rich or educated, naturally, would buy more cover than the poor as their property and their persons (valued by life earning-power) are worth more, though it is doubtful many would find that "just" in any normal sense.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A virtue of the Duff-Garland collection is to take zero-based approaches to punishment seriously. Forget for a moment the expensive misery of today's prisons. How can any state-inflicted pain be justified? There are two standard answers. Abstract as they sound, understanding them helps keep more practical issues straight.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The utilitarian answer judges punishment by its consequences: does it help or harm general well-being? Punishment's minus--pain to criminals--must be outweighed by its pluses: deterring or preventing crime, turning crooks into non-crooks. As with most "consequentialist" attempts to mark out right from wrong, trouble comes when punishment stops delivering good consequences (as many believe it has done): safer streets, less car theft, fewer repeaters, cheaper law enforcement. Is punishment still justified? Some robust utilitarians say it is not. Instead of vainly trying to police unneeded laws, they propose a sweeping decriminalisation of sanctioned conduct, starting with drugs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if useless practically, punishment may be needed for principle's sake. Punishment, argues the "just deserts" or "retributivist" school, is what criminals deserve, victims merit and society has to inflict if it is not to condone wrongdoing. A big change over the past 20 years, Messrs Duff and Garland note, is how far "consequentialism has been abandoned and retributivist ideas revived". This is not a fight with knock-outs. Utilitarians and retributivists have been at each other for centuries and are not likely to stop now. Ringside theorists can get more in "Punishment", a set of strictly philosophical essays.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In line with "just-deserts" theory have come mandatory sentences, strict sentencing guidelines and less elastic parole. "Same-for-all" sentencing sounds good in theory. Tough-on-crime politicians love it. But no system lives up to it. "Punishment" ends with a lively exchange about sentencing bias in capital punishment. If death is a just desert for brutal murders can it be just to execute only a few of the brutal murderers? This is an extreme example of a broader point. Fair punishment depends not just on its severity but on how it is shared out. You need not be a Marxist to ask why, in practice, rich or educated criminals are at less risk of jail than poor or ignorant ones. A hard-nosed answer, heard on left and right and found at places in these books, is that real-world law enforcement is as much to do with "rabble control", to put it savagely, as with justice or fairness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another live issue involving fairness is "due process", from arrest to trial. Some, like Harold Rothwax, a New York state criminal judge feared for his quick lip and stiff sentencing, think it has become a crook's charter. He attacks the build-up of defendants' rights in America since the 1960s. His bugbears, familiar to watchers of American court dramas, include the exclusion of wrongly obtained evidence, the Miranda warning to suspects, the speedy-trial right, the defence's one-sided access to prosecution evidence and the rule that silence from the accused is not incriminating (a rule relaxed, controversially, in England and Wales). Judge Rothwax would roll all that back, though his actual proposals, some of them sensible, amount to less of a counter-revolution than that sounds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"In the Name of the Law" is a stimulating polemic from the other side of the Atlantic (and of the political divide) by David Rose of the <i>Observer</i> newspaper. English criminal justice, he argues, cannot avoid grotesque miscarriages such as the Birmingham Six, the Guildford Four and the Maguire Seven. His prime suspect, plausibly, is not the police (better trained and less corrupt than in the past) but bad prosecutors. More speculatively, he favours a more inquisitorial system of justice on continental European lines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After reading these books, a betting person would still have to expect nastier, more crowded prisons for the time being. Set against the weary, aggrieved public mood about law and order in America and Europe, these books have a theoretical flavour. The final two apart, none can be recommended to speech-writers for candidates to high office. Still, they are full of provocative questions and vigorous argument: just right for stirring up sharper debate.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
