<html><head><title>As they see it</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="4gr3.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Ex-Yugoslavs on Yugoslavia</b></p>
<h2>As they see it</h2><ul><li>P<font size=-1>OSLEDNJI</font> D<font size=-1>ANI</font> S<font size=-1>FRJ</font> (T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>AST</font> D<font size=-1>AYS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> Y<font size=-1>UGOSLAVIA)</font></a>&nbsp; By Borisav Jovic.<br>
<li>M<font size=-1>OJE</font> V<font size=-1>IDJENJE</font> R<font size=-1>ASPADA</font> (M<font size=-1>Y</font> V<font size=-1>IEW OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> B<font size=-1>REAK-UP)</font></a>&nbsp; By Veljko Kadijevic.<br>
<li>K<font size=-1>AKO</font> J<font size=-1>E</font> S<font size=-1>RUSENA</font> J<font size=-1>UGOSLAVIJA</font> (H<font size=-1>OW</font> Y<font size=-1>UGOSLAVIA</font> W<font size=-1>AS</font> D<font size=-1>ESTROYED)</font></a>&nbsp; By Stipe Mesic.<br>
<li><a href="4ex83.html">I<font size=-1>ZA</font> Z<font size=-1>ATVORENIH</font> V<font size=-1>RATA</font> (B<font size=-1>EHIND</font> C<font size=-1>LOSED</font> D<font size=-1>OORS); Part I</font></a>&nbsp; By Zdravko Tomac.<br>
<li><a href="4ex84.html">I<font size=-1>ZA</font> Z<font size=-1>ATVORENIH</font> V<font size=-1>RATA</font> (B<font size=-1>EHIND</font> C<font size=-1>LOSED</font> D<font size=-1>OORS); Part II</font></a>&nbsp; By Zdravko Tomac.<br>
<li><a href="4ex85.html"></i>O<font size=-1>KOVANA</font> B<font size=-1>OSNA</font> (B<font size=-1>OSNIA</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> C<font size=-1>HAINS)</font></a>&nbsp; By Adil Zulfikarpasic, Vlado Gotovac, Miko Tripalo and Ivo Banac.<br>
<li><a href="4ex86.html">B<font size=-1>OSNJAK</font> A<font size=-1>DIL</font> Z<font size=-1>ULFIKARPASIC (Adil Zulfikarpasic; Bosnian)</font></a>&nbsp; By Milovan Djilas.<br>
</ul><ul></ul>


<p>BOOKS and television documentaries seeking to explain the violent break-up of Yugoslavia are legion. But they are mostly by onlookers. Books by participants have a special value, hard as it is for ex-Yugoslavs to come to terms with their terrible recent war.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among Serb writers the big issue is who "lost" Yugoslavia. Borisav Jovic wrote an absorbing diary covering 1989-92. Though not a principal, he was an important supporting player. In the critical 12 months after May 1990, he was president of Yugoslavia's eight-member federal presidency. On May 15th 1991 he chaired, in effect, its last meaningful session. On the agenda was the choice of his successor. It was Croatia's turn in the chair and normally the 12-month job would have passed to the Croat member, Stipe Mesic. But the Serbian republic and its allies contrived to block his appointment, which provoked a constitutional crisis and opened the way to civil war.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Jovic was never the equal of Slobodan Milosevic, the president of Serbia, but he had a voice that counted on the little-known though influential Council for the Protection of the Constitutional Order. His insider's diary suggests that Serbian policy in those critical early months was more fluid and less under Mr Milosevic's control than was generally supposed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Jovic claims to have tried (and failed) to prod into action General Veljko Kadijevic, who was defence minister from 1988 to 1992. In March 1991 he even resigned as head of the presidency, which under Yugoslavia's constitution commanded the armed forces. His aim, he says, was to create a vacuum into which the generals might step by staging coups against the democratically-elected governments of Croatia and Slovenia. But, on Mr Jovic's account, Mr Kadijevic and the senior generals hesitated, fearful as they were of armed resistance in those republics and anxious about the West's reaction to the use of force, so missing the best moment for decisive action.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In his own book, which came out before Mr Jovic's, General Kadijevic anticipates and defends himself against any charge of "losing" Yugoslavia. He blames, rather, the shortsightedness and irresponsible jockeying of Yugoslavia's politicians, the high number of desertions among Serb conscripts and the rapacious insubordination of Serb paramilitary bands sent in to cause trouble or worse in Bosnia and Croatia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;General Kadijevic, a true Tito man, mistrusted and despised Mr Jovic's raw Serb chauvinism. Like him, however, he has an animus towards the Slovenes, and especially to <i>Mladina</i>, a satirical Slovenian news magazine, which he accuses of going out of its way to humiliate the Yugoslav armed forces as far back as the mid-1980s. His other fixed idea, surprising perhaps in someone who knows West Point so well, is that western powers plotted the break-up of Yugoslavia--when the West strove too long or not effectively enough to keep it together.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Croatia, by contrast, arguments tend to take the malign intent of Serbia, or of its nationalists, for granted and to concentrate instead on the tactics of Croatia's president, Franjo Tudjman. Mr Mesic has written a vivid account of the events of 1991 as seen from the Croat side. But for outright criticism of Mr Tudjman, Zdravko Tomac's is the book. He was a top Croatian Communist who lost to Franjo Tudjman's party in the 1990 election, then joined Mr Tudjman's war-time coalition as vice-premier in 1991, only to fall out with his boss over Bosnia, outraged as he was by Mr Tudjman's eagerness to carve it up with Serbia. In the second volume of his well-documented book, appropriately sub-titled "Who killed Bosnia?", he judges Mr Tudjman's policy in Bosnia a disaster, not least for Croatia, and the main cause of the war between Croats and Muslims in Bosnia, which nearly left the Serbs there outright victors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Croatia and Slovenia seceded, poorly armed Bosnians had a miserable choice: live with nationalist Serbia or fight. Could the Bosnian government have avoided war, with its attendant massacres and flights of people, by accommodating the Serbs? Milovan Djilas discussed this question in Budapest shortly before his death in 1995 with Adil Zulfikarpasic, a businessman and philanthropist who lives in Zurich.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Djilas, a Montenegrin, was one of the great figures in post-war Yugoslavia. During the second world war he fought as a partisan with Tito, Yugoslavia's long-time leader, who had him jailed for dissent in the 1950s. In the late 1980s, when Serb nationalism replaced communist orthodoxy in Belgrade, Djilas derided that too. Mr Zulfikarpasic, who comes from an old Bosnian Muslim family, was also a partisan, but no Communist. Having made a fortune abroad, he returned to Bosnia in 1990 to promote a non-confessional liberalism. Few listened. Bosnia's voters split on sectional lines--Muslim, Serb and Croat. Disappointed, he left again to build up an institute of Bosnian learning and culture in Zurich.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Zulfikarpasic did try to reach a peaceful accommodation for Bosnia with Mr Milosevic. Significantly, he believes that it might have succeeded but for the wrecking tactics of Bosnia's Muslim president, Alija Izetbegovic. Mr Zulfikarpasic also had a wide-ranging and often scintillating debate, published now as a book, with three members of the opposition in Croatia: Ivo Banac, a Yale historian, Vlado Gotovac, an ex-dissident, poet and leader of Croatia's Social-Liberal Party, and Miko Tripalo, a reform Communist from the Tito era (who died late last year). Their book defies fashionable "Bosnia-pessimism" and ends with an affirmation of faith in a liberal, non-confessional and multicultural Bosnia.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
