<html><head><title>Middle East without prejudice</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="3gr1.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<h1>Middle East without prejudice</h1>

<p><b>A sweeping new history of the Middle East shows the diversity of its past and smashes many current stereotypes</b></p><ul><li><a href="3ex25.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>IDDLE</font> E<font size=-1>AST</font></a>: 2000 Y<font size=-1>EARS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font> <font size=-1>FROM</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> R<font size=-1>ISE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> C<font size=-1>HRISTIANITY</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> P<font size=-1>RESENT</font> D<font size=-1>AY</font>&nbsp; By Bernard Lewis.<br>
</ul><ul></ul>

<p>THE term "Middle East" is a 20th-century creation, given currency by an American admiral and writer on geopolitics, Alfred Thayer Mahan, in 1902. But the countries it encompasses have a history that spans millennia. More pertinently, the Middle East includes a much greater variety of society and culture than common stereotypes allow. Despite all attempts to freeze or enforce an identity, be it imperial, religious or ethnic, the states and peoples of the Middle East have always learnt and taken from each other.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What gives the region unity, and justifies writing a broad history, is this story of interaction. Bernard Lewis has chosen an even wider canvas than his subtitle suggests: one of his themes is that before even the rise of Christianity and Islam, the region was being shaped by Iran, by Egypt and by the settled civilisations of southern Arabia. Beneath later appearances of uniformity, diversity continued: the spread of the Islamic armies in the seventh century was at first comparatively light, leaving religious and administrative structures intact, and regional attempts to create a single political entity were disrupted by conflicts within the Muslim empires.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Anyone wanting support for the idea that in "Islam" the spiritual and the secular are fused, or for the idea that Islamic states have in some fundamental way been different from other states, will be disappointed--but also freed from pointless argument. For history's answer to so many current quarrels--Does Islam permit separate states or secular rules? Is Islam compatible with nationalism?--is an emphatic "yes". The realism in the words of a ninth-century <i>wazir</i> in Baghdad has a modern ring: "The basis of government is jugglery. If it works, and lasts, it becomes policy."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lewis is also concerned to balance a view of the region as essentially an Arab civilisation. Again and again Iran appears as a source of influence. The rise of the Turks in the 11th century produces a third major contribution, and one that lasted, in its imperial Ottoman form, until this present century.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Europe is present as a target of invasion up to the 17th century and as an encroaching economic and political force thereafter. But, on Mr Lewis's time-scale, more weight is given to the influence of Central Asia and China. Commercially, west and east Asia were linked by silk and pottery. Militarily, it was the comparative strength of China in the east that pushed the Huns, Mongols and Turks to the west.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The impact of European modernity forms the main subject of the book's last part, which goes up to the present day. Mr Lewis's concluding judgment is that, for better or worse, the peoples of the Middle East are now on their own. They can, he says, no longer count on outside support for propping up or getting rid of dictators and they have no grounds any more for blaming their problems on outsiders. This bracing message needs stating, and stating again, for it is sinking into the political discourse of the Middle East all too slowly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Without footnotes, this is by intention a general book. The lucid narrative is backed up by maps and by a rich chronology. But it is no bland summary. Mr Lewis engages openly in many controversies. He includes assessments and throw-away lines that will intrigue and infuriate. Mr Lewis's judgment that "In the earnestness and seriousness of their loyalty to Islam the Turks are equalled by no other people" is likely to make some of the faithful elsewhere sit up. His stress on the importance of Sufism, a popular and critical belief linked to mysticism, brings out a dimension of Islamic life that outsiders too often miss. Sufism is indispensable to an understanding of the thought of Ayatollah Khomeini, as it is to the politics of contemporary Turkey and the Caucasus, and perhaps to Bosnia too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lewis is particularly good on shifts in religious belief and in the language of politics and power. Summaries of political and economic history are combined with detailed expositions of the meaning of <i>jihad</i> and of terms of authority. On other questions he is less sure and less successful. His chapter on the ruled, as opposed to their rulers, is entitled "The Commonalty". Yet women rate but a paragraph and the mass of the labouring population scarcely more. The account of the Iranian revolution misses the degree to which its highly politicised ideas drew on western concepts: no Koranic <i>sura</i> (chapter) enjoins revolution, economic development or independence. The judgment that, in the Arab-Israeli dispute, outside powers should be blamed for stopping one side from defeating the other rings oddly at a time when some Israelis and some Palestinians, though haggling, are at least trying to work out a way of living together.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This overview invites comparison with the brilliant work with which Mr Lewis began his professional writing career over four decades ago, "The Arabs in History". Yet while it covers much of the same ground, with undiminished erudition and fluency, there are, in addition to a broader geographical and temporal scope, some differences. It is perhaps significant that, while in the earlier book the overthrow of the Ummayad empire in the ninth century was described as a revolution, comparable to those of France and Russia, it is the rise of Islam itself which is now cited as revolutionary, and the comparison with the events of 1789 and 1917 is reserved for the Islamic Revolution of Iran.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A summary of a life's reading and reflection, this is, quibbles apart, a fine and challenging book. It gently corrects many illusions about the Middle East and restores to Mr Lewis a calm authority that his engagement in certain over-heated recent controversies seemed to have ruffled.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Above all, it is a historian's tribute to the people of the Middle East, which refutes on almost every page the common image of social stagnation or cultural irrationality. This book will remind every reader, including those from the Middle East itself, how diverse and ever-changing this region has always been.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
