<html><head><title>Blood on the veld</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>African history</b></p>
<h2>Blood on the veld</h2><ul><li><a href="3ex36.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> A<font size=-1>NATOMY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> Z<font size=-1>ULU</font> A<font size=-1>RMY</font> <font size=-1>FROM</font> S<font size=-1>HAKA</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> C<font size=-1>ETSHWAYO</font></a>: 1818-1879&nbsp; By Ian Knight.<br>
</ul>

<p>IN A desperate appeal for annexation, Mohesh described his people as "the lice in the Queen's blanket". The plea won the Basutho chief sympathy in Victorian London but also amiable contempt. The British recruited compliant Africans to help them run the empire. They reserved their admiration for the proud warrior tribes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The fearsome Masai of East Africa, with lion-killing as a rite of passage, excited the British imagination. So did the Matabele of southern Africa, who gave Cecil Rhodes a run for his pots of money. And, after they broke a British square, Kipling wrote a famous bit of doggerel in praise of the Fuzzy-Wuzzy: "So 'ere's to you Fuzzy-Wuzzy, at your 'ome in the Soudan; You're a pore benighted 'eathen but a first-class fightin' man." But no Africans were more noble in the eyes of imperial Britain than the Zulu.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Ian Knight shows, the prowess of the Zulu was no myth. In 1879, at the battle of Isandlwana, Zulu warriors armed mainly with knobkerries, throwing spears and assegais, and protected by shields made from animal hides, wiped out a modern British army equipped with artillery, rockets and Gatling machine-guns.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The descriptions of battle, particularly of close combat where "the killing achieved levels of stark primeval savagery", are not for the squeamish. Unlike Stephen Taylor in his much broader "Shaka's Children: A History of the Zulu People" (HarperCollins; 1994), Mr Knight is interested only in how the Zulu kingdom created such a magnificent army, and what made the army tick. He examines how Zulu warriors were enlisted, trained and accommodated, how they were led and fed, and what they believed, what they wore and how they were equipped. His account provides a mesmerising read for those who like their history concentrated and straight.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
