<html><head><title>Blood curdling</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="4gr8.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>African wars</b></p>
<h2>Blood curdling</h2><ul><li><a href="4ex88.html">S<font size=-1>EASON</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> B<font size=-1>LOOD</font></a>: A R<font size=-1>WANDAN</font> J<font size=-1>OURNEY</font>&nbsp; By Fergal Keane.<br>
<li><a href="4ex68.html"></i>W<font size=-1>AR</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> V<font size=-1>ISIONS</font></a>: C<font size=-1>ONFLICT</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> I<font size=-1>DENTITIES</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> S<font size=-1>UDAN</font>&nbsp; By Francis Deng.<br>
</ul>



<p>DOES the world need to know where the knife went in? How many times the axe chopped through flesh and bone? Yes, says the journalist. Usually. Rwanda was different.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In April 1994 the South African election had drawn every journalist in Africa southwards (many thought the voting would end in violence). The aeroplane crash at Kigali on April 6th 1994 which killed the presidents of Rwanda and Burundi did not distract them. Nor did the reports of subsequent killings in the Rwandan capital. Editors did not want to hear about a nasty war between two groups with silly names in a tiny African country.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So the story came out in dribs and drabs and did not quite get told for a long time. When the journalists did arrive, they soon ran out of words and images. Up close the story was untellable. Some even found their motivation to go on telling it began to dry up. The adrenalin which normally drives their search for the story and getting it out suddenly dissipated.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But they had nightmares for weeks after. One journalist described how she kept dreaming about finding friends lying dead around her house. Another went home saying he did not want his wife and children, he did not want anyone, to read about what he had witnessed. The rest of the world simply did not need to know about this.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fergal Keane went to Rwanda in the aftermath of the genocide to make a television programme. The flyleaf of his "Season of Blood" describes it as: "A necessary book, telling a story that must be told." For whom? Certainly for Mr Keane. He describes how the immensity of the evil has destroyed something in him, how Rwanda keeps a hold on his consciousness as no other story ever has done.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His flowing prose describes the bodies bobbing in the Kagera river and the piles of corpses at Nyarubuye parish, but he fails to discover why almost all the Hutus in Rwanda participated in the methodical murder of their Tutsi neighbours. (In many instances when they grew tired and hungry from so much chopping and stabbing and slashing, they slit the Achilles tendons of their victims and returned to kill them after lunch.) The book that comes closest to answering the question why remains G&eacute;rard Prunier's "The Rwanda Crisis: History of Genocide" (Columbia University; Hurst; 1995).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sudan is also a state which has a deep ethnic divide. In fact it has several but the one which has grown into war is between the Arabic-speaking, Islamic north and the black African, animist or Christian, south. Francis Deng, a Sudanese foreign minister turned academic, has written an excellent analysis of this division that actually offers some solutions. An assertive and intolerant Islamist government in the north will never be able to unite the country, says Mr Deng. He accepts that the huge gap between north and south, cultural, political and religious, means that "partition may be the only option".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike Rwanda, Sudan could be partitioned, although it would leave large numbers of non-Muslims in what would, on present trends, become an Islamist state. There are some 2m southerners in and around Khartoum, already vulnerable to the whims of state officials. If Sudan broke up, they would need some international protection or Sudan could become an even more ghastly place than it is today.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the Rwanda crisis broke there was hardly a recent book in French on the country and no book in English. Perhaps that neglect contributed to Rwanda's isolation and the inability of the world to understand and respond to the crisis there. In which case, Mr Deng has done Sudan a great favour. The world has been told.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
