<html><head><title>Good eggs</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="3gr9.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Amateur investors</b></p>
<h2>Good eggs</h2><ul><li><a href="3ex29.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> B<font size=-1>EARDSTOWN</font> L<font size=-1>ADIES'</font> S<font size=-1>TITCH-IN-</font>T<font size=-1>IME</font> G<font size=-1>UIDE</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> G<font size=-1>ROWING</font> Y<font size=-1>OUR</font> N<font size=-1>EST</font> E<font size=-1>GG</font>. </a>&nbsp; By Ian Knight.<br>
<br>
</ul>


<p>THE Beardstown ladies are an only-in-America phenomenon. A combination of real appeal and media hyperbole has turned these mostly elderly members of a successful Illinois investment club into celebrities. In popular imagination, they rival even Warren Buffett, a famously folksy and sage long-term investor.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since 1983, when their present investment club was formed, the 16 ladies have had an average annual return of around 23%--well above the 16% return on the overall stockmarket in which they invest. Few professional money managers have done as well. Even so, their financial shrewdness might have gone unnoticed but for equal canniness with the press.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1994 the group published "The Beardstown Ladies' Common-sense Investment Guide", which mixed investment advice with homespun wisdom and jokey recipes (for instance, stockmarket muffins that are guaranteed to rise). A bestseller, it helped launch thousands of new investment clubs. These days the ladies schmooze so much on talk-shows, it must be hard scheduling investment meetings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Folksiness, however, should rarely be taken at face value. Most of the ladies have professional backgrounds and are far more sophisticated than they let on. Nor is it deemed polite to note that they owe their success to a couple of exceptional shares, and that their portfolio is worth not millions but something over $100,000.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Their new book is a well-intentioned attempt to cash in on fame. It contains advice on investing ("we like stocks and stock mutual funds for long-term retirement planning") but is mainly an easy-to-read guide to financial planning. The book taps the puritanical meanness that is deep-rooted in American culture, yet at odds with today's consumerism. Readers will no doubt be thrilled to save a few dollars a year by making their own sandwiches, by taking coffee to work in a thermos flask and by making a few dollars from recycling lazy colleagues' soft-drink cans. Invest all this money in the stockmarket, wait for it to grow and then buy that dream ranch. In effect, the ladies are doing their bit to boost America's feeble personal savings rate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All in all, the ladies' advice is not startling: investing is not the mystery it seems and it is never too late to save for retirement. What is clever is to serve up these commonsense truths with recipes and anecdotes to make them more homely and palatable.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
