<html><head><title>Jumbo-sized</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="4gr4.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>The German chancellor</b></p>
<h2>Jumbo-sized</h2><ul><li><a href="4ex87.html">H<font size=-1>ELMUT</font> K<font size=-1>OHL</font></a>: D<font size=-1>IE</font> B<font size=-1>IOGRAPHIE</font>&nbsp; By Karl Hugo Pruys.<br>
</ul>

<p>HE SEEMS to get bigger and bigger in every way. It is not just a matter of girth, though in writing a cookery book jointly with Hannelore, his wife, Helmut Kohl indicated that he was not looking for any slowdown in growth there; in two bites he will demolish a hamburger that takes a lesser mortal ten. His stature as a world leader seems to grow bigger too as Margaret Thatcher, Fran&ccedil;ois Mitterrand and others of his political stature depart and as his commitment to a federal Europe looks an increasingly lonely pursuit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Maybe the years also set him apart from other leading politicians. Come November he will have been chancellor for longer than Konrad Adenauer was--14 years and one month. But there is another reason for his remoteness which Karl Hugo Pruys rightly dwells upon in his biography in German of this political "monster" (the author's word, and one that somehow shocks because Mr Pruys served as Mr Kohl's parliamentary spokesman). The chancellor has no intimate friends.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He is above friendship, except of the world-ordering kind with such people as Boris Yeltsin or Bill Clinton. With them, his strong sense of history brings out a sentimental streak larded with goodwill. Embracing them is to embrace huge notions like reconciliation, security and the destiny of Europe. Otherwise, as it is with friends, so it is with would-be heirs. The worst thing that can happen to a rising politician in his Christian Democratic Party is to be touted as a potential successor to Mr Kohl. Pretty soon he is not. The chancellor sees to that. He seems ever more solitary too in German foreign policy, making it himself. Since the retirement of Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the job of German foreign minister has seemed increasingly redundant.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kohl's monster-quality is his obsession with politics. He does precious little else, save indulge in the pleasures of the table. He positioned himself in his surprisingly lean mid-40s (some of the photographs in this book are a treat) to become conservative candidate for chancellor after discovering that he was quick to make decisions. And he has been quick--sometimes embarrassingly so, as when he took Ronald Reagan to a war cemetery where it turned out that some <i>Waffen-</i><font size=-1>SS</font> men were buried. More impressively, he jumped at the chance of German unification when others hesitated; he swapped the D-mark for East Germans' worthless Ost-marks to sustain unification; and he laid down the principles of Maastricht with Mitterrand to advance his vision of European integration, starting with a common currency.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A shortcoming of Mr Pruys's biography is that he does not reach big conclusions or draw the big picture. His insider's account is a compendium of a thousand Kohl-bites. He could plead that it is too early for any measured analysis of Mr Kohl. But for ordinary Germans the "monster" does seem to have pulled off an extraordinary feat at the end of a horrifying century. He has put things right with Russia, Israel, Poland, France, the Netherlands and the other nations which, in their different ways, had most to hold against Hitler's Germany. They had still not quite come around to accepting Germany's good intentions until Helmut Kohl came along.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
