<html><head><title>City of the Century</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl208.jpg"><img src="cs208.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>C<font size=-1>ITY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> C<font size=-1>ENTURY</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>PIC</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> C<font size=-1>HICAGO</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>AKING</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> A<font size=-1>MERICA</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Donald Miller. <br>
<i>Simon &amp; Schuster; 704 pages; $35</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="7bt208.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
The rise of Chicago is a great American story. Chicago grew from a desolate
fur-trading post of some thirty settlers to the most dynamic city in North
America, if not the world, in the lifetime of one of its early residents. In the
1830s Chicago barely existed, but by 1893 it had beaten out New York as the
site of the World's Columbian Exposition, with its still-famous "White City."
Chicago then was a center of power and culture, the metropolis of the new and
the revolutionary, a place people visited to see the shape of the future. It was
the city of the century.
<p>The epic of Chicago is the story of the emergence of modern America. The same forces and personalities that created Chicago helped make America the most powerful national in the world by 1900. Chicago was widely considered the most typically American of the nation's big cities, a scene of boiling economic activity and technological ingenuity, American industrialism's supreme urban creation. "Here of all her cities," wrote the novelist Frank Norris, "throbbed the true life--the true power and spirit of America."</p>
<p>Chicago was also a city of extreme, even violent contrasts. Although it was the most "American" of cities, more than three quarters of its residents were of foreign parentage in 1893. Garden city of parks and tree-bordered boulevards, it nevertheless had most of its streets filled with uncollected horse manure and putrid animal corpses. Temperance capital of the country--headquarters of Frances Willard's Woman's Christian Temperance Union--it had one saloon for every two hundred persons, and its world-famous vice district operated around the clock with police protection. Home of the empire-building capitalists Philip Armour, George Pullman, and Marshall Field, Chicago was the center of the nation's trade-union and anarchist movements and the site of some of the most violent labor disturbances of the industrial age. A city supposedly given over entirely to money-making, it produced some of the finest young writers and reporters of the late nineteenth century, as well as an amazing group of architects and engineers--Louis Sullivan, Frank Lloyd Wright, William Le Baron Jenney, and John Welborn Root--who invented modern urban architecture and with it the steelframe skyscraper, the most audacious engineering achievement since the Gothic cathedrals.</p>
<p>Theodore Dreiser thought Chicago a symbol of a "tremendous" American future; Rudyard Kipling said that having seen Chicago he urgently desired never to see it again. But no matter how observers differed in their reactions, few disputed Henry Adams's conviction that nineteenth-century Chicago was the best place to observe "the new energies" of the age. A city ahead of its time, Chicago foretold the major conflicts and challenges of the new world of science, technology, and rapid social change that Americans anticipated with fear and fascination.</p>
<p>City of idealists and dissenters, builders and visionaries, thieving aldermen and plundering capitalists, nineteenth-century Chicago was the site of some of the greatest achievements and failures of American urban life. The story of its unresolved struggle between order and freedom, growth and control, capitalism and community, remains instructive for our time, as we seek ways to build and maintain cities that retain their humanity without losing their energy.</p>
<p>Donald Miller's powerful narrative embraces the entire urban drama-- Chicago's wild beginnings, its reckless growth, its natural calamities (especially the Great Fire of 1871), its raucous politics, its empire-building businessmen, its world-transforming architecture, its rich mix of ethnic cultures, its community of young writers and journalists, and its staggering engineering projects--which included the reversal of the Chicago River and raising the entire city from prairie mud to save it from devastating cholera epidemics.</p>
<p>Beautifully written and filled with fresh insights, City of the Century throbs with the pulse of the great city it brilliantly brings to life. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
