<html><head><title>Plot development</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="7gr4.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Cities: Chicago</b></p>
<h2>Plot development</h2><ul> <li><a href="7ex207.html">H<font size=-1>ERE'S</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> D<font size=-1>EAL</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> B<font size=-1>UYING</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> S<font size=-1>ELLING</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>A</font> G<font size=-1>REAT</font> A<font size=-1>MERICAN</font> C<font size=-1>ITY</font>.&nbsp;  By Ross Miller. <br>
 <li><a href="7ex208.html">C<font size=-1>ITY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> C<font size=-1>ENTURY</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>PIC</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> C<font size=-1>HICAGO</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>AKING</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> A<font size=-1>MERICA</font>.&nbsp;  By Donald Miller. <br>
</ul>


<p>AMAZED by Berlin's late-19th-century building boom, Mark Twain joked that the German capital made "even Chicago seem old". More than 100 years on much of downtown Chicago looks positively historic. The torch of newness long since passed elsewhere. While Berlin is again a giant building site, Chicago's developers are taking a break for digestion. Even its 110-storey Sears Tower, once a symbol of over-reaching modernity, has lost the tag of the world's tallest building to the Petronas Twin Towers in Kuala Lumpur.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The briefest tour of Chicago takes you back to a classic era of modern architecture, to offices by Louis Sullivan, low houses by Frank Lloyd Wright and a justly famous mid-century skyline. This was a time of brimming confidence in new design, when nature, technology and society, or so it seemed, all worked in harmony. A local newspaperman and poet-patriot, Carl Sandburg, voiced this hopefulness when he said that the city's soaring buildings would need "hinges on the top two storeys to let the moon go by".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not for lack of moonlight that Ross Miller takes a dark view of his subject--the past 30 years or so of city development in Chicago. The story begins in the 1960s when the city administration of the late Richard Daley encouraged huge building projects as a way to revive Chicago's downtown area. It continues as the uncelebrated Amoco, Hancock and Sears skyscrapers duly rise up and ends with the hog-fest of commercial over-building in the 1980s for which Chicago is still paying. As an emblem of these failures, Ross Miller focuses on a three-acre chunk of downtown land known as "Block 37"--a boarded-up site that was razed for construction but perversely never built on.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though Ross Miller's angry disillusion makes for a lively read, his judgments are often overbroad and the book bogs down in wearisome details of deals and double-crosses among Chicago's big developers. It could have said more about city planners and given wider scope to Ross Miller's eye as an architectural critic.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Quite different in tone is "City of the Century" by a historian, Donald Miller. His topic is the city's growth, in all its variety, from 1830 to 1893. Inspired by an earlier urban historian and mentor, Lewis Mumford, he seeks to use the buildings of Chicago as an archival historian would use documents. Though even for "city biography" this method has its limits, Donald Miller lovingly describes the work of the great builders of late-19th-century Chicago, Daniel Burnham, John Root and Sullivan, who brilliantly exploited the steel frame, powerful lifts and effective central heating. Though this ground has been covered before, Donald Miller deals more widely with the changing material face of the city, describing its railways, canals, meatpacking plants and steel mills. Engaging character-sketches break up a book whose rollicking, celebratory tone would otherwise grow tiresome (there is too much "biggest" this and "most dynamic" that).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Urban history is a stream and cut-offs are arbitrary. Chicago's World Fair in 1893 makes as good an end-point as any. But Donald Miller ignores it when he chooses, squeezing in marginally 19th-century figures like Thorstein Veblen, a social critic who started at the University of Chicago in 1892, as well as clearly 20th-century ones such as the novelist Theodore Dreiser, who grew up partly in Chicago, and Wright himself. Wright worked as a young draughtsman in Sullivan's office, and mocked his survival-of-the-fittest political theories as so much "baying at the moon". That was when you could still see it.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
