<html><head><title>Truth and consequences</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h1>Truth and consequences</h1>
<p><b>Faction vies with fiction among this summer's talked-about novels</b></p><ul> <li><a href="7ex201.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>AST</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> S<font size=-1>AVAGES</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Jay McInerney. <br>
 <li>B<font size=-1>ABEL</font> T<font size=-1>OWER</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By A. S. Byatt.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Chatto &amp; Windus; 617 pages; &#163;16.99. Random House; $25.95.</i> <br>
 <li><a href="7ex181.html">D<font size=-1>ANGEROUS</font> L<font size=-1>OVE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Ben Okri. <br>
 <li>I W<font size=-1>AS</font> A<font size=-1>MELIA</font> E<font size=-1>ARHART</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Jane Mendelsohn.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Jonathan Cape; 145 pages; &#163;9.99. Knopf; $18.</i> <br>
 <li><a href="7ex204.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> F<font size=-1>REQUENCY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>OULS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Mary Kay Zuravleff. <br>
 <li><a href="7ex205.html">F<font size=-1>REMDER</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Russell Hoban. <br>
 <li><a href="7ex180.html">L<font size=-1>OVE</font>, A<font size=-1>GAIN</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Doris Lessing. <br>
 <li><a href="7ex179.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>OMAN</font> <font size=-1>WHO</font> W<font size=-1>ALKED</font> <font size=-1>INTO</font> D<font size=-1>OORS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Roddy Doyle. <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

<p>ONCE upon a time readers consulted a biography, an encyclopedia, a historical textbook or some other source of factual information when they needed to know about something that had really happened--some deliciously scurrilous detail of a famous life, say, or an important political event. But many novelists are now treading the path pioneered by Norman Mailer and writing faction (definition: an artful mingling of fact and fiction). Read them and you can be informed and entertained at the same time--without always knowing which is which.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some of this summer's biggest and most ambitious English-language novels--from America, Nigeria and England--are books of this kind. And one of the best of them is "The Last of the Savages", a dissection of the turbulent 1960s and their aftermath by Jay McInerney. His is the story of an unlikely friendship between Patrick, an Irish-Catholic boy from a dull New England mill town, and Will Savage, the flamboyant and unpredictable scion of a family from the Old South who is trying to put behind him his forebears' associations with slavery. The boys grow up together--at prep school and later at Yale. Patrick slips easily into a career as a corporate lawyer; his old friend Will, promoter of the new sound of soul and a kind of priest of the higher hippiedom, spins out of control.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This book, the fourth by this young New York writer, is intelligently paced, consistently funny and delightfully unpredictable. It is sensibly and believably anchored in historical fact, but the factual references never weigh too heavily on the reader's mind or interrupt the flow of the narrative.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The principal impediment to a fuller enjoyment of past novels by Ben Okri, the Nigerian who won the Booker Prize in 1991 for "The Famished Road", has been his tendency to indulge in vapidly rhapsodic writing. It has often been hard to tell whether he was describing dream or reality--and it did not seem to matter much anyway.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such acts of self-indulgence seldom mar Mr Okri's "Dangerous Love", which is a story of compound life in the straggling outskirts of Lagos, Nigeria's commercial capital. This time he has given us credible characters--the painter, Omovo, for example, who is hopelessly in love with another man's wife; the girl herself, Ifeyiwa, and her cruelly pathetic and tyrannical husband.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The novel is set in the 1970s, and therefore in the aftermath of civil war between Odumegwu Ojukwu's Biafra and the forces of the federal government. Some abiding sense of the continuing destructiveness of that war, both physical and psychological, imbues the story with a special atmosphere from start to finish, and adds an almost indescribable feeling of tension, anxiety and hopelessness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But it is in the descriptions of Lagos and the wretchedness of compound life itself that Mr Okri has really excelled himself this time. Note, for instance, how this subject matter gets absorbed into Omovo's paintings: "Metal. Hot road. Copper sun. Sweating drivers. Busy hawkers. Policemen accepting bribes. Lights on painted metal..."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Babel Tower" is by A. S. Byatt, an English novelist who won the Booker Prize a year before Mr Okri. At its heart is the story of a relationship between the clever daughter of a Yorkshire schoolmaster and the son of a "country" family whom she marries. The marriage is a disaster: the husband finds it inexplicable that his wife, who has experienced the social and sexual freedoms of university life in the 1960s, should be dissatisfied by a future of child-care and country idleness. He beats her. She runs away, taking their only son with her. The whole thing comes to trial: an acting out of the battle between the new freedoms of the 1960s and the older order represented by the judiciary.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Running in parallel with this story is another: the tale of another novel, "Babble Tower", which recounts the rise and fall of a Utopian community. The work is brought to trial for obscenity. Regrettably, large and tedious sections of archaic language from "Babble Tower", the book within a book, are quoted in the novel itself. Another fault is to dwell on the "issues" of the 1960s--sexual liberation, the pill and so on--in a pedagogical way.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The subject of "I Was Amelia Earhart", a short first novel by Jane Mendelsohn, a young American author, is much as its title suggests: it is an ingenious elaboration upon the story of Amelia Earhart's last flight, which took place July 1937, as if spoken by that "goddess of flight" (as the press described her) herself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The best bits are the details of Amelia Earhart's life: physical appearance and personal mannerisms that the novelist must have gleaned from her researches into the subject. The worst bits are the fanciful descriptions of what may "really" have happened to the aviatrix and her navigator after they lost radio contact and disappeared into the Pacific.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mary Kay Zuravleff's "The Frequency of Souls" is a much more praiseworthy first novel--if only because its setting is unusual, and must have demanded a lot of original research. Ms Zuravleff has delved into the world of refrigerator designers, an unexciting profession on the face of it but one which is just as likely to exhibit signs of real human life as any other.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;George Mahoney, her man, can see nothing beyond the plain, honest facts of the physical world until Niagara Spense, his new research colleague, arrives. Niagara may look outwardly unattractive, but her strange beliefs about the ability of souls not only to survive but also to communicate with the living, at first appals and then begins to fascinate stolid George. The novel does not travel far in the terms of its plot, but it is rich in humour and in its cunning observation of human behaviour.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Russell Hoban, an American long resident in London, has always written fiction which has been extremely difficult to categorise. And it is again so with "Fremder", a fascinating cocktail of futuristic fantasy and science fiction set in the middle of the 21st century.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The difficulty with many sci-fi novels is that they are vehicles for interesting ideas--usually scientific or sociological--but such matters as characterisation or topography get too little attention. This is not the case with Mr Hoban's new novel. It introduces an earth transformed by decades of pollution and social unrest. Fremder himself is the lone survivor of an interplanetary expedition but nobody knows why or how he survived, not ever Fremder himself. The novel is the unravelling of this secret.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To fall at the 46th fence is regrettable, but Doris Lessing has managed to do it. Two years ago she wrote "Under My Skin", one of the most remarkable autobiographies to have appeared since the second world war. Now she has written one of the weakest and least plausible novels by an eminent writer within recent memory.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Love, Again" is a relentless tale of love, and of how an older woman can be in thrall to passion almost to the point of self-destruction. The woman in question is the director of a small London theatre company which is staging a play about a young woman who dies for love. The novel crawls along at the pace of a sun-struck snail, and as it does so it works its theme of star-crossed love <i>ad nauseam</i>. There are passages of great brilliance, especially in the opening pages when the reader is gulled into thinking that this is yet another remarkable book by Mrs Lessing, but the writing disappoints all too soon, and then it goes on and on and on disappointing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And finally from this recent crop of fiction comes something quite unexpected. Roddy Doyle, a fine comic novelist from Dublin, and yet another winner of the Booker Prize, has written something sad and moving. It is the story, told by herself, of an ordinary, 39-year-old working-class Dublin woman whose husband abuses and batters her. Reading "The Woman Who Walked Into Doors", which has no stylistic adornments whatsoever, is a sobre experience. It is all the more affecting for that--and more true to life than any biography, encyclopedia or historical textbook.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
