<html><head><title>The Last of the Savages.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl201.jpg"><img src="cs201.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>AST</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> S<font size=-1>AVAGES</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Jay McInerney. <br>
<i>Bloomsbury; 276 pages; &#163;15.99. Knopf; $24.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="7bt201.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
His ancestors may have owned and mistreated slaves in the Mississippi Delta,
but Will Savage was working off his historical debt through a lover affair with
black soul music. He arrived grooving at his New England prep school in the
mid-sixties, to the awed fascination of Patrick, his Irish-Catholic room-mate
from a dreary New England mill town. Theirs was an unusual friendship that
was to last for decades.
<p>While Patrick aspired to all that the Ivy League and convention had to offer, Will defied his white Southern family's wishes, especially his father's, in marrying a beautiful black woman. He became a dedicated scout and promoter of Soul, a pioneer of haute hippiedom and eventually an underground legend. From a mid-life point of affluent Park Avenue domesticity, the lawyer Patrick would look back on his intense friendship with Will and the single most daring and unpredictable choice he allowed himself in his studied course of upward mobility.</p>
<p>The Last of the Savages is a dazzling novel about friendship, music and race relations, and about family for better of worse. It embraces an interracial love story, an overview of American social changes circa 1965 to 1995 and the portrait of an abiding male intimacy that is funny, profound and unforgettable. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
