<html><head><title>Dangerous Love.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl181.jpg"><img src="cs181.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>D<font size=-1>ANGEROUS</font> L<font size=-1>OVE</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Ben Okri. <br>
<i>Phoenix House; 325 pages; &#163;15.99.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="7bt181.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Dangerous Love, an epic of daily life, is Ben Okri's most accessible and most
disarming novel. In simple terms it is a love story, set against the background
of seventies' Nigeria in the aftermath of the civil war, among young people
forever marked by the experiences and memories of a people torn apart. As the
title implies, it is a story of doomed love, of two 'star-crossed' lovers, separated
not by their families, but by the very circumstances of their lives.
<p>It is also a story of a dangerous time, of a nation painfully finding its identity in a post-colonial age, saturated with corruption and with selfdoubt, struggling to reconcile the old ways with the new. And yet through it all runs a strange spirit of hope, for it is also a celebration of ordinary lives lived under impossible conditions. Somehow, in the midst of helplessness and decay, love can still flourish and flower.</p>
<p>Full of the sound and smell of Africa, Dangerous Love is Ben Okri's most personal and most political work and it is without doubt one of his most beautiful. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
