<html><head><title>The Frequency of Souls.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl204.jpg"><img src="cs204.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> F<font size=-1>REQUENCY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>OULS</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Mary Kay Zuravleff. <br>
<i>Chatto &amp; Windus; 243 pages; &#163;14.99. Farrar, Straus &amp; Giroux; $23.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="7bt204.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
The Frequency of Souls is a wry, funny and touching novel in the tradition of
Anne Tyler or John Irving - yet utterly unique.
<p>George Mahoney is a refrigerator designer wedded to facts and the physical world, with more than a passing interest in dinosaurs. Niagara Spense, his new colleague, spends her spare time seeking electrical evidence of life beyond the grave - via an old valve wireless. Niagara is six foot tall, with cloth-brown hair, a hearing aid, and glasses thicker than George's own. George cannot stop thinking about her, despite his solid marriage, pretty wife and two children.</p>
<p>George's behaviour becomes unpredictable. He lunches out, wears different clothes - and contemplates adultery. His wife Judy, a trim and dynamic real estate agent, picks up some of the signals but fortunately for George she's too busy worrying about their twelve-year-old son, Harris, who may be a genius or just a troublesome child with a weight problem. Harris plots the science project which he hopes will get him out of going to 'fat' camp, while Niagara, like a force of nature, turns George's world upside down.</p>
<p>Full of surprises, witty and compelling, The Frequency of Souls tells a wickedly original story which traces the mysterious sparks and enduring currents of love. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
