<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>OMAN</font> <font size=-1>WHO</font> W<font size=-1>ALKED</font> <font size=-1>INTO</font> D<font size=-1>OORS</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Roddy Doyle. <br>
<i>Jonathan Cape; 222 pages; &#163;14.99. Viking; $22.95</i>.<i></i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="7jb179.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
RODDY DOYLE was born in Dublin in 1958. His first novel, The
Commitments, was published to great acclaim in 1987 and was made into a
very successful film by Alan Parker. The Snapper was published in 1990 and
has also been made into a film, directed by Stephen Frears. The Van was
shortlisted for the 1991 Booker Prize; Stephen Frears' film will be released in
1996. Paddy Clarke Ha Ha Ha, which won the Booker Prize in 1993, was the
largest-selling winner in the history of the prize and has been published in
nineteen languages.
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
