</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Gene's-eye view</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Sociobiology</b></p>
<h2>Gene's-eye view</h2><ul> <li><a href="7ex182.html">N<font size=-1>ARROW</font> R<font size=-1>OADS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> G<font size=-1>ENE</font> L<font size=-1>AND</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By W.D. Hamilton. <br>
</ul>

<p>ON A spring afternoon at the Berlin zoo in 1989, a small crowd was gathered in front of the turkey enclosure. For there, just in front of the cage, a tall man with a large head, craggy features and a shock of white hair was flapping his arms, tapping his feet, and emitting "gobble gobble" noises: he was dancing a turkey mating dance. And the turkeys were joining in.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Few in the crowd would have known that they were looking at W. D. ("Bill") Hamilton, one of the greatest evolutionary biologists since Darwin. Publishing infrequently (the curriculum vitae that he sends out has a list of publications that is a single page) and almost always alone, he rarely had his work accepted by <i>Nature</i> or <i>Science</i>. But he revolutionised biology.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As a postgraduate at the University of London, he worried about altruism: when, if ever, should an organism put itself at risk for another? His answer, published in two parts in the <i>Journal of Theoretical Biology</i> in 1964, inadvertently founded the field of research now known as sociobiology. Roughly, his idea is that if apparently altruistic behaviour carries a big cost--such as death or sterility--then it will happen only if the two organisms in question are near relatives. Such organisms have a high proportion of genes in common. If gene-spreading is the aim, helping to rear a sister's children can sometimes be more effective than having children of your own.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This explanation of altruism has surprising power. It explains, for instance, why females in so many species of ant and bee work tirelessly to bring up their sisters instead of having nests of their own: because of a peculiar genetic system, the sisters share more genes with each other than they would with any of their children. Nor was it just the treatment of altruism that was radical. The gene's-eye view of the world has taken on even more importance now it seems that different genes within an organism can have different "interests" and that these in turn can affect evolution.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From the questions of why babies die and of why creatures get old (and why some of them have a menopause--humans are not alone in this, some aphids have one too), to whether animals are ever spiteful, to the advantages of being in the middle of a herd, to the sex lives of the bugs that live on dead wood, Bill Hamilton turned to whatever he found interesting.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He is revered by students and often envied by colleagues, and everyone who has met him has a story to tell. (A favourite: his youngest daughter was once heard to exclaim, "Hey, Dad, look. There's a really interesting weevil in the sugar bowl!"). But perhaps the best person to tell such tales is Mr Hamilton--and in this volume he does so. Each of 15 papers is preceded by a specially written introduction. In these short essays, he tells anecdotes, muses on scientific questions and ponders what, if anything, his work can reveal about people.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Erudite, funny, sometimes moving, occasionally strange, he tells of himself as a young man so lonely that late at night he worked out algebra on the benches of Waterloo station, of getting his first job as a lecturer because the only other applicant turned the offer down, of dressing up in a baker's costume to acquire a colony of rare ants from a biscuit factory, of plotting with a colleague to trick<i> Nature</i> into accepting their papers, of watching and quietly cheering as two stag beetles fought on (but not over) his boots. Readers with little knowledge of biology may find this collection difficult in places--but it will entertain and, perhaps, inspire.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
