<html><head><title>Jerusalem in the Twentieth Century.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl188.jpg"><img src="cs188.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>J<font size=-1>ERUSALEM</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> T<font size=-1>WENTIETH</font> C<font size=-1>ENTURY</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Martin Gilbert. <br>
<i>Chatto and Windus; 400 pages; &#163;20</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="7bt188.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
When the twentieth century opened, Jerusalem was an outpost of the Ottoman
Empire, a provincial town ruled from Constantinople. As the century closes it is
a major city, the capital of an independent nation, and still a vital centre of
religious worship for three world religions.
<p>The story of those hundred years, from the twilight of Turkish rule to the advent of the twenty-first century as Jewish Jerusalem celebrates the 3000th anniversary of its foundation - is fascinating, often tragic, always gripping, and vital to our understanding of the Middle East.</p>
<p>Martin Gilbert's earlier volume, Jerusalem: Rebirth of a City, was an acclaimed history of the city in the nineteenth century. This new study comprises a vivid and authoritative history of the crucial years which followed. Rooted in contemporary sources and scholarship, it springs from his intimate knowledge of the city and its people.</p>
<p>Here is Jerusalem's dramatic modern story, including the city's liberation from the Turks by the British army in 1917, the Balfour Declaration with its promise of a Jewish National Home, the years of the British Mandate - when the rapid growth of a modern city was frequently disrupted by violence - the Second World War, the British withdrawal on the eve of the battle for Jerusalem in 1948, the creation of the State of Israel, the division of the city into two disparate parts, the Six Day War of 1967, the city's reunification, the rebuilding that followed, the Intifada years, and, finally, the uneasy yet hopeful agreements of the nineties between Israel and the Palestinians.</p>
<p>Lucid, readable, essential history, Jerusalem in the Twentieth Century covers every facet of Jerusalem's life - political, cultural, architectural, intellectual, religious and social. The conflicts, traumas, aspirations and achievements of an often disputed yet always vibrant city, and of a whole region, are reflected in its pages. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
