<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>J<font size=-1>ERUSALEM</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> T<font size=-1>WENTIETH</font> C<font size=-1>ENTURY</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Martin Gilbert. <br>
<i>Chatto and Windus; 400 pages; &#163;20</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="7jb188.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
Martin Gilbert is a Fellow of Merton College, Oxford, and an eminent
historian. He is well known as the official biographer of Churchill and as a
chronicler of the Holocaust and of Jewish history. His books include Jerusalem:
Rebirth of a City, The Holocaust, First World War, Second World War and The
Day the War Ended (8 May 1945). He lives in London, and has a home in
Jerusalem. He was knighted in 1995.
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
