<html><head><title>An obstacle in the path of peace</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="7gr5.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Cities: Jerusalem</b></p>
<h2>An obstacle in the path of peace</h2><ul> <li><a href="7ex188.html">J<font size=-1>ERUSALEM</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> T<font size=-1>WENTIETH</font> C<font size=-1>ENTURY</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Martin Gilbert. <br>
</ul>

<p>THE end of the second world war, writes Martin Gilbert, "left Jerusalem stranded like a beached whale on the shores of conflict". Not, to be sure, how most people see the golden city. Yet, now more than ever, Jerusalem is a large immobile obstacle in the path of a lasting peace between Israelis and Palestinians. Meron Benvenisti, an Israeli who understands the Palestinians and who was once a deputy mayor of the city, was putting it correctly when he wrote: "There is no other place where one feels the tragedy of two nations fighting for their homeland more than in Jerusalem."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sir Martin is a brilliant chronicler of Jerusalem's conflicts, at least in the first half of the 20th century; his feeling for its tragedy is less in evidence. Having described the 19th-century city in an earlier book, he now carries the story on to the last days of the Ottoman empire and the British mandate, through the bloody rush of events that led to Israel's birth and the city's division and reunification, down to its less-than-certain present. He is a master at bringing complicated history briskly alive through anecdote and quotation, plundering newspapers and letters for contemporary viewpoints.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He packs in the main events but lightens the narrative with telling detail. Here, for instance, is an old man commenting on the execution of an Arab nationalist by the Turks: "He was a good man, greatly respected; therefore we all assembled to see him hang." A Christian Arab writes to the military governor, "I do beseech Your Excellency to grant my request, for the sake of J. Christ, Esq; a gentleman whom Your Honour so closely resembles."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1917 the mayor and elders of the city, ceremonially bearing its keys, sought out a British conqueror to hand them to but found only "two wandering and bewildered cockney sergeants from Camden Town". This anecdote foreshadows another, 30 years later and not told in this work, of how a British high commissioner, on Britain's way out, was asked to whom he would give the keys and replied that he would probably leave them under the mat.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The struggle for those keys, or at least the side-door key to East Jerusalem, is the city's continuing story--and Martin Gilbert narrates it scrupulously. His sympathies, however, are openly with Israel. In the countless battles, the terrorism and the counter-terrorism, the dead are numbered but the Jewish dead are more likely to spring from the statistics with little labels making each death a sadness. He accepts Israel's territorial need to build an unbroken circle of new Jewish suburbs around Arab Jerusalem. And he gives the Israelis, in particular Teddy Kollek, who was Jerusalem's mayor for 28 years, too much credit for making life better for the city's Arab residents. Mr Kollek, a great publicist, may have had good intentions but they did not work out in practice.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although this history ends with the funeral of Yitzhak Rabin, Israel's murdered prime minister, and the outburst of Islamist suicide-bombings, the author remains hopeful. The city of Jerusalem, he writes, can feel pride in "a century of creativity and satisfaction, exuberant life, determination, civic achievement". Rabin is quoted as saying, shortly before his death: "Jerusalem has a thousand faces, and each one of us has his own Jerusalem." So be it. Sir Martin depicts one Jerusalem; the city has other faces, too.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
