<html><head><title>Savages.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl225.jpg"><img src="cs225.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>S<font size=-1>AVAGES</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Joe Kane. <br>
<i>Macmillan; 273 pages; &#163;16.99.</i> <i>Knopf; $25</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="8bt225.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
A remarkable firsthand account, by turns hilarious, heartbreaking and thrilling,
of a small band of Amazonian warriors and their battle to preserve their way of
life from the scourge of civilization.
<p>Joe Kane, author of the bestselling Running the Amazon, returns to the river to search for the Huaorani, a nation of 1,300 nomadic warriors so remote that their language is unrelated to any other on earth; so fierce that for millenia they have turned all comers away from their land, a territory in the middle of the Ecuadorian Amazo the size of Wales.</p>
<p>But now, the Huaorani are besieged by hell-bent oil companies, dogged missionaries, zealous indigenous bureaucrats and strarry-eyed environmentalists intent on helping them 'better' themselves.</p>
<p>Kane's account of the efforts of the Huaorani to vault from Stone Age to Petroleum Age, to move faster than the forces of change, brings us face-to-face with the nature of our built-in need to develop the world willy-nilly and our inability to acknowledge to basic purpose of development. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
