<html><head><title>Savages.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl225.jpg"><img src="cs225.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>S<font size=-1>AVAGES</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Joe Kane. <br>
<i>Macmillan; 273 pages; &#163;16.99.</i> <i>Knopf; $25</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="8jb225.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
Joe Kane's writing about the Amazon for the New Yorker earned him the
Overseas Press Club Award for best environmental reporting. He was a
member of the expedition that made the first complete navigation of the
Amazon River; his book about that journey, Running the Amazon, was a
bestseller. He lives in Oakland, California.
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
