<html><head><title>A right to a past</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="8gr2.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Indigenous peoples</b></p>
<h2>A right to a past</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex225.html">S<font size=-1>AVAGES</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Joe Kane. <br>
</ul>


<p>IF YOU belong to a remote tribe living on top of millions of barrels of oil in a heavily-indebted country, you might as well give up and get ready to move. The Huaorani people of central Ecuador, 1,400 semi-nomadic semi-warriors, refused. "Savages" is an account of how they tried and failed--it seems inevitably--to hang on to their lands and their way of life.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The savages intended in the title are not the Huaorani, despite their penchant for naked spear-wars. Their lives have been so remote from the rest of the world for so long that their language has no terms for counting: "enough" and "not enough" are sufficient. Until recently, the typical Huao would meet just 70 or 80 people in the course of a lifetime.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Joe Kane is not dewy-eyed about the Huaorani, however. Hunting and gathering, he learns the hard way, is no picnic. The Huaorani live short and often sick lives in which hunger and violence are strong features. And when his Huao friends visit him in Quito, they are the houseguests from hell. That clash of cultures aside, they come off rather well. It is hard not to like a fellow like Moi, who swore never to return to Los Angeles after a trip to drum up support exposed him to his first vegetarians: "Barbarians," he shuddered.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Huaorani seem afraid at the prospect of companies tapping the riches beneath their soil. To understand why, Mr Kane visits Lago Agrio, where the Cofan Indians live. Their village, too, had the misfortune to be seeping with oil. During its exploitation, there were six major spills, which the companies cleaned up by hiring workers to scoop up the filth with their hands and then put it into hundreds of open waste pits. For this, they were paid a dollar a day, with most of that then taken back to pay for rent and incidentals. Promises not to exploit a wildlife reserve were broken, and no one tried hard to limit land-seizures in this crowded country. The result for the Cofan Indians: "They are a listless and defeated bunch."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though depressed, Mr Kane is not a Luddite. He understands that pumping oil is what oil companies do. But he is persuasive that it could be done less brutally. The companies themselves agree, to a point. One firm did not want to go into the Oriente, as the region is known, until it had the public approval of a respected environmental group. A noble thought, and one that betrays a different sensibility from that of 19th-century buccaneers on the economic frontier. Unfortunately, this led mostly to political in-fighting of the most unseemly kind, as the oil companies sought out tame tribal folks and various western environmental groups waded in.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kane saves a special contempt for Robert Kennedy of the Natural Resources Defence Council, who jetted to Ecuador for five days, then cut a deal with the oil company he thought would do the least damage. No doubt his heart was in the right place, but these "environmental imperialists", as an Ecuadorean memorably terms them, butted in to make bad decisions for people who were able to articulate their own desires perfectly well.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kane has the intellectual courage--too rare among rainforest activists--to ask: Do the Huaorani have the right "to be protected from change"? The answer he seems to come to is no--but they should be given a large say in how they make the adjustment. A group of Cofan Indians who are running eco-tours in the rainforest is an example of what he has in mind.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The larger question is whether today's powers-that-be are willing and able to accommodate themselves to this outlook. In the Huaorani case, they were not. There was much sound (from the government and oil companies) and much fury (from the Huaorani and their allies) but never a meeting of minds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Joe Kane has done something unusual: he catches a moment--the end of a small, ancient civilisation--in a kind of amber. The Huaorani will never be the same. But it is some compensation at least that their memory has been recorded for outsiders in the pages of this excellent book.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
