<html><head><title>Three Moons in Vietnam.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl262.jpg"><img src="cs262.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HREE</font> M<font size=-1>OONS</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> V<font size=-1>IETNAM</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Maria Coffey<br>
<i>Little Brown; 291 pages; &#163;18.99</i>.<br>
</p><br>
<a href="9jb262.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
Maria Coffey is the author of Fragile Edge (1989), A Boat In Our Baggage
(Little, Brown 1994), which describes a year-long journey by folding boat to
some remote corners of the world, and Sailing Back In Time (1996). She has
also contributed to The Guardian, The New York Times, The Globe and Mail,
Sea Kayaker Magazine and Outdoors Illustrated. A native of England, she now
lives on the west coast of Canada with her husband Dag Goering, who is a
veterinarian and a photographer.
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
