<html><head><title>Sweet and sour</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr6.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>



<p><b>America's Vietnam</b></p>
<h2>Sweet and sour</h2><ul> <li>S<font size=-1>PARRING</font> <font size=-1>WITH</font> C<font size=-1>HARLIE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Christopher Hunt. &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Anchor; 289 pages; $12.95.</i> <br>
 <li><a href="9ex264.html">A P<font size=-1>HOENIX</font> R<font size=-1>ISING</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Zo&euml; Schramm-Evans. <br>
 <li><a href="9ex262.html">T<font size=-1>HREE</font> M<font size=-1>OONS</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> V<font size=-1>IETNAM</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Maria Coffey<br>
 <li><a href="9ex261.html">V<font size=-1>IETNAMERICA</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Thomas Bass. <br>
</ul>


</i>



<p>VIETNAM is no longer just for the nose-pierced hard-core traveller; neither is it yet suitable for the blue-rinse set. Still, enough Vietnamese have enough English, and moxie, to enable reasonably intrepid visitors to get where they want to go with no more hassle than in any other poverty-stricken dictatorship.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So it is not surprising that travel writers are descending on the place. One of these is Christopher Hunt, a former financial writer for <i>The Economist</i> who went to Vietnam to research a novel and instead rode a Russian motorbike along as much of the Ho Chi Minh trail as he could find. He is a genial and unpretentious sort who does not pretend to Great Thoughts on things Vietnamese. But he is good company. For example, he gets to Hue, and realises he just does not give a damn that it is Vietnam's cultural capital. So he skips seeing the emperors' tombs, and buzzes off to make a date with a waitress. She stands him up. He moves on.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Hunt is also refreshingly free of guilt about the war--he was 12 when Saigon fell--and this spares the book the pointless agonising that too many writers on Vietnam seem compelled to affect. The war is obviously an important piece of the puzzle that is Vietnam, and the Ho Chi Minh trail is a relic of it, but Mr Hunt uses the trail as a way to get to today's Vietnam, not as a vein-opening pathway to an exquisite angst<i>. </i>The device works nicely. All kinds of rogues seem to find him, from gangster wannabes to pimps to the more pathetic kind of American Vietnam vet, and the result is an evocative, funny book that rings true. There are worse places to see Vietnam from than Mr Hunt's pillion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Travel books written by unfunny, miserable people, however, are a slog. Zo&#145; Schramm-Evans's falls into this category. She admits she did not know much about Vietnam, and several weeks there obviously did not help much. "The Lonely Planet Guide" seems to be her main reference source. And though Vietnam has 70m people, half of whom are practising their English at any given time, she meets few of them. The ones she does meet tend to be guides or drivers, and too often she ends up screaming at them--bad strategy in Asia, and rotten manners anywhere.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Maria Coffey is much better company in an account of a journey she and her husband Dag made via boat and bike along the Vietnamese coast. Before this sounds too worthy for words, it is not. They are not the kind of travellers who are not happy if they are comfortable; in fact, they bitch rather nicely about smelly buses, foul hotel rooms and grasping officials. They chose to go by boat because, well, Dag likes them, and Maria likes Dag, and they thought they would meet lots of locals. In the event, they did, including a boat handler whose favourite author is Nietzsche, a Vietnamese-American hustler, and two remarkable children.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Mr Hunt and Ms Coffey found, Vietnam is full of graceful, generous and charming people. But there is a dark side as well. Take the treatment of children born to Vietnamese mothers and American fathers. Such children were routinely maltreated and often expelled from their homes. When America decided in the 1980s to allow these Amerasians to come to America, Vietnam was happy to see them go. Their story is told by Thomas Bass. From being despised, Amerasians suddenly became the hottest of commodities: a free ticket to America. Many were sold to the highest bidder. With fraud so rampant, American officials became cynical, and deserving cases were shut out. In the end, 20,000 Amerasians and 60,000 purported family members came to America.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a variety of reasons, Utica, a dilapidated industrial city in upstate New York, got a lot of them, and Mr Bass follows the Amerasian story there. There are some happy endings, but many more ambiguous ones. Some have formed gangs; some have gone on welfare. Others are doing better. Local industries see the Amerasians and their families as docile and hard-working and have been willing to hire them. Younger kids are adapting to school. But it is hard to see many of the Amerasians, whose average schooling lasted three years, ever realising the American dream. They are the final casualties of the American war, and a reminder that travelling away from home is the best way to gain a perspective on it.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
