<html><head><title>Sweet Liberty</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl239.jpg"><img src="cs239.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>S<font size=-1>WEET</font> L<font size=-1>IBERTY</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>RAVELS IN </font>I<font size=-1>RISH</font> A<font size=-1>MERICA</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Joseph O'Connor. <br>
<i>Picador; 372 pages; &#163;15.99</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="8bt239.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Award-winning novelist Joe O'Connor's passion for America began during
childhood holidays in the beautiful west of Ireland wilderness of Connemara,
populated exclusively by Gaelic speakers, sheep and, above all, American
tourists. His growing love affair with all things American led to an
extraordinary tour across the United States, to visit the nine different towns,
within nine different states, called Dublin and the great cities and tiny hamlets
in between. Along the way he wittily deconstructs the legends of a whole
pantheon of Irish American heroes, from John F. Kennedy to Billy the Kid, and
explores the deep connections between the most powerful country in the world
and the tiny island nation from which forty-four million Americans claim
descendancy.
<p> His journey begins in Boston, the city the Irish Americans made most profoundly their own and moves on through Dublin, New Hampshire, then the Dublins of Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia, Indiana and Ohio. From Dublin, Georgia he makes a detour to Memphis to answer that most important question: was Elvis really Irish. He continues via Dublin, Texas, Las Vegas and San Francisco to Dublin, California. Interspersed with his travels are vivid accounts of the Irish immigrant experience and a rich exploration of the intertwined roots of American music, from Irish ballads to jazz, country, blues and gospel.</p>
<p> Sweet Liberty is a hilarious, poignant and utterly unforgettable coast-to-coast tour of the United States, a journey which celebrates the breathtaking diversity of the Irish influence on America, uncovers the secret relationship between William Butler Yeats and The Everly Brothers and actually manages to find a town called Dublin, somewhere on the planet, that doesn't have one single pub within its limits. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
