<html><head><title>Searching for strangers</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<h1>Searching for strangers</h1>
<h2>Finding strangeness when you travel is more art than luck</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex229.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Norman Lewis. <br>
 <li><a href="8ex246.html">D<font size=-1>ESERT</font> P<font size=-1>LACES</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Robyn Davidson. <br>
 <li><a href="8ex239.html">S<font size=-1>WEET</font> L<font size=-1>IBERTY</font></a>: T<font size=-1>RAVELS IN </font>I<font size=-1>RISH</font> A<font size=-1>MERICA</font>.&nbsp;  By Joseph O'Connor. <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

<p>NORMAN LEWIS has already proved that he is peerless as a travel writer. The enigmatic smile behind the easy prose, the controlled passion of his observation, the delicious asides have won him a world of readers. In the classic paradox of his genre he goes to the ends of the earth to find people that seldom move, whose culture accrues around them with the slowness and intricacy of coral. "I am looking for the people who have always been there and belong to the places where they live. The others I do not wish to see."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His quest for the indigenous may border on the quixotic in the fast-unravelling world, but this second volume of his autobiography begins just before the second world war when many cultures were still intact and some so beguilingly bizarre or beautiful it is hard to avoid a sense of sadness at the loss of such cherished paradises. He saw it before; we have it after.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the Costa Brava he could gain the trust of the unspoilt fishing village (Farol) by helping people tot up their sums at the village shop and by tracking down the right kind of fishing hooks (the ancient Roman type with no eyes). In the forests just north of Saigon in the era before saturation bombing, "once in a while a boar came trotting down the track, kicking up deep purple butterflies", buffalo worshippers were still around and also the Mois, a supposedly Malayo-Polynesian people who had been there almost as long as the trees themselves. In Laos, the unflinching polygamy of the royal family filled the streets of the capital with princesses all carrying parasols of five tiers. Ah, could we have but seen it. And it is easy to imagine the tall Englishman in Thailand quietly noting down the droll translation of a notice in Thai which was on display during one of their festivals:
<ul><font size=-1>All hat wearing. Brassi&egrave;res also to wear.<br>
All to dance.<br>
Partners to touch. Not walk behind.<br>
Ladies hair curl in permanent way.<br>
Low-caste no umbrella-ing.<br></font></ul>

<br>On the personal front he remains inscrutable: not for him the steaming entrails of selfhood laid out on the page. You learn that his ex-wife had re-married: "I therefore married Lesley, an old friend who had been helping me with my books." They settle in Essex, but their arrival in the early 1960s coincided with the ending of an era. Farmers annihilated weeds, wild plants, thrips, weevils, but also butterflies, moths and bees. Their poisoned corpses wiped out birds and hedgehogs who fed on them. Owls vanished. Swallows ceased to nest. "The year of our arrival the swifts had practically to queue to pass through the gap giving access to their nests in the attic. Three years later none remained. Worst of all the skies of Essex emptied of their larks. "My children..." (children?--if recollection is right, this is the only time they are referred to) "reached their teens before seeing a frog."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But one friendship is confessed--with Oliver Myers, an English archaeologist, whom he met on an Italian train in 1937--a friendship which lasted several decades until Myers's death. The attempts at supernatural communication Mr Lewis then took part in could not be a more powerful demonstration of this sceptic's depth of affection for his lost friend.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He goes to Peru happy to have the likeable Tony Snowdon tag along as his photographer but soon gets padlocked into royal ridiculousness. While purporting to pine for anonymity the photographer's luggage labels gave the game away: Right Honourable the Earl of Snowdon. In Mexico a shaman leads Mr Lewis to the top of the Sierra Madre where the Huichol custom is for the women to dip in the freezing river before dawn to promote sexual coldness, much appreciated by the males. Later the shaman invites Mr Lewis to come on a pilgrimage during which peyote would be hunted with bows and arrows because peyote were once deer who had magically changed themselves into the sacred cactus; the peyote would be prayed to and sung to before being eaten. But the shaman is murdered and Mr Lewis, now back in England, is haunted by the adventure he never took.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the years roll by the stories become sadder, notably when Mr Lewis returns to Farol and sees the municipal car park where all that beauty had been before and, even worse, when he goes to the brothel that is Thailand. On Brazilian Amazonia he highlights the massacres, land thefts and genocide, writing as one lucky to have witnessed an earlier world.</p>
<p><b>Old-age travellers</b>
<br>The search for the altogether "other" can take on a panicky flavour when the travel writer realises that the way of life he or she wishes to explore is on its last legs, as is the case with the Rabari nomads of Rajasthan in India. Robyn Davidson has produced two previous books, a somewhat fetid novel set in the rainforests of Queensland, and a newsworthy account of her travels by camel across the Australian outback. But neither is in the same league as "Desert Places", which is dazzling. Ms Davidson travelled in Rajasthan for months and grew up, quite violently, in the process.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;She starts as a romantic; a dreamer haunted by schlock images of sunsets on rippling desert sands; she ends shriven, with new stature as a person and as a writer. Ms Davidson goes to extraordinary lengths to tag along with the Rabari on their next great move and there is wonderful drollery in the way she muddles through the muddle that is India. When she finally gets what she wants, with the help of a well-connected mentor, Narendra, it is not just the lack of sleep, the mangy goats and sheep on or under her bed, but the loneliness of being unable to communicate that almost drives her mad. She struggles with "Teach Yourself Gujarati", which contains sentences such as: "The lock of your musket is rusty", "You will be hanged tomorrow" and "A sepoy shot himself".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If she stops for even a second in the middle of nowhere she has to cope with the subcontinental stare; as faces instantly cram the windows, the windscreen, poking, tugging, for after all she is an attractive white woman. Someone says: "You have rupees, a jeep, why do you want to live with poor people? Why do you want to walk?" Once she confides to Narendra about her need to be alone. He orders three black goat-hair mats for her to sit on. He himself sits on another mat approximately 15 yards away. A shepherd brings marigolds and strews them about her, backing away. A woman brings incense. Another water. She sits on her mat surrounded by dust, wind, rats, scrawny, tottering sheep, donkeys with ribs like washboards and 15 yards away 50 smiling people are watching with silent respect the white woman being alone.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;During the great trek she escapes from the hot grit and the hour upon hour of boredom waiting to shift camp by reading Proust, entering his cool privileged world. He lay in white sheets; she has women blowing snot, spitting and belching all around her. Men shivering with fever. Baby goats covered in sores drinking from her water pots and urinating on her mats. The air is dust. The horizon promises nothing but dust. "Where was I? Why was I here?"
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet she comes to deeply admire their use of laughter as a survival tactic and the way they always pass on truthful information to other nomads. She develops a particular warmth for them, especially for some of the women and children, but the jeep which she usually tries to avoid using is too much of a temptation to these people, although it does help immeasurably when they have to scout ahead to check the quality of the terrain. It is the same old song: 50% less land for grazing than there was ten years ago. Simply no room left in India and the nomads, despite all their flexibility, pragmatism and skills will be the first to be squeezed out. She arrives in some small and unutterably lovely place on the day the first ugly cement temple opens for celebrations. Once more the unique is being devoured by the homogenous.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In her worst moment she feels everything she is doing is fraudulent and absurd. "I knew nothing about the Rabaris and, even if I did, it would mean nothing to them, make no difference to them. I had understood nothing of where I was. And I would perpetuate the fraudulent by producing yet another useless artefact for western consumption, another bit of noise for a culture drowning in noise--an article for a glossy magazine with beautiful photos of beautiful India, beautiful noble Rabari." Ms Davidson has produced a most distinguished travel book full of a strange, tough beauty; gritty with the struggle to survive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Quite different are the appeals of "Sweet Liberty". The idea of visiting all the places in the United States called Dublin must have got a laugh in the pub. And there is a buoyancy and freshness to Joseph O'Connor's comical investigation of all nine Dublins. He writes with a poetic touch about his childhood holidays in Connemara where he fell in love with American tourists. But nothing he writes about America has the same impermeable sense of place. His American quest, being mad, is what is called a learning experience and his hyperbolic brightness sees him splendidly through the escapade. Needless to say most of the Dublins are duds and about as Irish as a Laotian princess's parasol.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His best moments are <i>en passant</i>. A guard at the Grand Canyon tells him how often people fall in: "I guess people are basically dumb...you gotta hole in the ground, folks are gonna fall in the sucker." Santa Fe is full of goodie-goodie veggies, fainting if you mention booze or fags. There is no Dublin in Tennessee but he does visit Elvis Presley's house, listening to tapes in the same little room where "the King" did his vocal tracks. The hair on the back of his neck does not so much stand up: "it was practically going for a walk round the block". He reacts to pop music with a buff's passion that might alienate the aged; the street beat bounces about in the prose like the songs. But he gets the ramshackle funkiness of it all. Classic travel writers may search out fast-disappearing strangeness, but Mr O'Connor finds a touching strangeness in the raw and the new.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
