<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Norman Lewis. <br>
<i>Jonathan Cape; 240 pages; &#163;18.99.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="8bt229.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
JACKDAW CAKE, Norman Lewis's first volume of autobiography, was
published to enormous acclaim. 'As a witness to his own times--the good, the
bad and the ludicrous--he is unmatched,' said the Sunday Times, while
Auberon Waugh hailed him as 'one of the best writers and most unusual
characters of our day'.
<p>Now Norman Lewis has written a further collection of memoirs that is a rich and funny and fascinating as the first. A wartime career in the Intelligence Corps, bachelor life in a crumbling fortress off the Pembrokeshire coast, reminiscences of Ian Fleming and Hemingway, travels in Guatemala, Vietnam, Burma, Spain, Cuba, Sicily, Brazil, Peru and India, rural seclusion in Essex-- Lewis describes them all with his characteristic humour, eye for detail and delight in the absurd. As Anthony Burgess said of Lewis's last book, An Empire of the East, 'His prose is almost edible...he is writing better than ever.' </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
