<html><head><title>Here, there, everywhere</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Fiction in France</b></p>
<h2>Here, there, everywhere</h2><ul><li><a href="3ex41.html">L<font size=-1>E</font> T<font size=-1>ESTAMENT</font> F<font size=-1>RANCAIS</font></a>&nbsp; By Andre&iuml; Makine.<br>
<li><a href="3ex40.html">L<font size=-1>A</font> Q<font size=-1>UARANTAINE</font></a>&nbsp; By J.M.G. Le Cl&eacute;zio.<br>
<li><a href="3ex42.html"></i>L'I<font size=-1>LE ET UNE </font>N<font size=-1>UIT</font></a>&nbsp; By Daniel Maximin.<br>
<li><a href="3ex43.html">I<font size=-1>CI</font></a>&nbsp; By Nathalie Sarraute.<br>
<li><a href="3ex44.html">L'E<font size=-1>NIGME</font></a>&nbsp; By Rezvani.<br>
</ul><ul></ul>



HE winter's literary phenomenon in France is Andre&iuml; Makine's "Le Testament Fran&ccedil;ais". A bolt from beyond the Urals, this novel by an almost unknown writer who came to France from Siberia eight years ago won both of the most prestigious French fiction prizes at the end of last year, the Prix Goncourt and the Prix M&eacute;dicis. Although the M&eacute;dicis was shared with "La Langue Maternelle" (a similar book by an exile from Greece), "doing the double" was until now unheard of.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Makine has ruffled the smooth surface of French publishing in other ways. The big Paris houses expect to get the big literary prizes in rotation, much as the large French banks once each took their agreed ration of the government-bond business. The Goncourt almost invariably goes to one or other of "Galligrasseuil", the collective name for the Paris "Big Three": Gallimard, Grasset and Le Seuil. But this time for once the Goncourt and the M&eacute;dicis both went not just to an unknown author but to a pippin-sized offshoot of Gallimard: Mercure de France.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The shock of all this to the tight world of French literary prizes should not obscure the fact that Mr Makine has written an agreeable novel, or rather an agreeable book that hovers between fiction and family biography. "Le Testament Fran&ccedil;ais"is the story of the narrator's French grandmother in self-chosen Siberian exile. The background is Russia's civil war, Stalinism and France, an ever-distant promised land imagined as a vivid place of sensuality and revolt, "where the cobbles of the streets had the extraordinary capacity to rise up as ramparts". This is an old-fashioned, linear narrative which tells a classic tale of personal growth. Its weeks high on the best-seller list (see box on next page) may be due as much to the story of the book as to the story in the book: a "Goncourt of the steppes" by a poor, solitary Russian, ignored by the big boys and now loaded with success.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"La Quarantaine" by J.M.G. Le Cl&eacute;zio, one of the dominant figures of contemporary French fiction, is set on Flat Island, a quarantine station for passengers on the way to Mauritius. The narrator tells of his grandfather L&eacute;on's quarantine, his fight for survival, his isolation on this island-cemetery, and also of the young L&eacute;on's awakening to love with Suryavati, a young woman born on the island. L&eacute;on himself then becomes a narrator, deciding to break with his biological family and join the family he has chosen for himself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His story frames that of Ananta, Suryavati's mother, who has come down the Ganges to end up on this island in the Indian Ocean. In some way each narrator finds a meaning to life through telling the story of an unknown, a real or imagined ancestor to whom he lends his voice.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Daniel Maximin is one of the new generation of French-speaking authors from the Caribbean, where French writing seems to be finding exciting new resources. In "L'Ile et une Nuit" a hurricane makes its way towards the home of a young Caribbean woman, Marie-Gabriel, who must deal with it as she can. Though put together with strict respect for the unities--time, place and action--this novel is poetically written and has a sensual intensity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An island, metaphorically, is somewhere you cannot run away from and where you have to face whatever is coming. For Marie-Gabriel, who appears in turn as character and narrator, the hurricane is a test. She must decide about what is essential: her life, her love. Gradually her speech sheds its everyday artifice and becomes an expression of naked desire. Measuring herself against the elements, Marie-Gabriel finds her mark, and her voice.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With "Ici", by contrast, readers are back with the severe charms of the <i>nouveau roman</i>. Nathalie Sarraute is one of the grand figures of this now venerable genre of semi-philosophical fiction in which nothing much happens but a vast amount is noticed, imagined or thought about. The crux of Ms Sarraute's new book is what gets said, its source, its moment of articulation. "Ici" (Here) is where words and phrases are uttered: not the bed or the bar but somewhere far more cerebral. A name on the tip of the tongue, a polite phrase, a stupid question, a silence even. Where do they come from? These seeming commonplaces she makes abstract and unfamiliar, writing, in her words, "to show what is there" in speech. On such questions Ms Sarraute focuses much analytical subtlety but, true to the rules of philosophical fiction, gives nothing so mundane as answers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"L'Enigme" is different again. The Knigh (sic) family's yacht, adrift at sea, is the stage for a literary mystery. The members of this singular family--poets, novelists and philosophers--have come together for a reading cruise. Suddenly, silence. The family has gone. The texts break off. What happened? That is the enigma for the novel's three sleuths: an academic theorist versed in the Knigh family's works; a poetical criminologist, skilled at literary clues and motives; and a marine investigator, who understands the sea's emotional power. The half-finished works on the deck of this intellectual <i>Marie Celeste </i>are evidence for a clever, crossword-like inquiry.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Russia and France, two islands, a yacht, even Ms Sarraute's "here" are all places, some real, some imagined. But does anything happen in them? Unenthusiasts for recent French fiction complain that too many novels written in France have no real action or subject-matter: they are not about anything. Mr Makine's book aside, this list might seem to bear them out. But the tradition of the reflective novel is an old one in France, much older than the <i>nouveau roman</i>. The theatre of the mind is treated there as a perfectly normal subject of fiction. In the proper hands--and these authors are each in their way strong writers--it can even be readable.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
