<html><head><title>Economic theory</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<h2>Economic theory</h2>
<p><b>This month's "Books in Brief" looks at the frontiers of economic theory where orthodox views are under attack</b></p><ul><li><a href="#1">M<font size=-1>YTH</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> M<font size=-1>EASUREMENT</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> N<font size=-1>EW</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMICS</font> <font size=-1>OF THE</font> M<font size=-1>INIMUM</font> W<font size=-1>AGE</font>&nbsp; By David Card and Alan Krueger.<br>
<li><a href="#2"></i>T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>AGE</font> C<font size=-1>URVE</font></a>&nbsp; By David Blanchflower and Andrew Oswald.<br>
<li><a href="#3">E<font size=-1>CONOMIC</font> G<font size=-1>ROWTH</font></a>&nbsp; By Robert Barro and Xavier Sala-i-Martin.<br>
<li><a href="#4">W<font size=-1>HITHER</font> S<font size=-1>OCIALISM?</font> </a>&nbsp; By Joseph Stiglitz.<br>
</ul>

</td></tr></table>
<a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>M<font size=-1>YTH</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> M<font size=-1>EASUREMENT</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>HE</font> N<font size=-1>EW</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMICS</font> <font size=-1>OF THE</font> M<font size=-1>INIMUM</font> W<font size=-1>AGE</font><br>
By David Card and Alan Krueger.<br>
<i> $29.95 and</i> <i>&#163;25.</i><br>
<a href="3ex47.html">Extract</a> - <a href="3jb47.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="3bt47.html">Biography</a><br>
</i>
</td></tr></table>
<a name="2"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left></i>T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>AGE</font> C<font size=-1>URVE</font><br>
By David Blanchflower and Andrew Oswald.<br>
<i>MIT Press</i>;<i> 495 pages</i>;<i> $39.95 and &#163;29.95</i><br>
<a href="3ex46.html">Extract</a> - <a href="3jb46.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="3bt46.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>WHAT sets pay levels? Why do people who want jobs not find them? Few markets match the labour market in complexity and importance. Frustratingly, few markets are so poorly understood. Standard economic theory treats the labour market like any other: the demand curve for labour slopes down, its supply curve slopes up and where they cross is the market-clearing or "equilibrium" wage at which anyone wanting work gets hired. Pushing up wages artificially--a minimum wage, for example--must, in this framework, leave some people without jobs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These two books dispute the standard theory, and in a novel way. Economists tend to posit theories first and test them later. These authors gather evidence that seems to puncture conventional wisdom and then suggest alternative theories.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Messrs Card and Krueger look at minimum wages. Their evidence, they believe, shows that raising minimum wage rates need not lower employment and may even at times increase it. Raising minimum wages, they add, can reduce inequality, by raising the relative pay of low-paid workers. This is a contentious topic and the Card-Krueger argument has caused glee on the left, horror on the right. But reactions on each side are probably overdone. Colleagues have questioned the methods and scope of the Card-Krueger findings. Nor is their suggestion that at the low end firms may be able to push wages below market levels likely to win universal approval.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The Wage Curve" is more ambitious. Its authors aim to establish a negative correlation between wage rates and unemployment that does not change with time or place: be she American, British or C&ocirc;te D'Ivoirean, they argue, someone hired in a region of high unemployment must earn less than an identical worker in an area of low unemployment. Their finding, if correct, is more startling than it sounds. The standard theory, assuming flexible wages, predicts that the labour market will clear at the appropriate wage level. But the world works differently, according to the authors: where unemployment is high, wages are simply stuck at low levels. The book's sheer quantity of observation makes it difficult to deny that high unemployment means low, not falling, wages. The hard question is why.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Messrs Blanchflower and Oswald deny that their curve is a mislabelled variant of the Phillips Curve (which claimed a negative link between wage inflation and joblessness). Nor, they say, does it reflect movements along an upward-sloping labour supply curve. Instead they propose alternatives including a "bargaining" model, in which high unemployment weakens workers' bargaining power and so depresses wages.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Blanchflower-Oswald findings pose a problem for the standard model. On the other hand, their alternatives are not wholly convincing either. Labour ececonomics is in ferment. This book is a good point of entry to the argument.</td></tr></table>
<a name="3"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>E<font size=-1>CONOMIC</font> G<font size=-1>ROWTH</font><br>
By Robert Barro and Xavier Sala-i-Martin.<br>
<i>McGraw Hill; 539 pages; $59 and &#163;29.95</i><br>
<a href="3ex45.html">Extract</a> - <a href="3jb45.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="3bt45.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>WHY do economies grow? What fixes the long-run rate of growth? These are some of the simplest, but also hardest, questions in economics. Growth or lack of it has huge consequences for a country's citizens. But for various reasons, growth theory has had long fallow patches. Happily, this is changing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1956 Robert Solow developed what became the standard neo-classical model of economic growth. Countries grow, on this theory, by accumulating labour and capital. Adding either obeys diminishing returns: the more labour or capital you already have, the more you need for a further given jump in output. One consequence is that an economy with less capital ought to outgrow one with more. Generally, they do. Another is that growth should eventually drop to zero. Awkwardly, it stays positive. To save the theory, long-run growth was explained by an outside factor, technical innovation, which is not in the growth function itself--hence the label "exogenous" for the Solow family of models.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Partial as it was, the Solow model won wide acceptance and growth theory slumbered for three decades. Then came two changes. One was an attempt to add technical change and other factors to labour and capital within the growth function so that the model might predict long-run growth without leaning on outside "residuals"--the so-called "endogenous" approach. The other was a huge number of factual studies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The authors explain all this and more with admirable clarity (and much demanding maths) in the first modern textbook devoted to growth theory. The main theories are examined. The stress throughout is on linking theory to fact. One of three chapters on empirical work suggests how much each of several possible factors would be needed to explain differing international growth rates--not an explanation itself, but an indispensable set of empirical benchmarks.
</td></tr></table>
<a name="4"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>W<font size=-1>HITHER</font> S<font size=-1>OCIALISM?</font> <br>
By Joseph Stiglitz.<br>
<i>MIT Press; 352 pages; $32.95 and &#163;27.50</i><br>
<a href="3ex51.html">Extract</a> - <a href="3jb51.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="3bt51.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>THIS title causes needless confusion: for the author, as for most people, outdated socialism is going nowhere. Mr Stiglitz writes, in addition, stodgy prose. Yet "Whither Socialism?" is to be recommended. It offers deep new thinking on a big subject: the role of the state. It is rigorous and accessible, a rare combination.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The book sets out to examine how the countries of Eastern Europe should reform their economies. The advice comes late, but this hardly matters. The book's strength is its criticism of standard accounts of market economics. Mr Stiglitz deals briskly with the empty dispute about whether there can exist a "middle way" between socialism and capitalism. Obviously there can, since every successful modern industrial economy has taken one. The pertinent, forward-looking question is how far, and in which ways, the state should now intervene.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The balance between state and market which Mr Stiglitz proposes will not seriously distress free-market liberals. But the reasons he advances are interestingly different from the common "markets-know-best" ones. "Whither Socialism?" makes good use of the best and newest work in several branches of economics, but pays particular attention to the economics of information. Gathering information is costly, which causes frictions in the smoothness with which markets adjust. Developing this insight, Mr Stiglitz sheds exciting light on what is perhaps the key issue of political economy in our time.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
