<html><head><title>Whither Socialism? </title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl51.jpg"><img src="cs51.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>W<font size=-1>HITHER</font> S<font size=-1>OCIALISM?</font> <br></h2>
<p>By Joseph Stiglitz.<br>
<i>MIT Press; 352 pages; $32.95 and &#163;27.50</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="3bt51.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p><p>Whither Socialism?</p>
</p><p>Joseph E Stiglitz
</p><p>The rapid collapse of socialism has raised new economic policy questions and revived old theoretical issues. In this book Joseph Stiglitz explains how the neoclassical, or Walraisian, model (the formal articulation of Adam Smith's invisible hand), which has dominated economic thought over the past half- century, not only may have provided an inadequate framework for understanding market economies but may have wrongly encouraged the belief that market socialism could work. Stiglitz proposes an alternative model, based on the economics of information, that offers greater theoretical insight into the workings of a market economy, further understanding into the failures of socialism, including market socialism, and clearer guidance for the setting of policy in transitional economies.
</p><p>Stiglitz sees the critical failing in the standard neoclassical model, and in models of market socialism derived from it, to be its assumptions concerning information, particularly its failure to consider the problems that arise from lack of perfect information and from costs of acquiring information. Going beyond the standard criticism centering on incentives and property rights, he also identifies problems arising from assumptions concerning completeness of markets and from the failure to focus on innovation. Stiglitz argues that not only has the existing paradigm failed to provide much guidance on the vital question of the choice of economic systems, the advice it has provided is often misleading. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
