<html><head><title>The old new right</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h1>The old new right</h1>
<p><b>For better or worse, the world has been changed by a batch of New York liberals transmogrified into neo-conservatives</b></p><ul> <li><a href="9ex285.html">W<font size=-1>HAT</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> D<font size=-1>O</font> A<font size=-1>BOUT</font>.</a>&nbsp; .. Edited by Neal Kozodoy. <br>
 <li><a href="9ex279.html">N<font size=-1>EO-</font>C<font size=-1>ONSERVATISM</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> A<font size=-1>UTOBIOGRAPHY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>AN</font> I<font size=-1>DEA</font>.&nbsp;  By Irving Kristol. <br>
 <li><a href="9ex259.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>SSENTIAL</font> N<font size=-1>EO</font>-C<font size=-1>ONSERVATIVE</font> R<font size=-1>EADER</font>.</a>&nbsp;  Edited by Mark Gerson. <br>
 <li>B<font size=-1>ACKWARD AND</font> U<font size=-1>PWARD</a>:</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> N<font size=-1>EW</font> C<font size=-1>ONSERVATIVE</font> W<font size=-1>RITING</font>.&nbsp;  Edited by David Brooks.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Vintage; 330 pages; $13</i> <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

<p>IN THE autumn of 1965 a group of intellectuals, most of them New Yorkers, launched a new journal called the<i> Public Interest</i>. Most of the group at the time would have called themselves liberals: Irving Kristol, Daniel Patrick Moynihan, Daniel Bell, Seymour Martin Lipset and James Q. Wilson among them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By the magazine's tenth anniversary, Mr Moynihan was admitting that its adversaries now called its editors and writers not liberals, but "neo-conservatives". The senator himself has now moved closer to a liberal position again. Others, especially Irving Kristol, have become avowed conservatives, <i>tout court</i>. But what matters more than the intellectual trajectory of individuals is that the <i>Public Interest</i> suddenly made it respectable (for the first time since the appearance of the <i>New Republic</i> in 1914, it could be argued) for a New York intellectual to be something other than on the left.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Together with <i>Commentary</i> magazine, which started to move in a similar direction at about the same time, the<i> Public Interest</i> helped to change the political orientation of a large part of the American intelligentsia. That transformation has had vast consequences not just for the United States but for the world. Although, of course, a handful of intellectuals had this mighty influence only because millions of thoughtful Americans did not like what they saw when they looked at the effects of the liberal policies that were collectively intended to produce a "Great Society".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Liberal" in the United States had become a euphemism for "left" or "social democrat". The instinct of American liberals, in opposition under Eisenhower, and in government under Kennedy and Johnson, was invariably to send for government. You identified a problem. You called in the social scientists to propose a programme to solve it. You called on the government to finance the programme: and the desired outcome would result.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What the neo-conservatives began to say was exactly the opposite of this. There probably wasn't a problem. If there was, social scientists probably misunderstood it. It was probably insoluble, and in any case efforts on the part of government to solve it would probably make it worse. That is a caricature: but it expresses the essential nature of the intellectual revolution launched by the neo-conservatives, and what made a difference was that in general they were in the habit of making their case with intellectual rigour.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet in a collection of essays, "What to Do About...", Norman Podhoretz, the editor of <i>Commentary</i> who took it to the right, reminds his readers that almost 50 years ago his own teacher, Lionel Trilling, had said that liberalism was "not only the dominant but even the sole intellectual tradition" in America.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Podhoretz reversed Trilling's proposition. Conservatism would now be the dominant, if not the sole intellectual tradition--were it not for the malign, vestigial hold on cultural institutions of "an intellectually necrotic class that is less and less able to provide a defence of its own ideas that seems persuasive to anyone but itself".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the past 20 years the neo-conservatives, helped by skilfully targeted foundation funding, have begun to create cultural institutions of their own: foundations, publishing houses, magazines, radio and television talk shows, journals, research institutes, think-tanks, some of them--like the Heritage Foundation, the American Enterprise Institute, or the editorial page of the <i>Wall Street Journal</i>--serious rivals to their once all-powerful liberal competitors. This has become, as Sidney Blumenthal put it, a "counter-establishment".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Will success spoil American conservatism? A trawl through some recent books suggests that the conservative intellectual movement may be passing from its Golden to its Silver Age. Certainly neo-conservatism, now big business in publishing, seems to be showing a tendency to look back to past triumphs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One publisher, for example, has brought out Irving Kristol's essays as "Neo-Conservatism: The Autobiography of an Idea". (This identification of author and idea, by the way, is not as vainglorious as might be imagined: Mr Kristol's friend Daniel Bell once said, "that isn't neo-conservatism, that's just Irving!")
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another publisher has come out with "The Essential Neo-Conservative Reader", a compendium of the movement's sacred texts. And "What to Do About..." has essays from <i>Commentary</i> offering solutions by eminent neo-conservative pundits on topics such as abortion, education, health care, welfare and the like, predicated on the assumption that Newt Gingrich would be running America by now.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These are on the whole impressive volumes. Irving Kristol's autobiographical memoir is a fascinating account of an intellectual journey from left to right. "The Essential Neo-Conservative Reader" is a reminder that neo-conservatives may know one another, but that does not mean they agree. Compare, for instance, two essays in "The Essential Neo-Conservative Reader": Mr Podhoretz's "My Negro Problem--and Ours", with its conclusion that "the wholesale merging of the two races is the most desirable alternative", with the paper from Mr Moynihan, "The Negro Family: the Case for National Action", which, ironically, makes a classical liberal case for massive government action to restore the African-American family structure.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other memorable milestones are Mr Moynihan's ringing <font size=-1>UN</font> speech denouncing the "Zionism is racism" resolution (1975), and the pioneering essay by Richard John Neuhaus and Peter Berger, "To Empower People" (1976), which restates the importance of "mediating structures"--neighbourhood, family, church--in resolving the dilemma of the welfare state: people want the benefits without the big taxes needed to deliver them. Both of these are also in "The Essential Neo-Conservative Reader".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;You do not have to agree with all, or any, of these essays to be convinced that the neo-conservatives (as a loose, often divided group) did bring formidable intellectual energy to attacking some of modern society's most intractable problems. In a brief but penetrating foreword to "The Essential Neo-Conservative Reader", a criminologist, James Q. Wilson, explains how neo-conservatism evolved. At first, he says, neo-conservatives wrote "in reaction to the less plausible ideas of the Great Society". Since then, he notes, in the absence of an activist government, neo-conservatives have had even less to agree about.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He does identify some common ground. One is the neo-conservative belief in the Law of Unintended Consequences; the conviction, that is, that things in general, and government policies in particular, never work out quite the way they are meant to. Another is the idea that neo-conservatives (by implication, unlike liberal intellectuals) share the general convictions of the average American.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Running an eye farther along the shelf, you are reminded that not all neo-conservatives share this populist instinct. Just like "liberalism" a generation ago, "neo-conservatism" is in danger of becoming a brand image used to market some pretty cliquish products. For example, a volume called "Backward and Upward: The New Conservative Writing", edited by David Brooks, formerly of the editorial page of the<i> Wall Street Journal</i>, contains essays of varying quality on such subjects as the conservative attitude to dogs, the Washington property market, childbirth, child abuse and other columnists' favourites.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One does not have to be a sockless populist to notice that several of these essays are written by the children of men who spoke out as conservatives when that was a brave thing to do: son of Buckley, son of Kristol, son of Podhoretz. Many of these papers, too, spend a lot of energy on denigrating the rival brand, often in ways that, if put out on television, might violate the advertising code of conduct. William Kristol, for example, unsubtly compares liberals to communists in the Soviet Union.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The sons of neo-conservatives call themselves conservatives. Neo-conservatism was the philosophy of a transitional generation, and the time has come, perhaps, for an audit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Several of the neo-conservative shibboleths belong in the debit column. Neo-conservatives bang on about a number of ideas which do not, perhaps, bear close examination. The Law of Unintended Consequences is not, after all, a scientific law, merely a clever name for a prejudice against government intervention. The End of Ideology means little more than "the end of all ideologies except this one". Another favourite neo-conservative slogan is "the New Class". Listed as members of the "New Class" by Irving Kristol are "...city planners, social workers, educators, criminologists, sociologists, public health doctors, and so on": a rather precise description, as it happens, of the founders of the <i>Public Interest</i>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The neo-conservatives can also be faulted for some polemical journalism dressed up as scholarship. They show, in particular, little awareness of the contradiction between the libertarian/free market stream of right-wing thinking and the authoritarian/traditionalist stream. More serious is the contradiction between their optimism about the United States when comparing it with other countries and their pessimism when considering the United States by itself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And yet, this remarkable band of publicists did change the world. For what they did understand, to borrow the title of a very different conservative intellectual (the southern reactionary Richard Weaver), is that ideas have consequences. For better or worse, the ideas of the New York neo-conservatives have had consequences which include the decline of liberalism, the rehabilitation of capitalism and the respectability among intellectuals everywhere of the idea that socialism is dead. Not bad for a few founders of little magazines.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
