<html><head><title>The Essential Neo-Conservative Reader.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl259.jpg"><img src="cs259.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>SSENTIAL</font> N<font size=-1>EO</font>-C<font size=-1>ONSERVATIVE</font> R<font size=-1>EADER</font>.<br></h2>
<p> Edited by Mark Gerson. <br>
<i>Addison-Wesley; 467 pages; $27.50</i>.<br>
</p><br>
<a href="9bt259.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
The Essential Neoconservative Reader captures the drama and historical
importance of neoconservatism's rise from 1965 to the present, by collecting
influential essays by its most noted figures--among them Irving Kristol,
Norman Podhoretz, Nathan Glazer, Daniel Patrick Moynihan, Gertrude
Himmelfarb, and James Q. Wilson.
<p>The word "neoconservative" was first used as a term of derision for disgruntled ex-liberals of the 1960s. Perhaps because of this, there has never been a central credo or organization unifying neoconservatism as a movement. With this collection, however, neoconservatism is cast in a new light, portrayed as a comprehensive outlook on economics, politics, society, and culture linked by common principles and a distinctive vision.</p>
<p>This anthology captures in the leading neoconservatives' own words the essence of this vision. Ranging in scope from the crisis in the black family to liberals' failure to grasp the importance of religion in America, some of the famous essays included here are Norman Podhoretz's "My Negro Problem--and Ours"; Irving Kristol's "Pornography, Obscenity, and the Case for Censorship"; Nathan Glazer's "The Campus Crucible"; and Daniel Patrick Moynihan's now legendary response to Idi Amin's infamous "Zionism Is Racism" resolution.</p>
<p>With a foreword by James Q. Wilson, this new anthology is both stimulating reading and a valuable historical compendium, destined to become the sourcebook for the history and ideas of neoconservatism. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
