<html><head><title>Downgraded</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Mexican economy</b></p>
<h2>Downgraded</h2><ul><li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>EXICAN</font> S<font size=-1>HOCK</font></a>&nbsp; By Jorge Castaeda.<br>
</ul>



<p>THERE are few more tragically compelling stories than the rise and abrupt fall of Carlos Salinas. Before he stepped down as Mexico's president in 1994 he had dominated the country's political stage with bold policies to open up a sheltered economy, culminating with the North American Free Trade Agreement (<font size=-1>NAFTA</font>). Then a bungled devaluation of the peso by his successors ruthlessly exposed the weaknesses in his legacy, and had central bankers fearing, briefly, for the stability of the world financial system. The United States stepped in, organising a $40 billion loan to bail Mexico out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Today Mexico is suffering an economic slump, high unemployment and banking troubles. Its stability is threatened by political violence and drug trafficking. Mr Salinas himself is in exile as almost a fugitive, and prosecutors investigating cases of murder and embezzlement are questioning his jailed brother.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Officials in both Mexico and the United States think the tardiness of the devaluation, and political shocks, including assassinations and the Zapatista rebellion in Chiapas in 1994, go far towards explaining Mr Salinas's failures. They are confident that the Mexican economy will swiftly recover as Ernesto Zedillo, Mr Salinas's successor, persists with market-based economic policies (as the terms of the bailout require).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Jorge Castaeda, a Mexican political scientist, disagrees. In this collection of essays, he argues that Mr Salinas's policies were doomed to fail--and so is the system of benevolent despotism that has kept the Institutional Revolutionary Party (<font size=-1>PRI</font>) in power for almost 70 years. The ex-president's liberal trade policies, and his obsessive search for foreign capital through <font size=-1>NAFTA</font>, are seen by Mr Castaeda as improvisations to maintain an over-valued exchange rate in order to placate Mexico's fractious middle class with cheap imported luxury goods. And he sees the shocks that rocked the Salinas regime in its final year as self-inflicted. The government, he says, swept away many of the <font size=-1>PRI</font>'s proven procedures for the settlement of conflicts among the political elite without replacing them with the modern representative democracy that Mexico needs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Castaeda's suggested alternatives to Mr Salinas's economic policies are half-baked, which is a pity because he is right about several important things. The failure of free-market policies to deliver much growth in Mexico (despite huge inflows of foreign money) before the devaluation should indeed worry policy-makers in Washington as much as it does those in Mexico city. So should the inequalities that persist in Latin America, and that Mr Castaeda thinks threaten the region's democracies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This study's conclusion is gloomy: with its weak, divided opposition Mexico is condemned to a slow decline of the existing system, accompanied by rising crime. Perhaps, but further instability could yet force change.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
