<html><head><title>A good likeness</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Charles Dodgson's alter ego</b></p>
<h2>A good likeness</h2><ul> <li><a href="9ex268.html">L<font size=-1>EWIS</font> C<font size=-1>ARROLL</a>:</font> <font size=-1>A</font> P<font size=-1>ORTRAIT</font> <font size=-1>WITH</font> B<font size=-1>ACKGROUND</font>.&nbsp;  By Donald Thomas. <br>
</ul>

<p>AFTER the compendious biography published last year by the Carroll authority, Morton Cohen, and another this summer by Michael Bakewell, readers might be forgiven for wondering--why another? And yet it could be argued that Lewis Carroll, or rather Charles Dodgson, was so odd a fish that the masses of material surrounding him--the thousands of letters, the nine volumes of diaries and scores of reminiscences--warrant several trawls.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Donald Thomas contends that Dodgson "is one of those figures who appear most clearly when seen against a background of the years through which he lived"--hence his title. This could probably be said of anybody, but it has the merit of letting the biographer off the psychological hook, which in Dodgson's case is perhaps best left to the men in white coats.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Here was a man who took train journeys with games and puzzles to tempt chance-met ten-year-olds into conversation, and who brought safety pins to the beach to help them pin up their little skirts. At the end of his summers, he would make lists of his conquests, entering their names and ages and birthdays; he would beg kisses, hold hands, and send flirtatious letters with teasing threats of a good spanking. Any modern parent would have turned him in. But our age is at once too sophisticated and too crude.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dodgson was the soul of correctness, fondly recalled by his Beatrices and Violets as a fascinating and wholly unembarrassing friend. No child was ever coerced. Chaperones were always invited. Principle and religion governed his life, and he outdid even Mrs Grundy in spotting "coarseness". When he protested to the actress Ellen Terry that some stage business of hers had shocked his small companion, she retorted that she thought he only brought "nice" girls to the theatre.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In order to avoid the psychiatrist's chair, Morton Cohen was inclined to find Dodgson a pedestal instead. There he stands a little unconvincingly, a tragic figure burdened with a guilt he could neither name nor understand. Donald Thomas is cooler. He is less interested in Dodgson's paedophilia than in its special Victorian flavour: both innocent and coy, robust and sentimental, prudish and prurient.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Inevitably, this biography often coincides with Mr Cohen's, down to the same quotations and anecdotes (though, oddly, Mr Thomas does not mention the earlier book). But it makes a real contribution in regrouping much of the material, making connections, opening it up. Dodgson's theatre-going is well known, but Mr Thomas threads his way through the West End streets, thick with whores, whose greeting, incidentally, was "Hello Charlie". He was a serious photographer, but Mr Thomas recalls that he shared the new art with the porn merchants whose shops he passed by.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This pervasive sense of contextual irony in Dodgson's life saves Mr Thomas's story from chronological fatigue. Towards the end he connects Mrs Grundy with an unwitting ally, Professor Krafft-Ebing, the exponent of the <i>fin-de-si&egrave;cle</i> science of sexual pathology. Society was becoming more knowing, and Dodgson's innocence more watchful. The celebration of Lewis Carroll by the French Surrealists, described in a fascinating chapter on his posthumous reputation, is somehow a fitting conclusion to the bizarre life of Charles Dodgson.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
