<html><head><title>Accounting for Growth.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl269.jpg"><img src="cs269.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>A<font size=-1>CCOUNTING</font> <font size=-1>FOR</font> G<font size=-1>ROWTH</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Terry Smith. <br>
<i>Century Ltd; 216 pages; &#163;14.99</i> <br>
</p><br>
<a href="9bt269.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
The first edition of Accounting for Growth was published in 1992. Unusually
for a book on accounting, it made the bestseller lists and was engulfed in
controversy. It examined whether much of the apparently good corporate
performance of the 1980s was in fact the result of accounting sleight of hand,
and analysed twelve different techniques of 'creative accounting'.
<p>Each of the techniques was illustrated with extracts from the accounts of public companies, enabling readers to perform their own analysis. The protests from some of the companies identified led to Terry Smith's dismissal from his post as Head of UK Company Research with UBS Phillips and Drew.</p>
<p>Since that date the work of the Accounting Standards Board has closed the door on some of these methods, but creative techniques have been developed. This new edition, completely revised and with eight new chapters, looks at events since 1992 and gives readers an up to date guide to surviving as investors in the accounting jungle. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
