<html><head><title>Of money, men and markets</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr8.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h2>Of money, men and markets</h2>

<p><b>The world of finance is full of complex ratios, complex structures and complex characters. All are hard to interpret</b></p><ul> <li><a href="#1">A<font size=-1>CCOUNTING</font> <font size=-1>FOR</font> G<font size=-1>ROWTH</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Terry Smith. <br>
 <li><a href="#2">I<font size=-1>NSTITUTIONAL</font> S<font size=-1>HAREHOLDERS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> C<font size=-1>ORPORATE</font> G<font size=-1>OVERNANCE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By G.P. Stapleton. <br>
 <li><a href="#3">L<font size=-1>EO</font> M<font size=-1>ELAMED</font></a>: E<font size=-1>SCAPE</font> T<font size=-1>O</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> F<font size=-1>UTURES</font>.&nbsp;  By Leo Melamed with Bob Tamarkin. <br>
 <li><a href="#4">B<font size=-1>UFFETT</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>AKING</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>AN</font> A<font size=-1>MERICAN</font> C<font size=-1>APITALIST</font>.&nbsp;  By Roger Lowenstein. <br>
</ul>

</td></tr></table>
<a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>A<font size=-1>CCOUNTING</font> <font size=-1>FOR</font> G<font size=-1>ROWTH</font>.<br>
 By Terry Smith. <br>
<i>Century Ltd; 216 pages; &#163;14.99</i> <br>
<a href="9ex269.html">Extract</a> - <a href="9jb269.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="9bt269.html">Biography</a><br>

<p>DAZED by depreciation? Perplexed by provisions? Then this guide, recently published in a revised second edition, is for you. In it, Terry Smith analyses in a concise and straightforward manner the ways in which British companies use "creative" accounting techniques. The first edition of the book, published in 1992, caused the heads of several big blue-chip firms cited in it to lose their tempers--and Mr Smith to lose his job as an analyst at a leading stockbroker in London. The latest version is unlikely to endear him to <font size=-1>UK</font> plc either.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unrepentant, Mr Smith argues that although new accounting standards in recent years have made it somewhat harder for companies to cook their accounts, there are still enough legal leftovers (and new ones appearing) to enable finance directors to "simmer" them. Among other things, he neatly dissects lawful but potentially misleading practices, such as using restructuring provisions to improve the appearance of a company's cashflow, and points to anomalies, such as the lack of a consistent standard for valuing brands. Hanson, Trafalgar House and <font size=-1>BTR</font> are among the firms whose accounts are shaken through his sieve.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are flaws in Mr Smith's approach. For instance, he states the obvious when he tells investors always to read the small print in company accounts and not to rely on a single financial ratio when assessing a firm's value. But this is nit-picking. His book is a boon for investors and a bane for bosses with something to hide.
</td></tr></table>
<a name="2"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>I<font size=-1>NSTITUTIONAL</font> S<font size=-1>HAREHOLDERS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> C<font size=-1>ORPORATE</font> G<font size=-1>OVERNANCE</font>.<br>
 By G.P. Stapleton. <br>
<i>Clarendon Press; 376 pages; &#163;50</i><br>
<a href="9ex275.html">Extract</a> - <a href="9jb275.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="9bt275.html">Biography</a><br>

<p>IN EXAMINING the powers of institutional investors in Australia and Britain, this lecturer in law at Melbourne University comes up with some modest but interesting ideas to make companies more accountable to their shareholders. He persuasively argues, for instance, that the listing rules of the London and the Australian stock exchanges should require all directors (ie, executive as well as non-executive ones) to be subject to retirement and re-election by rotation at least every three years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As provocatively, he also recommends that the rules of the two exchanges be amended to empower three-quarters of the co-directors to dismiss the directors of a listed company. Provisions against such sackings, he says, are inappropriate "given that it is now recognised widely that an important function of the board is to monitor--and thus, by implication, to make any necessary changes to the composition of--the executive management (which includes executive directors)". But, in the light of recent American regulatory experience, he is dubious about calls from the British Labour Party for shareholder voting by the trustees (or fund managers) of pension funds to be made compulsory.
</td></tr></table>
<a name="3"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>L<font size=-1>EO</font> M<font size=-1>ELAMED</font>:<br> E<font size=-1>SCAPE</font> T<font size=-1>O</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> F<font size=-1>UTURES</font>.<br>
 By Leo Melamed with Bob Tamarkin. <br>
<i>John Wiley &amp; Sons; 472 pages; $27.95 and &#163;17.95</i><br>
<a href="9ex270.html">Extract</a> - <a href="9jb270.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="9bt270.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>"WHILE Churchill might quote Disraeli...and John Kennedy might quote Tennyson, Leo Melamed quotes...Leo Melamed". Thus the chairman of a financial symposium in 1988 introducing the man who considers himself the progenitor of the world's financial futures markets. Mr Melamed has many qualities, but modesty is not one of them, as this autobiography demonstrates. Nor is brevity. Even though he has had the help of an experienced journalist, he often uses ten words where one would do.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That said, Mr Melamed's book contains some fascinating insights into the markets that he helped create while chairman of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (he retired in 1991). Intriguingly, he is worried about the risks that a few convoluted trading strategies involving futures and options could pose to financial stability. Coming from the "father of financial futures", that is a warning financial folk would be foolish to ignore.
</td></tr></table>
<a name="4"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>B<font size=-1>UFFETT</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>AKING</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>AN</font> A<font size=-1>MERICAN</font> C<font size=-1>APITALIST</font>.<br>
 By Roger Lowenstein. <br>
<i>Random House; 473 pages; $27.50. Weidenfeld and Nicolson; </i>&#163;<i>20</i><br>
<a href="9ex271.html">Extract</a> - <a href="9jb271.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="9bt271.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>WINSTON CHURCHILL once referred to Russia as "a riddle wrapped in a mystery inside an enigma". Students of financial markets feel much the same way about Warren Buffett, the boss of Berkshire Hathaway, an American investment firm that owns stocks in firms engaged in an eclectic range of industries. Roger Lowenstein provides some clues for solving the riddle and unwrapping the mystery that surrounds one of the world's greatest investors. But at the end, its subject remains an enigma.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Buffett fascinates because Berkshire Hathaway has consistently outperformed the stockmarket by picking "undervalued" equities. This flies in the face of "efficient market theory"--a belief among financial economists that, at any given moment, all the publicly available information about a company is reflected in its share price. On this view, those investors who do manage to outperform the market are lucky rather than skilful.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lowenstein, however, argues that Berkshire Hathaway's success has more to do with judgment than luck. As well as a knack for spotting undervalued stocks, Mr Buffett has an uncanny eye for spotting talented individuals who run their firms as if they were owners, not just managers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of this is well known to those who peruse Berkshire's annual reports, which Mr Buffett uses to convey his investment wisdom in a witty and self-deprecating style. Less well known is the personal history that shaped this philosophy. Thus the book probes Mr Buffett's past to find out what makes him tick. The picture that emerges is of a self-absorbed genius, who sometimes appears emotionally detached from his family; of a creature of habit, who is unwilling to experiment with the unfamiliar; and of an outsider who prefers to work from Omaha, Nebraska, rather than Wall Street. In short, if Mr Lowenstein is right, the secret of Mr Buffett's success may well have more to do with the man than his methods.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
