<h2>B<font size=-1>UFFETT</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>AKING</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>AN</font> A<font size=-1>MERICAN</font> C<font size=-1>APITALIST</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Roger Lowenstein. <br>
<i>Random House; 473 pages; $27.50. Weidenfeld and Nicolson; </i>&#163;<i>20</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="9jb271.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
Roger Lowenstein has been reporting for the Wall Street Journal for over a
decade. Lowenstein wrote the Journal's stock control 'Heard on the Street' from
1989 to 1991, and now writes a new financial column, 'Intrinsic Value'. He
lives in Westfield, New Jersey, with his wife and three children.
