<html><head><title>The Deutsche Bank</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl28.jpg"><img src="cs28.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> D<font size=-1>EUTSCHE</font> B<font size=-1>ANK</font>:<br> <font size=-1>1870-1995</font><br></h2>
<p>By Lothar Gall, Gerald Feldman, Harold James, Carl-Ludwig Holtferich &amp; Hans B&uuml;schgen.<br>
<i>Weidenfeld &amp; Nicolson; 946 pages; &#163;40</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="3bt28.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>The Deutsche Bank, Germany's biggest universal bank, celebrates its 125th anniversary in 1995. To mark thc occasion, it has asked five leading scholars to write its history. In close co-operation with the Deutsche Bank's Historical Archives, the authors have produced a work of milestone importance in business history.
</p><p>The work is primarily the story of a company. It traces the Deutsche Bank's evolution into a big bank, its positioning as a foreign trade and 'industrial' bank, and also its big international financing projects in East Asia, the Ottoman Empire and America, with all their foreign policy implications during the German Empire. It describes the bank's situation and business policy from the period of high inflation after the First World War to the world economic and banking crisis at the end of the Weimar Republic. The company's activities under the National Socialist dictatorship and the treatment of Jewish staff and customers are looked at in the same detail as banking business during the Second World War. The book documents the splitting-up of the bank and its reamalgamation after 1945 under Allied occupation policy and its emergence as today's international financial conglomerate. Furthermore, it portrays the leading bank managers, the changes in staff as well as the new directions in organizational structure, and shows the company's position in the banking landscape at different points in time.
</p><p>The book is also a contribution to the economic and social history of modern Germany, as the bank's progress is closely linked to the development of the economy and social change. The authors describe the Deutsche Bank's relations with German industry and the central banks of the time, as well as showing how the company responded to new demands from a society in flux.
</p><p>Finally, the history of the Deutsche Bank is inextricably involved with Germany's political history. 'The fiftieth anniversary, in 1920, took place in the context of a recently lost war and a revolution, a depreciating currency, and a very uncertain future. . . The seventy-fifth anniversary in the spring of 1945 was even more miserable and might well have been its last. That there would be a one hundredth anniversary of a reunited Deutsche Bank ... in 1970 was anything but predictable in the years immediately following the end of the Second World War, and there was no reason to think in 1970 that the Deutsche Bank would be celebrating its 125th anniversary with reopened branches in what was formerly the GDR.' (Gerald D. Feldman)
</p><p>Seldom is a major company privileged to have its history documented by such outstanding scholars, and never before have authors been given such generous access to sources of material - all for the reader's benefit. You have here the distinctive features of a successful company history: the general derived from the specific and the specific illustrating the general. This book makes banking history more exact and, at the same time, more vivid. The result is a work of equal interest to bankers and economists, to historians and to the many readers who believe that a knowledge of banking is today an essential part of political culture. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
