<html><head><title>Never idle</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>German banking</b></p>
<h2>Never idle</h2><ul><li><a href="3ex28.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> D<font size=-1>EUTSCHE</font> B<font size=-1>ANK</font></a>: <font size=-1>1870-1995</font>&nbsp; By Lothar Gall, Gerald Feldman, Harold James, Carl-Ludwig Holtferich &amp; Hans B&uuml;schgen.<br>
</ul>



<p>THIS huge volume exemplifies much of what is best in modern Germany: a lofty objective addressed with deep seriousness and with the deployment of resources on an enviable scale. Written by four dons under the direction of a professor of business at Cologne, this is no standard corporate pot-boiler. The narrative divides naturally at four watersheds: 1914, 1933, 1945 and, less familiarly, 1957, the date of the Bundesbank Act.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The hot potato in this vast enterprise was clearly the Nazi period. In 1970, when Deutsche Bank last took stock of its past, it was judged too soon after 1933-45 to attempt any sort of comprehensive treatment. The passage of a further quarter century and the deaths of nearly if not quite all of those personally involved--including that of Hermann Abs, spokesman (in effect, head) of the bank in 1957-67, but already a senior director of it in the early 1930s--have together at last made possible a thorough and independent study. Time has helped in other ways. On unification in 1990, 12,000 files in Potsdam were returned to the bank, whence they came under the eye of Harold James, a British historian selected to cover the period of Nazi rule.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was this section, naturally enough, which aroused the most interest when the German edition of this book was published a year ago. For Mr James muffles but does not mince his words. Making every allowance for the pressures put upon its directors and scrupulously avoiding the role of Recording Angel, he has some necessary things to say about the bank under Hitler.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Two examples must suffice: "The Bank became part of the machine of German imperialism, and its employees the agents of a brutal political process"; and, as to Abs's seat on the supervisory board of I.G. Farben, "We do not know whether this body discussed the establishment of a plant in Birkenau, using labour from the concentration and annihilation camp at Auschwitz. Might he not have wondered about what was going on?"
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Few pages can match for power and immediacy the letter sent to the chairman of the supervisory board, Franz Urbig, by the then spokesman of the board of directors on April 9th 1933. Born into the Jewish religion, but baptised, Georg Solmssen was well placed to judge, and to denounce as he does in this letter, both the true objectives of the Nazi leaders and the shameful silence and lack of solidarity shown by the bank towards its Jewish staff. At the launch of this book in Frankfurt last spring the management team of 1995 made it clear, in answer to some awkward questions, that while the historians were free to say what they wished, the bank had no intention of saying anything more.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At various times, the bank was criticised within Germany for being too Jewish, too Catholic, too cosmopolitan, too left-of-centre, too influential, too haughty, too big. A mainly American catalogue of accusations in 1945 comically mirrors an earlier Nazi charge-sheet. Whoever might be in power in Berlin, the bank needed to be vigilant in its own defence. The tactics had to vary, which might mean, for example, that one or two "token" Nazis were elected to the board--but all for banking.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Deutsche Bank these days looks proof against anything, including its own mistakes. Its embrace includes the great names of German industry--<font size=-1>BMW</font>, Daimler-Benz, Mannesmann, Siemens. Its personalities have often mattered, and the murder of Alfred Herrhausen by German terrorists in 1989 was an irreparable loss. As for Abs, he flits through these pages for more than 60 years, now taking the longest of spoons to sup with the German resistance, now escaping from war-torn Berlin in a delivery van belonging to the Karstadt department store, now fending off the accusation that he multiplied his income by ten between 1933 and 1945, now tactfully retiring like Cincinnatus to his fruit farm at Remagen, but always in demand and never idle--like the bank itself.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
