<html><head><title>Business management</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<h2>Business management</h2>
<p><b>This month's "Books in Brief" looks at the often controversial advice being offered to managers by fellow-bosses as well as by business gurus</b></p><ul><li><a href="#1">B<font size=-1>UILT</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> L<font size=-1>AST</font></a>: S<font size=-1>UCCESSFUL</font> H<font size=-1>ABITS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> V<font size=-1>ISIONARY</font> C<font size=-1>OMPANIES</font>&nbsp; By James Collins and Jerry Porras.<br>
<li><a href="#2">T<font size=-1>HE</font> HP W<font size=-1>AY</a>:</font> H<font size=-1>OW</font> B<font size=-1>ILL</font> H<font size=-1>EWLETT</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> I B<font size=-1>UILT</font> <font size=-1>OUR</font> C<font size=-1>OMPANY</font>&nbsp; By David Packard.<br>
<li><a href="#3">P<font size=-1>EOPLE</font>, P<font size=-1>ERFORMANCE</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> P<font size=-1>AY</font></a>&nbsp; By Thomas Flannery, David Hofrichter and Paul Platten.<br>
<li><a href="#4">T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>VOLVING</font> G<font size=-1>LOBAL</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMY</font></a>&nbsp; Edited by Kenichi Ohmae.<br>
<li><a href="#5">W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> I<font size=-1>NVESTMENT</font> R<font size=-1>EPORT</font> <font size=-1>1995</a>:</font> T<font size=-1>RANSNATIONAL</font> C<font size=-1>ORPORATIONS</font> L<font size=-1>AND</font> C<font size=-1>OMPETITIVENESS</font>.<br>
<li><a href="#6">M<font size=-1>ANAGING</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>A</font> T<font size=-1>IME</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> G<font size=-1>REAT</font> C<font size=-1>HANGE</font></a>&nbsp; By Peter Drucker.<br>
</ul>
</td></tr></table>
<a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>B<font size=-1>UILT</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> L<font size=-1>AST</font>:<br> S<font size=-1>UCCESSFUL</font> H<font size=-1>ABITS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> V<font size=-1>ISIONARY</font> C<font size=-1>OMPANIES</font><br>
By James Collins and Jerry Porras.<br>
<i>Century</i>/<i>HarperBusiness; 320 pages; &#163;20 and $25</i>.<br>
</td></tr></table>
<a name="2"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>T<font size=-1>HE</font> HP W<font size=-1>AY:<br></font> H<font size=-1>OW</font> B<font size=-1>ILL</font> H<font size=-1>EWLETT</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> I B<font size=-1>UILT</font> <font size=-1>OUR</font> C<font size=-1>OMPANY</font><br>
By David Packard.<br>
<i>HarperBusiness; 212 pages; &#163;11.99 and $17</i><br>
<a href="4ex91.html">Extract</a> - <a href="4jb91.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="4bt91.html">Biography</a><br>

<p>OUTSTANDING companies are scrutinised in "Built to Last" to find the secrets of their success. The 18 companies are drawn from a wide range of industries, but all are durable (their average age is over 90) and profitable (their shares have done far better than the stockmarket generally since 1926). The authors argue that what marks these companies out is not charismatic leadership (most have been led by unremarkable people) or even revolutionary products but a core ideology. This gives them a cult-like character. They transform their recruits into company clones (anybody who fails to conform is ruthlessly expelled). They promote almost exclusively from within, and are contemptuous of management fads.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Built to Last" is full of vivid examples and intriguing insights. It is marred only by its authors' fondness for such ghastly phrases as "big, hairy audacious goals". There are enough bad writers about management without good writers pretending to be bad ones.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For an insider's look at one of these model companies you cannot do better than read David Packard's account of how, starting with just $538 and a rented garage in Palo Alto, California, he and Bill Hewlett created not only a computer giant but also Silicon Valley. His formula for success is to think small, avoid fancy business-school models and cultivate small-town values.</td></tr></table>
<a name="3"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>P<font size=-1>EOPLE</font>, P<font size=-1>ERFORMANCE</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> P<font size=-1>AY</font><br>
By Thomas Flannery, David Hofrichter and Paul Platten.<br>
<i>Free Press; 269 pages; $27</i><br>
<a href="4ex92.html">Extract</a> - <a href="4jb92.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="4bt92.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>THOUGH highly fashionable, introducing a more flexible pay system has been anything but smooth. In many cases flexibility does more to depress the unlucky many, who feel that they are being undervalued, than it does to motivate the lucky few, who feel that they are at last getting their just deserts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, few companies are tempted to go back to the old ways. Jobs and occupational hierarchies are now less rigid and the ideal of linking pay to a person's performance rather than his position remains appealing. The trick is to introduce flexibility sensitively.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The three authors, who all work for the Hay Group, a management consultancy, advise employers to adapt pay policies to their company's culture. They identify four different types of company. Functional organisations, which stress reliability and routine, need pay systems that attract reliable types. Process organisations, which are close to their customers, should emphasise equal pay within teams but encourage differences between teams. Time-based organisations, which stress flexibility and speed, should use performance-related rewards. Network organisations, which thrive on alliances and ventures, should pay people according to what they bring to each project. This usually means paying a few stars far more than the rest.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This analysis ignores the way that pay can be used to transform cultures--for example, how Britain is using merit pay to introduce dynamism into its slothful university system. But in general it provides a salutary warning against the sloppy use of the most powerful signals any employer has at his disposal.</td></tr></table>
<a name="4"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>VOLVING</font> G<font size=-1>LOBAL</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMY</font><br>
Edited by Kenichi Ohmae.<br>
<i>Harvard Business School Press; 320 pages; $29.95. McGraw Hill; &#163;23.95</i>.<br>
<a href="4ex93.html">Extract</a> - <a href="4jb93.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="4bt93.html">Biography</a><br>
</td></tr></table>
<a name="5"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> I<font size=-1>NVESTMENT</font> R<font size=-1>EPORT</font> <font size=-1>1995:<br></font> T<font size=-1>RANSNATIONAL</font> C<font size=-1>ORPORATIONS</font> L<font size=-1>AND</font> C<font size=-1>OMPETITIVENESS</font><br>
<i>United Nations Conference on Trade and Development; 436 pages; $45. HMSO; &#163;33</i>.<br>
<a href="4ex94.html">Extract</a><br>

<p>KENICHI OHMAE, a former head of McKinsey's Tokyo office whose book "The End of the Nation State" was reviewed in the December issue of <i>The Economist Review</i>, has long been identified with the most touted management trend: globalisation. He argues that, in a world in which national boundaries are dissolving and consumer tastes coalescing, companies can thrive only if they adopt the "Anchorage perspective" (named after a town that is equidistant from New York, D&uuml;sseldorf and Tokyo).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His collection of essays includes some of the best written on globalisation in recent years, including a revisionist one from Robert Reich, America's labour secretary. The collection fails, however, to explore the limits of the globalisation hypothesis. Truly globalised firms are, in fact, rare. Look at most multinationals and you find that they are more national, or even regional, than global in everything from the membership of their boards to the distribution of their shareholdings to the composition of their suppliers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The best source of facts, figures and arguments on the multinationals is the United Nations' annual "World Investment Report". <font size=-1>UNCTAD</font> used to be highly critical of multinationals. It now seems almost to have fallen in love with them, and is forever praising them for setting a good example. The latest report thinks that "good practice" is ceasing to mean Japanese production methods, and is becoming Americanised yet again. It also notes the creation of highly successful hybrid management systems, produced by the collision between different cultures.</td></tr></table>
<a name="6"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>M<font size=-1>ANAGING</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>A</font> T<font size=-1>IME</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> G<font size=-1>REAT</font> C<font size=-1>HANGE</font><br>
By Peter Drucker.<br>
<i>Truman Talley Books; 353</i> <i>pages; $24.95</i><br>


<p>IN HIS 26th book, Peter Drucker is as insightful and eloquent as ever. It is a collection of recent essays on a wide variety of subjects, from reinventing government to the overseas Chinese, from family businesses to free trade, but the book is unified by three recurring themes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first is the sheer scale of contemporary managerial change. Mr Drucker argues that vertically-integrated companies are giving way to networked organisations; that loyal employees are being replaced by contract workers; and that knowledge workers are taking over from blue-collar workers as society's main wealth creators.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second theme is the cause of managerial failure. Mr Drucker argues that managers have failed to understand what it means to manage in revolutionary times; that they spend their time tinkering with their business when they should really be rethinking the whole theory on which it is based.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The third theme is the organisational contradictions which are racking society: between business's need for perpetual innovation and the community's need for stability; between the rapidly changing nature of knowledge and the limited capacity of the human mind; between society's interest in the common good and business's need to compete internationally. It would be hard to find a better introduction to modern management theory.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
