<html><head><title>The Evolving Global Economy</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>

</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>VOLVING</font> G<font size=-1>LOBAL</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMY</font><br></h2>
<p>Edited by Kenichi Ohmae.<br>
<i>Harvard Business School Press; 320 pages; $29.95. McGraw Hill; &#163;23.95</i>.<br>
</p><br>
<a href="4bt93.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>The Evolving Global Economy Making Sense of the New World Order
</p><p>Today's global economy is genuinely borderless. Information, capital, and innovation flow all over the world at top speed, enabled by technology and fueled by consumers' desires for access to the best and least expensive products.
</p><p>This instant migration of ideas and resources has rendered assumptions about international competition obsolete. In its wake, policymakers and managers have had to accept the legitimacy of many forms of capitalism, rework the mechanics of trade policy, and redefine the objectives and responsibilities of top-level management.
</p><p>The Evolving Global Economy collects 16 articles from the Harvard Business Review that illuminate the broad effort to rethink cross-border flows of economic activity. Contributions from strategists, executives, and scholars from the public and private sectors--including Gary Hamel and C.K. Prahalad, Michael Porter, Paul Krugman, and U.S. Secretary of Labor Robert Reich--help to define and shape the new terms of debate.
</p><p>as Kenichi Ohmae suggests in his preface, there is real danger--not just lost opportunity--in dealing with today's borderless economy as if it were a minor variant of post-war global configurations. The Evolving Global Economy will help managers understand how the complex interactions of the participants affect their own businesses and contribute to the ever-changing landscape of the global economy. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
