<html><head><title>The Missionary and the Libertine.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl206.jpg"><img src="cs206.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>ISSIONARY</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> L<font size=-1>IBERTINE</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Ian Buruma. <br>
<i>Faber; 336 pages; &#163;16</i>.<i>99</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="7bt206.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Now that the Cold War is over, there is much talk about a new kind of conflict,
a conflict, a conflict between civilizations. This has revived the notion (which
never quite disappeared) of an absolute division between East and West. The
Missionary and the Libertine collects Ian Baruma's essays. Many of them
originally published in The New York Review of Books, which should serve as
a counterblast to this fashionable idea. Baruma describes how Westerners have
been attracted and repelled by Asian sensuality. He explores the nature of
Japanese sexuality in movies, and the erotic dreams of young girls in Banana
Yoshimoto's work. He examines the cultural confusion in individuals--Benazir
Bhutto, Imelda Marcos, Yukio Mishima and V.S. Naipaul--and he goes on to
discuss the last days of Hong Kong as a British colony, the Olympic Games in
South Korea, the legacies of Pearl Harbor and of Hiroshima, Japan-bashing,
racial war, and the life of an black American baseball-player in Japan.
<p>Ian Buruma's intimate knowledge of the East allows him to disentangle the knotty thickets that bind culture and politics together. The Missionary and the Libertine will confirm his reputation as one of the leading writers on Asian affairs. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
