<html><head><title>Burum, burum</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Asian culture</b></p>
<h2>Burum, burum</h2><ul> <li><a href="7ex206.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>ISSIONARY</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> L<font size=-1>IBERTINE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Ian Buruma. <br>
</ul>

<p>WESTERN readers on the look-out for books about modern Asia are not on the whole well served. The choice so often comes down to formulaic tales of journeys by bike, raft or jalopy, or to worthy essays in political economy full of figures and theory. Ian Buruma is one of the few authors writing about Asia who can navigate successfully between romance and the academy. Though from Europe himself, he has lived in Asia and knows it well. His witty, pleasant writing brings the region to life. But he is up on intellectual trends and almost always has a point to make.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The Missionary and the Libertine" is a set of articles collected mainly from literary-and-political magazines. Its range is wide. Topics include, for example, odd attitudes to sex in the work of Banana Yashimoto, a Japanese novelist, as well as inconsistencies in the political ideas of Benazir Bhutto, the prime minister of Pakistan. Inevitably, collections of articles like this have their weaknesses, and there is something a bit forced in the attempt by the publisher to try to link together the disparate essays in this one as a "counterblast" to fashionable ideas about the clash between East and West. But Mr Buruma's writing offers plenty of compensations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He is alive to the variety and depth of Asian cultures, without being bewitched by the idea of Asian otherness. Such level-headedness gives balance to his political judgments. He is scornful both of Edwin Reischauer, a former American ambassador to Japan who is fawningly respectful of Japanese culture, and of Michael Crichton, a bestselling American novelist, whose paranoid fantasies about Japanese efforts to "control" the United States are devastatingly rebutted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In his last two essays Mr Buruma takes on the "Asian-values" school directly. This is a fat target. It is far from clear that hard-to-define moral and cultural patterns explain variations in economic performance between Asia and the West--or that such supposed patterns are in any meaningful sense Asia-wide at all. Mr Buruma's essay on Singapore is a particularly fine piece of work because it pins down by careful description just what it is about the country that makes it seem sinister to people with even vaguely liberal instincts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is harder than you might think. Western journalists often struggle to express what they dislike about Singapore, a country, after all, that is prosperous and well run, and has democratically-elected rulers. Too often they concentrate on comparative trivialities, such as the fabled ban on chewing gum or the caning of an American teenage vandal. Apter criticism risks losing readers in the minutiae of Singaporean law and politics. In contrast, Mr Buruma offers an anecdotal but exacting account of how the Singaporean courts and government operate. His essay should be placed in the hands of any outsider who wants to cut through the usual obfuscations and understand Singapore. It is also a fitting end to a fluent and enjoyable book.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
