<html><head><title>Carl Gustav Jung.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl274.jpg"><img src="cs274.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>C<font size=-1>ARL</font> G<font size=-1>USTAV</font> J<font size=-1>UNG</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Frank McLynn. <br>
<i>Bantam Press; 624 pages; &#163;25</i> </p><br>
</p><br>
<a href="9jb274.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
A graduate of Wadham college, Oxford and London University, where he
obtained his doctorate, Frank McLynn is a full-time author specializing in
biography. His previous books include lives of H.M. Stanley and Richard
Burton and a number of works on the Jacobite movement, including Charles
Edward Stuart. His most recent books are Hearts of Darkness, Fitzroy Maclean
and the widely acclaimed Robert Louis Stevenson. Frank McLynn has won or
been shortlisted for a number of literary prizes. He was Alistair Horne Research
Fellow at St Antony's College, Oxford, in 1987-88.
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
