<html><head><title>A hatchet job</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr3.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Freud's great rival</b></p>
<h2>A hatchet job</h2><ul> <li><a href="9ex274.html">C<font size=-1>ARL</font> G<font size=-1>USTAV</font> J<font size=-1>UNG</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Frank McLynn. <br>
</ul><p>PREVIOUS books by Frank McLynn include biographies of two intrepid Victorian explorers, H.M. Stanley and Richard Burton. They are subjects much more to his liking; Carl Jung, the explorer of the interior of the mind, is certainly not. Indeed, it is hard to fathom why anybody would wish to expend so much time and so many words on a person he finds so distasteful.

<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Again and again Mr McLynn denounces Jung--who, God knows, was no saint--for moral degeneracy in every sphere of his life. He was an ungrateful son. He despised his pastor father as a weakling and failure, and had mixed feelings about his mother, who appeared to him to be an ordinary woman at times but invested with uncanny powers at others. From this unedifying starting point, Mr McLynn indulges in the kind of reductive analysis of Jung that the psychiatrist despised: namely that all Jung's struggles in his personal and professional life go back to his relationship with mummy and daddy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Jung's relations with the other significant people in his life appear to have been just as unsatisfactory. He married his wife, Emma, for her money and then betrayed her through his many infidelities with other women, including patients. Mr McLynn's constant refrain is that the twin driving forces in Jung's life were sex and money. His subject also stands accused of being a bully towards his family, his colleagues and the many women who flocked around him. Then there is "his vocabulary of foul-mouthed abuse": he referred to one patient as a "slimy bastard", another as an "empty gasbag", and yet another "a pisspot of unconscious devils". And he told one to "stop buggering about and wasting my time."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of this sits easily alongside the current view of Jung as <i>homo religiosus</i> and guru of the New Age who helped to reconcile science and religion. The author devotes roughly a third of the book to Jung's relationship with Freud and his bias is evident--the Austrian is portrayed in a favourable light, the Swiss is denigrated. For instance, Mr McLynn dismisses the charge that Freud had an affair with his sister-in-law, Minna--an affair attested to by an authoritative historian, Peter Swales--but repeatedly refers to Jung's liaisons, often without any corroborating evidence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After he broke with Freud, his former collaborator and mentor, Jung went on the develop his own psychological system. This incorporated a number of key concepts. They included the collective unconscious, the repository of mankind's psychic heritage and realm of the archetypes--inherited patterns in the mind that exist through time and space. Then there were anima/animus, the image of contrasexuality in the unconscious of each individual, and shadow, the repressed unwanted aspect of a person. And there was the theory of psychological types--introvert and extrovert--influenced by William James's dichotomy of tough- and tender-minded individuals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Jung also developed his theory of individuation, which holds that each individual's goal in life is to achieve his own potential. This is the ultimate quest of an in-depth Jungian analysis.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr McLynn gets in a muddle when he attempts to grapple with any of the above. He fares better when dealing with Jung's interest in the occult and the paranormal. But his over-reliance on previously published materials gives his book a mildewy feel. His sources include Jung's "autobiography", which Sonu Shamdasani has shown to be largely the work of Jung's secretary.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The book contains many mistakes, including the following about Jung's long-time mistress, Toni Wolff: "When she called in Dr Gerhard Adler on 19th March 1953, she already knew she was dying." Adler was not a medical doctor and far from treating Toni Wolff was in Zurich to have a few sessions of analysis with her. It may, however, be enjoyed by those who like their history served up as faction.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
