<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev7/rv3/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113182835 text/html 15494
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:24:44 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:12 GMT
Content-length: 15308
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Into the abyss?</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="7gr3.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Russia's future</b></p>
<h2>Into the abyss?</h2><ul> <li>K<font size=-1>HRONIKA</font> V<font size=-1>REMYON</font> 'T<font size=-1>SARYA</font> B<font size=-1>ORISA</font>' (A Chronicle of the Times of 'Tsar Boris').</a>&nbsp;  By Oleg Poptsov.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Sovershenno Sekretno, Moscow; 541 pages; 12,000</i> <i>roubles.</i> <br>
 <li>N<font size=-1>OVY</font> S<font size=-1>TROY</font> (The New System).</a>&nbsp;  By Yuri Burtin.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Epitsentr Publishing, Moscow; 191 pages.</i> <br>
 <li>P<font size=-1>OSLE</font> Y<font size=-1>ELTSINA</font> (After Yeltsin).</a>&nbsp;  By Alexander Yanov.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Krug, Moscow; 316 pages; 14,000 roubles.</i> <br>
 <li>V<font size=-1>ERYU</font> <font size=-1>V</font> R<font size=-1>OSSIYU</font> (I Believe in Russia).</a>&nbsp;  By Gennady Zyuganov.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Voronezh Publishing House; 383 pages; 10,000 roubles</i>. <br>
</ul>

RUSSIA has always baffled foreigners. Five years after the banning of the Communist Party, the collapse of the Soviet Union and the apparent dawn of a liberal-democratic era, many Western hopes for change lie in ashes. Nor were all those hopes ill-informed or foolish. What went wrong? Or are the gloom and uncertainty attending the current presidential election themselves exaggerated? These four books, each very different but all by Russians, shed light on the obstacles facing liberal democracy in Russia and on what might be emerging in its place.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Oleg Poptsov is a liberal casualty of Russia's war in Chechnya. Appointed by Boris Yeltsin in early 1991 as head of Russia's new television channel, he kept his job for an extraordinary five years until fired last February just as Mr Yeltsin announced his bid for a second presidential term. Too many dead bodies on the evening news, Mr Yeltsin is said to have complained.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Poptsov's candour was bound to plunge him into trouble at some point, Chechnya or no Chechnya. Like Saint-Simon observing Louis XIV's court at Versailles, he etches unflattering vignettes of the men around the throne. Tsar Boris haunts these pages, ever more at the mercy of boyars and bureaucrats, who are as eager to foil him as to do each other down.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A Komsomol newspaper editor drawn into politics by perestroika, Mr Poptsov's sympathies are with his former boss but he never loses his objectivity or his gift for a telling phrase. He describes Mr Yeltsin, who was once a building engineer, as having a fragmented mind, "rather like prefab concrete panels". He recognises Mr Yeltsin's courage in entering politics on his own, his intuitive approach to complex matters of state and his feel for crowds, traits that fit logically with another, more damaging, one: the distrust of peers. Without a team of strong-minded advisers, Mr Poptsov predicted early on, Mr Yeltsin would quickly fall prisoner to the old apparat, whatever new label it chose to use.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From his television eyrie Mr Poptsov kept an eye on the revolving door to the president's office, through which Gennady Burbulis, Ruslan Khasbulatov, Alexander Rutskoi, Sergei Shakhrai and many others passed. One of the more acid portraits is of Alexander Korzhakov, Mr Yeltsin's chief bodyguard and closest confidant. At the height of Mr Yeltsin's struggle with Alexander Rutskoi in 1993, Mr Poptsov refused to screen a report attacking this dissident vice-president. "Never mind," Mr Korzhakov muttered, "they [Messrs Rutskoi and Poptsov] can share a cell together."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The danger for his former boss, as Mr Poptsov sees it, is a growing isolation and a steady restriction of the information reaching him from his closest aides. He laments "the triumph of those with whom the leader goes to the bathhouse, or celebrates around the dinner table, or swims, or hunts, or goes fishing."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This intriguing chronicle ends as "the bathhouse team" leads Mr Yeltsin into the Chechen adventure, an operation which the general staff had fooled themselves and the president into thinking would last but a few days. Without notes or index, this volume is a written equivalent of St Basil's cathedral in Red Square, a seemingly deliberate muddle in which readers not familiar with the chronology and plot are almost bound to get lost. But despite this it is also a treasure chest for anyone who wants to understand the inside workings of the Kremlin in the past five years.</p>
<p><b>From the outside</b>
<br>Like Mr Poptsov, Yuri Burtin is a liberal but, unlike him, a Kremlin outsider. A literary journalist, he speaks as one of the intelligentsia, far from the corridors of power. In this collection of essays and articles, he argues that Mr Yeltsin struck a strategic compromise with the old Soviet nomenklatura after the failed coup of 1991, a deal that betrayed Mr Yeltsin's earlier commitment to true democratisation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The author sees continuities between the new government and earlier Russian regimes, both Soviet and Tsarist. He compares the botched reforms of the 1990s to the partial abolition of serfdom in the 1860s under Alexander II. To him, the wretched Russian system of government is an <i>oboroten</i> (werewolf), forever changing its appearance but never its nature. "There is now less democracy in Russia than at the peak of perestroika," Mr Burtin writes. "Once again," he thinks, "there is no society, just the state and the population, the authorities and the people." On the basis of this consistently bleak view, Mr Burtin has argued since 1992 that Russia's democrats should keep a safe distance from the Yeltsin regime. The president's Chechen adventure and his abandonment of liberal supporters might well seem to reinforce this line of argument. But, for all its appeal, Mr Burtin overstates the view that there is little or nothing to choose between Mr Yeltsin and his nationalist opponents, and so fails to make his council of despair convincing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Alexander Yanov's vantage point is different again. Though also a liberal, he is a professional historian. Made to emigrate to the United States by the Brezhnev regime in 1974, he was allowed to return in 1990 and has watched politics in Russia closely since. Unless the West is more involved in Russia, he believes, the country may drift into fascism or something as bad. Mr Yanov was once what Russians call a "white raven" (a misfit) among American Soviet-watchers. In the peaceful Brezhnev era, his warnings about the rise of extreme Russian nationalism sounded simply eccentric. But a glance at a book Mr Yanov wrote in 1987, "The Russian Challenge and Year 2000", will show how far-sighted he was. In it, he predicted that communist and nationalist ideas would before long fuse into a potent ideology of counter-reform.</p>
<p><b>Back to Byzantium</b></b>
<br>In "After Yeltsin" Mr Yanov looks into a post-Yeltsin abyss and repeats his warning that Russia's fragile democracy faces a tide of communist and nationalist revenge. He offers a layman's tour of the intellectual background to the new Russian right, including the "Eurasianism" of Lev Gumilyov and the anti-Semitic nationalism of Igor Shafarevich--a tour which is itself a useful reminder that dangerous or pernicious ideas are seldom ravings from lunatics but more often well-argued points from clever, plausible minds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among the opposition figures interviewed by Mr Yanov for his research in 1993-94 was Gennady Zyuganov, a leader of the new Russian Communist Party. Mr Zyuganov has close links to a think-tank known as Spiritual Heritage which led the way in producing the very climate of ideas that Mr Yanov predicted. The label for him used here, "National Bolshevik", was originally applied to anti-communist White Russian intellectuals who in the 1920s accepted the Bolsheviks because they had preserved and strengthened Russia. Mr Zyuganov, similarly, believes in <i>derzhava</i> (a strong Russian state). No Marxist, he boasted to Mr Yanov that he had been expelled from the Communist Party under Brezhnev for his nationalist views.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Zyuganov is sometimes compared to Slobodan Milosevic, a standard example of the cynical office-holder who makes off in the lifeboat of nationalism as communism sinks. This is misleading. There is every sign that Mr Zyuganov's nationalist beliefs are sincere. Unlike Mr Yeltsin, with his intuition and his concrete panels, Mr Zyuganov is driven by historical ideas, most of them bizarre and distasteful to the Western mind but a genuine part nonetheless of an authentic Russian tradition. He is more careful with words and less colourful than Vladimir Zhirinovsky, a rival, but his anti-Western views are much the same. "I Believe in Russia" should be read and re-read by anyone who thinks that Mr Zyuganov is really a social democrat who might yet make a comfortable partner for the West. He takes a paranoid view of history in which Russia is a permanent victim of evil outside forces. Readers of "The Protocols of the Elders of Zion", a 1905 forgery, or of Soviet-era propaganda will find the Manichean tone depressingly familiar.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is nevertheless a rational core to his argument. Whereas Marx and Lenin took history's motor to be class struggle, Mr Zyuganov sees it as a geopolitical and spiritual battle between Russian and Western civilisation, dating back to the schism between Rome and Byzantium in 1054. Belief in "the clash of civilisations" may be wrong, but it is not absurd or dismissable out of hand. Were it so, the presence of Mr Zyuganov and the many Russians who think like him would look less irksome.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though he drops names right and left (Francis Fukuyama, Lev Gumilyov, Samuel Huntington, Oswald Spengler and Arnold Toynbee all get a mention), Mr Zyuganov draws most deeply on two 19th century Slavophile thinkers, Konstantin Leontiev and Nikolai Danilevsky, both of whom saw Russia as a distinct civilisation apart from the West. As Mr Zyuganov vividly describes it, medieval Western Europe was a militaristic armed camp, arrogant and intolerant, sending its crusading knights against the peaceful Slavic and Byzantine world to the East. As in Eisenstein's brilliant Stalin-era film, "Alexander Nevsky", the enemy comes from the West, not the East. (As a Eurasianist in the tradition of Gumilyov, Mr Zyuganov lets the invading Mongols off lightly by contrast.)</p>
<p><b>The threat to Holy Russia</b>
<br>While the East preserved Justinian's Byzantine-theocratic "symphony of powers" and collectivist values, the West, according to Mr Zyuganov, created an over-rational, individualistic, money-seeking society and a heartless, empty culture to go with it, peopled, as it were, with the brainchildren of Voltaire and Disney. Far from enjoying any moral superiority, Western colonialism exterminated whole peoples, whereas Russia's expansion into Siberia was "almost bloodless" and preserved local cultures. The expansion of Muscovy and the Russian state was simply a natural response to the "hegemonistic" aspirations of the West. By the 19th century, Mr Zyuganov goes on, the influence of the Jewish diaspora in Western Europe was "growing literally not by the day but by the hour", until it controlled the economic system, while the "messianic pretension" of the Jews to be the chosen people imprinted itself ever deeper on Western culture.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After this unpleasant flirt with an old and deep-rooted Russian anti-Semitism, Mr Zyuganov skates delicately around the Bolshevik revolution--a subject communists and nationalists find it hard to agree about. On balance, he writes, the revolution was a good thing as it strengthened the Russian state, purging it of "out-of-date feudal and bourgeois forms". Stalin gets high marks for restoring the traditional patriotic ideology of Russian statehood, but his good work between 1945 and 1953 was undone by Nikita Khrushchev's "thaw". The Cold War, on this view, was not the definitive ideological battle of communism and capitalism, but a passing episode in an unfinished war between two civilisations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The collapse of the Soviet Union, according to Mr Zyuganov, was the result of a well-laid plot by Western intelligence using a fifth column of Russian politicians. He blames the "open Russophobia of the denationalised part of society"--crudely coded language meaning mostly Russian Jews. Russia, he goes on, must recover its lost greatness and lost territories, while simultaneously seeking a spiritual rebirth through traditional values and religious ideals. It is not a rewarmed Marxism-Leninism that has to be feared if Mr Zyuganov or his ideas prevail but a return to the theocratic ideas of medieval Byzantium and to the Slavophile dream of Muscovy as a "Third Rome". "Today for the first time in three centuries we have a real chance to restore the symphonic unity of our spiritual and state traditions," he writes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the cherished mentality of <i>sobornost</i> (collective spirituality) is incompatible with capitalism, Mr Zyuganov thinks Russia must resist being drawn into a world economic system that may leave it dependent on hostile outside forces. The enemy here is the West's "trading and financial cosmopolitan oligarchy", which seeks "world domination" and which, with its faithless Russian helpers, is trying to impose on Russia a "cosmopolitan regime expressing the interests of world capital and the local comprador bourgeoisie". So much for foreign investment and the <font size=-1>IMF</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How far Mr Zyuganov's views are shared by his party colleagues is uncertain. Nor is it obvious how far he may be able to further them under Yeltsin II or apply them in a post-Yeltsin Russia. But at least those views are now known; and nobody can say they did not have fair warning.


<br><br><p><img src="7gr3-1.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
