<html><head><title>On Dover Beach</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="8gr7.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>English critics</b></p>
<h2>On Dover Beach</h2><ul> <li>M<font size=-1>ATTHEW</font> A<font size=-1>RNOLD</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Nicholas Murray.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Hodder &amp; Stoughton; 336 pages; &#163;20</i> <br>
</ul>

<p>IN HIS poem, "Rugby Chapel", Matthew Arnold remembered his father as "a mighty oak". His father, Thomas Arnold, immortalised in the novel "Tom Brown's Schooldays" and in Lytton Strachey's portrait in "Eminent Victorians", is probably the most famous English public-school headmaster. He was an earnest and forceful character, the influential proponent of a hearty Christian ethic, and must, by any standards, have been a difficult act to follow. Yet somewhat in vain does Nicholas Murray search for the psychological effect that such a father might have had; apart from a youthful flippancy and facetiousness, almost certainly a reaction to his father, Matthew Arnold emerges from "under the boughs" his own man, a great poet and a noted man of letters.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Matthew Arnold was born in 1822, the second child of Thomas and Mary Arnold. His early childhood by the Thames at Laleham, not far from London, before his father's appointment to Rugby School, appears to have been idyllic. It bred in him a love of the Thames, and themes of running water and waves and seas recur in his poetry. His love of the river was augmented at Oxford where, with the poet Arthur Hugh Clough and other friends, he appears to have had one of those times on which legends of Oxford are created--arguing, learning, pastoral days of male companionship; his is the line about Oxford: "And that sweet City with her dreaming spires."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To marry Fanny Lucy Wightman, the daughter of a judge, he needed an income; so in 1851 he became an inspector of schools, a job he was to hold for 35 years, long after his poetry and criticism made him a literary celebrity. He inspected schools from Bethnal Green to Pembroke Dock, travelling which would not be done very much faster today. He also reported on education in Europe. It would have been interesting to learn more of what he, with his intelligence and a liking for children, observed in those Victorian institutions. He remained strongly in favour of education for all, for, as he put it, "the little ploughboy". He felt that the new elementary schools would be important for "civilising the next generation of the lower classes, who, as things are going, will have most of the political power of the country in their hands."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new middle classes he abhorred, calling them "the Philistines", in the grip of an unthinking materialism brought on by "the absorbing and brutalising influence of our passionate material progress...our railways, our business and our fortune-making." He had it in for the Atlantic telegraph--"that great rope with a Philistine at each end of it talking inutilities." What would he have said of the Internet?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He was in essence, a high-flown intellectual, deeply immersed in the classics. When he became professor of poetry at Oxford, his famous lectures were on the translation of Homer. He claimed that the role of the critic was "simply to know the best that is known and thought in the world". Seen in recent times as elitist and in his own times as supercilious, he was more complicated than that. It was said of him that when he woke each morning he was convinced that everything was an open question. A staunch Liberal, he was reactionary in some of his views, almost socialist in others. Any pomposity was tempered with a vivacity and sense of humour, and behind his superior airs was a modest and playful man, if somewhat egotistical.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His family life, though clouded by the deaths of three of six children, was otherwise content, and meant a great deal to him. He loved animals and had a passion for wild flowers. By the end of his life he was much sought after socially, a distinguished member of the chattering classes of the time. Though his poetry petered out, he continued to write articles and to pontificate. He died suddenly on his way to meet his daughter and granddaughter who were arriving at Liverpool from America.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;We are left now with some marvellous poetry, combining high intellect and great feeling, examples of which--"Dover Beach" or "The Scholar-Gipsy" for instance--will always be found in anthologies. His evocations of the country with descriptions of all manner of wild flowers, of birds, and especially of elms, have some of the nostalgic fascination of old watercolours.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A strength of this biography is its picture, worked up from contemporary papers, of an educated and well-connected person's life in the mid-19th century. Arnold went for walks with Wordsworth, a family friend, in the Lake District; was entranced (though not persuaded) by Cardinal Newman's sermons at Oxford--"subtle, sweet, mournful"; he was on familiar terms with both Disraeli and Gladstone; he disdained Tennyson, thought highly of George Sand; and entertained Charlotte Bront to tea--"past thirty and plain". The walk-on parts add much to the fascination.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
