<html><head><title>Aye aye, sir</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>English critics</b></p>
<h2>Aye aye, sir</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex234.html">N<font size=-1>OT</font> E<font size=-1>NTITLED</font></a>: A M<font size=-1>EMOIR</font>.&nbsp;  By Frank Kermode. <br>
</ul>


<p>YOU will feel you have definitely met someone after reading this autobiographical memoir, but what sort of someone? As empty as the velvet box that throws the dice, but also deflated in some manner by the vigours of being alive? Yes, perhaps. But also someone interesting, annoying, appealing, spiky, friendly, self-knowing and self-ignorant.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Frank Kermode is one of Britain's most distinguished literary scholars--professor at London, Cambridge and Harvard, author of acclaimed critical works, noted editor, wise arbiter of theoretical quarrels, though you would not catch him boasting about any of that, not straightforwardly at least. He is clever and self-aware enough to know that the personality behind a famous life is not the long-playing record itself but only a scratch on it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kermode is a fearless memoirist, not at all afraid of the ridiculous at the heart of the sublime. A whole chapter is called "Errors", 63 bitter-wry pages which detail the life of a literary intellectual, including an ill-judged moment as editor of the <font size=-1>CIA</font>-backed magazine, <i>Encounter</i>. As such you have to admire this crafty book, whose subtlety borders on deviousness. He invites you to meet him with the same gesture, as he suggests he is not worth meeting. This is not exactly humility but the unusual grandeur of a personality that prefers to be alone, solo, sufficient. He is not the Greta Garbo of English criticism nor a Manx hermit in an igloo of stone, but a reclusive mind nonetheless that, after reading its thousand books, seems to have rather given up on humanity, and not just on others, but on himself too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is hard to identify the mysterious quality of this memoir. Is he trying to erase himself, line by line, like a ferocious child with a valuable manuscript? Or is it that the creative artist is the overflowing vessel and the critic the one that must make itself hollow to sound the echoes? Again, is the odd quality absence, a science he seems to have perfected in his life? As a Manx child he was "exiled from the life and language of the English". The world was "away". But he himself was also in exile from the concerns and social integers of his parents. He did not feel "at home in my homeland".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These feelings are profoundly shared by many a creative writer, and are sometimes the great engines of mighty works. So it is again curious that he felt he had no power as a creative writer and, meeting the old suspicion and perhaps prejudice of disgruntled writers, accepted the fate of a critic. Yet his criticism is not at all as insignificant as he would sometimes have you believe: he has even made literature out of the rattling bones of academic pursuits and is blamed (or praised) for helping introduce a tincture of French literary theory to Anglo-American letters. When finding himself at war in the moil of fashions and trends, he has lifted the reluctant sword, and for this, among other things, he was suitably knighted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Going to war in the conventional meaning--the second world war, that is--he found a fragmented world of inane-seeming naval officers and an equally inane warlessness wherever he went. He was surely in the war but the war was not where he was. This passage in the book has already been compared to Evelyn Waugh's work, but there is no novelist's distance here. We are invited in a way to be appalled by his officers at every turn, indeed throughout the book to be appalled by the things that appal him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A memoir by a literary man is always going to be a construct. In that regard it is a compulsive book, and neatly structured. It is not always clear why he has chosen to focus on a particular matter. As he says in another context, "the inward eye can be overworked". As an interrogation of whatever it means to possess a "self" it is brutally insistent about the lightness, meanness and slightness of being alive. And yet what redeems the book from the hint of hollowness at its heart is the firm impression that a certain man has been met, a sort of king in his day, insisting on the more honest outfit of the commoner.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
