<html><head><title>Splash!</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl227.jpg"><img src="cs227.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>S<font size=-1>PLASH</font>!:<br> G<font size=-1>REAT</font> W<font size=-1>RITING</font> <font size=-1>ABOUT</font> S<font size=-1>WIMMING</font>.<br></h2>
<p> Edited by Laurel Blossom. <br>
<i>Ecco Press; 254 pages; &#163;26</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="8bt227.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
A unique anthology, Splash! gathers together fiction, essays, and poetry that
explore one of the most popular activities around the world. Swimming inspires
the imagination as no other sport, and the diverse and celebrated writers
included here illuminate its many facets--from sport to recreation to metaphor.
<p>Laurel Blossom, a poet and lifelong swimmer, has drawn upon an amazing array of material for this collection. Ray Bradbury, John Cheever, Laurie Colwin, James Dickey, Dawn Fraser, A E. Housman, Maxine Kumin, Doris Lessing, Jack London, Diana Nyad, Sharon Olds, Mary Oliver, Anne Sexton, Stevie Smith, Calvin Trillin and John Updike are among the authors she has selected to bring their considerable and varied talents to bear on the subject of swimming.</p>
<p>With a preface by George Plimpton and an informative introduction by the editor, Splash! plunges with verve and insight into the pools of literature and the imagination. From exotic landscapes to the simple joy of the neighborhood pool from myth and science fiction to the drama of competition Splash! contains the very best writing on swimming. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
