</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>In the amniotic mere</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="8gr4.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Swimming</b></p>
<h2>In the amniotic mere</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex227.html">S<font size=-1>PLASH</font>!</a>: G<font size=-1>REAT</font> W<font size=-1>RITING</font> <font size=-1>ABOUT</font> S<font size=-1>WIMMING</font>.&nbsp;  Edited by Laurel Blossom. <br>
</ul>

SWIMMING and writing have a lot in common, writes the fetchingly named Laurel Blossom in her introduction to this unusual collection of verse and prose. Lord Byron was the first Englishman to swim the Hellespont. Paul Val&eacute;ry hailed swimming as "a delight only comparable to love". Scott Fitzgerald wrote, "All good writing is swimming under water and holding your breath." As she gets used to the pool, Ms Blossom's own stroke quickens. "Both swimming and writing", she continues, "engender...[a]...trance-like state in which the imagination flourishes without censor or restraint." Well, yes, but so can bicycling or sitting in a bar. Yet it would be cheap to carp. Ms Blossom's topic is swimming and she has produced a remarkable anthology on a fascinating theme.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A less playful editor might have concentrated on the athletic feats of professional swimmers. But Ms Blossom, a poet first and swimmer second, has wisely chosen to focus on imaginative writing. Some of the characters in these poems and stories--the pompous ass of John Updike's "Lifeguard", or the unfortunate chap in Ray Bradbury's "The Women", for example--barely get their feet wet. Swimming emerges as a far from simple pleasure. The little boy in R. Bruce Moody's tale, "Water", wants to please his father by learning to swim, but is terrified of dying in the sea: "A drop could kill him. Death was moist." The troubled protagonist of Monica Wood's tale, "Disappearing", rather hopes that she will vanish into the water. The swimmer in Maureen Stanton's "Water" loves the honesty of an activity that makes people "look like they were just born: wet and slick and ugly." But in what is arguably the prose highlight of this collection--John Cheever's "The Swimmer"--the main character plunges ever further into deceipt and concealment with each pool he crosses in rich suburbia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Blossom does even better with the poems--using them to punctuate the collection with a skill that comes from her craft (although she is too shy to include any of her own). They vary in style and tone--from the old-fashioned elegance of A.E. Housman's retelling of the Hero and Leander story, "Tarry, delight", to the bleary haze of James Dickey's hungover swim in "Coming Back to America". Lest readers drown in metaphors, there is wry light relief-- Thomas Lux's "Tarantulas on the Lifebuoy", for example, or a two-line Ogden Nash-like entry by John Ciardi, "On Being Much Better Than Most and Yet Not Quite Good Enough". ("There was a great swimmer named Jack/Who swam ten miles out--and nine back.")
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No book of swimming writing can ignore the strange people who endure hours of pain and monotony in the water: champion swimmers. There are some modestly upbeat essays, like that of a long-distance veteran, Diana Nyad, who writes that "fatigue, pain and huge waves are manageable", but not the cold, which will numb a swimmer's limbs and end the bravest venture in minutes once the temperature drops low enough. Thankfully brief is the unattractive boasting by an Olympic gold-medal winner who writes: "...most swimmers back away from the pain; a champion pushes himself on into agony."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But even in the area of competitive swimming Ms Blossom has been careful to keep her poise. A letter from an American adventurer, Richard Halliburton, reminds readers of a time when the only serious swimmers were gung-ho wags who swam great distances with brandy to sustain them. In an extract from "Water Dancer", Jennifer Levin conveys with rhythmic verbal swells the agony of an open-water swimmer who beats a cruel sea, vomiting the whole way. And if you can stomach the symbolic lapping of the lines across the page, Maxine Kumin's poem, "400-Meter Freestyle", is as excellent a description of today's champ as any: one who is so practised that "thrift is his wonderful secret; he has schooled out all extravagance."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By the end, you may well feel like the lad in David Allan Evans's "The Celebration". Although he and his friends have all dived into the same spot in the same lake, Thomas is surprised to find that "every one of us had a different dive, a different story to tell." Ms Blossom has done a terrific job capturing the elusive experience of swimming. If only she or her publishers had thought up a decent title.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
