<html><head><title>Children of Darkness and Light</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl75.jpg"><img src="cs75.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2></i>C<font size=-1>HILDREN</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> D<font size=-1>ARKNESS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> L<font size=-1>IGHT</font><br></h2>
<p>By Nicholas Mosley.<br>
<i>Secker &amp; Warburg; 240 pages; &#163;15.99.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="4jb75.html">Jacket Copy</a><br>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>Nicholas Mosley, born in 1923, is the author of a dozen novels, most recently the Whitbread Award-winning Hopeful Monsters. Films have been made of two of his novels. Accident (using a screenplay by Harold Pinter and directed by Joseph Losey) and Impossible Object. He has also written non-fiction books on politics and religion, and most recently, his autobiography Efforts At Truth. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
