<html><head><title>Risk averse</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="4gr18.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Fiction in England</b></p>
<h2>Risk averse</h2><ul><li><a href="4ex102.html">L<font size=-1>AST</font> O<font size=-1>RDERS</font></a>&nbsp; By Graham Swift.<br>
<li><a href="4ex75.html"></i>C<font size=-1>HILDREN</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> D<font size=-1>ARKNESS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> L<font size=-1>IGHT</font></a>&nbsp; By Nicholas Mosley.<br>
<li><a href="4ex72.html"></i>A W<font size=-1>HITE</font> M<font size=-1>ERC</font> <font size=-1>WITH</font> F<font size=-1>INS</font></a>&nbsp; By James Hawes.<br>
<li><a href="4ex101.html"></i>E<font size=-1>NGLISH</font> S<font size=-1>ETTLEMENT</font></a>&nbsp; By D.J. Taylor.<br>
</ul><ul></ul>

ONCE upon a time the English novel was ambitious. In the great era of Dickens, Thackeray and George Eliot, novelists took it upon themselves to invent whole worlds and to people these worlds with busy and credible characters. Now too often the story and the people in it potter about.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On this spring's bookshelves, Graham Swift's "Last Orders" is a prime example. Mr Swift is one of the best known novelists in a generation now in its mid-40s. His finest book is "Waterland", a sweeping evocation of the history and atmosphere of Fenlands England. His latest novel is on a much smaller scale. It tells the story of a group of old friends who are preparing to scatter the ashes of Jack Dodds, a Bermondsey butcher, off the end of Margate pier--as he himself had requested them to do.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In part, "Last Orders" is the story of the men's sombre car journey from East London, through Kent, to the Kentish coast. In part, it is a collection of reminiscences by each of the characters in turn--"Vic", the undertaker, whose establishment had been just across the way from Jack's butchery; Vince, the second-hand car dealer, who had been Jack's adopted son in all but name; "Raysy" the gambler, who had struck up an illicit friendship with Amy, Jack's wife.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Little by little, a portrait of the man and his life emerges--petty, sad, frustrating. Mr Swift's novel captures the language of working-class East London, and convincingly describes the lore of undertaking and butchery--the scenes in the Smithfield meat market are especially well done. But the novel is not opened up by his decision to tell the story through a series of discrete monologues. This technique reduces its potential imaginative scope, and makes it less multifarious, and more bitty and claustrophobic, than it need have been.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nicholas Mosley's "Hopeful Monsters" won literary prizes. He seems unlikely to repeat that triumph with "Children of Darkness and Light". The narrator is Harry, a semi-alcoholic journalist whose marriage may be on the point of collapse. He is a man whose life is governed by intellectual obsessions which take him to the former Yugoslavia, where he investigates claims that a group of children have seen a vision of the Virgin Mary on a hillside, and to Cumbria, where he experiences a deep sense of unease because he appears not only to have been expected but to be known...This is the world of a kind of sub-Kafka--all this deep spiritual unease is supposed to create convincing parables out of a tormented inner life. Mr Mosley gives his readers nothing but drift and pretentious humbug. The monologue form is little more than a mask for a fashionable intellectual incoherence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;James Hawes's " A White Merc with Fins" is set in London and, though written as a first-person narrative, makes a brave attempt to represent the world of a capital city. Mr Hawes is a comedian of manners, and this novel, his first, is a breathless, expletive-stuffed black comedy told by a man of 28 whose London life has hit a nadir of boredom and inconsequence. To remedy this, the hero dreams up an audacious bank robbery that requires the help of the <font size=-1>IRA</font>--only this will rescue him from the receding hairline, the world of the bedsit, the hellish meltdown towards drugs and the under-class. The novel is short enough for the monologue form to retain its force. It possesses briskness, humour and originality.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;D.J. Taylor's third novel, "English Settlement", deserves a better critical reception than it has got, if only because it tries to encompass so much. It is set in the London of 1990. Margaret Thatcher is about to be ousted as prime minister and the Iraqis are sitting pretty in Kuwait. The money men are being toppled from their thrones; the "good times" are over.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The world of Scott Marshall, a young American, is falling to pieces too. He works for <font size=-1>KLS</font>, a predatory management consultancy based in London. Neither his job nor his social life is secure. He moves uneasily through a disconcerting milieu of upper-class girls whose coded language and eccentric behaviour patterns are almost incomprehensible to him. He is haunted by his own past in West Virginia. Why did his father leave his mother? Why did she never talk about her childhood in England?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Half way through the novel, Scott is seconded to a fourth-division English soccer team with instructions to sort out its finances. His discovery of a serious financial swindle puts his own life in danger.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Taylor has taken on much that is difficult here: describing London through the eyes of an arrogant, though often mistaken and bewildered, young American; making sense of the complicated workings of the City without having that knowledge intrude upon enjoyment of the story; and shifting back and forth between America and England in an attempt to chart the differences between their respective national identities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other English novelists need to be reminded of the importance of taking risks of this kind. Reality is not merely--and not principally--what goes on inside our own heads. It is also what we make of what is outside us.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
