<html><head><title>A White Merc with Fins</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl72.jpg"><img src="cs72.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2></i>A W<font size=-1>HITE</font> M<font size=-1>ERC</font> <font size=-1>WITH</font> F<font size=-1>INS</font><br></h2>
<p>By James Hawes.<br>
<i>Cape; 281 pages; &#163;12.99.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="4bt72.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>THE DAZZLING DEBUT of an immensely exciting new voice in British fiction, A White Merc with Fins speaks, tongue firmly in cheek, eyes wide open and razor sharp, to an entire generation.
</p><p>It's the funny, unexpected story of a 28-yearold with dreams but no focus?, for whom temping has become permanent and home a shack in his sister's London garden. Hobbling from Saturday night to Saturday night, he realises that he is looking at nothing but 30, a receding hairline and a bedsit. The MC (Middle- Class) dream is melting down towards drugs, crime and the underclass.
</p><p>Then the God of temping slips him the keys to Michael Winner's private bank - and The Plan kicks in. It needs a bit of help - Suzy the Black Widow, who drives like she is breathing through the carbs; Brady, the big Reservoir Doggie gobshite; Chicho, homesick for garlic and charcoal heaven - and, courtesy of Mr Supaservice, a white Merc with fins. Oh yes, and something seriously macho, something he can only get from some people he half wishes he didn't know ...
</p><p>How, and how well, he pulls it off is the action that propels this funny, acutely observant, completely captivating first novel. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
