<html><head><title>Today in Jerusalem</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr5.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>The state of Jewry</b></p>
<h2>Today in Jerusalem</h2><ul> <li><a href="9ex260.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>ONTROVERSY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> Z<font size=-1>ION</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Geoffrey Wheatcroft. <br>
</ul>

<p>A WELL-INFORMED layman, Geoffrey Wheatcroft guides the reader gently through the thickets of Zionist history and thought without exhausting him with inaccessible detail. His theme is the impact of Zionism on world Jewry. No conclusions are reached at the end of the journey; only a web of paradoxes. Israel has changed the thinking of Jews everywhere. But is Israel the answer to the "Jewish question"?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Wheatcroft is wondrously fair. The Zionist dream was undoubtedly colonialist--and there were voices warning the dreamers of the injustices to come--but the founding fathers were men of their time, the 1890s, which was the heyday of European imperialism. Israel, in its early years, did some terrible things, but its record was no worse than that of other embattled countries forced to defend themselves. Jews have been brutal to Arabs, but Arabs have been even more brutal to one another. His coldest anger is reserved for western governments, particularly America's, which did so little to offer shelter to European Jewry at its direst time--and then proceeded to expiate their offence at the Palestinians' expense.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He delights in ironies and oddities. Theodor Herzl, a founding father, relaxed by listening to the music of Richard Wagner, that eminent anti-Semite. Arthur Balfour, the British foreign secretary who in 1917 declared his government to be in favour of a Jewish national home in Palestine (while ambiguously decreeing that this should not affect "existing non-Jewish communities"), told Cosima Wagner (the composer's widow) that he "shared many of her anti-Semitic postulates." Vladimir Jabotinsky, the advocate of physical force in founding the new state, spent his leisure translating Sherlock Holmes into Hebrew.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How has Israel affected the Jewish diaspora, above all in America? The worst predictions of anti-Zionist Jews have not come to pass: Israel has not endangered Jewish interests or stamped Jews as strangers in their native land. Dual loyalty has not proved an intolerable burden. But, as Mr Wheatcroft argues, there is a problem. Jews in the diaspora are passionate supporters of Israel, but most of them have no intention of living there. This puts them in a false position. Since for their own reasons they do not want the discomfort of making <i>aliyah</i>, they are expected to be not only passionate but also uncritical supporters.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Israel is by no means the normal Central European state that the 19th-century dreamers envisaged. It is an intensely nationalistic country. Other ironies: most Israelis are descended from people who would not have left their homelands for choice; most Jews have not chosen to go to Israel. The establishment of the Jewish state, Mr Wheatcroft argues, has in many ways complicated, not resolved, the Jewish question. And yet: the very existence of Israel makes Jews in the diaspora sleep more secure in their beds: they may not want to go there to live but are glad that it is there.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
