<html><head><title>The Controversy of Zion.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl260.jpg"><img src="cs260.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>ONTROVERSY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> Z<font size=-1>ION</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Geoffrey Wheatcroft. <br>
<i>Sinclair-Stevenson; 396 pages; &#163;17.99</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="9bt260.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
After centuries of dispersion from their ancient home, of persecution and of
degradation, the Jews were gradually emancipated in the nineteenth century But
high hopes were dashed, as antisemitism, stimulated by the new nationalism
sweeping Europe, took over from the old religious Jew-hatred. All too often,
Jews found themselves still despised and rejected, strangers in the land where
they lived, haunted by the 'Jewish Question'.
<p>A succession of Jewish prophets now dreamed a new dream. In 1896, the Viennese journalist Theodor Herzl published The Jewish State. It proposed an astonishing answer to the Jewish question: Jewish nationalism or Zionism. The Jews should recognise that they were not a religious group merely, but a true nation waiting to be reborn. They should return to their ancestral home in the Land of Israel. Meantime, the poor downtrodden Jews of Tsarist Russia were fmding another practical 'Zion' across the Atlantic, and in numbers which would entirely alter the Jewish story.</p>
<p>A 'Jewish homeland' was created in Palestine, which became a Jewish state, though only after the Jewish people had undergone the most terrible catastrophe in their history. This new state was born out of physical struggle, but also after fierce controversy. There were Jews who hated Zionism, and antisemites who welcomed it.</p>
<p>Today, there is a Jewish state which is a source of deep pride to those Jews--the majority--who live outside it. But, as this remarkable and original book shows, it is also a source of anxiety. For all the astonishing achievements of Israel, Zionism did not so much 'answer the Jewish question', as Herzl claimed it would, as complicate it still further. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
