<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>ONTROVERSY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> Z<font size=-1>ION</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Geoffrey Wheatcroft. <br>
<i>Sinclair-Stevenson; 396 pages; &#163;17.99</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="9jb260.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
Geoffrey Wheatcroft is a journalist and author. He was born in London in 1945,
the son of an economist and a social worker, and was educated at University
College School in Hampstead and as a scholar of New College, Oxford, where
he read modern history. He then studied typography before spending several
fruitless years in publishing. He joined the Spectator in 1975 as assistant editor
and in 1977 became literary editor, as well as columnist and reporter.
<p>In 1981 he went to report from South Africa and to write his first book, The Randlords, a history of the South African mining magnates. In 1985 he joined the Evening Standard to edit the 'Londoner's Diary' and subsequently became the paper's opera critic. In 1989 he published Absent Friends, a collection of biographical essays. After several years' writing freelance for various newspapers including the Daily Mail, the Guardian and the Independent on Sunday, as well as American papers and magazines, he is now a columnist with the Daily Express.</p>
<p>He and his wife Sally Muir, a fashion designer, live with their young daughter and son near Bath, where he spends as much time as he can watching cricket and racing, fishing, and collecting books. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
