<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HROUGH</font> F<font size=-1>ORTRESS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> R<font size=-1>OCK</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>TORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> G<font size=-1>ENCOR</font> 1895-1995.<br></h2>
<p> By J.D.F. Jones.<br>
<i> Jonathan Ball (Johannesburg); 277 pages; 135</i> rands<br>
</p><br>
<a href="9jb265.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
JDF Jones is a writer and journalist who is based in London but has been
deeply involved in South Africa for many years. A Welshman, JDF started
working as a journalist after graduating from Balliol College, Oxford. His work
took him to South and East Africa and then to London to the Financial Times,
where he was successively Foreign Editor, Managing Editor, South Africa
Editor, founding Weekend Financial Times Editor, and Arts and Literary
Editor. He continues to contribute to various newspapers, principally the
Financial Times. His recent novel, Freeland, is set in East Africa and a
forthcoming novel concerns the exploits of John Buchan in South Africa in
1905.
