<html><head><title>Through Fortress and Rock</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl265.jpg"><img src="cs265.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HROUGH</font> F<font size=-1>ORTRESS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> R<font size=-1>OCK</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>TORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> G<font size=-1>ENCOR</font> 1895-1995.<br></h2>
<p> By J.D.F. Jones.<br>
<i> Jonathan Ball (Johannesburg); 277 pages; 135</i> rands<br>
</p><br>
<a href="9bt265.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Three young Germans came out to South Africa more than a hundred years
ago to seek their fortune: the brothers George and Leopold Albu, and the
mining engineer Adolf Goerz. They were to found, respectively, General
Mining and Finance Corporation and Union Corporation - the two companies
which would eventually become Gencor, South Africa s second largest business
group, which has today become one of the world's most important mining
houses.
<p>But the Albu brothers - and Goerz, who died young - have been the least recorded of the 'Randlords' who created modern South Africa at the turn of the century. In comparison with Rhodes, Barnato, Beit, and the rest, the Albus have been forgotten. Here, they and their families are resurrected.</p>
<p>This is not a conventional corporate history. JDF Jones has been given a free hand by Gencor in its centenary year to tell - vividly, without discretion - the true story of the group which emerged from the merger of the (Afrikaner) General Mining/Federale Mynbou and the (very English) Union Corporation.</p>
<p>It is a books intended for the general reader, not the specialist, and seeks to set the tale of a giant world corporation against the complex, erratic and sometimes bloody history of South Africa over the same century. JDF Jones believes that the story of one major institution can illustrate, and illuminate, the political and economic history of South Africa in the extraordinary 100 years which span the Jameson Raid to Majority Rule. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
