<html><head><title>Uitlanders</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr9.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>South African mining</b></p>
<h2>Uitlanders</h2><ul> <li><a href="9ex265.html">T<font size=-1>HROUGH</font> F<font size=-1>ORTRESS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> R<font size=-1>OCK</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>TORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> G<font size=-1>ENCOR</font> 1895-1995.&nbsp;  By J.D.F. Jones.<br>
</ul>

<p>AMONG the least known of the 25 "Randlords", the European emigrants who sailed for South Africa in the late 19th century to make their fortunes in the diamond and gold fields, are George and Leopold Albu, the sons of a Berlin coach-builder, and Adolf Goerz, a mining engineer from Mainz. Yet the companies they founded, General Mining and Union Corporation, were the beginnings of what today is Gencor, South Africa's second-biggest mining house and the world's biggest exporter of steam coal and producer of ferrochrome and titanium dioxide.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Goerz died too young to fill out this story, but the travails of General Mining and the Albu brothers, who as teenagers arrived at the Cape and trekked for 28 days in an ox-wagon to Kimberley, provide intriguing insights into South Africa's shifting ethnic snobberies. The Albus were Jewish, as were 13 of the other 23 Randlords. They were also German and backed by German finance. They fell out with the English Randlords, including Cecil Rhodes, when they disapproved of the Jameson Raid of 1895-96 into President Paul Kruger's Transvaal and they further alienated the City of London when they supported the Boers in the 1899-1902 Anglo-Boer war.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;J.D.F. Jones, a former foreign editor of the <i>Financial Times</i>, suggests that George Albu was the perpetual outsider, torn between a desire to be accepted by the English Randlords and a loyalty to his roots. He suffered doubly, as did the more famous Oppenheimers, first from anti-Semitism and then from anti-German sentiment during the first world war. As George Albu rose up the Johannesburg social ladder, his early charitable commitments--to a German hospital, a Jewish orphanage--waned. By the 1930s, with property in London's West End, a grand mansion in Johannesburg and a hunting lodge in the bush, he had turned himself into a thorough Englishman; and got knighted. Like the Oppenheimers, his family today are Christians.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A generation later, a similar quest by ethnic outsiders for acceptance by the clubby English business world took place--this time, by Afrikaners. Until the 1950s they had been regarded by English-speakers as poor whites, South Africa's barefoot bigots. Thanks to the election of the National Party in 1948, and to the clandestine workings of the Afrikaner Broederbond, today's big Afrikaner companies--Rembrandt, Sanlam, Volkskaas--prospered, and with them a new Afrikaner elite. However, the great challenge was the exclusive world of mining, "which for 75 years had featured the English-speaking members of the Chamber of Mines and of its canteen, the Rand Club in Johannesburg."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Wennie du Plessis, an Afrikaner and a Broeder, founded Federale Mynbou in 1953 as a coal-mining concern. But it was William Coetzer who built it up, with the help of state patronage during the apartheid era, into a big diversified mining house which, in 1963, bid for control of the Albus' General Mining. It is often said that Federale Mynbou had Harry Oppenheimer, head of Anglo American, to thank for the deal: he magnanimously sold his stake in General Mining, so the story goes, to help promote Afrikaner business. Mr Jones tells a different tale: Anglo's offer, he says, came with strings that tied Fedmyn to selling its diamonds through De Beers, part of the Oppenheimer empire, and gave De Beers control of any further diamond finds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Only five years later, Tom Muller, the Afrikaner head of the merged General Mining/Federale Mynbou, became president of the Chamber of Mines, a social triumph for Afrikanerdom. By 1980, to the consternation of other English-speaking mining groups, the Afrikaner mining house had seized control of Union Corporation to form Gencor. The symbolism was striking: among the mining houses the <i>arriviste</i> Afrikaners had beaten in the race, a century after the Randlords first arrived on the reef, was Gold Fields of South Africa, heir of Cecil Rhodes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This book has an unintended timeliness. The social tide is shifting again in South Africa. Gencor remains essentially white, but Anglo American is making a great fanfare of selling its stake in a holding company, Johnnic, to black businessmen. However, the really big test of post-apartheid social change will be the appointment of a black head of the Chamber of Mines.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
