<html><head><title>A sightless universe</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="8gr6.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Writers' biographies</b></p>
<h2>A sightless universe</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex223.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>AN</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>IRROR</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> B<font size=-1>OOK</font></a>: A L<font size=-1>IFE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> J<font size=-1>ORGE</font> L<font size=-1>UIS</font> B<font size=-1>ORGES</font>.&nbsp;  By James Woodall. <br>
</ul>


<p>BLIND Milton dreamt of paradise; Jorge Luis Borges, the finest writer Argentina has produced, filled his own blindness with mysterious streets, twilight gardens, metaphysical conundrums, hoaxes, and infinite catalogues of dusty books on the shelves of forgotten libraries. A man who lived to be troubled by Isabel Peron and the Falklands-Malvinas war (memorably described by him as "two bald men fighting over a comb"), remained, to himself, a Victorian, living with his mother into old age and retaining the courtesies and gallantries of the era in which he was born.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His life went on in his head, fiercely and sharply imagined. Outside that, he worked as a librarian, ate soup and steak, took his siesta, worked again, dined with friends, and spent insomniac nights. His journeys round the world to meet his adoring acolytes were sightless from his fifties onwards. On a visit to St Andrews in 1971 he asked to be left to meditate by the North Sea; a friend found him later facing the wrong way, and gently turned him round.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Borges's life was not only defiantly internal; it was a teasing double existence, in which the private man treated the public writer as a different, irritating being. "Borges", the public man, was clever, a bit of a braggart, the lion of caf&eacute; society in Buenos Aires, Geneva, Seville and New York; the private man wished only to stay in his apartment, his mother's son, fingering old maps and manuscripts, keeping out of the light. Although he was obsessed by repetition and tricks of time, he loathed any repetition of himself. From childhood he avoided mirrors, and professed himself afraid even of "crystals, mahogany and limpid water". He dreaded losing control of himself, whether in drink, drugs or sex, and eschewed all of them. Restraint was to be desired in everything; especially in writing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mario Vargas Llosa once commended Borges with saving Spanish from its natural excess. Borges was well equipped to do so, since his first experience of language was English. As a child, he read Cervantes in an English translation and romped through Wells, Twain and Stevenson; as an old man, he loved best to hear the works of Kipling and Gerard Manley Hopkins. His love of English went right to its roots, to Anglo-Saxon and Old Norse, which he began to study in his sixties. The headstone of his grave in Geneva is inscribed <i>"and ne forhtedon na" (</i>and should not be afraid<i>)</i>, a quotation from the Anglo-Saxon "Battle of Maldon". While elsewhere in Latin America the magical-realist writers seemed possessed by heat and fever, flowers and blood, Borges retained always the cool detachment of the European north.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet he believed in magic as deeply as the rest. He did not try to write naturalistic fiction until he was old, insisting there was no "integrity" in it. The typical Borges story (as seen in "Labyrinths", "Fictions", or "The Aleph", his three greatest works) is of a musty volume, discovered in a library, which offers clues to the history of a strange imaginary country. This is fiction dressed as non-fiction, or even as scholarly research, but with an overlay of mischief. Borges once supposed he would write novels, but settled on short stories because they were easier to control. Later he turned to poetry because, blind as he was, he could hold the metrical structures longer in his memory.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is clear that Borges is not an easy biographical subject. The task has become harder in recent years, as his widow and relations have exercised tyrannical control over his estate. Nonetheless, James Woodall makes quite a mess of it. He was frustrated in several avenues of his research, and seems to have sulked as a result, refusing to explore other paths that might have been useful: above all, Borges's own writings. Mr Woodall remarks early on that to try to fish biographical fragments out of the stories is "a dead end". Maybe so, but it is also true that all Borges is in his writings, sprouting like bizarre tendrils out of the mundane life. It would not take great imagination to enjoy the contrast between, say, the precisely described streets and corners of these imaginary worlds and the streets of Buenos Aires, whose tiniest details and moods Borges recognised even when he wandered them in darkness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But like Borges, so often paralysed before real life, Mr Woodall is paralysed before his subject, resorting to mind-numbing lists of literary acquaintances and minor publications, mangling both his own English and Borges's immaculate syntax, and refusing either to give the book a sense of place, or to let it breathe. One particularly important example will suffice. To the west of Buenos Aires, even pressing into its outermost suburbs, lie the vast pampas. Like all Argentines, Borges breathed them and dreamed them. He thrilled himself with gaucho romances, especially the Argentine epic "Martin Fierro"; he recalled that a gunfight witnessed in a dusty pampas town "impressed me far more than the kingdoms of the world". The "horizontal vertigo" of the plains surely influenced the bizarre spatial planes of his earlier stories, just as gaucho violence is strewn through his later ones. Yet the pampas are never once described for the reader, even in Borges's words. Reading this biography, you are made blind yourself; yet not, alas, with Borges's imagination to save you.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
