</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Hitched to a star</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="7gr2.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Lives: Emerson</b></p>
<h2>Hitched to a star</h2><ul> <li><a href="7ex184.html">E<font size=-1>MERSON</font> A<font size=-1>MONG</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> E<font size=-1>CCENTRICS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Carlos Baker. <br>
</ul>

<p>THE lives of the writers, thinkers and hangers-on who surrounded Ralph Waldo Emerson in Concord, Massachusetts, have been dissected so much that the group's central figure is often easy to lose sight of. Even in a work like this, which seeks to put Emerson firmly in his social circle, he towers effortlessly above it: this "celestial", this "beacon", this "god of my idolatry", as Louisa May Alcott called him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The aim of the Concord group was nothing less than the creation of a culture for a brand-new America. And though Emerson was never convinced that his rambunctious young country had found a voice as eloquent, free and sweeping as it deserved, his followers never doubted it had; and it was his.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He took their worship quietly. As the title of one of his early writings, "Society and Solitude", suggests, Emerson was torn between enjoying and fleeing from the company of his fellows. Try as he might to live in out-of-the-way spots, the world found its way to his gate. He believed that these visitors had a right to "the freedom of your inner house"; he also believed, with equal firmness, that he wished to be "alone with the Alone", in "a barn chamber with a salad or a potato". He was seldom so lucky.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To his close friends he showed great kindness, editing their poems, encouraging their writing, secretly paying the rent on smallholdings where they tried, in the ineffectual way of thinkers, to live farmers' lives. But he was instinctively a cold man, and acknowledged it. The moment the conversation became too intense, or the overtures too personal, he could feel "the crystals shoot and the drops solidify". It was much like the discomfort felt by his friend Henry Thoreau when the group squashed into his tiny cabin at Walden Pond for conversation: it was difficult to keep enough distance between them "when they begin to utter the big thoughts in big words".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Big thoughts there were, in plenty. In many ways the title of this excellent life is misleading; for Emerson was no less eccentric than his friends, merely more circumspect. Every member of the group was wrestling, in his or her different way, to understand the nature of divinity, the "God in nature", and man's relation to him (or it). Although not all were fully-flown Transcendentalists as Emerson was, almost all found the established forms of religion unsatisfactory. As Emerson put it, at about the time he resigned his own pastorate in 1832: "How they can make such a fuss about the case and never open it to see the jewel--is strange, is pitiful." On Sundays, when Concord was at church, Emerson would be in the woods, though taking care that nobody saw him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even in the mid-19th century, such insistence on a divine immanence in man and nature, with its implied denial of a personal God, was still eccentric, if not blasphemous. Bronson Alcott, Louisa May's father, had to close down his little school after overdosing his charges with Wordsworth and Plato; Jones Very, a wild young poet, had to be suspended from his Harvard post after announcing that "Christ's second coming was in him". Yet Emerson not only protected these men, but carefully cultivated their enthusiasms. To his death he carried a pocket compass with him, not to know his direction, but "to hold the visible god in my hand".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To many of his followers, the "visible god" was already among them. Margaret Fuller, the editor of the short-lived <i>Dial</i>, in which many of the group's writings first appeared, was besotted with Emerson, forever thrusting her face into his, breathily informing him of the "heaving bosom "of nature, and demanding to know whether he loved her. Thoreau, in his strong grey trousers, suited for climbing trees or wading into ponds, a man possessed with "this maggot of Freedom", took the room at the top of the stairs in Emerson's house, happily becoming his odd-job man. Even the quietly sceptical Nathaniel Hawthorne, who first appears in this book with his hat over his handsome eyes, observing the "terrible giant Transcendentalist" at a party, becomes enmeshed with him. Emerson's comment in his journal after Hawthorne's death in 1864 is typical and affecting: "It was easy to talk with him--there were no barriers;--only, he said so little, that I talked too much."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is easy to be moved by these pages. Carlos Baker's triumph in this biography, which was published posthumously, is to draw the reader so deeply into the circle that he, too, becomes a member of it. When characters go off to Europe (many still believing that American culture is too thin a gruel to sustain them), they are missed; when they die, there is genuine regret at their disappearance. And nothing is more unsettling than the decay of the great central tree, Emerson himself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He lived long enough--79 years--to mourn the death of Lincoln, and stayed open-minded long enough to welcome with unreserved joy the appearance of Walt Whitman's "Leaves of Grass" in 1855. Here at last, he believed, was a distinctive poetry worthy of America, words that could "cut and bleed", as he liked them to: even if, as he wrote to Carlyle, some of Whitman's passages "read like an auctioneer's inventory of a warehouse". But in the end it was words that deserted him, so that he could not remember even the name of his wife, and once called his dressing gown "the red chandelier". A year or so before his death, one of his acolytes noted with surprise an "earthliness" in him. The god was, after all, human; Concord was not the promised land. But it had come close enough.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
