<html><head><title>Crystal-ball(s)?</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="7gr8.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Global economy</b></p>
<h2>Crystal-ball(s)?</h2><ul> <li><a href="7ex187.html">M<font size=-1>ARKET</font> U<font size=-1>NBOUND</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Lowell Bryan and Diana Farrell. <br>
</ul>

<p>THE authors work for McKinsey, which is arguably the world's most successful management consultancy. It earns its living by selling advice to big companies. To stay big in today's economy you have to know (or guess) not only how many people are going to buy your product tomorrow. You must also know (or take a line on) what is likely to happen virtually everywhere in the world--and not simply tomorrow but over the next ten or 20 years. So in order to satisfy anxious and demanding clients, McKinsey needs to think big thoughts about things to come.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A lot of this thinking goes on under the aegis of what McKinsey calls its global institute, a think-tank in Washington, <font size=-1>DC</font>. It has published several impressive studies, most notably on productivity. This book, a more accessible version of a technical report put out last year, is nothing if not ambitious. It tries to answer two complex questions. How much bigger and how much more integrated can the world's financial markets be? And what is their growing power likely to mean for governments?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lowell Bryan knows about banks and Diana Farrell about financial services, so it is hardly surprising that they see in the swelling power of financial markets a force mainly for good. This is because, on their projections, the rich world's citizens are about to save a lot more money just as the developing world, having embraced market economics, is bursting with juicy investment chances. Both worlds might therefore be blessed: the poor with a "productivity transfusion" of capital and know-how; the rich with fat investment returns to see people through old age.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So is everything for the best in the best of all possible financial worlds? The McKinsey forecasters are not so bullish. The rich world's governments may yet mess things up, they believe: many rich countries, having granted their citizens large welfare entitlements, are borrowing ever-larger amounts to pay for them rather than increasing taxes or reducing benefits.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If, their argument goes on, governments resort to printing money to finance their deficits or, worse still, default, they may cause "havoc" in the markets, with horrid political and social consequences. Even if havoc is avoided, such governments might, by adopting bad policies, force their citizens' savings to be spent on consumption instead of the profitable investment that is newly available in the developing world.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many pundits worry that financial markets are undermining governments' power. What worries these soothsayers is that politicians may undermine the inexorably growing power of financial markets. Some readers might sense a contradiction: if the markets are becoming so powerful, how can the policies of governments overwhelm them? The authors' bluff answer is that the economic strength of governments now consists mainly of the Samsonite power to destroy: they will find it increasingly difficult to control exchange rates or domestic interest rates as the global financial market grows in relation to the real economy. But governments, the authors argue, are still able to bring the temple crashing down upon people's heads--a bleak view of the role of politics.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
