<html><head><title>The Last Stand</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl96.jpg"><img src="cs96.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>AST</font> S<font size=-1>TAND</font><br></h2>
<p>By David Harris.<br>
<i>Times Books</i>;<i> 373 pages</i>;<i> $25</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="4bt96.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>Here is a compelling American tale--a story of greed gone wild. This is the saga of the takeover of the Pacific Lumber Company, and how a small Northern California town was divided against itself; as told by a master storyteller.
</p><p>The fight begins when the Pacific Lumber Company, operated by the Murphy family since 1904 with a strong tradition of both employee care and selective cutting of the last privately held redwood forest in America, is bought out by the huge Texas-based conglomerate Maxxam, Inc. (financed in part by Michael Milken). Eager to cash in on the thousands of acres of valuable lumber, the new owners sharply increase production. When members of the radical environmentalist group Earth First! get involved, strapping themselves to the giant redwoods to halt cutting, the battle becomes explosive. But for all the financial maneuvers, demonstrations, and lawsuits, it's a battle nobody wins.
</p><p>The Last Stand is a story of greed, fanaticism, and devotion that ranges from the paneled boardrooms overlooking Wall Street and Rodeo Drive to the banks of the Eel River, and that races through the mountains hiding the nation's most infamous marijuana-growing industry, and also curves past Pacific Lumber's cavernous mills, source of the great majority of the world's high-grade redwood lumber. By chronicling the takeover of Pacific Lumber, David Harris gives us a metaphor for the disappearance of an arguably more gentle, kinder capitalism-- a capitalism that, in large measure, was responsible for an America now under siege. The Last Stand is a book about how some people, often against their will, end up killing the very thing that had long given them sustenance and shelter-- the forest itself. It is, finally, about what Wall Street does to Main Street and what progress does to the planet.
</p><p>If John Ford were alive, he would make The Last Stand into a thrilling Western, for its every part stands as a metaphor for a war now raging across the country: a battle for the very soul of the nation. David Harris brings his astonishing literary gifts, as well as his own moral passion and keen eye for nuance and human complexity to this riveting and important story. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
