<html><head><title>Spare that tree</title></head>
<!-- Changed by: manar hussain, 19-Jul-1996 -->
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>American redwoods</b></p>
<h2>Spare that tree</h2><ul><li><a href="4ex96.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>AST</font> S<font size=-1>TAND</font></a>&nbsp; By David Harris.<br>
</ul>

<p>LONG before anybody knew how to spell ecology, Pacific Lumber Company was a model forestry and logging firm as well as a model of corporate paternalism. It was also the owner of the last big swathes of old-growth redwood forest in private hands until it fell foul of the greedy takeover culture of the 1980s. Its capture by Charles Hurwitz, a Texan obsessed with cash-flow, signalled the end of an era and the beginning of a struggle.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At stake were the remaining giant redwood trees, <i>sequoia sempervirens</i>, of California's coastal forests. Some of them were more than 1,000 years old; many of them were more than 200 feet (60 metres) high and 15 feet wide. Under the Murphy family, members of which operated the firm from 1904 onwards, these prize assets were treated with deference. For decades Pacific Lumber practised "selective" cutting of its trees rather than the ugly "clear-cutting" technique favoured by so much of the North American industry. And it had a policy of never cutting more timber than its lands' new growth, ensuring that it would always have trees to cut.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To corporate raiders in the 1980s, however, the company was a steal. Its share price under-valued its assets, particularly if new owners could speed up production and raid its rich pension fund. Sure enough, in February 1986 Pacific Lumber was taken over by Maxxam, a conglomerate owned by Mr Hurwitz. Shortly thereafter the company began to cut down trees as fast as its mills could cut them up. Cash-flow, not old growth, was the mantra of the new managers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first half of David Harris's engaging account shows how Pacific Lumber stumbled into losing its independence. Its board was remarkably naive, hiring investment bankers but giving them an incentive to sell the firm for the highest price. It failed to make use of what appeared to be strong defences against takeover.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for Mr Hurwitz, he played a weak hand with great skill. In retrospect his leveraged takeover was a classic of the 1980s. The deal's sponsors were Michael Milken and Drexel Burnham Lambert, the pioneers of the junk-bond market. According to Mr Harris, Mr Hurwitz's allies also included Ivan Boesky, an arbitrageur, and Boyd Jeffries, a broker, both of whom subsequently served criminal sentences for various offences.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second half of "The Last Stand" chronicles the takeover's aftermath. Mr Hurwitz's tactics were countered by activist greens in California. They fought physically and in the courts against the predatory behaviour of Pacific Lumber. In so doing, they drew national attention to the plight of the redwoods.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This fine and occasionally sinister tale is ultimately depressing. Greed remains the dominant ethos in the logging industry. Pacific Lumber has been broken into separate entities, and efforts to preserve the old-growth trees as a national park have faltered. Mr Harris's title is apt.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
