<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>W<font size=-1>HY</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> E<font size=-1>ARTH</font> Q<font size=-1>UAKES</font><br></h2>
<p>By Matthys Levy and Mario Salvadori.<br>
<i>Norton; 215 pages; $25</i> <i>and &#163;18.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="4jb71.html">Jacket Copy</a><br>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>MATTHYS LEVY, an architectural engineer and principal of Weidlinger Associates, one of America's leading structural engineering firms, has won numerous awards, including the ASCE Innovation in Civil Engineering Award. MARIO SALVADORI, author of Why Buildings Stand Up, is James Renwick Professor Emeritus of Civil Engineering and Professor Emeritus of Architecture at Colombia University and the recipient of numerous awards including the Hoover Medal from the ASCE. Levy and Salvadori are also coauthors of Why Building Fall Down. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
