<html><head><title>Why the Earth Quakes</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl71.jpg"><img src="cs71.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>W<font size=-1>HY</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> E<font size=-1>ARTH</font> Q<font size=-1>UAKES</font><br></h2>
<p>By Matthys Levy and Mario Salvadori.<br>
<i>Norton; 215 pages; $25</i> <i>and &#163;18.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="4bt71.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p><p>WHY THE EARTH QUAKES</p>
</p><p>We expect anything to move, but not the earth! And we certainly do not expect mountains to throw the earth's innards into the sky! Nothing is as frightening as to feel the earth shake under our feet or to see flaming lava spew from unknown depths, moving mercilessly towards us.
</p><p>The aim of the authors of this book, who have personally experienced such terrifying catastrophes, is to demystify their causes and to explain in layman's terms not only their origins but how, at long last, we may defend ourselves from the powerful assaults of earthquakes and volcanoes.
</p><p>By exploring the miracle of the universe's creation, Why the Earth Quakes leads the reader through a brief, fascinating voyage to the birth and growth of our planet with its cracked and constantly shifting crust.
</p><p>The origins of earthquakes and volcanoes, often called the crucibles of creation, are explained through the stories of the worst natural disasters of all time: Lisbon, 1755, which was ravaged by the destructive force of a tsunami; San Francisco in 1906, whose fires left over 500 dead, 5,000 injured, and 100,000 homeless in its wake; Alaska in 1964, the largest recorded earthquake in North America, which deformed a larger area of the earth's surface than any other quake in history; Vesuvius, which buried the ancient cities of Herculaneum and Pompeii in A.D. 79; Krakatau, its huge clouds of ash in 1883 gave the world a true foretaste of a "nuclear winter"; Mount St. Helens, which destroyed an entire mountain and killed 61 people in 1980; and Kobe, which left over 5,000 dead and over 20,000 injured in 1995. These are the names of some of the earth-shaking events that form the background for an exploration of the nature of earthquakes and volcanoes, the prediction of their behavior, and an up-to- date description of the measures we can take, socially and personally, to protect ourselves from their destructive nature.
</p><p>Technical issues needed to understand the behavior of earthquakes and volcanoes such as plate tectonics and seismic gaps are explained in clear and concise terms. Over one hundred illustrations clarify them for both the general reader and the professional. One section of the book is dedicated to answering the most commonly asked questions about how to be ready and avoid the worst consequences of our earth's onslaughts. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
