<html><head><title>Shock tactics</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="4gr11.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Earthquakes</b></p>
<h2>Shock tactics</h2><ul><li><a href="4ex71.html">W<font size=-1>HY</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> E<font size=-1>ARTH</font> Q<font size=-1>UAKES</font></a>&nbsp; By Matthys Levy and Mario Salvadori.<br>
</ul>


<p>IN KAMCHATKA, the inhabitants blamed a monstrous dog; in Chile, legend told of two tussling snakes. Buried bulls, elephants, frogs and fish have all had their proponents. Matthys Levy and Mario Salvadori are more hard-headed as they seek to explain why earthquakes happen. They skim through the mythology and press on through the history of the world's greatest quakes to summarise modern seismic theory--and its lessons for architects, engineers and town planners.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Those lessons were sharpened last year when the Hanshin earthquake flattened much of Kobe in Japan, killing 5,000 people and leaving 300,000 homeless. Geological mistakes had diverted the attention of seismologists to a region north of Kobe. Civil planners had allowed elevated highways to be supported on poorly reinforced concrete columns. Building codes in Japan and other countries were re-examined after many more buildings in Kobe collapsed than engineers had believed likely, just as they were after the Northridge quake hit southern California a year earlier.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Why the Earth Quakes" cites both the Northridge and Kobe disasters in describing how hard it is to prepare for earthquakes--and how important it is to do so. In Northridge a programme (conceived after a 1971 earthquake in San Fernando) was in train to add steel jackets to the columns that support elevated freeways. The columns already strengthened survived almost unharmed in the quake.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To survive earthquakes, structures must be flexible enough to absorb some shaking, though not so rubbery as to wave in the wind and become uncomfortable. Modern construction methods also include springy foundations and hydraulic pumps to isolate buildings from the ground, and so let them float free of terrestrial infirmity. The eight-storey Los Angeles University Hospital had a bed of lead-and-rubber buffers which absorbed most of the motion of the Northridge quake, and it was the only emergency hospital able to run properly immediately afterwards.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Levy, an architectural engineer, and Mr Salvadori, a professor of civil engineering, explain well how these things are done. But theirs is not a textbook. It provides simple accounts of the basic principles of seismically sound construction, supported by large, clear diagrams.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The same approach--short, simple chapters and plenty of illustration--is used to explain the geological causes of earthquakes. Plate tectonics is polished off, volcanoes enthusiastically explored, <i>tsunamis </i>(tidal waves) described. The authors even provide a 12-page cosmology to explain the fiery mantle on which the tectonic plates float and grind against each other.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As an introduction to the wide range of earthquake lore, the book works. Readers comfortably settled far from seismic danger will find the authors' enthusiasm enjoyable; those whose ten-storey brick homes lie closer to faults will hope that an enjoyable book never becomes useful.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
