<html><head><title>Never better</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Human welfare</b></p>
<h2>Never better</h2><ul><li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>TATE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> H<font size=-1>UMANITY</font></a>&nbsp; Edited by Julian Simon.<br>
</ul>


<p>RELAX. You might think everything is getting worse. In fact, almost everything--the environment, health, living conditions--has been getting steadily better since records began, and will probably continue to do so. That is the thesis of "The State of Humanity".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Julian Simon, an American academic who has a reputation for annoying the greens, has written the introduction and conclusion. His opinions sandwich 56 chapters, each penned by a different expert, most of whom rely on statistics rather than mere opinion to make their point.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some of the improvements in human welfare should lighten the mood of the most glum. For many millennia, life expectancy at birth hovered around the mid-20s. Over the past few centuries it has increased to over 70 years in many parts of the world. Much of this rise is due to the defeat of smallpox, typhus, scarlet fever, bubonic plague and other deadly diseases. Medical knowledge, sewerage, better nutrition--such advances have made people healthier than ever before. Those who worry about today's rapid rate of population growth often forget that it has been driven by a wonderful trend: a big fall in the death rate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other cheerful trends include the spread of education (since the 1960s the proportion of children enrolled in school has risen, in rich and poor countries alike), durable economic growth in most parts of the world and an increase in food production in line with population growth.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The book's weakness is not the quality of its analysis. Sufficient evidence is usually cited to demonstrate the benign nature of this or that trend. Its flaw lies instead in the selection of trends. One chapter, for example, concentrates on the standard of living of black Americans, showing that it has improved dramatically over the past century or so. This misses the point: inequality. Black Americans still lag behind whites in many ways: they earn less, suffer higher rates of unemployment and live shorter lives. Similarly, in pointing to better standards of health and welfare in poor countries these smug experts obscure the huge gap between the rich and poor worlds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They are also almost exclusively concerned with long-run trends, even when these mask short-run catastrophes. In his conclusion, Mr Simon verges on bad taste when he points out that the Black Death interrupted economic progress and population growth merely for a century or so. He is right to argue that people are too ready to believe doomsayers, but fails to recognise that gloom has its uses. Dire warnings have averted disasters. Food productivity rose in the 1970s partly because fear of famine spurred governments to subsidise agricultural research. Similarly, fear of global warming is now encouraging research into ways of reducing the cost of clean fuels. If human progress is inevitable, that may be because humans are always worrying about what might go wrong.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
