<html><head><title>The Heart of the Game.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl286.jpg"><img src="cs286.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> H<font size=-1>EART</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> G<font size=-1>AME</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Paul Hemphill. <br>
<i>Simon &amp; Schuster; 288 pages; $23</i>.<br>
</p><br>
<a href="9bt286.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
In early April 1993, Paul Hemphill hopped in his car, drove right past Atlanta-
Fulton County Stadium--home of the major-league Atlanta Braves--and
continued south, ninety miles down I-75, to attend the home opener of the
Macon Braves, a Class A affiliate of the Atlanta Braves franchise. It's not that
he had grown tired of baseball; he was just weary of the bickering and excesses
of the major league game. By attending the home opener of the minor-league
Macon Braves, Hemphill was looking for the heart of the game.
<p>For every spoiled and selfish major-league ballplayer who sneers at the fans and neglects the details of his craft, there are dozens of eager, earnest, hard- working kids toiling in the minors, dreaming of the moment they will someday "crack the show." Down in the minor leagues, uncorrupted by money and greed, the game is played by kids just out of high school or college; kids still learning how to live on their own, struggling to get by on meager salaries, and learning through the endless daily repetition of drills, practice, and the games themselves--what being a professional baseball player is all about.</p>
<p>One such kid is Marty Malloy, a 5' 10", 160-pound, scrappy second baseman working his way through the Braves' farm system. Hardworking, resilient, and gritty, Marty Malloy is a throwback to a time when the game was played with love and desire, when the only kind of strike the players knew was the one that blind umpire called against them the night before. Not blessed with overwhelming physical abilities, but burning with the desire to learn, Marty is the physical embodiment of every boy's dream of playing professional ball.</p>
<p>In The Heart of the Game, Paul Hemphill takes us through Marty's 1994 minor- league season with the Class A Durham Bulls--the same season that was abruptly called to a halt at the major-league level. We see Marty's daily struggles as he attempts to make his way through the Braves' system: his trouble hitting lefthanded pitching, his need to master the double-play pivot, his difficulty coping with life on the road, and his struggle to make ends meet on his $1,100 a month salary. By watching Marty overcome these hardships and merit a promotion to the next level, we learn about the love, the desire, the hard work and the effort that go into the making of every ballplayer, superstar or not.</p>
<p>With charm, grace, and style, Paul Hemphill tells this story like no one else can. Once a second baseman himself, Hemphill enjoyed a very brief career in the minor leagues. Now, we ride with him as he follows Marty's fledgling baseball career through all of its ups and downs. To watch Marty Malloy drop a bunt down the third base line, or elude the flashing spikes of a runner hoping to break up a doubleplay, or recklessly chase a foul ball into the brick wall that surrounds the field, is to remember what we first loved about the game of baseball, and to realize that while big stars come and go, it's the prospect who represents the heart and soul of the game itself. In a book that lilts with the sultry rhythms of a baseball summer, Paul Hemphill brilliantly chronicles the education of a minor league ballplayer--and through him, of all who play the game. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
