<DOCNO>WT22-B01-247</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000277-B036-117</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev9/rv2/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113181419 text/html 10956
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:10:31 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 12-Sep-96 11:02:47 GMT
Content-length: 10770
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Rough diamonds</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr2.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Baseball dreams run up against reality</b></p>
<h2>Rough diamonds</h2>

<p><b>America's national pastime continues to inspire more good yarns than other sports</b></p><ul> <li><a href="9ex286.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> H<font size=-1>EART</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> G<font size=-1>AME</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Paul Hemphill. <br>
 <li>A<font size=-1>T</font> F<font size=-1>ENWAY</a>:</font> D<font size=-1>ISPATCHES</font> <font size=-1>FROM</font> R<font size=-1>ED</font> S<font size=-1>OX</font> N<font size=-1>ATION</font>.&nbsp;  By Dan Shaughnessy.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Crown; 241 pages; $24</i>. <br>
 <li>W<font size=-1>RIGLEYVILLE</a>:</font> A M<font size=-1>AGICAL</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font> T<font size=-1>OUR</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> C<font size=-1>HICAGO</font> C<font size=-1>UBS</font>.&nbsp;  By Peter Golenbock.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>St Martin's Press; 540 pages; $24.95</i>. <br>
 <li>T<font size=-1>HIS</font> S<font size=-1>IDE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> C<font size=-1>OOPERSTOWN</font><i></a>:</i> A<font size=-1>N</font> O<font size=-1>RAL</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> M<font size=-1>AJOR</font> L<font size=-1>EAGUE</font> B<font size=-1>ASEBALL</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> 1950s. By Larry Moffi. <i>University of Iowa Press; 262 pages; $24.95</i>.<i> Distributed in Britain by </i> <i> &#163;23.95.</i> &nbsp; <i></i>  <br>
 <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> G<font size=-1>AME</font> T<font size=-1>HAT</font> W<font size=-1>AS</a>:</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> G<font size=-1>EORGE</font> B<font size=-1>RACE</font> P<font size=-1>HOTO</font> C<font size=-1>OLLECTION</font>.&nbsp;  By Richard Cahan and Mark Jacob.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Contemporary Books; 246 pages; $35. Distributed in UK by Gazelle &#163;31.99</i> <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

<p>"BULL DURHAM" marked a turning point--not so much in the history of baseball as in the history of baseball nostalgia. Most earlier baseball films had treated the sport reverently. On-screen players faced adversity and indulged occasionally in disreputable behaviour, but Hollywood's overall view of baseball differed little from baseball's view of itself--that is, as a sport that ranks as dear to Americans as dad and pumpkin pie.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Bull Durham" was different. With one brief but memorable exchange the film sliced through the sap encrusting the sport's image. A young batboy hands a wizened veteran, Crash Davis (Kevin Costner), a bat with a heartfelt, "Get a hit!"--the kind of exhortation familiar to anybody who has ever seen a baseball movie. In this version, though, Crash tells the kid to "Shut up!" Utterly unexpected, these words check nostalgia with reality.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thankfully, several recent baseball books have managed to carry on the flame lit in 1988 by "Bull Durham": portraying baseball's sins with enough sensitivity and intelligence to heighten, rather than obscure, the sport's innate charms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Inspired but imperfect, one of these, "The Heart of the Game: The Education of a Minor-League Ballplayer", is written by Paul Hemphill whose short-lived drive for baseball fame laid the groundwork for a novel, "Long Gone", about a fictional 1950s team called the Tampico Stogies. (A year before "Bull Durham", "Long Gone" was made into a film that was all but overlooked at the time.)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Hemphill decided to write "The Heart of the Game" as a reaction to the sport's labour-management strife and the arrogance of its players (he had watched an autograph-seeking youngster get stiffed by a millionaire outfielder). Searching for solace in the minor leagues, Mr Hemphill stumbled upon Marty Malloy, a second-baseman who reminded him of himself as a young man. Mr Hemphill decided to spend a season hanging around Mr Malloy and his teammates on (appropriately enough) the real-life Durham Bulls.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The story line is promising: how does a baseball-obsessed youngster not only manage to climb the sport's treacherous career ladder but also learn to live on his own, far from his close-knit family? Mr Hemphill carries it off with mixed success.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He paints a convincing portrait of Mr Malloy's isolated upbringing in Trenton, Florida, and his family's devotion to his career. He also airs serious issues--Marty's out-of-wedlock child and the probable racism of his father--without upsetting the baseball-driven story. And he shows, briefly but successfully, how wise old baseball men serve as surrogate fathers to rookies--until they have to fire most of them for not being good enough ballplayers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, Mr Hemphill's reach exceeds his grasp. Having chosen Mr Malloy as his subject, he is stuck with him, and although Mr Malloy may be an Everyman, he is not a compelling one. Mr Hemphill surely must have understood this: he quotes him directly only a half-dozen times, and not for more than a sentence or two. Marty Malloy would be the first to admit that he is no intellectual, and that is hardly a sin. But the reader expects a little more self-awareness in a 288-page exposition of somebody's life.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike Mr Malloy, Dan Shaughnessy's Boston Red Sox, in "At Fenway", often fall victim to over-intellectualisation. Although their record is not nearly as poor as that of some of their rivals, they inspire unparalleled fatalism among their supporters (perhaps a reflection of the region's puritanical heritage). Ivy-league professors regularly appear on television to wax philosophical about Boston's cursed Red Sox, who have not won the World Series since 1912, the year their fabled Fenway Park was built.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fortunately, Mr Shaughnessy, a columnist with the <i>Boston Globe</i>, has covered the team for long enough to have acquired a sceptical as well as a loving eye. He good-naturedly pokes fun at the antics of the "Red Sox Nation", and tells his readers to adore not only the majesty of Fenway's "Green Monster" left-field wall but also the advertisement that predated the wall's famed coat of green paint. "The Red Sox Use Lifebuoy Soap," the ad read; Mr Shaughnessy reports that fans used to snicker, "The Red Sox use Lifebuoy, but they still stink."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Best of all is Mr Shaughnessy's story-telling, about everyone from maniacal statisticians to doomed ballplayers to over-eager partisans. Consider Monte Dutton, a Red Sox fan who named a lamb on his farm in South Carolina "Fenway". After watching a Red Sox first-baseman, Bill Buckner, let a crucial ball go through his legs during the 1986 World Series--an event that soon came to embody the team's jinxed nature--Mr Dutton discovered that Fenway had died during the game. "The Silence of the Lamb," Mr Shaughnessy deadpans. Baseball fans are certainly the richer for this weird and whimsical collection.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Probably the only rivals to the Red Sox in the pantheon of lovable baseball losers are the Chicago Cubs of Wrigley Field. Peter Golenbock, an established baseball chronicler, has produced an encyclopedic, 74-chapter history of the team since the 1876 World Series. It will put Cubs fans in nirvana, but strike anyone else as virtually unreadable. The pages are so densely packed that the best that can be said for the book is that some enterprising writer might one day use it as the basis for a Shaughnessy-style "At Wrigley".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Larry Moffi's "This Side of Cooperstown" manages to escape Mr Golenbock's trap, in part because its reach is much more modest. Designed as a history of baseball in the 1950s, it features interviews with 17 retired players who exhibited modest skills on the field. Mr Moffi presents their reminiscences almost unfiltered, an approach that does not allow for much authorial analysis. Yet this low-intensity narrative serves well, providing players with the opportunity to ramble on, something that usually turns out to be a pleasure.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even more pleasurable than hearing the jabber of old-timers is a chance to look at their photographs. "The Game That Was" provides that pleasure in spades. Snapped over several decades by George Burke and George Brace of Chicago, these 376 images languished in Mr Brace's filing cabinets until two Chicago newspaper editors convinced him to co-operate on a book.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Its design and text are marvels of intelligence, taste and restraint. The reproductions are crisp, the layout is austere and the captions find precisely the right words--and not one more--to encapsulate each image's significance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Particularly poignant are the thematic sections. Early Wynn earns a place in the book's "tough guy" grouping for replying, when asked if he would throw at his own mother, "It would depend on how well she was hitting." Dale "Moose" Alexander qualifies as a "tough loss" not merely for injuring his knee while sliding home but for being burned by a trainer who mishandled the electric equipment he used to treat the player. Mr Alexander, who got gangrene and almost lost his leg, recalls matter-of-factly: "I was finished in the majors." The authors assign Sig Jakucki to the "notorious" bunch for his response to a request from a one-armed teammate, Pete Gray, for assistance: "Tie your own goddamned shoes, you one-armed son of a bitch." Even Crash Davis might have winced at that.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
