<html><head><title>Single portions</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="8gr3.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Living alone</b></p>
<h2>Single portions</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex224.html">H<font size=-1>ERMITS</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> I<font size=-1>NSIGHTS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>OLITUDE</font>.&nbsp;  By Peter France. <br>
</ul>

<p>IN FEBRUARY 1965 a refrigerator was delivered to Thomas Merton's hermitage. It bothered him: after all, he had spent many years hoping that his monastic superiors would allow him to live alone, and it did not seem right that a hermit should use a fridge. The apparently frivolous issue of how many domestic appliances a hermit needs prompted, says Peter France, one of Merton's most important insights into the solitary life, namely that it can be judged only by the inner experience, not by the external surroundings. Trappings have little to do with Trappists.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In his elegant, witty and instructive book, Mr France describes the importance of a solitary life by means of a study of some of those who have best lived it. He does not pretend to have written a full, historical survey of hermits--deliberately, he includes nothing at all about the great western medieval mystics. Instead, he leads his reader round his personal mentors, in a vast circle that begins, and ends, with the Taoist ideals of the fifth century <font size=-1>BC</font> for which Merton developed an enthusiasm. According to the Tao, something superior to society is waiting to be discovered in solitude. It is a dream as old as humanity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There have been many who lived holy, lonely lives of whom virtually nothing is known and little can be said. But an odd element in the whole adventure is that, often, men who choose to cast themselves out of society are sought after by the rest of humanity for advice on how best to live within it. The classic example is St Antony the Great, who in search of seclusion pressed ever further into the Egyptian desert only to emerge after 20 years to share his wisdom with a hungry world. Such men speak little of their own asceticism or even of their spiritual experiences. Their demeanour is their lesson. Mr France uses the touching words of a great scholar, Helen Waddell, to describe the impression left by the desert fathers: "It was their humility, their gentleness, their heart-breaking courtesy that was the seal of their sanctity to their contemporaries, far beyond abstinence, or miracle, or sign."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One early hero was Crates, a pupil of Diogenes. He sold all his lands and left his money deposited in a bank, with the instructions that, if his sons grew up to become ordinary, ignorant people, they would inherit it; if, on the other hand, they blossomed into philosophers, his money was to be given to the poor. Though not exactly a hermit, Crates seemed to have had the right--or at least an interesting--idea.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Charles de Foucauld made the decision for himself, a hundred years ago. He was a great character. By the time he was 20 he was immensely rich, fat and self-indulgent, preferring to step into a low-slung carriage after a good dinner so as not to have to make too much effort lifting his foot. Yet his conversion experience was so powerful that by the end of his life he was a poor, zealous missionary to the Tuaregs, a latter-day desert father whose rule is still followed by the Little Brothers of Christ.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The rich were, of course, not ever thus. In the 18th century, there seemed no need to do something yourself if you could pay someone else to do it for you. In an enjoyable interlude, Mr France wanders into the terrain of the ornamental hermit, employed to wear a long beard and hold an hour-glass as part of the garden furniture of a large estate. He even provides suggestions from a textbook for suitable abodes for such employees, ranging from the humble, mossy hut to the full, top-of-the-range, six-roomed, shell-lined Gothick grotto. An early flowering of political correctness put paid to such mutually lucrative ventures, and the hermit was replaced by a disappointing dummy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But it would be unfair to leave this book on that note. After the Greek philosophers, the monks of Mount Athos and the <i>startsy</i> of Russia, it is best to return to Thomas Merton. "The hermit", he wrote, "has a very real place in a world like ours that has degraded the human person and lost all respect for that awesome loneliness in which each single spirit must confront the living God." Not everyone would put it that way. But Merton's reflections on solitude will stir many readers, just as they have obviously moved Mr France.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
