<html><head><title>Economic enlightenment</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h2>Economic enlightenment</h2>
<p><b>Sound economic policy draws on analysis by good economists and on history's lessons. "Books in Brief" looks at recent contributions in both areas</b></p><ul> <li><a href="#1">G<font size=-1>ETTING IT</font> R<font size=-1>IGHT</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Robert Barro. <br>
 <li><a href="#2">P<font size=-1>OP</font> I<font size=-1>NTERNATIONALISM</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Paul Krugman. <br>
 <li><a href="#3">M<font size=-1>ANAGING</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> B<font size=-1>RITISH</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMY</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> 1960s.</a>&nbsp;  By Sir Alec Cairncross.<br>
 <li><a href="#4">I<font size=-1>NTERNATIONAL</font> M<font size=-1>ONETARY</font> C<font size=-1>O-OPERATION SINCE </font>B<font size=-1>RETTON</font> W<font size=-1>OODS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Harold James. <br>
</ul>

</td></tr></table>
<a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>G<font size=-1>ETTING IT</font> R<font size=-1>IGHT</font>.<br>
 By Robert Barro. <br>
<i>MIT </i><i>Press; 208 pages;</i> <i>$20 and &#163;14.95</i>.<br>
</td></tr></table>
<a name="2"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>P<font size=-1>OP</font> I<font size=-1>NTERNATIONALISM</font>.<br>
 By Paul Krugman. <br>
<i> Press; 240 pages; $22.50 and &#163;14.95</i><br>


<p>ECONOMISTS are widely, and often accurately, accused of being unable to write. These top American academics are refreshing exceptions. Both have produced sets of essays written for non-economists; their pieces combine sophisticated economic reasoning with simple, lucid and even humorous prose.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Getting it Right" is based on articles written by Robert Barro for the <i>Wall Street Journal</i> since 1991. It ranges from a discussion of the impact of democracy on economic growth to the economics of regulating smoking and of term limits for incumbent politicians. The unifying theme is provided by Mr Barro's classically liberal outlook (which emphasises the importance of property rights, free markets and minimal government intervention) and by rigorous analysis.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whether the subject is monetary policy in Latin America, tax rises under the Clinton administration or the merits of regulation to save endangered species, these essays apply basic premises of economic reasoning (eg, that people behave rationally, that markets are the most efficient way to allocate resources) to reach logically impeccable conclusions. Many of the essays--including the one that advances powerful arguments in favour of index-linked bonds as a way for governments to borrow--are currently topical.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Paul Krugman's offering is more breezy in style, more provocative in tone and more narrow in scope. His aim is to undermine "pop internationalism"--a term he coined for the (mistaken) conventional wisdom that he feels has replaced serious discussion of world trade. This takes several forms. It includes the common misconceptions that countries are locked in an economic battle with each other and that third-world growth threatens rich countries. Its hallmarks, according to Mr Krugman, are the use of glib assertion, the misuse of statistics and a failure to understand basic trade theory.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Krugman's crusade against "pop internationalists" is both warranted and well-executed. Much popular discussion of international trade is economically illiterate. He is right to point out, for instance, that the oft-used analogy of a country "competing" in the global market in the same way that a firm "competes" is nonsense. A country whose productivity increases more slowly than others will grow more slowly (and become relatively poorer). It will not go out of business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Several of the articles reproduced in the book caused a stir when they were first published and still merit attention now. One is a prescient speech Mr Krugman gave in Mexico city in 1993 predicting the devaluation of the peso. Each is worth reading. But you can have too much of a good thing. Taken as a whole, it must be said, this collection is repetitious, and Mr Krugman's arrogant tone eventually begins to grate.
</td></tr></table>
<a name="3"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>M<font size=-1>ANAGING</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> B<font size=-1>RITISH</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMY</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> 1960s.<br>
 By Sir Alec Cairncross.<br>
<i> Macmillan</i>; <i>275 pages; &#163;45</i><br>

<p>SIR ALEC CAIRNCROSS was at the heart of British economic policymaking throughout the 1960s, first as economic adviser to the British government between 1961 and 1964 and then as head of the Government Economic Service from 1964 to 1969. So at one level this is a fascinating, and highly personal, account of Britain's decade of "stop and go" economic policies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a deftly woven tale of successive chancellors (first Conservative, then Labour) who were united in their emphasis on economic growth, their belief that demand management was the best way to achieve it, and their failure to deal with balance-of-payments problems until it was too late. With clarity and candour, Sir Alec charts Britain's lurches from one foreign-exchange crisis to the next, the eventual devaluation of the pound by the Treasury under James Callaghan in 1967, and the struggle to avoid a second devaluation thereafter.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Beyond its historical merit, the book provides a telling indictment of the mechanisms and pretensions of government activism. Policymakers were fond of economic planning in the 1960s. The National Economic Development Council was created in Britain, and national plans drawn up and annual targets set for economic growth, with scant regard paid to how they were to be achieved. Incomes policies were introduced to restrain wage inflation. Micromanagement of the business cycle through taxes and government spending was the norm.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Two now conventional tenets of modern economic policymaking--the role of monetary policy in controlling inflation and of "supply-side" reforms in promoting higher productivity and growth--were then virtually ignored. For those who find the current orthodoxy uninspiring, Sir Alec's recollections are a valuable reminder of the awfulness of some of the alternatives.
</td></tr></table>
<a name="4"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>I<font size=-1>NTERNATIONAL</font> M<font size=-1>ONETARY</font> C<font size=-1>O-OPERATION SINCE </font>B<font size=-1>RETTON</font> W<font size=-1>OODS</font>.<br>
 By Harold James. <br>
<i> OUP;</i><i> 620 pages; &#163;30 and $45</i><br>

<p>COMMISSIONED by the <font size=-1>IMF</font> from an independent scholar for its 50th birthday celebrations, this could have been one more worthy official history. Fortunately, it achieves much more. Skip the dull bits on <font size=-1>IMF</font> minutiae and you have a thought-provoking survey of the post-war world economy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Harold James describes the construction of the "Bretton Woods system" (so named because the conference in July 1944 at which the basic structure of the <font size=-1>IMF</font> and World Bank were agreed on was held at Bretton Woods, New Hampshire). Unsurprisingly, much of the emphasis is on monetary co-operation: the gradual establishment of currency convertibility in Europe beginning in the late 1950s; the growing tensions of the "Bretton Woods" fixed-exchange-rate regime in the 1960s; its collapse in the early 1970s and the attempts to manage a "non-system" of floating exchange rates since. But Mr James ranges far beyond exchange rates. The often-acrimonious relations between poor countries and the "international system", the impact of the oil shocks of the 1970s, the debt crisis and the collapse of the Soviet block are all assessed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Three broad themes underlie the narrative: relations between monetary issues and broader changes in global trade and output; the extent to which global economic developments can be frustrated by the policies of individual governments; and how far international institutions such as the <font size=-1>IMF</font> can try to mitigate this.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Like the best histories, this one delights with unexpected detail: for instance, the tale gleaned from the Russian archives of why the Soviet Union declined to join the <font size=-1>IMF</font> in 1945. Surprisingly, and unlike many other books on the world monetary system, it is a lively and enjoyable read.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
