<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000277-B036-281</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev9/rv7/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113181541 text/html 5143
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:11:53 GMT
Last-modified: Wednesday, 11-Sep-96 11:55:05 GMT
Content-length: 4957
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Uses and abuses</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr7.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>American presidential power</b></p>
<h2>Uses and abuses</h2><ul> <li>S<font size=-1>ECRET AND </font>S<font size=-1>ANCTIONED</a>: </font>C<font size=-1>OVERT</font> O<font size=-1>PERATIONS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> A<font size=-1>MERICAN</font> P<font size=-1>RESIDENCY</font>.&nbsp;  By Stephen Knott.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Oxford; 258 pages; $27.50</i> <br>
</ul>

<p>DURING the American Revolution, General George Washington authorised an attempt to kidnap the third son of King George III, the future King William IV. When the British burnt the White House and the Capitol, ex-President Thomas Jefferson suggested that the United States retaliate by hiring impoverished Londoners to burn St Paul's.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Stephen Knott strings together similar incidents, most of more moment. His coverage of the war for independence and the first century of the United States is far fuller than his sketchy treatment of more recent events. There is no mention, for instance, of Theodore Roosevelt's success in encouraging and supporting the rebellion and separation of Panama from Colombia in order to obtain territory for an inter-oceanic canal. Yet this is arguably the most successful and the best-known covert action in American history. Also omitted is a fiasco: President Kennedy's Bay of Pigs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The study is devoid of humour or any sense of the dramatic. Mr Knott takes intrinsically interesting material and makes it dull. For example, he explores George Washington's wartime activities as his own highly effective spymaster yet misses the chance to quote from the general's most extraordinary letter. In it Washington, writing to one of his agents, says he believes that he is supposed to sign off with a fictitious name but has "forgotten the name and must be reminded of it again."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Knott's avowed aim is to demonstrate that from Harry Truman to George Bush, American presidents conducted their clandestine foreign policy in a manner that remained faithful to the practices and beliefs of their revered predecessors. He is combating what he regards as the myth that covert operations are a cold-war phenomenon. His approach is to examine actions which were considered permissible by the early presidents and their secretaries of state and compare them with operations recently under attack.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One of the more remarkable episodes occurred in the 1840s. President John Tyler and his secretary of state, Daniel Webster, used the contingency fund, created for secret foreign operations, to influence opinion leaders in Maine to accept a treaty settling the disputed boundary between Maine and Canada. A big part of the money for this domestic effort was provided, with the administration's consent, by the British government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Knott correctly acknowledges that this episode was one of the most blatant abuses of presidential covert power in American history. But he does not appreciate that his own judgment demonstrates the flaw in his approach. The simple fact that a president has created a precedent does not infallibly make it lawful or wise for his successors to follow it. The Sedition Act of 1798, which made publishing criticism of the government criminal, violates modern concepts of democracy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Secret and Sanctioned" provides a useful, if less than totally reliable, episodic account of many little-known events in American foreign policy. But its author's premise that he is rebutting a serious attack on the future of covert activities fails to recognise that, even after the implosion of the Soviet Empire, there is no serious opposition to the United States maintaining the capability to do mischief--a capability that great powers have always possessed.




<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
