<html><head><title>Zinc futures</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Caf&eacute; society</b></p>
<h2>Zinc futures</h2><ul> <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> P<font size=-1>ARIS</font> C<font size=-1>AFE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By W. Scott Haine.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Johns Hopkins Univ</i>er<i>sity Press; 368 pages; &#163;33 and $39.95</i> <br>
</ul>

<p>NATHALIE SARRAUTE, a diva of the post-war French novel, flew into a paddy not long ago when an incautious fellow customer, noticing her writing at her table, asked why she chose to compose her works in a caf&eacute;. It was, she raged, the first time she had been interrupted in 40 years, each morning of which she had spent writing at that same table.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Sarraute notwithstanding, it has to be wondered how much fiction is written in Paris caf&eacute;s these days by anyone, known or unknown. Whether because there are fewer writers to spot or simply because they are becoming less fun, Paris caf&eacute;s, it seems, are in decline. The news from the terraces is that their number has fallen by half since 1980 to a mere 10,000 today. That compares with 42,000 Paris caf&eacute;s in the last half of the 19th century. From 1789 onwards, caf&eacute;s were a theatre of revolutionary talk, as a regular, Karl Marx, gratefully observed. Balzac dubbed caf&eacute;s "the parliament of the people". Napoleon III posted police spies in all the caf&eacute;s of his capital to monitor dangerous talk.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Caf&eacute;s evidently are no more places of fun to Scott Haine than they are to Ms Sarraute. His academic study of their place in French social history is worthwhile and in places even interesting, though never likely to return zip to caf&eacute; life. You learn, for example, that the early opening hours of Paris caf&eacute;s started last century when the average Parisian working man was at <i>"le zinc"</i> by six in the morning for a ritual <i>petit blanc </i>and shot of cognac; also that the zinc-topped bar was introduced in the 1820s and instantly became a popular place for big-city backchat--it still is, though made of cheaper stuff.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By ending with the 19th century, this book leaves out many of the best-known caf&eacute;s: the Flore and Deux Magots at St-Germain-des-Pr&eacute;s, the Caf&eacute; de la Paix at the Op&eacute;ra, the Select and the Closerie des Lilas in Montparnasse. The one familiar establishment discernible here is the Procope, an oldie in the Latin Quarter. Today's favourites are 20th-century upstarts.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
