<html><head><title>Resurrected</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="4gr5.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Lyndon Johnson</b></p>
<h2>Resurrected</h2><ul><li>G<font size=-1>UNS</font> <font size=-1>OR</font> B<font size=-1>UTTER</font></a>&nbsp; By Irving Bernstein.<br>
</ul>

<p>LYNDON JOHNSON'S domestic achievements are overshadowed by his conduct of the Vietnam war. Even well-informed pundits tend to leave him out when they talk about activist government. They refer to the tradition of Woodrow Wilson, Harry Truman and the two Roosevelts. At recent Democratic conventions, there have been rows over whether to mention Johnson's name.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Irving Bernstein seeks to redress the neglect of Johnson's legislative successes at home where, with typical crudeness, the president told his subordinates: "You got to learn to mount Congress like you mount a woman." He concentrates on 17 significant statutes and analyses their origins, their contents and the often complex political manoeuvring that Johnson used to secure their enactment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Bernstein is surely right when he concludes that only <font size=-1>FDR</font> matched <font size=-1>LBJ</font> in legislative effectiveness. Roosevelt's programme was a response to the Great Depression. Despair was in the air. The existing system had failed. Change was obviously required. Johnson acted without the stimulus of necessity--the economy was surging; the nation confident. Such efforts as his "War on Poverty" were motivated by his belief that government now had the knowledge to cure old problems and the obligation to do so. Optimism and hubris led to the great domestic programmes, as well as to Vietnam.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the home front, the United States at last provided medical care for its old and poor. Many blacks were enabled to vote for the first time. Women and racial minorities were protected against discrimination. Immigration was cleansed of its bias in favour of northern Europeans. The federal government started to tackle pollution and urban slums. It also sought to improve education at all levels. Improbably, Johnson, a philistine, did more for the arts than any other president: the Kennedy Centre in Washington, the National Endowment for the Arts and commercial-free public radio and television networks are among his legacies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Bernstein's examination of <font size=-1>LBJ</font>'s legislative programme is masterly. The errors and omissions come when he turns to foreign affairs. He is under the impression that Johnson and a small group of advisers chose to wage war in Vietnam in the face of informed and popular opinion. In fact, both the political establishment and the American public initially supported American intervention in Vietnam. Mr Bernstein wrongly asserts that David Halberstam and other influential newsmen stationed in Vietnam in 1963 were doves. They were believers in the war; they disagreed with the way it was being fought.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Bernstein treats well one of the most critical and least remembered episodes of Johnson's presidency. Days before the 1968 American presidential election, <font size=-1>LBJ</font> stopped the bombing of Vietnam in the expectation that negotiations would soon begin among the Americans, the North Vietnamese, the South Vietnamese and the Vietcong. Public opinion polls were showing that Hubert Humphrey, the Democrat candidate, was closing on Richard Nixon, the Republican candidate. Intelligence sources revealed that, through intermediaries, Nixon was advising the South Vietnamese not to enter into negotiations. Johnson passed the information to Humphrey, who declined to make it public. Had Humphrey been less fastidious he might well have won the tight election.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
