<html><head><title>Prodigious</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="8gr9.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b></b></p>
<head>English history<h2>Prodigious</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex230.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> Y<font size=-1>OUNGER</font> P<font size=-1>ITT</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>ONSUMING</font> S<font size=-1>TRUGGLE</font>.&nbsp;  By John Ehrman. <br>
</ul>

<p>THE younger William Pitt was, by any standards, a prodigy. Elected to parliament at the age of 21, he was chancellor of the exchequer at 22 and prime minister by the time he was 24. Apart from a short break in the early 1800s, he remained in Downing Street until his death at the age of 46 in 1806, shortly after hearing of Napoleon's victory at Austerlitz and 25 years to the day since he first took his seat in the House of Commons. He had spent almost the whole of his adult life in his country's highest office.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The shock of Pitt's sudden death was tremendous, as though Winston Churchill had died following Dunkirk. Where there had been a mighty object, there was suddenly a void. When the speaker announced a motion in the Commons proposing that a memorial be erected, "The silence was death-like, and several of the hardiest oppositionists said it was like an electrical shock upon the House, and that they could hardly breathe." Walter Scott--not yet Sir Walter Scott--wrote:
<ul><font size=-1>Now is the stately column broke<br>
The beacon-light is quench'd in smoke<br>
The trumpet's silver sound is still<br>
The warden silent on the hill.<br></font></ul>
<br>Thousands attended the lying-in-state.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Scott's phrase "stately column" was apt. Inwardly a mercurial man, with wide swings of mood, a short attention span and no family to sustain him, Pitt--like so many other top politicians--protected himself from the outside world by sculpting a statue of himself. And the statue, though contrived, had its own reality. Pitt's aloofness was unfeigned. His confidence in his own capacities was immense. "The image", John Ehrman writes, with characteristic subtlety, "was the ultimate support in easing the tensions of which it was itself a part." Contemporaries, not surprisingly, found him an enigma.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Pitt was, as Mr Ehrman notes, one of the last prime ministers able to engage himself in the whole range of his administration's activities. The scope of government was small in the 1800s. Britain was a European, not yet a world-imperial power. Pitt could immerse himself for a time in the details of naval reform (he was an enthusiast for gunboats, with some support from Lord Nelson). Even so, his approach to government was more that of the 19th century than of the 18th. He believed in information, measurement and system. In an age when dilettantes could still flourish in politics, he was a professional.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Pitt's claims to being one of the greatest British prime ministers are legion. He towered above his more brilliant but less disciplined contemporaries: Edmund Burke, Charles James Fox and Lord Shelburne. He created a new ruling coalition, comprising the king (the only intermittently demented George III), the City of London and the <i>nouveaux riches</i> (numbers of whom he gartered or ennobled). An ally of William Wilberforce, he won respectable support for a serious attempt to end the slave trade. A disciple of Adam Smith, he did more than anyone before Sir Robert Peel to advance the cause of free trade.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the nine years covered by "The Consuming Struggle"--1797 to 1806, the last of Pitt's life--his record was more mixed. The brutal repression of the 1798 Irish uprising and the patched-up Act of Union that followed only deepened the already deep enmities between Ireland and England and between Catholics and Protestants, especially since Pitt failed in his effort to secure for Irish Catholics full civil rights in their own country. Pitt was also a clumsy and maladroit leader in the wars against France. He was neither a gifted military strategist nor a sound military administrator, and his formidable domestic political skills largely deserted him on the foreign stage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Pitt's most enduring achievement of his final years was, typically, a fiscal innovation: the graduated income tax, introduced in 1789 to help finance the French wars. Pitt, who had devoted much of his life to putting his country's finances on a sound footing, was determined not to finance the wars just by raising loans, and a levy on incomes seemed the only alternative. But even in Pitt's day the tax was unpopular--not because it was a tax on incomes as such but because of the "invidious inquisition" (Pitt's own words) that administering it inevitably entailed. Repealed at the end of the French wars, it became a permanent part of the British tax system only in 1842.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Pitt himself was a prodigy, his biographer is, if anything, even more prodigious. This is the final volume of a three-volume life, on which Mr Ehrman has been working for 44 years, almost as long as Pitt lived. The first volume appeared in 1969, the second in 1983. The whole runs to 2,327 pages. The footnotes in the present volume alone defy counting. Writer and subject are so comfortable with one another that the reader imagines them shaking hands on their first meeting in Elysium. Mr Ehrman's judgments are carefully weighed, his prose elegant, his knowledge of politics in the age of Pitt unsurpassed. He can take complete pride in everything he has done.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, he has not quite finished (even though he may justly think he has). A book of this erudition on such a fascinating subject deserves a far wider readership than these three massive volumes will ever achieve. Mr Ehrman (or his helpers) should get down to an abridgement at once.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
