<html><head><title>Trade's triumph</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>The Uruguay round</b></p>
<h2>Trade's triumph</h2><ul><li>T<font size=-1>RADERS</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>A</font> B<font size=-1>RAVE</font> N<font size=-1>EW</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font></a>&nbsp; By Ernest Preeg.<br>
<li><a href="4ex89.html"></i>R<font size=-1>ESHAPING</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> T<font size=-1>RADING</font> S<font size=-1>YSTEM</font></a>&nbsp; By John Croome.<br>
</ul>




<p>NOW that the Uruguay trade round is over and the World Trade Organisation (<font size=-1>WTO</font>) is at work, why should anybody want to read the story of the negotiations? Arguments over such arcana as agricultural price supports and voluntary export restraints are hardly promising literary material. Yet both Ernest Preeg, an American trade official turned journalist, and John Croome, a veteran of the <font size=-1>GATT</font> civil service, have chosen to write detailed accounts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As might be expected, these books have much content in common. But, as befits a book published by the <font size=-1>WTO</font>, Mr Croome's concentrates more closely than Mr Preeg's on the details of the negotiations. Mr Preeg's book has a broader sweep. It has more, for example, on the way<i>s</i> in which the importance of regional trade initiatives, such as the North American Free-Trade Agreement <i>(</i><font size=-1>NAFTA</font>), grew during the round, partly out of American frustration over the slowness of progress in the <font size=-1>GATT</font> negotiations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike Mr Croome, Mr Preeg concludes by asking: where next for world trade? He points out that the <font size=-1>WTO</font> is not the only show in town: regional agreements will keep growing; and the spectre of aggressive unilateral trade action, especially by the United States, will not go away. Yet his general prognosis for freer trade in the world is optimistic. He may be right, but some of his reasoning is very curious: it is based, he says, "on the four-week period [in late 1993]...when first the United States Congress defeated the blatantly protectionist drive against the <font size=-1>NAFTA</font> and then the Uruguay round was concluded". As the recent popularity of Pat Buchanan on the presidential campaign trail shows, protectionists are not so easily quashed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, these dry histories of trade diplomacy are worth reading--not only (or even mainly) as works of reference on the round itself, but also because the story of the round gives plenty of pointers to the possible future course of global trade liberalisation. There is still much to be done: the Uruguay round made world trade freer, not free.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
