<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>C<font size=-1>OUNTRY</font> H<font size=-1>OUSE</font> B<font size=-1>REWING</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> E<font size=-1>NGLAND</font>:<br> 1500-1900.<br></h2>
<p> By Pamela Sambrook.<br>
<i> The Hambledon Press; 332 pages; &#163;25 and $45.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="8jb243.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
PAMELA SAMBROOK was born in Staffordshire and educated at Stoke-on-
Trent and St Hugh's College, Oxford. She received a doctorate from Keele
University for a thesis on the finances of the Anson family:(who became the
Earls of Lichfield). At.Shugborough, the house built by the Ansons, she started
one of the very first farm museums and restored to working order various
kitchens, the house laundry and the brewhouse. With the help of professional
brewers, several successful brews were produced and sold at Shugborough and
at a local pub. Her involvement aroused her interest in country house brewing.
 She teaches at Keele University and the Open University and is actively
involved in the study of food history.
