<html><head><title>Beer and skittles</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Manufacturing in Britain</b></p>
<h2>Beer and skittles</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex243.html">C<font size=-1>OUNTRY</font> H<font size=-1>OUSE</font> B<font size=-1>REWING</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> E<font size=-1>NGLAND</font></a>: 1500-1900.&nbsp;  By Pamela Sambrook.<br>
 <li><a href="8ex244.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> B<font size=-1>RITISH</font> T<font size=-1>OY</font> B<font size=-1>USINESS</font></a>: A H<font size=-1>ISTORY SINCE</font> 1700.&nbsp;  By Kenneth Brown.<br>
</ul>


</i>
<p>A VISITOR to Germany, who strays beyond the confines of its cities, is bound to notice the presence, in almost every small town, of a local <i>Brauerei</i> whose mellifluous product is available in the neighbouring inns. The united Germany boasts some 1,300 breweries, diverse in their output but united in high quality.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At one time the many breweries of England's country houses provided a similar diversity. As late as 1800 over half the nation's beer came from such breweries. The beer produced by them represented the last vestiges of the feudal payment in kind. The allowance or "luance" of beer--as much as a gallon a day--to harvest workers, laundrymen, bakers, gardeners, icemen, carpenters and household servants provided the staple national drink before the eventual victory of tea, coffee and other non-alcoholic beverages. To satisfy such demand, country-house breweries turned out prodigious quantities. According to Pamela Sambrook's intriguing study of this "cottage" industry, an annual production of 5,000 gallons of ale and 7,000 gallons of weaker "small beer" was common for many country-house breweries as late as the mid-19th century.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the second half of the 19th century country-house brewing fell into decline. In part this was due to government intervention, industrialisation and the rise of the temperance movement (which turned its attention from spirits to beer in the 1830s). Gladstone's Beer Act of 1880 levied tax on country-house beer at the same rate as commercial beer and seven years later the Truck Act made payment of wages in beer to farm servants illegal. Yet the real problem was that private brewing never achieved the standardised quality needed for selling it in commercial markets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Country-house brewers, unrestricted by law, would flavour their beer with the most miscellaneous ingredients. Hops might be swapped with ground ivy or long pepper, yeast replaced by Castile soap, a mixture of flour and eggs, essential oil or barley and quintessence of malt or wine, while the beer itself might be flavoured with plants, ranging from dandelion to new hay. One early 19th-century observer of private brewing, Thomas Poole, noted among the cures for "foxed" or "ropey" beer additions of chalk, unslaked lime, powdered oyster shells, wormwood, oatmeal, bay salt, isinglass or, most drastically, a mixture of mutton, tartar salt and eggshells. Despite, perhaps because of, these rescue attempts, he saw hundreds of gallons of bad beer thrown away at a time. Quality control, essential to commercialisation, was simply not a country-house forte.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The British Toy Business" also deals with quality troubles. Kenneth Brown observes that by 1850 the toy trade in Britain was so easy to enter and price competition so fierce that quality was deteriorating, sometimes to the extent that the dolls possessed legs "innocent of calves, insteps and ankles" with bodies turned on lathes and "confounding all distinction of front and back, left and right". Soon Germans so dominated the quality end of the British market that the author of an alarmist book "Made in Germany" (1896) complained that "to a large...extent our children's playthings...are made in Germany."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There were technical breakthroughs in early 20th-century British toy-making, such as William Britain's technique for hollow-casting toy soldiers and Frank Hornby's Meccano. But between 1932 and 1960 the industry lived less from innovation than from a long period of import protection. By the 1960s a British consumer group complained that British toys were designed casually, made contemptuously and sold irresponsibly. The end came swiftly. Between 1979 and 1982 five of the top eight domestic manufacturers went into liquidation and along with them the childhood names of Meccano, Airfix, Matchbox, Corgi, Pedigree and Triang. This collapse bears all the familiar marks of British industrial malaise: poor design, poor marketing, bad financial management, inefficient manufacturing combined with bad government policy. The lesson by contrast from the L&ouml;wenbr&auml;u brewery or the Steiff toy factory seems to be: produce a good, popular product to a consistent standard, and your chances of survival are high.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
