<html><head><title>You do need a weatherman</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Weather</b></p>
<h2>You do need a weatherman</h2><ul> <li><a href="7ex210.html">B<font size=-1>RAVING</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> E<font size=-1>LEMENTS</a>:</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>TORMY</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> A<font size=-1>MERICAN</font> W<font size=-1>EATHER</font>.&nbsp;  By David Laskin. <br>
</ul>

<p>FEW things except other people's dreams are as dull as other people's weather. Extremes here make no difference. Weather that is always hot (Sahara), always cold (Antarctica) or always changing (England) is reliably dire. To be worth talking about, weather has to be unpredictable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The skies between the Gulf Stream waters and the redwood forests pass this test. Moving house in Kansas can mean getting caught in a tornado. Winter storms trap East Coasters inside for days. March frosts kill Florida oranges while sunshine bakes Alaska. Save possibly during August nobody in Oregon can ever tell you when it will stop raining.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nothing has shaped life in North America more than the weather, according to David Laskin, a self-confessed "weather nut". You do not need to swallow that claim whole to find this history fascinating. Prehistoric man, he writes, crossed the Bering Strait because of the weather. South-western Indian civilizations crumbled, he argues, because of its pitiless power. European explorers may have sailed to America in part to escape the consequences of a mini-permafreeze back home.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the colonial era, many leading Americans were also "weather nuts", including Cotton Mather, Benjamin Franklin and Thomas Jefferson. On July 4th 1776, the day independence was declared, Jefferson bought a pricey thermometer, followed a few days later by an expensive barometer--perhaps, Mr Laskin muses in a moment of patriotic sentiment, to "wipe the meteorological slate clean and begin afresh with the best new instruments..."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many pioneers went West assured that "rain follows the plough" even in parched regions--a misconception brutally refuted in the Dust Bowl of the 1930s. James Pollard Espy, a mid-19th century scientist known as "the Storm King", was luckily never able to test his proposal for coaxing rain out of western skies: torching a 700-mile-long stretch of forest every week.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Laskin is particularly good on meteorologists and on why people often prefer forecasts from weathermen (and women) to impersonal weather services. The old Weather Bureau once had to plead with a Denver newspaper to spike a popular weekly forecast that ran side by side with the official one. The competing prognosticator, who usually beat the professionals for accuracy, was a 90-year-old veteran who based his forecast on how a war wound felt that week.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A chapter is spent on the National Weather Service's tracking of "the storm of the century" in 1993. But last winter another storm came--too late for this book--that made 1993's a dim memory. That was bad luck for Mr Laskin, but bears out a more general point of his: people's weather memories are selective. Research suggests that drought survivors routinely underestimate the frequency and severity of droughts. And in the debate over global warming--a subject Mr Laskin treats with admirable detachment--climate is frequently confused with weather, which is here today, gone tomorrow--or next month.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
