<html><head><title>What the world is reading</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">


<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top>

</td></tr></table>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<br>
<h2>What the world is reading</h2>

<p>SOME national stereotypes simply refuse to die. If bestsellers are a guide, paranoid Americans are beset by hidden foes. A serial killer, recombined dinosaurs, a bogus general, a judge on trial and runaway bacteria are all currently some of their favourite fears.</p>
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nostalgic Brits continue a wistful love-affair with more heroic pasts and indulge their fondness for animals that talk. Three of the British bestsellers are war-time novels. Another continues trading in the antique genre of cold-war spying. The wry tales in ''Cross Channel" play on the English longing to be French and relief at not being.</p>
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is no surprise that on the French list literary novels (see adjoining article) jostle pot-boilers. But the emphasis on childhood is astonishing. Six of the ten novels listed star the young, eight if the back-to-roots exile books are counted. Is romanticism sweeping France? Has wide-eyed Rousseau outdone sardonic Voltaire? Amid smashed ideals and public scandal, innocence evidently appeals.</p>
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The land of exports reads imports. One only of Germany's top ten is German. No theme stands out among the other nine: Germans, it seems, will read almost anything in translation. National self-loathing? Likelier, too much self-preoccupation among German novelists.
</p>

<br>
