</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Settling down to a good old read</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Fiction from Spain</b></p>
<h2>Settling down to a good old read</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex245.html">M<font size=-1>ALENA</font> <font size=-1>ES</font> <font size=-1>UN</font> N<font size=-1>OMBRE</font> <font size=-1>DE</font> T<font size=-1>ANGO</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Almudena Grandes. <br>
 <li><a href="8ex199.html">M<font size=-1>ODELOS DE</font> M<font size=-1>UJER</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Almudena Grandes.<br>
 <li><a href="8ex198.html">L<font size=-1>A </font>P<font size=-1>IEL DEL</font> T<font size=-1>AMBOR</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Arturo Perez-Reverte.<br>
 <li>V<font size=-1>IAJE DE</font> E<font size=-1>STUDIOS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Menchu Gutierrez.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Siruela; 112 pages; Ptas 1,500</i> <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

AFTER General Franco's death in 1975 Spain seemed to leap frantically into the modern mode, especially in its two competing cities, Madrid and Barcelona, in what was known as the <i>movida</i>. Stylish, fun-loving and forgetful of the long dreary dictatorship, Spanish culture was best personified by film maker Pedro Almodovar's outrageous kitsch and daring transgressions. Moral censorship melted away, and writers (and readers) indulged in sexual fantasies. Almudena Grandes, born in 1960, won a porno fiction prize in 1989 for her novel "Las Edades de Lulu" (The Ages of Lulu), but moved beyond porno pastiche with "Malena es un nombre de tango" (Malena is the name of a tango) in 1994, released as a film this year. This sprawling, passionate novel is narrated by Malena, the tomboy twin discovering her rebellious self through her sexual awakening, first lover (a cousin), husband, and work in Madrid, as she simultaneously pokes her nose into her complicated family history. The novel satisfies any reader's curiosity about a family skeleton-cupboard with vivid portraits of the odder characters against a realistic backdrop of upper-middle-class Madrid and a country estate near Caceres. Revealing family secrets is treated as politically therapeutic on the ground that "the greatest crime of Francoism has been the kidnapping of the whole country's memory". This novel is a "Buddenbrooks" narrated by a bright, naughty woman at odds with her world, liberating her animal self.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Almudena Grandes's latest offering in the bestseller list is a collection of longish short stories called "Modelos de Mujer" (Models of Woman). All the stories are told by women, but Ms Grandes rejects the notion of feminist literature, and claims to write "to get even with the world". What strikes a reader is the range of these stories, though all deal with love. The book opens with a ghost story in a woman's asylum where a chorus of female voices allows the reader to piece together the humorous appearance of a ghost anarchist murdered during the civil war. The second story is a light-hearted account of an overweight middle-aged woman's re-encounter with a past lover, her food problems, her life expectancies. Ms Grandes is acute on colloquial speech, on how contemporary clich&eacute;s enter her characters' inner lives. There is a story about vengeance where a girl eats the grubs prepared by her grandfather for catching fish. Another story has an alcoholic mother tame her sexy, rebellious daughter with secret doses of some illegal drug in order to say she has a model daughter. The two best stories are built up on exact social satire, yet touch deeper chords. The title story, "Modelos de Mujer", opposes a beauty queen on a film set in New York with her vital but plump Spanish minder (many of Ms Grandes's female narrators are big women, and suffer from fashion).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The final story is a moving account of being brought up by a maid in Madrid. The middle-aged narrator discovers, or invents, that she was not her bullying, crippled mother's daughter, but her maid's illegitimate one, and finally runs off with her lover, as her nanny had done before, after arranging a nursing home for her dictatorial mother. All the stories are funny, all deal with love, fashion, modern Madrid, and liberation. Ms Grandes mocks the trivial modernity of 1990s Madrid, and pleads for more passion "because passion carefully chooses its victims".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Arturo Perez-Reverte's sixth novel, "La Piel del Tambor" (The Skin of the Drum), sets out to capture the tensions in modern Spain, and opens with a hacker breaking into secret files in the Vatican. Mr Perez-Reverte is a master of intelligent suspense, and reader-friendly action. The ramifying plot has Lorenzo Quart, an investigating soldier-like priest, sent by the Vatican's office of foreign affairs to track down this hacker and report on the scandals and deaths surrounding an old baroque church in post-Expo-1992 Seville. Inevitably, there is a power tussle between a corrupt banker and his separated, aristocratic wife over the demolition of a church and the consequent property deal, with an astronomy-addicted but traditional priest in the middle.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This priest, Don Priamo Ferro, sells off church paintings to restore his church, and fights the developers with his assistant, an American lay nun. The old Spain, embodied by this priest who still gives mass in Latin, by gipsy scoundrels, by the labyrinth of Seville's streets, and the new Spain of computers, faxes, gold cards, trilingual secretaries and pony-tailed policemen meet in the streets of Seville (a map is provided). The investigating priest, Quart, talks to everybody, and steps beyond his neutrality to defend the traditional Catholic values of faith; then the plot reaches its climax with the murder of the journalist, as the old priest is accused and then kidnapped by a rival faction. In a Graham Greene-like way, Mr Perez-Reverte contrasts the moral flaws of Quart, the modern priest, succumbing to a woman and the church's betrayals with crooked property developers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This novel, in fact, is an update of Spain's greatest 19th-century novel "La Regenta" by Leopoldo Alas, which anatomised Spain through the character of Machiavellian priests. However, more than dissecting current Spain, Mr Perez-Reverte is playfully modern in an Umberto Eco way, with many textual clues in the plot, from actual postcards to quotations from treatises to Quart's strange name (possibly the keyboard sequence 'qwert'), and a journalist jokingly called Bonafe, but such post-modernistic tics do not interfere with a smoothly written, realist novel. The priest Quart does not run off with the sexy aristocrat and the hacker turns out to be a 70-year-old duquesa. The novel is also a hymn to Seville where everybody knows everybody ("Sevilla is a neighbourhood patio; we love gossip"), a city where the "past lives with the present, without any problems".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, recent Spanish fiction is not all "light" and "modern". Not every writer suffers from historical amnesia or caters to trends, as if reality were an Almodovar movie. Recent work by any of the following--Antonio Mu&ntilde;oz Molina, Alvaro Pombo, Javier Marias, Carmen Martin Gaite--would contradict that idea. However, the most striking novel that moves away from recreating Old Spain-New Spain dichotomies is the experimental "Viaje de Estudios" (Study Trip) by Menchu Gutierrez, born in 1957. The novel leaps from realism (a train journey inland, class rooms, a monastery) into a disconcerting parable of a Kafkaesque nature where orphans at a university take what you can only surmise is an initiate's journey, with a confessor and a teacher as guides, into a timeless zone with frightening black holes and even stranger white holes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The narrator's final act of self-discovery involves an acceptance of incoherence as belonging to the nature of things: behind the world of the senses and common sense lie physical surprises and conundrums that upset tidy habits of mind. Ambitious burble? Not at all. Talk from serious physicists of time travel or parallel universes must make writers worry that the imagination has deserted their world for science. Ms Gutierrez tries admirably to keep up with modernity, without recourse to flashy, post-modernist stunts.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
