<html><head><title>Feet of Clay.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl233.jpg"><img src="cs233.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>F<font size=-1>EET</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> C<font size=-1>LAY</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Anthony Storr. <br>
<i>Harper</i><i>Collins; 253 pages; &#163;18</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="8jb233.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
Anthony Storr was born in 1920 and educated at Winchester, Christ's College,
Cambridge, and at Westminster Hospital. He qualified as a doctor in
1944, and subsequently specialized in psychiatry. His publications include The
Integrity of the Personality, Human Destructiveness, Jung, The Dynamics of
Creation, The Art of Psychotherapy, Solitude, Freud, and Music and the Mind.
He has contributed reviews and articles to many papers, including the Sunday
Times, the Times Literary Supplement and the lndependent. Dr Storr is a
Fellow of the Royal College of Physicians, a Fellow of the Royal College of
Psychiatrists, and Fellow ot the Royal Society of Literature. He is also
Honorary Consulting Psychiatrist to the Oxfordshire Health Authority, and an
Emeritus Fellow of Green College, Oxford.
