<html><head><title>Magnetic</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="8gr13.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Gurus</b></p>
<h2>Magnetic</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex233.html">F<font size=-1>EET</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> C<font size=-1>LAY</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Anthony Storr. <br>
</ul>

<p>WHEN Martin Gardner published the second edition of his "Fads and Fallacies in the Name of Science" in 1957, he noted that most of the outraged letters which greeted its first publication had objected only to one chapter while praising all the rest. These critics did not, however, agree about which chapter was the unfair one. Each of the irate correspondents enjoyed seeing the fallacies of others debunked. They were just angry to find their own pet fads treated alongside them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Anthony Storr can expect a similarly mixed mailbag after this excellent book, subtitled "A Study of Gurus". Followers of Freud may chortle over Gurdjieff (chapter two), but will probably frown when they get to chapter six (Freud). Jesuits and some others may be pleased to see Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh bagged (chapter three), but be less happy with chapter seven (the Jesuits and Jesus). Yet Dr Storr is more tender-hearted than Mr Gardner. Except for his treatment of recent gurus who turned murderous (Jim Jones and David Koresh), the engaging Dr Storr is always ready to find the honest, beneficent and even beneficial side of his subjects.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This study has twin attractions. Anyone who has ever wondered what Rudolf Steiner or Gurdjieff actually said, but who has been forgivably wary of devoting any time to the writings of these men, will find an intelligible account of their incredible views. Gurdjieff's theory of the solar system, for instance, gives a new meaning to the old term "lunatic" and should not be missed. But this is also a book with a thesis. Dr Storr argues that gurus are not so much distinguished from the average person by what they believe, more by how they believe it. One intriguing suggestion he makes is that the deviants with whom gurus have most in common are those confidence-tricksters whose remarkable success is due to the fact that they have partly conned themselves before they get round to conning others.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The theme of "Feet of Clay" is continuity: there is no obvious gulf separating sanity from madness and one shades into the other by barely perceptible degrees. The guru's philosophy grows out of motives and experiences that are widely shared. This generous attempt to run roads from the suburbs of the soul out to the wilder shores of humanity may make it easier for Christians and Freudians to accept the company into which Dr Storr ushers them. Both Freud and Jesus may be gurus in Dr Storr's sense, but this does not necessarily make them mad, bad and dangerous to follow.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, "The wisest men", according to Euripides, "follow their own direction/ And listen to no prophet guiding them." This quotation from "Iphigenia in Tauris" forms the epigraph and moral of Dr Storr's book. His favourite guru appears to be Mother Meera, who specialises in silence. "It may sound ridiculous to suggest that, if someone must seek a guru it is best to choose one who does not speak, but I mean it at least half-seriously." This view is partly supported by his own working experience as a psychologist. He recalls a patient who lay mute on the couch for 50 minutes. He had followed her lead and remained silent himself, whereupon the patient announced that it had been their best meeting so far.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
