</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Beyond our ken?</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="8gr12.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>The reliability of science</b></p>
<h2>Beyond our ken?</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex255.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>ND</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>CIENCE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By John Horgan. <br>
 <li><a href="8ex256.html">W<font size=-1>HY</font> T<font size=-1>HINGS</font> B<font size=-1>ITE</font> B<font size=-1>ACK</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Edward Tenner. <br>
</ul>

</i>
<p>BLAME Mary Shelley. When her anti-hero, Victor Frankenstein, meddled with forces he did not understand, she gave voice to the impulse to question science. The monster has been on the loose ever since. In these two books science-doubt strays into the establishment. John Horgan, a journalist with <i>Scientific American</i>, argues that science's great age is done and that there is much that mankind will never understand. Edward Tenner, who edited scientific books at Princeton University Press, catalogues technology's perverse, frustrating consequences. Neither book quite rings true.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The idea that today's theories might not be surpassed is tempting, especially to scientists. In the breathless words of Richard Feynman, a Nobel-prizewinning physicist, "We are very lucky to be living in an age in which we are still making discoveries. It is like...America--you only discover it once." In many areas of science Mr Horgan thinks that the Jamestown settlers have landed. Biology rests on Darwin and on modern genetics; cosmology has the big bang; physics has quantum mechanics and the standard model describing the structure of matter. In other areas--defining consciousness or unifying the social sciences, the author doubts whether voyagers will ever strike land.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What is left? Mr Horgan, borrowing a term from literary theory, suggests "ironic" science: learned, but untestable speculation on the significance and interconnections of established theories. Edward Witten, a physicist at Princeton, dreams of superstrings, which are unimaginably tiny loops of energy in many dimensions. Stephen Hawking, a British cosmologist, contemplates wormholes linking distant regions of space-time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet science is not just grand theory. "Mere problem-solving", as the book dismissively calls it, is how most scientists spend most of their time. Moreover, the difference between "ironic" science and "real" science does not stand up. What was Newton doing when he speculated on the structure of matter? What about Kepler's belief in the celestial music of the spheres? The "ironies" of past scientists have either been forgotten or transmuted into straightforward modern theory.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The real weakness of Mr Horgan's claim is that it is itself untestable. Successful theories are, by definition, good at explaining what people currently think needs explaining. Inadequacies show up later, as new facts are learned and old ones take on new significance. The late 20th century may be the last age of grand theory. Then again, it may not be.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though packaged as science-doubt, "Why Things Bite Back" underlines just how much everyday science is still to be done. It is a catalogue of unintended consequences: medicine has helped cure acute illness and injury, but chronic diseases are commoner as a result; miracle crops and new animals let loose in strange habitats have run wild; forest fires have been prevented, but the unburned growth that collects makes fires worse when they do occur; safer cars and sports equipment makes people more reckless, and so on.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;True or plausible those claims may be, but they do not add up to a new or startling message. Too many of Mr Tenner's examples are familiar and who, after <font size=-1>DDT</font> or mad-cow disease, seriously thinks that technology does only good? Despite its critical tone, this book lacks the passion of an all-or-nothing polemic. Mr Tenner is simply too sensible to dismiss science and technology out of hand, acknowledging that on balance they leave most people better off. When things do go wrong, his answer is not Luddism but greater vigilance and better technology. "Try again, Frankenstein," Mr Tenner seems to be saying, "only this time get it right."


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
