<html><head><title>Why Things Bite Back.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl256.jpg"><img src="cs256.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>W<font size=-1>HY</font> T<font size=-1>HINGS</font> B<font size=-1>ITE</font> B<font size=-1>ACK</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Edward Tenner. <br>
<i>Fourth Estate; 346 pages; &#163;18.99</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="8bt256.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Why do new roads lead to bigger traffic jams? Why after all the advances made
in medicine are there deadlier diseases around than ever? Why are labour
saving devices destroying our dreams of the leisured society? Why does every
major technological advance lead to paradoxical, unforeseen and unintended
consequences? It seems as if the world we have created is intent on getting
even. Things bite back.
<p>In this ground-breaking study, Edward Tenner--who has taught at Princeton and conducted research at the Institute for Advanced Study--shows that with every great advance there is a corresponding revenge effect: pest-control which spreads pests, exercise which diminished fitness, communication which impedes the flow of information. The asbestos curtain which once offered protection from one hazard now itself represents a long-term chronic problem. As we complicate the systems which govern our lives, revenge effects multiply.</p>
<p>Technology demands more, not less, human work to function. Technology has increased the need for vigilance not reduced it. For every acute problem solved, a chronic problem comes up in its stead.</p>
<p>Why Things Bite Back, carefully and extensively documented, brings together themes and material from widely differing disciplines (epidemiology, ecology, social psychology, traffic engineering, organisational behaviour). It offers a template from problem solving across the board--whether in business management, agriculture or for coping, indeed, with the general stress of living in the technological world. Like Charles Handy's Age of Unreason or Francis Fukuyama's The End of History and the Last Man, Edward Tenner's Why Things Bite Back is a book to change forever the way we think about the modern world and our place in it. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
