<html><head><title>Click and clip</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Terraforming gardens...</b></p>
<h2>Click and clip</h2><ul> <li>P<font size=-1>ERFECT</font> P<font size=-1>LANTS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Roger Phillips and Martyn Rix.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Macmillan; &#163;39.99 for </i><font size=-1>CD-ROM</font><i>; &#163;12.99 for book.</i><font size=-1> CD-ROM</font> <i>distributed in America by Maxis $39.99; book published by Random House $23</i> <br>
</ul>

<p>IF PLANTING a garden involved no more than finding the right subjects for particular locations, a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> would be an ideal tool. Users can scroll quickly through a wide range of plants, calling up for each an informative photograph and text that gives details of its cultivation, care and favoured growing conditions. Those who seek a plant for a chosen spot, of a particular height, colour and growing habit, enter their criteria and the disc will produce a short list to choose from. In essence, a good <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> is a quick and convenient tool for deciding what to grow, handier to use than a reference book and easier to manipulate than a television gardening programme.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Using "Perfect Plants" is a bit like visiting a garden centre without leaving your desk. When, having browsed among more than 2<i>,</i>000 plants, you find some that you might want to buy, you transfer them to an electronic "shopping cart" for later review. Window-shopping this way can be easier than the real thing. You can search, for example, for shrubs that tolerate shade and cold winters, and that were introduced in the 18th century, if your garden is historically correct. These devices are practical and work well. Text is admirably clear and more comprehensive than in the printed version. The photographs, too, look much more handsome on screen than in their necessarily reduced size in the book.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To appeal to <font size=-1>PC</font>-users who are not gardening professionals, publishers feel they need to offer glitzy extras, including customised background music, in the hope that this will make the device an irresistible joy to use and convince customers that it is worth the money. In "Perfect Plants", some of these add-ons work well. Most centre around Roger Phillips, a veteran garden writer and <font size=-1>TV</font> presenter, whose cheerful voice, exuding enthusiasm and lightly-worn expertise, accompanies short video clips. His presence gives an authorial identity that some discs lack.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The section on plant care works well. In 35 half-minute clips, Mr Phillips gives tips on pruning, planting, propagating and much else. The advice is clear and, of necessity, concise. After a couple of viewings of the clip on pruning clematis, even a novice would be confident about wielding the secateurs without doing mortal damage to the plant. Clearly you cannot take a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> with you into the garden as you are actually doing the work, but this is not a serious objection: it is, after all, rare to see gardeners perusing books as they work. There are, as well, six garden tours, each offering a 90-second gallop around a particular kind of garden (four in America, two in Britain), though these clips are too short to be useful. The disc's biggest failing may be inherent in the technology: an absence of depth and discursiveness. It can tell you what flower to grow in what conditions, but not why you should want to. Roses, for instance, arouse conflicting passions that are unreflected here. "Perfect Plants" takes you through scores of varieties without addressing the question of whether you should be looking for a hybrid tea, with its showy bloom but ungainly habit, or a less assertive shrub rose, which has a more manageable overall shape. And to cover your wall, would a climber or a rambler be best, and what is the difference between them? And why do you want to grow roses anyway? On those points, this disc is silent.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
