<html><head><title>The multimedia wipeout</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="7gr12.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h2>The multimedia wipeout</h2>

<p><b>Why are CD-ROMs such bad business?</b></p><ul></ul>

<p>WHEN "A Brief History of Time", a rather hard-going science book from a little-known boffin, unexpectedly sold more than 5.5m copies in the early 1990s, publishers scoured the planet for science writers who could repeat the success. They failed--nobody could quite work out why the book had done so well, but it was pretty clear that book-buyers were not keen to have another baffling tome gathering dust on their coffee tables.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This was a lesson multimedia publishers might have remembered when a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> called "Myst" from a little-known software firm sold 2m copies after its release in 1993. Again, nobody quite knew why it had been such a success--publishers of "Myst" had expected to sell only 80,000 copies. But the triumph was enough for dozens of companies to declare that the multimedia <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> age had arrived, and invest heavily in a race for the next "Myst".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Today, most of those companies are a bit wiser and a lot poorer. Multimedia <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s have failed even to match the success of Nintendo's simple video-game machines. Overall, they sell pretty well--more than $1 billion last year, worldwide--but most of the companies that make them are losing money at it. In the past six months alone, three leading <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> publishers--Sierra On-Line, The Learning Company and Davidson--have been bought up in an industry consolidation. Other media giants, from Time-Warner to Hearst and Turner Broadcasting, largely left the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> market after disappointing sales. Dozens of smaller firms have gone under.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By rights, <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s should be a great business. There are some 20m multimedia <font size=-1>PC</font>s in the world, a total that will probably jump by 50% this year, and it seems a fair assumption that anybody who can afford a $2,000 computer will be willing to part with a few dollars for the software to make it sing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reality is harsher. The average multimedia <font size=-1>PC</font> owner buys less than one <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s a year--disappointing parsimony when measured against the more than 2,700 <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> titles that the industry released last year, each costing anything from several hundred thousand dollars to $10m to produce. A <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> fetches on average less than $10 today, a low figure that reflects the high volume of free or discounted <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s in the marketplace. Of that $10, the publisher and the developer together make about $2, after the distributor, retailer and others take their cut. At that rate, a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> that costs $1m to make--the average for entertainment titles is $1.5m, according to Dataquest, a consultancy--would have to sell at least 500,000 copies to break even. More than 100 such titles were released last year, yet fewer than 20 passed that sales target.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One explanation for these bleak figures is that most <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s are rubbish. For all their video and sound, few are more entertaining than the Pac Man video game of a decade ago. The transition from floppy discs to <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s increased the data-holding capacity of a disc nearly 400 times, but it did not increase the stock of creativity and good ideas in the world. To make matters worse, some of the better <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s are very expensive: the top games sell for an average of about $40 each. Multimedia developers blame the medium itself. <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s may seem to have a huge capacity--almost 600m bytes of information--but high-quality video can eat that up in about ten minutes. A new disc standard known as <font size=-1>DVD</font> with much more capacity is in the works, but that will take years to win acceptance. (<font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s took nearly a decade to reach even today's popularity.)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, it seems likely that by the time the <font size=-1>DVD</font> standard catches on, many of us will not be looking to discs at all for our entertainment. The greatest competition <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s now face is from entertainment and information features on the Internet, where there are essentially no space restrictions at all and everything is just a mouse-click or two away. This is why many analysts treat <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s as an interim technology, to be overtaken in time by the near limitless capacity and variety of computer networks. But that could take years. For now, most multimedia customers face <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s or nothing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is not necessarily a bad thing. Some <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s are worth their price, if you can find them. Most are sold in software shops, which have limited shelf space--often enough to hold just a hundred or so titles, less than 1% of those available. Predictably, the space goes first to the biggest brands--the Microsofts, Broderbunds and Mindscapes. The small publishers, which often have the most creative titles, are least likely to find a spot. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most shelf space, in any event, goes to cardboard. Because <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s are tricky to sample (shops try to avoid demonstration computers, which customers seem to crash with alarming regularity), <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> publishers use big boxes (mostly full of air) to show off a disc's charms. Add promotional gimmicks, such as plastic flying saucers, and shops are lucky if they can squeeze a few dozen titles on a wall. A bright-sounding idea to deal with this distribution bottleneck--persuading <font size=-1>PC</font>- makers to "bundle" their software free with new computers--boomeranged as consumers got the impression that <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s were give-aways.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Publishers are now backing away from bundling, and desperately hunting for some other way to make multimedia publishing a profitable business. Some are drawing a lesson from the Internet's success and offering "hybrid" <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s that combine multimedia on disc with updates and interactivity online. Publishers are also offering more for the money. Making a sellable <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> nowadays can take Hollywood-standard production. "Wing Commander IV", a game released earlier this year, cost $10m to make and stars Malcolm McDowell.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Hollywood analogy may go further. More and more the multimedia industry fits the Hollywood business model, where a few hits support a lot of misses. Hence the consolidations: only big companies can afford the losses. Small firms with the big ideas are finding it ever harder to survive. For them, the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> business is becoming a choice between three destinations: consolidation, the net or the bankruptcy courts.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
