</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Making it up</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Britain's monarchy</b></p>
<h2>Making it up</h2><ul> <li><a href="11ex336.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> Q<font size=-1>UEEN</a>:</font> A B<font size=-1>IOGRAPHY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> E<font size=-1>LIZABETH</font> II.&nbsp;  By Ben Pimlott. <br>
</ul>

<p>THE most important long-term decisions are sometimes taken by people who have no idea what they are doing. Ben Pimlott, in his excellent biography of Queen Elizabeth, gives the impression that the British monarchy is in such desperate trouble today because the queen and her courtiers a generation ago failed to take heed for the future. They were inexorably moving into an impasse--but did not know it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The queen inherited her conception of the monarchy from her father and grandfather. Ascending the throne at the age of 25, she had no ideas of her own. All she knew for sure was that she had to do her duty, and her duty consisted of marrying well, producing heirs, travelling widely in the Commonwealth, presiding over large numbers of ceremonial functions, reading the state papers that were set before her and keeping well out of party politics. Her duty also consisted of maintaining her own dignity and that of her family.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Maintaining her dignity in practice meant social detachment as well as personal remoteness. She came from the British aristocracy. Her friends were all from that closed circle, and she shared both their interests--horses, dogs and shooting--and their lack of interests--books, big ideas and high culture in any form. After a few exciting forays into the outside world as a teenager, she sought the company only of people like herself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, her temperament was as conservative as her surroundings. Her political views were mildly liberal--in the "One Nation" Tory manner--but socially and in her work habits she became set in her ways early in her reign and has remained so ever since. As Mr Pimlott says, she was against innovation: "Tradition, the rhythm of the royal seasons, doing things the way they had always been done, were her best comfort."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They were also her undoing. They led to sleepwalking, when the monarchy's future--her family's if not her own--depended on lynx-eyed alertness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Mr Pimlott shows, the monarchy during most of the present century rested on three supports: the British people's deference to their social superiors; the press's extreme reluctance to intrude too far into the royal family's private affairs; and the fact that--miracle of miracles--most of the royals, with the embarrassing exception of Edward VIII, who insisted on marrying an American divorc&#233;e, led unexceptional personal lives. What the queen seems not to have taken into account was the possibility, indeed the probability, that sooner or later all three supports would crumble.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though no one knew it at the time, the turning point came in the late 1960s. The queen and her advisers took it for granted that they could carry on much as before: rich, remote, socially aloof, moral exemplars to the nation. But simultaneously they decided to prove that the royal family was human--and also to court short-term popularity--by encouraging the <font size=-1>BBC</font> to transmit an extended documentary showing intimate details of the royals at work and play. That did it. Fully two-thirds of the population watched. Private lives became public. The mystery of royalty became mere glamour. "It was difficult", Mr Pimlott remarks drily, "once the genie of this kind of publicity had been let out of the bottle, to put it back in."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The publicity-unleashing documentary resulted from a tactical decision. What was lacking was a thought-through strategy. An old-fashioned, George VI-like monarchy might still have been possible, just, but only if the queen, her husband and all four children had been ready to lead blameless lives and avoid all controversy. Failing that--and the odds against such stringent conditions being fulfilled were enormous--the only option was to scale the monarchy down radically, with the royals not only paying taxes but taking jobs, giving interviews and--who knows?--perhaps even sending their children to state schools. As it was, the royals insisted on trying to remain on their pedestal and were knocked off.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Pimlott's biography of the queen is first-class history: well researched, well informed and gently ironic. He offers, instead of revelations, a balanced portrait of one person doing one job at one time. Junior members of the royal family should read it with care. All the signs are that--despite much thrashing about--they have still not decided what they want the future shape of the monarchy to be. If they do not decide wisely and soon, it may not have one.



