<html><head><title>River requiem</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="10gr5.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Hydromelancholics</b></p>
<h2>River requiem</h2><ul></ul>

A R<font size=-1>IVER</font> L<font size=-1>OST</font>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>IFE AND</font> D<font size=-1>EATH</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE
C</font><font size=-1>OLUMBIA</font>. By Blaine Harden. <i>Norton; 271 pages; $25</i>

<p>THOUGH not the longest river in North America, the Columbia is by far the most powerful. Draining an area larger than the eastern seaboard from Maine to Virginia, it falls nearly twice as far as the storied Mississippi in only half the distance. On its tumbling course it releases the energy of the Hiroshima bomb every half hour and provides a third of America's hydroelectric power. It is, or was, the world's greatest salmon hatchery, producing billions of salmon fry each year, hardy millions of which returned upstream against its cold, fast currents.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Untrammelled power was what struck the explorers Lewis and Clark when they paddled their canoes down the river's foaming rapids in 1805. Today, writes Blaine Harden, it is a different waterway, hardly worthy of the name "river", and he calls it instead a "managed pool". Sixteen dams on the Columbia and the Snake, its main tributary, control about every drop of water that flows from the Cascade Mountains into the vast Columbia Basin. So complete is human domination of the Columbia that it can be scheduled like a haircut for speedboat races, where 150-mph boats require slack water and precise depths.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With the river's flow has gone its salmon. Once counted in the millions, they now return by the hundreds--if at all. Many are barred from their spawning grounds by dams built without fish ladders; others lay eggs only to have the fry killed by spinning turbines and unnaturally warm waters as they try to reach the Pacific. Of the 400 native fish species formerly found in the Columbia, one-quarter are extinct and more than half are at risk of the same fate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In place of the salmon and the once-wild river, Mr Harden writes, has come a wave of farmers, barge owners and electricity customers. They see the river's cheap power and irrigation water as almost a customary right and balk at any suggestion that they might help pay the costs that controlling the Columbia have imposed on the region. To educate them, Mr Harden tallies that cost: diminished salmon runs; scattered Indian tribes who built a culture around salmon and now eat canned salmon provided by the government; millions of tax dollars spent on subsidised irrigation and power generation; and the creation of what may be the most polluted hazardous waste-site on the planet at Hanford, Washington, which was built in part because of its nearness to plentiful hydroelectric power.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although his subject is a river, Mr Harden's prism is those who work on and around it. Through his eyes you meet what seem like an unending parade of vain, greedy, wilfully ignorant individuals, many of whom say they never realised salmon swam in the Columbia or that their dam-formed lakes swamped a way of life that had existed for thousands of years. Instead, an engineer who designed dams insists they actually helped salmon when all the evidence shows the opposite. A farmer has no qualms about using (or selling at a profit) irrigation water that has cost taxpayers $2.1m in all for a 960-acre (390-hectare) farm. To barge operators it is not odd to make a town 200 miles inland a seaport.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Harden is not easy on these people. Rather than proud and independent empire-builders, they are, he says, "deadbeat debtors, unable to pay the bills they have run up, unwilling to acknowledge that debts even exist". But Mr Harden is equally tough on a newer generation: those "suburbanites with money and education and subscriptions to <i>Audubon</i> magazine" who would like the salmon saved because it sounds nice (despite billions in cost) or who want the Columbia reserved as a windsurfing playground.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why this ambivalence? Mr Harden, who has covered civil wars for the <i>Washington Post </i>from Africa and Yugoslavia, understands complexities. He knows, too, that reporters cannot wholly take themselves out of a story. Mr Harden benefited from the Columbia's destruction. During the 1930s depression his father helped build the huge Grand Coulee Dam. The savings put young Blaine through private college in eastern Washington and graduate school on the East Coast.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite this fine book's title, Mr Harden draws few firm conclusions. A returning native son, he writes less as judge or policy analyst than as a melancholy chronicler. "A River Lost" records in fascinating detail how the well-being of those who live off the Columbia's largesse was purchased with billions of federal dollars and how one of the West's most majestic rivers was sacrificed to economic advance.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845679600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
