<html><head><title>Money making</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="11gr9.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Practical economics</b></p>
<h2>Money making</h2><ul> <li><a href="11ex347.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> B<font size=-1>USINESS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMICS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By John Kay. <br>
</ul>



<p>"IF YOU'RE so smart, why aren't you rich?" This is a fair question to ask people selling financial advice, says John Kay in explaining how economics can be used to analyse business problems. It is a fair question to put to economists too: if they know so much about businesses and markets, why aren't they coining it?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The question would not stymie Mr Kay, who has achieved success both as an academic and as a businessman. He has long been a professor at the London Business School and has recently (too recently for the dust jacket of this collection of essays) been appointed director of Oxford University's new business school. To take up this post, he is relinquishing the chairmanship of London Economics, his successful economic consultancy firm.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The Business of Economics" contains 20 essays by Mr Kay that have appeared in newspapers and academic journals. Some of these are excellent. Mr Kay has a gift, rare among academic economists, for explaining how economics can be put to practical use. He points out that most economists are not, as people seem to believe, preoccupied by making inaccurate predictions about growth rates, inflation and unemployment. The majority specialise instead in microeconomics: the analysis of industries and markets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The best of his essays apply microeconomic analysis to everyday questions in a lucid and entertaining way. Why, for instance, is there never a shortage of taxis at Heathrow airport? Because the government sets fares too high, giving cab drivers an incentive to queue while passengers find other means of transport. Will technological advance mean that markets for audio-visual media come to be dominated by a few giants? Stop worrying, says Mr Kay. It is unlikely that anybody will have a monopoly of talent, publishing or distribution; a fragmented industry of large firms and small is more likely.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other articles examine what makes companies successful. Mr Kay argues that too many managers get carried away with a "vision" of their firm: as a result they think too little about its particular strengths and weaknesses, or about the nature of its markets. A favourite example is the misconceived attempt in the 1980s by Saatchi &amp; Saatchi, a British advertising company, to expand into a global advertising business by buying rival firms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, Mr Kay's least satisfactory arguments are those that will get the most attention, at least in Britain. He is a proponent of the "stakeholder" approach to capitalism, and he is seen as something of a hero by Tony Blair's New Labour and something of a villain by right-wingers. He does not believe that the purpose of companies is to maximise profits for their shareholders. They are not, he argues, owned by shareholders in any meaningful sense but are "social institutions". Shareholders are just one of several groups of stakeholders with claims on the firms. Others include customers, employees, suppliers and so on.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is either trivial or meaningless. Few companies, bar perhaps monopoly utilities, can afford to have a miserable workforce or disgruntled customers. If, that is, they want to be successful. Presumably, that means making money for their shareholders.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
