<html><head><title>Down the test tubes</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Subsidising scientific research</b></p>
<h2>Down the test tubes</h2><ul> <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMIC</font> L<font size=-1>AWS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>CIENTIFIC</font> R<font size=-1>ESEARCH</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Terence Kealey.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Macmillan; 384 pages; &#163;45</i> <br>
</ul>

<p>SOMETIMES the only way to convey the flavour of a banquet is to let people sample the grub themselves. Sink your teeth into the following typical morsel, footnotes and all, from a chapter entitled "Dr Pangloss was Right", in Terence Kealey's astonishing book:

<ul><font size=-1>What are the most important determinants of technological development? Are they the so-called supply factors of new science and new discoveries such as thinkers like Musson and Robinson,</font><font size=-2>47</font> Parker,<font size=-2>48</font> Rostow<font size=-2>49</font> or Rosenberg<font size=-2>50</font> believe, or are they the so-called demand factors of the search for greater profits as Marx, Schmookler<font size=-2>51</font> and Zevin<font size=-2>52</font> believe? It does not matter, as under <i>laissez faire</i> both needs are met. Is technological development largely a matter of giant leaps forward as Schumpeter<font size=-2>53</font> or Kuznets<font size=-2>54</font> believed, or does it emerge from the cumulative, anonymous, accretion of thousands of small improvements as Usher,<font size=-2>55</font> Gilfillan,<font size=-2>56</font>Landes,<font size=-2>57</font> Fishlow,<font size=-2>58</font> Hollander,<font size=-2>59</font> Hall<font size=-2>60</font> and Enos<font size=-2>61</font> believe? It does not matter, <i>laissez faire</i> meets both ends.</font></ul>


Reader, take <i>The Economist</i>'s word that it matters not a whit whether you have ever before heard of Gilfillan, Schmookler or Enos; nor whether you are a partisan of Kuznets or a critic of Landes; nor even whether you are allergic to footnotes. Mr Kealey, a teacher of biochemistry at Cambridge University, has produced one of the most appetising and sustained polemics ever concocted on a serious topic.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As it happens, the author's single-minded aim is to persuade you that the public funding of science and technology is not only unnecessary but also counter-productive. But you will enjoy this book even if the proper funding of science is a matter of utter indifference to you. For in following the argument you will discover along the way why it was the barbarians who invented soap and the stirrup (and why the Romans did not); what happened after Francis Bacon stuffed a chicken's carcass with snow at the foot of Highgate hill (and why the wretched man deserved his horrible fate); and what the fact that Marx abandoned the illegitimate child he sired through his wife's maid tells you about the public funding of universities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What, though, if you do care about the proper funding of science? This book is thoroughly iconoclastic. Mr Kealey refuses to buy the argument that one thing the state really does need to pay for is science and technology, and that by doing so it can boost economic growth. This, he argues, is an illusion fostered by Bacon, who got technology quite the wrong way around, and which has been sustained ever since by people with a vested interest in receiving state handouts. In practice, he says, technology arises from trial and error by practical people going about their business, and the speed of discovery is determined largely by the extent of economic freedom.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To prove his case, Mr Kealey deploys a prodigious erudition. He reviews antiquity, and discovers that "plunder empires" like the Roman one collapsed because they neglected technology, whereas "market empires" thrived. He ridicules the idea that scientific understanding leads to new technology, on the ground that it is almost always the reverse that is true. James Watt's improvement of the steam engine in the industrial revolution owed nothing to Joseph Black's scientific study of latent heat. Farmers bred new strains of animals and crops for millennia before Gregor Mendel systematised the scientific laws that underpinned what they were doing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Mr Kealey's history, it is almost always commerce that comes first, techno logy second and science third. And yet in modern times governments have taken the opposite view, pouring subsidies into universities to fund research that firms would do voluntarily if they could see the way to profit from it. Mr Kealey notes that European governments have lately subsidised dozens of initiatives to help their electronics industry, but that it is the largely unsubsidised American firms that have triumphed. State funding has turned academic science itself into "an artificial, self-referential, government-funded asylum".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a brilliant book, but also an over-stated one, and there is something of the curmudgeon and the martyr in its author's tone. Mr Kealey admits that he has often felt lonely ploughing his <i>laissez-faire</i> furrow and ends by declaring that he has striven to obey Solzhenitsyn's instruction to "pursue the truth regardless of the consequences". One certain consequence is that he will be denounced as a traitor by colleagues in the publicly funded universities whose very reason for being he has called into question. Yet he may also have provided a good reason for maintaining such institutions. Where else can a free spirit afford to bite so hard the hand that feeds it? Certainly not in the <i>laissez-faire</i> world of business.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
