<html><head><title>What the world is reading</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">


<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top>

</td></tr></table>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<br>
<h2>What the world is reading</h2>

<p>

Spain's bestseller lists are notably pointy-headed. Compare them with America's. Relatively few Spaniards buy books and those who do have rather literary tastes. Serious novels, including two reviewed above, bulk large on our fiction list from Spain this month--a list that includes essays and reflections or what the French call <i>belles lettres</i> as well as novels proper.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Few writers in Spanish are more bankable than Gabriel Garcia Marquez. His latest ''fiction'', an imaginative account of a real-life kidnapping of nine journalists in his native Colombia in 1990, is top. But Carmen Martin Gaite, one of Spain's own leading novelists, is second with ''Lo Raro es Vivir'' (The strange thing is living), dwelling here, as before, on women's lives. Indeed, apart from Stephen King (America) and Susanna Tamaro (Italy), the rest of the fiction list is also notable for its native provenance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though dying in English, the essay as a form is alive in Spain, even if this sampling has an undertow of cultural pessimism. Jose Saramago's ''Sobre la Ceguera'' (On Blindness) questions the solidity of Western society, Manuel Vincent writes of 1960s dreams gone sour and Vicente Verdu in ''El Planeta Americano'' (The American Planet) calls for resistance to America's cultural imperialism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The last of these three books is third on the non-fiction list--more evidence that in the Spanish-reading world fiction is not segregated from non-fiction as rigidly as it is elsewhere. To confuse things a bit more, at the top of the non-fiction list is the latest hit by another leading Spanish novelist, Manuel Vazquez Montalban.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A protean author, he writes journalism, thrillers and literary novels. His latest book, ''Un Polaco en el Corte del Rey Juan Carlos" (A Pole at the Court of King Juan Carlos) revives the old device of a <i>faux-naif</i> observing his own country as a foreigner. He has interviewed 30 important people and takes readers into Spain's corridors of power.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Civil war is a bitter but popular theme as three non-fiction bestsellers show. Spaniards at last are writing their own books about their civil war (1936-39). And Jose Antonio Mendiluce, who ran the United Nation's relief effort there, laments western inaction during Yugoslavia's (1991-5).

<br>
