<html><head><title>Enigmatic</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>The world's bureaucrats</b></p>
<h2>Enigmatic</h2><ul> <li><a href="11ex340.html">C<font size=-1>IVIL</font> S<font size=-1>ERVICE</font> S<font size=-1>YSTEMS</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> C<font size=-1>OMPARATIVE</font> P<font size=-1>ERSPECTIVE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  Edited by Hans Bekke, James Perry, and Theo Toonen. <br>
</ul>


<p>CIVIL-SERVICE reform is a global business. Consultants, large and small, earn fat fees from advising governments on modernising their bureaucracies, and sometimes on how to clear up the mess left by earlier reformers. The flow of advice was once mainly from rich to poor countries. But in the past decade the industrial countries themselves have been the scene of frantic consultancy activity and another big market has opened up as the former communist states seek (or are offered, unsolicited) guidance on how to create bureaucracies fit for new democrats.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Consultants themselves are a pragmatic lot. Academic social scientists are much more disposed to try to develop theories and a language to debate them in. The dozen chapters in this book, based on papers given at an academic conference, include an agreeably learned account of the evolution of government servants since the Middle Ages, an authoritative outline of theoretical and methodological problems, an elegant deconstruction of the clutch of activities commonly labelled "new public management" and a review of the international diffusion of specific reforms during the 1980s and 1990s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Overall, it left this reviewer in an ambivalent frame of mind. It is obviously important for all concerned to be clear about what is being discussed. One basic question, for instance, centres on numbers. How useful is it to compare the size of the "civil service" between countries that legally or technically define the institution in different ways? Are there organisations or activities whose employees are not really part of the civil service at all, even though they are locally classified as civil servants? What about the staff of lighthouses, railways, schools, driving-test depots or the agencies the British call quangos?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More subtly, if it is accepted that civil servants must be distinguished from politicians working in government, on which side of the line do you put political advisers in Britain, political appointees in the United States and personal appointments in Mexico? In what important sense are any of these not civil servants? Do they all fall into the same category?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such questions may seem pedantic, as may the book's definition of civil services as "mediating institutions that mobilise human resources in the service of the affairs of the state in a given territory". (This is not wholly satisfactory: where does it place, for example, the independent non-government organisations that are now put under government contract to provide essential services?) But without an agreed language to describe and compare, descriptions are liable to be unhelpful and comparisons misleading.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the other hand, its academic rigour notwithstanding, this book sharply illustrates the gap that can separate those interested in theory and those concerned with practice. It is hard not to regret that some 150,000 words devoted to the analysis and description of contemporary institutions throw so little light on how the resultant theories might be applied to those institutions.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
