<html><head><title>Civil Service Systems in Comparative Perspective.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl340.jpg"><img src="cs340.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>C<font size=-1>IVIL</font> S<font size=-1>ERVICE</font> S<font size=-1>YSTEMS</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> C<font size=-1>OMPARATIVE</font> P<font size=-1>ERSPECTIVE</font>.<br></h2>
<p> Edited by Hans Bekke, James Perry, and Theo Toonen. <br>
<i>Indiana University Press; 346 pages; $39.95 and &#163;15.50</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="11bt340.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Over the past decade, civil service systems in eastern Europe, Africa, and China have undergone
significant transformation. Even in the United States, civil service has been subjected to successive
waves of reform. But while civil service systems play critical roles throughout the world, our
knowledge about them and the changes they are undergoing is remarkably limited. This book aims to
describe and analyze civil service systems throughout the world, to understand how they function and
how they might best be managed, and to lay the foundation for future theoretical work.
<p>The essays are arranged in five thematic sections. Part One provides a general orientation to issues of theory and methodology. Part two is devoted to an examination of the history and structure of civil service systems. Part three explores contextual characteristics of civil service systems. Part four looks at civil service systems from holistic perspectives. Part five examines change and transformation in civil service systems. The editors' concluding chapter examines common themes and proposes an agenda for future research. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
