<html><head><title>Blob of mercury</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>A literary life</b></p>
<h2>Blob of mercury</h2><ul><li>F<font size=-1>ORD</font> M<font size=-1>ADOX</font> F<font size=-1>ORD</a>:</font> A D<font size=-1>UAL</font> L<font size=-1>IFE</font>&nbsp; By Max Saunders.<br>
</ul>


<p>IN HIS novels, in his reminiscences, in his dazzling chatter and in his morals and conduct, Ford Madox Ford is like a blob of mercury in the palm of the hand. Glittering, it slips and slides and is never still. But, then, is not mercury a seeming contradiction, a liquid metal? Ford's novels, especially his central masterpiece, "The Good Soldier", certainly suggest that he viewed human character and behaviour like that, as being fluid and perpetually in motion. In doing so, he in effect invites his readers to avoid making any moral judgment. Which, of course, is a way of deflecting judgment from his own shifty conduct.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His great achievement was to realise and present that sense of fluidity and endless motion in his novels. He did so by harnessing his subjective insights to an objective technique of presentation. His latest biographer, Max Saunders, uses the fine phrase "ironic pathos" to describe Ford's approach and treatment in his fiction. Ford, not least because of his knowledge of himself, was obsessed with the ever changing and pathetic patterns of life; but he was able to stand aside from them in his novels and present them objectively, neutrally and ironically. This is where Ford shows that mercury is a metal.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He did so, spasmodically, elsewhere. He helped to sustain Joseph Conrad at a crucial stage in Conrad's creative development. He was a perceptive literary critic, actively encouraging the <i>avant-garde</i> movement in literature without becoming a member of it. As an editor he recognised and fostered the talents of Ezra Pound, D.H. Lawrence and later Ernest Hemingway. The quality of the two literary reviews he edited was outstanding. But they were short-lived. They brought nothing but financial calamity to Ford's backers, dissolving in acrimony, with Ford, true to himself, sidling away from responsibility. It is not just that Ford was unreliable. He was, like mercury, essentially slippery.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That much is plain in his continual retelling and remoulding of anecdotes about himself, both in speech and in prose. He was, as he put it, giving an "impression" of the events. Conscience did not guide Ford's consciousness. Promiscuous by nature, he satisfied his own appetite, constantly falling in and out of friendship and love. Polygamous is perhaps a fairer word than promiscuous to describe his attitude towards women. He needed them. But at heart, one suspects, he despised them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So slippery a man as Ford presents a problem to any biographer. Which version of what Ford said happened, did happen? Or, even more to the point, did it happen at all? Sometimes there is only Ford's word to say that it did--and that word is, to put it mildly, elusive. Five years ago, Alan Judd adroitly and successfully skirted round the difficulty by following Ford's own method and presenting an "impression" of the man. Not unkindly one hopes, Mr Saunders describes Mr Judd's biography as "novelistic". It is not a path that Mr Saunders, a literary academic, can or cares to follow. Rather, as literary biographer, he must track down every scrap of evidence, balance one piece against another and then assess their significance to his subject's creative output.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Saunders does so exhaustively--and exhaustingly--first from one angle, then another and then yet another. One sixth of his book is occupied by footnotes; another twelfth by his examination of "The Good Soldier". And this is simply the first volume of two. It ends with Ford on his way to the Western Front in 1916 and, thus, to a shattering series of experiences which, after the war, he turned to triumphant account in the Tietjens tetralogy. This then, as the publisher acknowledges in its price, is a scholarly biography aimed at scholars. It helps to clear the air. It does not make for easy reading. And it raises a question. Does Ford Madox Ford really merit such intense care and immense labour? Perhaps--but only just perhaps.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
