http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev12/rv2/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113123613 text/html 8536
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 12:32:30 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 03-Dec-96 18:24:34 GMT
Content-length: 8352
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Second best?</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="12gr2.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Brothers and sisters</b></p>
<h2>Second best?</h2><ul> <li><a href="12ex358.html">B<font size=-1>ORN</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> R<font size=-1>EBEL</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Frank Sulloway<br>
 <li>P<font size=-1>ECKING </font>O<font size=-1>RDER</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Joy Berthoud.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Gollancz; 256 pages; &#163;9.99</i> <br>
</ul>


</i>

<p>THIS review requires an admission. Your correspondent is a first-born. She is therefore, on Frank Sulloway's reckoning, predisposed to be a "tough-minded conservative", with a tendency to "reject new ideas", especially when the innovation appears to challenge "long-established principles". The reader of these two books will search in vain for similar frankness about their birth order from Mr Sulloway or Joy Berthoud. That is a shame, for both authors believe that birth order is one of the most important influences on personality.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Sulloway has written by far the better book. Ms Berthoud confines herself to a string of anecdotes about famous people and friends who fit her preconceptions. We learn that "children in large families may lack parental attention", that first-borns strive to "meet their parents' high expectations"; that second children are sometimes rebellious and sometimes lazy; and that youngest children can easily be spoilt. Her breezily written book makes no attempt to test her theories, let alone deal with examples that do not fit. The main fun, for London journalists, will be trying to count how many of their chums appear in it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Sulloway of Harvard University is another matter. He knows that there is a long debate on the effects of birth order on personality. He admits that most reviews of the issue, including a mammoth survey of the scientific literature by two Swiss scholars, C&eacute;cile Ernst and Jules Angst, have failed to establish a connection. But he is struck by the history of Charles Darwin's findings on evolution, and especially by the fact that Darwin's close colleagues, faced with the same evidence on which he based his ideas, refused to abandon their belief in creationism. Why should it be, Mr Sulloway wondered, that some people rapidly espouse new insights while others cling to their old, erroneous ways of thinking?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To discover the answer, he has set to work on a mountain of data: mainly, studies of reactions to 28 new scientific ideas, spread over five centuries. His list includes the Copernican revolution, Newtonian physics, and Einstein's theories of relativity. For good measure, he tosses in five "conservative" theories, including spiritualism and eugenics.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Studying the reactions of contemporaries to these ideas, he finds that most scientific innovations, especially radical ones, were initiated and championed by "later-borns"--those who are not first-borns. He even quantifies his conclusion: later-borns are 5-15 times more likely to espouse radical ideas than first-borns in the early stages of a scientific revolution, while first-borns are twice as likely as later-borns to support conservative ideas. "Some people", he concludes, "are born to rebel."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For this view, he has a Darwinian explanation. Siblings within a family compete with each other for parental attention. In nature, older siblings sometimes carry the struggle to extreme lengths: blue-footed booby chicks peck their baby brothers and sisters to death if they are not getting enough to eat. In human families, younger siblings have usually had a raw deal: in ancient Japan, they were nicknamed "cold rice", after the custom of feeding them on disagreeable leftovers. Whether younger siblings develop their revolutionary traits as a result of this sort of treatment, or as a sort of Darwinian specialisation, Mr Sulloway is not entirely clear.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sadly, the principle seems altogether more complicated when applied to politics. Sometimes, it works a treat: one of the most striking of Mr Sulloway's many graphs shows the extraordinary tendency, during the Reformation in Europe, for first-borns to be martyred for adhering to the Catholic faith and later-borns to be martyred as Protestants. But the history of the French Revolution is more confusing. It was, Mr Sulloway argues, essentially a conflict between older and younger brothers. Royalists were largely first-borns. But so were the most extreme leaders of the monarchy's opponents. The moderates tended to be middle children. In the national convention that voted on whether to execute Louis XVI, first-borns were the most sharply divided group. Those from the upper classes were more likely than any other group to vote for mercy; those from the lower classes, to vote against it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"First-borns lead fashionable reforms, populist reforms and orthodox science," concludes Mr Sulloway. Later-borns espouse unpopular social causes, radical revolutions and radical scientific ideas, he says, sounding a mite as if stretching characteristics to fit the history.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The book's broad drift is hard to quarrel with. To earlier ages, it would have seemed odd not to accept that people's experiences within their own families are a powerful influence on their subsequent behaviour. After all, for centuries, birth order determined people's wealth, political power, marriageability and survival prospects. In some societies, it still does. We accept, readily enough, that differences between families--social factors--can shape political and social attitudes. Why should we give so much less weight to differences within families--linked to birth order?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Three points, however, are missing from Mr Sulloway's book. First, birth order is only one of the ways in which people's experiences in their family shape their lives. Relations with parents--do they die? love you? split up?--are surely also important. And even the counterpoint of "first-born" and "later-born" is an inadequate description of the impact of siblings. Most people would instinctively assume that their gender and number was just as important; it would be good to have evidence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Secondly, his assumption that sibling behaviour is driven chiefly by instinctive competition ignores the instances where siblings collaborate for the good of the family, or gang up together against "outsiders", including parents.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is lastly a broader question. It is almost certain that a smaller proportion of people around the world have siblings than ever before in history. Put in a more roundabout way, the proportion of later-borns to first-borns is shrinking, and, if Mr Sulloway is right, that could have wide-ranging consequences. He blames, for example, the resistance of 19th-century French scientists to Darwin's theory of evolution on the unusually small size of French families, which led to a scarcity of innovatory younger sons. Will family shrinkage produce a society that is more conservative and authoritarian--a world fit for stick-in-the-mud first-borns? This first-born, for one, hopes not.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
