<html><head><title>Born to Rebel.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl358.jpg"><img src="cs358.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>B<font size=-1>ORN</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> R<font size=-1>EBEL</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Frank Sulloway<br>
<i>Little, Brown; 653 pages; &#163;20. Pantheon; $30.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="12bt358.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Born to Rebel begins its far-reaching inquiry with the puzzle of sibling
relationships. Why are individuals from the same family often no more
similar in personality than those from different families? The family, as
it turns out, is not a 'shared environment' but rather a series of distinct
micro-environments in which siblings experience the family in different
ways.
<p>In Born to Rebel, Frank Sulloway presents a pioneering view of how family structure affects individual development. Birth order, he shows, is a key factor in understanding the dynamics of sibling relationships and is so fundamental to the family experience that its effects transcend gender, social class, and time. Drawing on the work of Darwin and the powerful insights to emerge from the new science of evolutionary psychology, he offers a provocative analysis of the genetic and environmental influences that together shape human behaviour.</p>
<p>Most persuasively, Sulloway's findings offer conclusive evidence that the family, with its powerful interpersonal dynamics, is a cauldron for historical change. Through revolutions in scientific and historical thought, from the Reformation to the Darwinian theory of natural selection, Sulloway demonstrates that the primary engine of history is located within families, not between them, as Marx believed. Sulloway also shows that Sigmund Freud, with his psychosexual approach to family relationships, failed to understand the true causes of individual development.</p>
<p>By moving the basis for individuality and rebellion to the tension that exists between siblings in their quest for parental favour, Born to Rebel is certain to transform the nature of biographical, sociological and historical inquiry. it confirms, in lucid and accessible argument, the contention of sociobiologist Edward 0. Wilson twenty years ago: that Darwin's evolution theories provide a solid scientific foundation for the understanding of human activity. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
