<html><head><title>Few questions asked</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>British history</b></p>
<h2>Few questions asked</h2><ul> <li>H<font size=-1>OPE</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> G<font size=-1>LORY</font></a>: B<font size=-1>RITAIN</font> 1900-1990.&nbsp;  By Peter Clarke.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Allen Lane/Penguin Press; 464 pages; &#163;25 and $29.95</i> <br>
</ul>

<p>PROFICIENT, lucid and civil, Professor Peter Clarke's study of the United Kingdom in the 20th century marshals a fluent narrative and wide range of data for the launching volume of Penguin's new history of Britain. Mr Clarke's strengths lie in two fields rarely combined, but both on display here: high politics and practical economics. For contemporary taste, and the purpose of the series, he offers regular intervals of social and cultural commentary too. The result is an agreeable, reliable textbook. But Mr Clarke's approach has a price. Nearly a century is covered in fewer pages than A.J.P. Taylor devoted to 30 years in his "English History 1914-1945"--in more ways than one the shadow behind this work; and attention is allocated with mechanical evenness among them, at the rate of a chapter for every eight or nine years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The consequences are, necessarily, a flattening of dramatic structure and foreshortening of analytic perspective. The decisive experiences of British history in this century were the two world wars. Besides their effects, everything else has been secondary. Here, fatally, these heights are reduced to the same level as the lowest marshlands--the first world war is dispatched in less space than the time of Harold Wilson. Under such a metronomic rhythm, proportional significance drains away. The neutralising effect is reinforced by the curiously undemanding way in which leading politicians of every camp tend to be described. An extreme case is Lloyd George, treated with conventional sentimentality ("at his incomparable best"); but even James Callaghan becomes "in many ways an impressive figure as a prime minister". Occasional wry asides do not really alter a tone of generalised indulgence, that falters only at Margaret Thatcher.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Leniency of portraiture could be taken as no more than an amiable quirk. But it reflects an underlying uncertainty of theme. For what were the historic tasks against which the temperaments of successive leaders are to be measured? Mr Clarke begins his book by criticising the over-concentration of recent literature on the issue of national decline. Loss of empire may have reduced British power in the world, but the welfare of the British people has steadily increased, as economic growth and social reform have vastly improved the lot of the majority. This was Taylor's conclusion a generation ago. Since then Britain's relative standards of prosperity and welfare have sunk within the <font size=-1>OECD</font>, while absolute levels of inequality have increased. So Mr Clarke cannot end his story in quite the same way. He must instead regret that Britain missed its early chance of joining Europe, and note the toll exacted since.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, as he acknowledges, the reason Britain cold-shouldered the European Economic Community was the illusion of continuing global status. Social progress cannot be considered simply a redeeming counterpoint to imperial decline, since the one was shaped and limited by the other. Britain in 1900 was the world's premier power, and the maintenance of empire the overriding concern of its rulers. Everything distinctive about the British state was related to that one paramount aim. Yet, in Mr Clarke's account, the first world war comes virtually out of the blue, in an otherwise peaceable domestic narrative. Though assuring his readers that Britain "did the right thing" in 1939, he does not raise the more critical question whether it did so in 1914. The plunge into European killing is all but taken for granted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Similarly, in the inter-war period, the strategic calculations of an imperial establishment are largely pushed off-stage: foreign policy reduced to emergency fare. Caustic historians of the right--Correlli Barnett, Maurice Cowling, John Charmley--offer a more vivid sense of the realities of British power in these years. Mr Clarke's centrist pastels do justice neither to the scale of imperial destiny, nor to the price it exacted. His verdict on the post-war record is an epitome of insular complacency. "British decolonisation", he opines, "was to prove relatively successful, leaving few of the scars suffered by other ex-colonial powers." So much for the partitions of India, Cyprus, Ireland--an unfinished toll of dead exceeding that of Algeria and Indochina.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The home scene is covered much more deftly. But even here, the peculiar structures of the British political order and social conflict are assumed rather than assessed, in a story that rarely pauses for comparative scrutiny. The reasons why a pre-democratic electoral system stayed unchanged; why Conservatives displaced Liberals rather than vice versa; why Labour so rarely ruled, when most voters were working-class; why attempts to regenerate industry regularly misfired; why education never achieved national coherence--questions like these fall out of the frame. The antiquated cast of the British state, now timidly at issue in current politics, finds no historical reflection here. The European Union may well make short work of such insouciance. In one of the silliest claims a publisher has made in years, Penguin announces--under the signature of David Cannadine as general editor--its new series as "the definitive history of Britain for our day and generation". On present evidence, as befits such hype, it risks anachronism at birth.





<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
