<html><head><title>Magical and spiritual</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr15.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Fiction from France</b></p>
<h2>Magical and spiritual</h2><ul> <li>L<font size=-1>A</font> N<font size=-1>UIT</font> L<font size=-1>A</font> N<font size=-1>EIGE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Claude Pujade-Renaud.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Actes Sud; 459 pages; FFr138</i>. <br>
 <li>L<font size=-1>A</font> S<font size=-1>ORCI&Egrave;RE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Marie Ndiaye.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Minuit; 192 pages; FFr85.</i> <br>
 <li>L<font size=-1>A</font> V<font size=-1>IERGE DU</font> G<font size=-1>RAND</font> R<font size=-1>ETOUR</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Rapha&#145;l Confiant.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Grasset; 394 pages: FFr139</i>. <br>
 <li>L<font size=-1>E</font> R<font size=-1>OMAN D'</font>A<font size=-1>DAM ET</font> E<font size=-1>VE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Bernard No&#145;l.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Stock; 242 pages; FFr120</i>. <br>
 <li>E<font size=-1>CLAT</font> <font size=-1>DE</font> S<font size=-1>EL</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Sylvie Germain.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Gallimard; 176 pages; FFr89</i> <br>
</ul><ul></ul>


IN FRANCE the start of this new publishing year is a crowded and jostling affair, with more than 300 novels appearing on the autumn lists. It is a pleasure to discover among them a few good books.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From Madame de La Fayette to Michelet, French writers have often been fascinated by the nature of female power. The exploration continues through the heroines of some of the best of this autumn's novels. They are witches, go-betweens, mystical figures, and together almost create the impression that the power of women can be described only in supernatural terms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Claude Pujade-Renaud concentrates on the confrontation between two women on a December night in 1714. A nocturnal interview with the new queen of Spain leads to the fall of Anne-Marie des Ursins, the governess to the children of Philip V of Spain. Through the marriages and intrigues that she had organised over 20 years, Anne-Marie had guided the destinies of many of the royal courts of Europe, which she hoped to bring under the control of Louis XIV.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In "La Nuit La Neige" ("Night, Snow") the thoughts and memories of that night's protagonists are subtly intertwined in a polyphony of mostly women's voices. The voices return again and again to that fateful confrontation behind closed doors, seeking to explore its secrets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What emerges from the story is an understanding of a certain type of female power. Anne-Marie des Ursins complains that her enemies attribute the practical fruits of her intelligence to witchcraft; for through their eyes a woman who wields power succeeds only by foul means, through potions or exploiting her sexuality. The reader soon comes to understand that the causes of Anne-Marie's downfall are to be sought in the struggle between her, the dowager, and a young queen unversed in courtly machinations who is attempting to establish her authority.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Witchcraft in this case is only the political pretext for demonising a woman's power. It is a reality in Marie Ndiaye's "La Sorci&egrave;re" ("The Sorceress"), which imperceptibly installs the fantastical at the very heart of the banal and everyday. In "La Femme Chang&eacute;e en B&#158;che" ("The Woman Turned into a Log") she told the story of a woman whose husband abandons her and offers her child to the devil, who lives in a dreary building in the Parisian suburbs. In her latest novel she takes us immediately to a house in a dormitory town, where Lucie, a housewife, leads her twin daughters, Maud and Lise, down to the cellar to teach them the secrets of witchcraft which are passed on from mother to daughter.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lucie has been abandoned by her husband, as was her own mother before her. Both women were estranged from their spouses because they possessed powers that the men found repulsive. Despite her powers, Lucie fails to bring about a reconciliation between her parents (her mother ends up turning her father into a snail). She also fails to retain her daughters, whose own powers soon prove to be enormous. They eventually turn themselves into crows and fly off for good. In this dissolution of family ties, Lucie's everyday life is gradually consumed by the fantastical. What Ms Ndiaye provides is minute observation of a trapped creature and its reactions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Superstition and the supernatural are also at the heart of Rapha&#145;l Confiant's "La Vierge du Grand Retour" ("The Virgin of the Great Return"). It tells of the arrival in the French West Indies of a statue of the Virgin Mary that has purportedly brought about a number of miracles in metropolitan France. Philom&egrave;ne, a whore and saint, and Dictionneur, a living dictionary, gradually see through the fraud. It represents a joint effort by local churchmen and the <i>b&eacute;k&eacute;</i> (white) power structure to subdue the black population through trickery and to embezzle their offerings to Mary.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The d&eacute;nouement sees the wrong-doers punished, sinking into the sea together with their booty , while the "son of the devil himself" splits his sides laughing as he urinates on the object of adoration. Interweaving references to the Bible with stories from the popular quarter of Morne-Pichevin, the narrator traces the emergence of a unifying faith, suited to creoles. Through it they free themselves from their chains, and give the female deity a new significance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Le Roman d'Adam et Eve" ("The Story of Adam and Eve"), an erudite metaphysical thriller, is a reflection on the meaning of the original couple, and particularly on the role of the woman, who led mankind into temptation. Intrigued by a puzzling collection of photographs of women and landscapes, the narrator investigates the disappearance of Jean, the attractive and fashionable photographer who took them. The only clues are a forgotten play by Bulgakov, itself entitled "Adam and Eve", the book of Genesis and the incomplete and sometimes enigmatic stories of old Stalinist barons. In the course of his investigations, the narrator/detective gets caught up in the tortuous by-ways of the Stalinist Soviet Union, which attempted, in its own way, to create a New Man and a New Woman. And later in the machinations of the mafiaesque Russian capitalists who have succeeded the Stalinists.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A puzzle also lies at the heart of Sylvie Germain's "Eclat de Sel" ("A Fragment of Salt"). Ludvik's life and memories are left in pieces after two turning points. The first comes when he sees a blind couple dancing, the worse for drink, at a kitsch-ridden ballroom in Marianske Lazne. This spectacle persuades him that he can no longer live like a sleep-walker in communist Czechoslovakia, suffering from "blindness of the soul". The second comes when he leaves his Parisian lover, and returns to Prague, "satiated with freedom but weak in ideals".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Back in Prague, he wanders through the city, allowing his memory to unfold as a collage of diverse fragments, within which he attempts gradually, and eventually successfully, to detect the pattern that will free him of his disgust at life. Like Everyman, he has to escape from a life too full of meaning, too full of ideology, and simply one morning to open his eyes once again to gaze desiringly on the world. Whatever other criticisms may be levelled at this summer's French novels, they cannot be accused of lack of ambition.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
