<html><head><title>Flash art?</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="10gr4.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>The Renaissance</b></p>
<h2>Flash art?</h2><ul> <li><a href="10ex300.html">W<font size=-1>ORLDLY</font> G<font size=-1>OODS</a>:</font> A N<font size=-1>EW</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY OF THE</font> R<font size=-1>ENAISSANCE</font>.&nbsp;  By Lisa Jardine. <br>
</ul>


<p>LISA JARDINE'S richly illustrated tour of well-trod ground offers what an academic colleague has obligingly blurbed "an entirely new approach to the Renaissance". Her supposedly novel tactic is to focus on commodities and acquisitions, on the pursuit of splendour and the minutiae of trade, so as to establish that "the seeds of our own...bravura consumerism were planted in the European Renaissance".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The claim is certainly bold; but is this style of history really so original? In the 19th century it would have been. There is not much talk of economics in Jacob Burckhardt's "The Civilisation of the Renaissance in Italy", first published in 1860 and still rightly regarded as the single best introduction to Renaissance studies. Writing history, of course, has moved on since then and the idea that wealth had something interesting to do with the creative abundance of certain cities in 15th-century Europe is hardly news. Ms Jardine's laborious documentation of the commercial struggles that were being fought while the great artists and thinkers of the Renaissance painted and thought will be familiar stuff to historians and students.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And to the general reader. Accessible and popular works, such as those of Sir John Hale, have ploughed this furrow for a long time and with less fuss. A mere 23 pages on "Cash and Culture" in his recent book, "The Civilisation of Europe in the Renaissance" (HarperCollins, 1993) says more or less everything the curious lay person might want to know on this subject.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He also issues salutary warnings to those who would make too much of economics here. Although he writes of the Renaissance as a "purchasing extravaganza", he points out that the broad correlation between creativity and commerce is weak. Other Italian cities--notably Genoa--were as commercially active as Florence, yet produced few significant artists, writers or thinkers. The prosperity of Elizabethan England, to take another example, still left it a net importer of fine and decorative arts. So if Ms Jardine wants to establish that her lavish and almost interminable descriptions of the goods that princes and merchants fought over, commissioned and treasured shed light on the period when modern Europe rivalled classical Athens, then she has a lot of arguing to do.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet she does none. Instead, the reader gets a wealth of detail about the materials and craftsmanship of knick-knacks, soft furnishings and masterpieces that is aimless and therefore, frankly, boring. When she pauses on her tours of the stores to point to a moral in this welter of shopping and selling, the offering is usually trite. (Did you know that it was "market demand as understood by the printer and his backers" which decided "choices of texts and strategies for distributing them"? Yes.)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Ms Jardine is correct in her conclusion that the world you now inhabit, "with its ruthless competitiveness, fierce consumerism, restless desire for ever wider horizons, for travel, discovery and innovation...is a world which was made in the Renaissance", then her documentation of these facets of early modern Europe might have a point. Perhaps she is correct. But she offers no evidence that is genuinely relevant to this claim, for she never considers whether ruthless competitiveness and the rest of it might not have existed before her chosen period.




<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
