<html><head><title>Worldly Goods</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl300.jpg"><img src="cs300.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>W<font size=-1>ORLDLY</font> G<font size=-1>OODS:<br></font> A N<font size=-1>EW</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY OF THE</font> R<font size=-1>ENAISSANCE</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Lisa Jardine. <br>
<i>Macmillan; 470 pages; &#163;25</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="10bt300.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
The flowering of civilization, the rebirth of classical scholarship and the
emergence of some of the greatest artists and thinkers the world has known:
this is the traditional view of the Renaissance.
<p>WORLDLY GOODS provides a radical reinterpretation of that Golden Age of European culture. In it, Lisa Jardine argues that while crowned heads and merchant entrepreneurs competed with each other to acquire works of art from the leading artists of the day, vicious commercial battles were being found over silks and spices and over who should control the centres for international trade around the globe. The rapidly expanding trade in printed books--a new marketable commodity seized upon with equal enthusiasm by investors and consumers--disseminated the 'new learning' via publishing houses and printing presses across Europe, stimulating what was to become the European intellectual tradition by accident as much as by design.</p>
<p>WORLDLY GOODS examines the material culture of the Renaissance in all its locations, from it western borders in Christendom to its eastern one in the Islamic Ottoman Empire. It shows how a determination to show magnificence on the part of the wealthy easily became crude competitiveness and avarice as they vied with one another to acquire rare and exotic moveable goods: paintings, tapestries, printed books, precious gems, brocades and damasks, bronzes and palaces. In doing so, Professor Jardine gives us both a dazzling vision of a rapidly changing world and a completely new understanding of the Renaissance. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845679600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
