<html><head><title>Emily Smith versus Maria Perez</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="11gr4.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Positive discrimination in America</b></p>
<h2>Emily Smith versus Maria Perez</h2><ul> <li><a href="11ex338.html">I<font size=-1>N</font> D<font size=-1>EFENCE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> A<font size=-1>FFIRMATIVE</font> A<font size=-1>CTION</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Barbara Bergmann. <br>
 <li><a href="11ex344.html">T<font size=-1>RAGIC</font> F<font size=-1>AILURE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Tom Wicker. <br>
 <li><a href="11ex343.html">W<font size=-1>HEN</font> W<font size=-1>ORK</font> D<font size=-1>ISAPPEARS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By William Julius Wilson. <br>
</ul>





<p>CONSIDER a rich young woman applying to an elite university. Her mother is Mexican: call her Perez. Her father is a white Anglo: call him Smith. If her parents had thought about it with an eye to this day, they might have chosen to call her, say, Maria Perez. Under America's affirmative action policy, she would have a much better chance of getting the college place if she could tick the Hispanic box on the application form. But if her parents instead chose to call her, say, Emily Smith, she faces much stiffer competition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is circumstances like these that make affirmative action such a contentious issue in America. Does the fate of Maria/Emily Smith/Perez do justice to the disadvantaged minorities that affirmative action was supposed to serve? Probably not.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now consider another case, of a poor young black man: call him Leroy Washington. He has finished high school and has applied for a job. The interviewer is dubious--not that she's a racist, mind you, but she's hired his kind before and they are just too unreliable and difficult to work with. The company, a smallish one that does not have to apply employment preferences, is truly sorry to say they can find nothing for him. Would affirmative action have helped this young man? Perhaps so.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Neither of these scenarios is implausible. Those who oppose affirmative action use the first as evidence of the evils of race-counting; those who favour it point to the all too common plight of America's Leroy Washingtons. There is a middle ground to be trod here. Polling data show that Americans strongly support such programmes for the poor as early education, job training and so on--a fact that seems lost in the current shrill political debate. They just don't like quotas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The problem is that, like abortion, affirmative action was dealt with through fiat, not legislation. Thus both issues have brought out the most unseemly side of the American character--self-righteousness galloping left and right--rather than the muddled decency that is more typical of it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Barbara Bergmann's "In Defence of Affirmative Action" contains much muddled decency. The title tells it all. She knows that discrimination exists; using a convincing set of social-science arguments and statistics, she proves it. Ms Bergmann is less convincing when she asserts not only that affirmative action is the best possible response to the problems everyone admits exist, but that it can be effective, rational and precisely targeted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, Ms Bergmann is surely right to point out that by ending racial preferences, America will not--hey presto!--become a colour-blind society. Those who think that it will should take the Jesse Jackson test. He noted that when he heard footsteps behind him on a deserted street and saw a white person, he felt relief. So much for colour-blindness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tom Wicker brings up the footsteps-on-the-deserted-street scenario in "Tragic Failure: Racial Integration in America". But he seems to think that only white people fear the sight of young black men at night (and are thus irredeemably racist). This is the great flaw in his decent and muddled book: he sees everything through an exclusively racial prism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On affirmative action, which he likes, Mr Wicker is his own worst enemy. He notes, for instance, that without quotas (which the Supreme Court struck down and many universities merrily re-instituted), Berkeley would see the "admissions of even academically qualified blacks fall by 40% to 50%". Which begs the question, is it appropriate that academically unqualified students (including football players and daughters of rich alumnae) be admitted? Apparently it is, even though one side-effect of racial preferences in elite universities is high drop-out rates for those groups so privileged.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The last and best book in this sample is William Julius Wilson's. It is an ambitious attempt to rally the country behind a basically non-racial vision to help the poor. His point is that, for the first time in history, there are substantial (mostly black) neighbourhoods where the majority of adults are idle. This fractures society, fosters crime and makes the cycle of poverty an ever more vicious one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Affirmative action plays only a small role in Mr Wilson's scheme of things. In a previous book, "The Truly Disadvantaged", he even argued against race-based preferences, suggesting instead that disadvantage was a better, less divisive standard. He has changed his mind. He now believes that racism has affected black Americans so profoundly, and uniquely, that only preferences based on a combination of race and disadvantage are appropriate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The devil of establishing any kind of preference is, of course, in the details. This is not a niggling point. It is the way affirmative action has been implemented, not its goals, that offends so many Americans. Not only has it been extended to Eskimos in Virginia and Tongans in Washington, but the actual practice has sometimes been close to sinister. Take race-norming, in which different ethnic groups were tested only against each other, not the pool as a whole. If the idea were not so demeaning (it was outlawed in 1991) it would be a classic example of technocracy gone wild. To this pragmatic issue, Mr Wilson does not speak.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He is on surer ground with his other prescriptions--notably to improve schools, in which he would include expanding school choice. Even the jobs programmes of public works he recommends might find a hearing when Americans get sick of stuffing people into prisons.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most important thing Mr Wilson does, though, is remind Americans that black residents of the ghetto--themselves a minority of black Americans--are not a different species. As his evocative interviews with hundreds of residents in Chicago's black belt show, the values of most ghetto residents are much the same as those of Americans as a whole. But these values--hard work, education, personal responsibility--are more difficult to achieve, and to transmit, when there are no jobs nearby, where the schools stink, and when the worst people seem to be the best off. Change the conditions, he argues, and the rest will come naturally.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
