</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>D<font size=-1>ICTIONARY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>IDDLE</font> E<font size=-1>AST</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Dilip Hiro. <br>
<i>St Martin's Press; 353 pages; $30. Macmillan; &#163;45</i><br>
</p><br>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
Born on the Indian subcontinent, Dilip Hiro was educated in India, Britain and
America. He has been living in London since the mid-1960s, and is a full-time
writer and journalist, and a frequent commentator on Middle Eastern and
Islamic affairs on radio and television in Britain and North America. His
articles have appeared in the Washington Post, Wall Street Journal,
International Herald-Tribune, Toronto Star, Sunday Times (London), Observer,
Independent and Guardian. He is the author of several books on the Middle
East, including Inside the Middle East, Iran under the Ayatollahs, Islamic
Fundamentalism, The Longest War: The Iran-Iraq Military Conflict, Desert
Shield to Desert Storm: The Second Gulf War, and Lebanon, Fire and Embers:
A History of the Lebanese Civil War.
