<html><head><title>Unpuzzling the Middle East</title></head>
<!-- Changed by: manar hussain, 19-Jul-1996 -->
<!-- Changed by: manar hussain, 19-Jul-1996 -->
<!-- Changed by: manar hussain, 19-Jul-1996 -->
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="8gr10.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h2>Unpuzzling the Middle East</h2>

<p><b>Even in secular Middle Eastern nations, there is no politics without Islam</b></p><ul> <li><a href="#1">G<font size=-1>OD</font> H<font size=-1>AS</font> N<font size=-1>INETY-</font>N<font size=-1>INE</font> N<font size=-1>AMES</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Judith Miller. <br>
 <li><a href="#2">T<font size=-1>HE</font> I<font size=-1>RANIANS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Sandra Mackey. <br>
 <li><a href="#3">A<font size=-1>LGERIE</a>:</font> L<font size=-1>E</font> B<font size=-1>ONHEUR</font> <font size=-1>OU</font> S<font size=-1>ON</font> C<font size=-1>ONTRAIRE</font>.&nbsp;  By Zahir Far&egrave;s. <br>
 <li><a href="#4">L<font size=-1>A</font> S<font size=-1>ECONDE</font> G<font size=-1>UERRE</font> <font size=-1>D'</font>A<font size=-1>LGERIE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Lucille Provost. <br>
 <li><a href="#5">D<font size=-1>ICTIONARY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>IDDLE</font> E<font size=-1>AST</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Dilip Hiro. <br>
</ul>

</td></tr></table>
<a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>G<font size=-1>OD</font> H<font size=-1>AS</font> N<font size=-1>INETY-</font>N<font size=-1>INE</font> N<font size=-1>AMES</font>.<br>
 By Judith Miller. <br>
<i>Simon &amp; Schuster; 367 pages; $30</i><br>
<a href="8ex240.html">Extract</a> - <a href="8jb240.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="8bt240.html">Biography</a><br>
</p><p>JUDITH MILLER, a <i>New York Times</i> journalist who has written on the Middle East for 20 years, is afraid that resurgent Islam and the modern world cannot be reconciled. She fears that the Arabs, having been variously betrayed by Nasserism, socialism and Baathism, may yet disastrously embrace another ideology that will prevent them regaining, as she puts it, "the prosperity, dynamism, tolerance and imagination that once characterised their civilisation".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Islamists, she argues, win power if others wield it badly. From Algeria to Syria, she notes a depressing readiness by the authorities to counter dissent with repression rather than by encouraging economic development. But dissent will not be crushed. Should regimes therefore co-opt the Islamists? Ms Miller is not convinced they should: efforts were made in Egypt to promote tamer strands of the Muslim Brotherhood, with mixed results. Ms Miller broadly accepts the view of Islamists as irredeemably radical.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This book has been criticised for taking a stereotypical view of the region as gripped by "fundamentalism". At times, it reads that way. But Islam, fundamental or otherwise, is less Ms Miller's theme than a device linking country-by-country chapters. (Iraq, which has denied her a visa for the past decade, is omitted.) Her strength is reporting. Ms Miller goes to the right places and interviews the right people, be they high or humble. Her analysis, even when debatable, is accessible to the layman without insulting the expert.</td></tr></table>
<a name="2"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>T<font size=-1>HE</font> I<font size=-1>RANIANS</font>.<br>
 By Sandra Mackey. <br>
<i>Dutton; 464 pages; $26.95</i><br>
<a href="8ex231.html">Extract</a> - <a href="8jb231.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="8bt231.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>JUST as the Iran of Khomeini and his successors has demonised the west, particularly the "Great Satan" America, so the west reacts to Iran. Supporter of terrorism abroad and oppressor of women at home, the Islamic Republic of Iran is what westerners love to hate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Welcome, then, to Sandra Mackey and "The Iranians". She notes the rich, persistent influence of Iran's pre-Islamic past. Whereas the Arabs dismiss their unimpressive pre-Islamic era as the period of <i>jahiliyya</i> or ignorance, the Iranians look back on sophisticated kingdoms and complex civilisations. (The decision of the Shah, a modern parvenu, to celebrate 2,500 years of the royal dynasty at Persepolis in 1971 was hubristic.) In Iran's history Islam is an Arab transplant, vying over the centuries with the tradition of kingship for the soul of the nation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Islamists who overthrew the Shah are part of a continuing contest, and the older their revolution the less its fire. Now that many mullahs drive Mercedes and take bribes, Ms Mackey spies the same seeds of self-destruction that marred the Shah's era. Iran, for her, is a society "split between a very small, very rich minority and a larger middle class struggling to survive, and the overwhelming majority of the poor." Ms Mackey accordingly believes that America's strategy of isolating Iran wins its current regime patriotic support and risks making "a monster from an adversary".</td></tr></table>
<a name="3"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>A<font size=-1>LGERIE:<br></font> L<font size=-1>E</font> B<font size=-1>ONHEUR</font> <font size=-1>OU</font> S<font size=-1>ON</font> C<font size=-1>ONTRAIRE</font>.<br>
 By Zahir Far&egrave;s. <br>
<i>L'Harmattan. 276 pages; FFr150</i>.<br>
<a href="8ex237.html">Extract</a> - <a href="8jb237.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="8bt237.html">Biography</a><br>

</td></tr></table>
<a name="4"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>L<font size=-1>A</font> S<font size=-1>ECONDE</font> G<font size=-1>UERRE</font> <font size=-1>D'</font>A<font size=-1>LGERIE</font>.<br>
 By Lucille Provost. <br>
<i>Flammarion. 204 pages; FFr110</i><br>


<p>ZAHIR FARES, an Algerian official educated as an economist in France, describes the causes he believes have brought his country to the brink of open civil war. Power in Algeria, he writes, has never been monopolised by one person. Unlike in neighbouring Morocco or Tunisia, Algeria's presidents and prime ministers have come and gone as if guided by invisible stage machinery. What mechanism? Algeria's predicament, Mr Far&egrave;s thinks, is the result of a clash between the perfectly legitimate nation-building aims of its rulers and the cruel demands of adjusting to world markets. That conflict would have tested any government. Algeria's army-dominated rulers made things worse, with poor development planning, massive corruption and harsh treatment of dissent.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As a former Algiers-based official from France's finance ministry, Lucille Provost knows whereof she writes: French policy towards Algeria. She criticises French governments for their reluctance to treat Algeria as a normal country like any other. Though France's colonial war there ended 35 years ago, French politicians of left and right have found it hard not to treat Algeria as an amputated part of their national territory. French economic aid poured in. But it was too little to avert economic disaster or win government thanks (an official anti-France campaign was launched in Algiers late last year), and too much to persuade the Islamists that France's "non-interference" was anything but a sham.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;France instead ought to have taken its distance from Algeria's rulers, Ms Provost argues. France now, she believes, should promote talks among all sides in Algeria with help from America and even Britain, who, she says, have kept better relations with Algeria's Islamists.</td></tr></table>
<a name="5"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>D<font size=-1>ICTIONARY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>IDDLE</font> E<font size=-1>AST</font>.<br>
 By Dilip Hiro. <br>
<i>St Martin's Press; 353 pages; $30. Macmillan; &#163;45</i><br>
<a href="8bt242.html">Biography</a><br>

<p>NO SINGLE volume can be a comprehensive reference book for a region as varied as the Middle East. But Dilip Hiro makes an impressive attempt. Entries on subjects as diverse as the Kharijis, the original Muslim "fundamentalists", and Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon are models of informed compression. Mr Hiro can see both sides of an argument, applying the same stringent scrutiny to the Zionists' Irgun and to the Arabs' Islamic Jihad.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Inevitably, there are gaps. "Iran-Contra Affair", for example, is cross-referenced to "Irangate"--which then makes no reference to the Contras or to Colonel Oliver North. But this is carping. The real regret is that Mr Hiro and his publishers have chosen (presumably for reasons of space) to confine their Middle East to its geographical dimensions. Given Libya's adventurism under Colonel Qaddafi or today's turmoil in Algeria or the triumph of Islamic fundamentalism in Sudan, all of which have repercussions throughout the Middle East, it seems odd to exclude the Maghreb and Sudan.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
