<html><head><title>God Has Ninety-Nine Names.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl240.jpg"><img src="cs240.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>G<font size=-1>OD</font> H<font size=-1>AS</font> N<font size=-1>INETY-</font>N<font size=-1>INE</font> N<font size=-1>AMES</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Judith Miller. <br>
<i>Simon &amp; Schuster; 367 pages; $30</i><p>JUDITH MILLER, a <i>New York Times</i> journalist who has written on the Middle East for 20 years, is afraid that resurgent Islam and the modern world cannot be reconciled. She fears that the Arabs, having been variously betrayed by Nasserism, socialism and Baathism, may yet disastrously embrace another ideology that will prevent them regaining, as she puts it, "the prosperity, dynamism, tolerance and imagination that once characterised their civilisation".</p><br>
</p><br>
<a href="8jb240.html">Jacket Copy</a> - 
<a href="8bt240.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Extract</p></b>
EGYPT
<p>There are some kinds of laughter that make you cry. AL-MUTANASSI, poet (A.D. 915-965)</p>
<p>ON MY FIRST DAY as Cairo bureau chief of The New York Times in August 1983, I saw a donkey drop dead just outside my office on Kasr el Nil, a major commercial street where smart shoppers, young men on motorbikes and bicycles, donkey carts, taxis, and smoke-belching buses jostle for space on the narrow roadway. In lls-degree heat--almost as hot as my office, where the air conditioning had broken down yet again an hour earlier--the donkey probably died of exhaustion.</p>
<p>I was watching from my second-story window as the donkey stood still for a few seconds while his owner beat him across the neck and head. Then, without warning, the donkey fell over dead.</p>
<p>Instantly, a small crowd gathered around the animal, yelling advice at the owner, who by this time understood that further whipping would not revive his poor beast. But he had no idea what to do next. He put his hands on top of his white-turbaned head, the headdress typical of socalled Upper Egypt, which is, in fact, in the southern part of the country, and rocked back and forth in grief.</p>
<p>At this moment, a taxi swerved to avoid hitting the donkey and collided instead with another small black-and-white taxi. The drivers leaped out of their cars, yelling and waving their fists. The crowd grew larger, turning away from the distraught donkey owner and toward the two men on the verge of a brawl. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
