<html><head><title>God Has Ninety-Nine Names.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl240.jpg"><img src="cs240.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>G<font size=-1>OD</font> H<font size=-1>AS</font> N<font size=-1>INETY-</font>N<font size=-1>INE</font> N<font size=-1>AMES</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Judith Miller. <br>
<i>Simon &amp; Schuster; 367 pages; $30</i><p>JUDITH MILLER, a <i>New York Times</i> journalist who has written on the Middle East for 20 years, is afraid that resurgent Islam and the modern world cannot be reconciled. She fears that the Arabs, having been variously betrayed by Nasserism, socialism and Baathism, may yet disastrously embrace another ideology that will prevent them regaining, as she puts it, "the prosperity, dynamism, tolerance and imagination that once characterised their civilisation".</p><br>
</p><br>
<a href="8bt240.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Judith Miller has spent much of her life in the Middle East covering the region
from Jerusalem and Tel Aviv to Teheran, from Amman to Algiers and
Khartoum.
<p>Vivid, lucid, authoritative, God Has Ninety-nine Names is superb journalism which reveals the meaning of the tumultuous events that will shape Arab-Israeli relations as well as the prospect for war or peace in the region and the potential for worldwide terrorism.</p>
<p>Miller takes us deep within the militant Islamic movements in ten Middle Eastern countries: Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Sudan, Algeria, Libya, Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, Israel, and Iran. She shows that as there is no unified Arab world, so there is no unified Islam, for even in the Koran, God has ninety-nine names.</p>
<p>For all her intimate knowledge of the region and its people, Miller is first of all a storyteller who leads the reader into a crowded prison courtyard in Omdurman, where she sits as the only woman amid a thousand or more Islamists awaiting the hanging of an old man, a Sudanese intellectual sent to the gallows for betraying his religion. She takes the reader on a tense visit to the terrorist headquarters of militant Islam's Hezbollah just above the Israeli border in Lebanon, and later on a bouncing tractor across a Libyan oasis with the halfmad, half-shrewd, and always operatic Colonel Muammar Qaddafi, and then into a top secret Israeli interrogation room, where she watches a terrorist leader, who happens to be an American citizen, in the act of betraying his Palestinian comrades.</p>
<p>The militant Islamic movements that Miller describes are as different as the countries in which they have arisen. Seeking to replace secular government with holy writ, some of these radical groups propose nonviolent change, while others take to their guns, but the tendency for all these movements is to shift opportunistically between persuasion and violence as the regimes they oppose weaken under crushing demographic and developmental burdens.</p>
<p>Relying on her personal relationships with leaders as diverse as Libya's vain and mercurial Qaddafi, Jordan's contemplative yet fearless King Hussein, and Israel's late Yitzhak Rabin, Miller introduces her readers to the region's ruling powers. She shows that their methods of combating militant Islam are as diverse as the Islamic movements themselves, ranging from the murderous state terror of Syria's Hafiz Assad to the policy of cooptation practiced by Saudi Arabia's autocratic king.</p>
<p>Miller offers abundant evidence to convince advocates of human rights to mistrust the intentions of these movements as she documents the threat many of them pose to women, intellectuals, Christians, and other minorities in the Middle East. But she also shows how the failure of most Middle Eastern governments to combat, much less solve, the problems of underdevelopment has permitted these militant groups to flourish and in some cases, perhaps, eventually to prevail. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
