<html><head><title>Webzine dreams</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="3gr13.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Internet magazines</b></p>
<h2>Webzine dreams</h2>

<p><b>With electronic "little magazines", the new "digirati" are aiming to transform literary and cultural journalism</b></p><ul></ul>



"JOURNALISM", declares <i>Salon, </i>one of the Internet's new interactive literary and cultural magazines, "has become a pitiful giant, ensnarled by commercial formulas and political tribalism. Where once its voice shook mountains, it now squeaks cautiously and banally. The Net allows publishers to burst these bonds, to howl again."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Howl", of course, was Allen Ginsberg's cry of rage and protest way back in 1956. Put out by City Lights, a tiny San Francisco publisher, it was the Beat generation's poetic manifesto and anticipated the counter-culture of the 1960s. Now <i>Salon </i>seems to be predicting that the Internet will do something similar for publishing. The explosion of on-line magazines--about 150 have been launched in the past year alone--shows that net publishing is cheap and easy. For even a casual surfer, the Internet's multimedia side, the World Wide Web, has overnight become the biggest newsagent in the world, with on-line magazines catering to any taste, from literary theory to conspiracy theory, with much hip "attitude" thrown in.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A similar publishing underground emerged around the photocopier a decade or so ago. Amateur "zines" flowered by the hundreds in the 1980s, often out of the music scene. About the same time in the computer world, bulletin board systems (<font size=-1>BBS</font>s)--computers hooked to telephone lines users could call into--began sprouting by the hundreds. The Internet combines these two cultures, without many of their distribution limitations. Paper zines go hand to hand or by post. <font size=-1>BBS</font>s take technical skill and tend only to serve people a local call away. The Internet, by contrast, is easy to use and global.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many of the Internet's new "web-zines" or "e-zines" ruminate about the net, about computers, indeed about anything digital. But publications of wider interest are also springing up, designed from scratch for hypertext and multimedia. Computer geeks-turned-writers and fans-turned-critics pump out pages of new material daily. It may not be quite yet the counter-cultural revolution hoped for by <i>Salon</i> and still less the "way new journalism" dreamed of by the digital literati or digirati--jacked-in, latter-day Tom Wolfes with technical savvy and cultural poise. But it looks headed that way in an exciting and creative turmoil.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These are a few of the better web-zines that it is chic to hit:<br><li><i>Hot</i>w<i>ired</i> (<a href="http://www.hotwired.com/">http://www.hotwired.com</a>) was the first big-time Internet magazine, and in certain ways still defines the genre. It started barely two years ago as a "walk-the-talk" version of its print-parent <i>Wired.</i> Nowadays the two share little but their modish pose. <i>Hot</i>w<i>ired </i>has its own editorial content, staff and readers. It has wisely dropped <i>Wired</i>'s psychedelic typography in the interest of faster downloads and readable screens.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Its cultural coverage includes capsule reviews of books, music and <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s; new art; a serialised bodice-ripper; and criticism of television (American only, alas) and films. Sports coverage ranges from tips on trick knees to a climbing diary, while its travel section, in one recent week, looked mockingly at Japan and delved into New York kitsch. There is a bit of politics, a hand-waving economics column and an unhelpful agony aunt: (Q:"I've got no friends." A:"Talk to someone.")<br><li><i>Suck</i> (<A href="http://www.suck.com/">http://www.suck.com</a>) was founded last year by two more-wired-than-thou production workers at <i>Hotwired</i>, full of scorn for the media's fawning over dim Internet offerings. It is a daily outpouring of delightful vituperation, done as a single, snaking column of text. Often working all night, the team writes scathing reviews of digital sacred cows. Favourite targets are <i>Wired</i> and the Web efforts of traditional media everywhere. When Time Warner decided to copy <i>Suck </i>with an imitation (<i>Netly News</i>: (<a href="http://www.pathfinder.com/Netly/">http://www.pathfinder.com/Netly</a>), the Sucksters unmasked the feeble pretender while it was still in development. No media multinational caught dressing is pretty. Ominously, <i>Suck</i> has now been bought by <i>Hot</i>w<i>ired</i>, although it is still run independently. Fans are watching for any signs of a creeping sell-out.<br><li><i>Word</i> (<A href="http://www.word.com">http://www.word.com</a>) carries its attitude in its design. Unfortunately, in between its surreal, changing graphics is writing that brings up memories of student literary magazines. Despite a <i>Hot</i>w<i>ired</i>-like breadth of subject matter, <i>Word </i>is a lot more style than substance (<i>Spiv</i>, launched in January by Turner Entertainment, is an even more frothy example of this). But with its creative use of the Web's hypertext linking and multimedia, <i>Word </i>gives a glimpse of what Internet publishing will be, especially when faster connections (over a modem and a regular telephone line, <i>Word</i>'s flowing visuals become stuttering tedium) allow its graphic designers free rein. This is no surprise. <i>Word </i>is published by an Internet consulting firm which uses it as a showcase for its talents. Indeed, <i>Urban Desires</i> (<a href="http://www.desires.com/">http://www.desires.com</a>), a less showy but equally interactive web-zine, is published by a competing consulting firm.<br><li><i>Feed</i> (<a href="http://www.feedmag.com/">http://www.feedmag.com</a>) is the opposite of <i>Word</i>: all substance, little style and very little pose of any kind. It takes a detached view of new technology. It values the net as a medium, but prefers to carry its own message: multimedia click-fests are no substitute for solid thinking and fine writing. <i>Feed</i> offers essays and dialogues on cultural topics from Hollywood's failed flirtation with techno-thrillers to the link between today's geeks and yesterday's hippies. Counter-cultural preoccupations are evident: a debate on drug-law reform now rages on its pages. But <i>Feed</i> is not revolutionary. "The current frenzy to re-invent journalism from scratch looks like a dangerous mix of unchecked hubris and cultural amnesia," <i>Feed</i>'s editor says. This is cyberspace for grown-ups.<br><li><i>Salon </i> (<a href="http://www.salon1999.com/">http://www.salon1999.com</a>) also offers a safe haven for 40-somethings unmoved by surfing metaphors. Like <i>Feed</i>, it concentrates on books, movies, television, music and " ideas", all with an un-<i>Suck</i>-like seriousness and maturity. A sample of recent fare: an interview with Helen Mirren, a look at Martin Scorsese's use of music, a report on a Bruce Springsteen tour and a photo-essay on young black men. Well-known authors keep the writing at a high, if predictable, standard. Where are those new voices, where is the howling that <i>Salon </i>grandly promised? Perhaps the no-names do not write well enough to attract corporate sponsors, of which <i>Salon </i>has many. The net world may not be so different from the old world after all.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
