<html><head><title>Two opinions</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="12gr8.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Law on CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>Two opinions</h2><ul> <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>UPREME</font> C<font size=-1>OURT</font> <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>.</a>&nbsp;   &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Walnut Creek; $39.95</i>. <br>
 <li>USSC <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>.</a>&nbsp;   &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>InfoSynthesis Inc; $145</i> <br>
</ul>



<p>THE full set of the official reports of the United States Supreme Court from 1790 forward fills more than 500 substantial volumes. Because of the critical role the court plays in deciding the biggest political issues in America, from the availability of abortion to the geographic boundaries of legislative districts, access to its opinions is useful not only to lawyers but also to political scientists, ethicists and political philosophers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This leaves an obvious gap in the market for a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> that contains all the opinions of the Supreme Court--opinions which cannot be copyrighted and so can be reproduced without payment of royalties. Such a portable guide would be much cheaper than the 500 tomes and would save law firms many yards of bookshelf space. Unfortunately, Walnut Creek has not produced it. Its single disc contains 544 cases filed from 1988 to 1994 plus the written arguments of the attorneys to the court in 48 cases filed in 1991 and 1992. In its lack of completeness, the disc is akin to publishing only volume 23 of a 25-volume encyclopedia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Walnut Creek's method of legal citation is deficient, the search methods are primitive and the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> comes without instructions. An attorney and a professional computer expert we collared could not work out how to use it, although a law librarian had the necessary intuition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The InfoSynthesis Supreme Court <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> contains over 5,000 opinions, including full coverage from 1966 onwards, together with another 450 earlier leading cases. It now holds the equivalent of some 200 volumes of the "United States Reports", but will be updated twice a year and extended backwards at the rate of an additional seven or eight years each year until it includes every opinion, a remarkable feat in its way.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Useful documentation is provided. A variety of sophisticated search methods are available, including indexed full-text searching for words or phrases using Boolean operators, "wild cards", proximity searches, wordstems and thesaurus operators. Hyperlinking permits the user to click and go readily from one opinion to an opinion it cites. The disc is a model of intelligent development of a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
