</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Villains all</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Japan</b></p>
<h2>Villains all</h2><ul><li><a href="4ex69.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> D<font size=-1>ARK</font> S<font size=-1>IDE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> J<font size=-1>APANESE</font> B<font size=-1>USINESS</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HREE</font> I<font size=-1>NDUSTRY</font> N<font size=-1>OVELS</font>&nbsp; By Ikko Shimizu; translated by Tamae Prindle.<br>
</ul>

HOSE who have been lured to fiction about Japan by the likes of Kazuo Ishiguro ("A Pale View of Hills", "An Artist of the Floating World") might reasonably be pained by this book. It is appallingly written (or translated?). The three novels it contains have rudimentary plots and wooden dialogue. In literary terms they reach the standard of the comic books known as <i>manga</i> much read by Japanese adults, although perhaps are not as well crafted. But do not be put off. They are of interest. They depict Japanese business as nasty and businessmen as villains. As the books sell in large numbers in Japan this is presumably how ordinary Japanese view the driving force of the world's second biggest economy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Commerce is equated with prostitution in "The Ibis Cage". Making such a link is not in itself original. Tarts become tarts for the money. What distinguishes this story is its emphasis on investment. Sugika is a businesswoman. She has invested much time and money in training her daughter to be appealing to men. The daughter is now 18 and a virgin. Sugika reckons that one night with her daughter, when she will be "deflowered", should be worth 1m ($9,500). She settles for 600,000, with 500,000 for subsequent "pillow services".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the novel "Keiretsu" (business partnership) the boss of Tokyo Motors is a bully. His front teeth are stained from smoking. He is "short, pudgy". He has "bleary eyes that bespoke heavy drinking the night before". His full loathsomeness emerges as he plots to get control of the firm that supplies Tokyo Motors with headlights. Cheaper headlights are his aim, or, as the novel puts it, he wants to "suck" the firm into his "radical cost-reduction scheme".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The villain in "Silver Sanctuary" is not a person but the banking system. A woman cashier feels persecuted in the stifling world of money and starts going out with men, using bright lipstick and even drinking whisky. Eventually she gives up her career and any prospects of marriage. "I'm already 29," she announces mournfully.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Villainy in business is not new to fiction. Evil tycoons turned up regularly in British popular fiction in the 1930s, although cost-reduction schemes were not the basis of their misdeeds. A typically sinister figure was an arms maker stirring up trouble to provide a market for his goods. That is old-fashioned stuff, but women over the hill at 29 and tycoons reluctant to use a toothbrush are also characters with a dated air about them. However, these novels, for all their awfulness, may be a reasonable reflection of Japanese concerns. The electronic marvels for which Japan is admired are for export; domestically, Japan is reluctant to abandon the past.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Japan's capacity for self-abasement has become a clich&eacute;. In Ikko Shimizu, author of more than 100 novels, this clich&eacute; has found its appropriate voice.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
