</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Real, yes; but is it still magic?</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="7gr15.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>



<p><b>Latin American fiction</b></p>
<h2>Real, yes; but is it still magic?</h2><ul> <li><a href="7ex194.html">L<font size=-1>ITUMA</font> <font size=-1>EN</font> <font size=-1>LOS</font> A<font size=-1>NDES</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Mario Vargas Llosa. <br>
 <li><a href="7ex200.html">N<font size=-1>OTICIA</font> <font size=-1>DE</font> <font size=-1>UN</font> S<font size=-1>ECUESTRO</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Gabriel Garcia Marquez. <br>
 <li><a href="7ex197.html">S<font size=-1>ANTA</font> E<font size=-1>VITA</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Tomas Eloy Martinez. <br>
 <li><a href="7ex196.html">M<font size=-1>ADAMA</font> S<font size=-1>UI</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Augusto Roa Bastos. <br>
 <li><a href="7ex193.html">L<font size=-1>A</font> L<font size=-1>EY</font> <font size=-1>DEL</font> A<font size=-1>MOR</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Laura Esquivel. <br>
 <li><a href="7ex195.html">D<font size=-1>UERME</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Carmen Boullosa. <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

WHEN Latin American literature hit the bestseller lists in the late 1960s readers delighted in the fantasy worlds of unpredictable happenings and larger-than-life characters. Actually, the so-called "boom" writers insisted less on the magic than on the realism of their writing. Gabriel Garcia Marquez, the best-known "boomer" of all, liked to say that any resemblance to real people or events in his fiction was due not to coincidence but to the author's hard work. Often trained, like him, as journalists, other Latin American novelists saw themselves as chroniclers of a forgotten continent, writing for local readers ignorant of their hinterlands and for foreign readers attracted by exotic settings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After a six-year gap filled by a long but failed attempt to become Peruvian president, Mario Vargas Llosa returned to fiction with "Lituma en los Andes". The novel investigates disappearances in an abandoned mining community high up in the bleak Andes through a recurrent character, a police sergeant called Lituma. Mr Vargas Llosa writes brilliantly crafted novels which baffle readers with shifts from past to present and intertwining plots. Using acute dialogue (mostly lost in translation), Mr Vargas Llosa explains through Lituma what life is like in areas made remote as much by the altitude and barren land as by the Shining Path guerrillas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lituma feels himself a Martian, and so will readers as they learn about such sinister oddities as Pishtacos, a white man who kidnaps Indians to boil down their fat or about villages where foreigners are stoned to death. Only a cantina-keeper and his witch-doctor wife understand the closed Indian world. That the guerrilla Abimael Guzman has been captured and that the Shining Path is no longer a threat in Peru does not detract from the novel's appeal, but does show the risks factual fiction runs when competing with the news.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Noticia de un Secuestro" is Mr Garcia Marquez's exploration of what bedevils his country, Colombia: the power and arrogance of the Cali and Medellin drug barons, especially Pablo Escobar. The author has gone to extraordinary lengths to get the exact details about those kidnapped--the wife of a powerful newspaper owner, a television personality, and others linked to the Gaviria government. All his narrative skills are deployed in this journalistic tour-de-force, as if non-fiction best explores Colombia's ills. The writer here is able to comment on actuality and bemoan the ruthlessness and appeal of a man like the legendary Escobar.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Heading bestseller lists from Argentina to Mexico is Tomas Eloy Martinez's ten-years-in-the-writing novel "Santa Evita", which explores the potency of the Evita Peron legend. It opens with Evita's death from cancer of the womb in 1952, and narrates the outlandish farce of what happened to her embalmed corpse. This is factual surrealism, and Mr Eloy Martinez, a fine journalist at <i>Pagina 12</i>, enters his fiction to transpose long interviews with Evita's hairdresser, with the widow of the secretive code-specialist and spy, Moori Koenig, who is in charge of hiding the corpse, and with the embalmer himself, Dr Ara.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The novel reads more like a folder of files and notes interlaced with speculations as to why Evita became such a potent myth (between 1952 and 1954 the Vatican received nearly 40,000 letters attesting to Evita's miraculous powers). The central character of Moori Koenig is memorably evoked, as are details such as the embalmed corpse's smell--almonds and lavender--or the eight identical dolls made of Evita to fox the Peronist <i>descamisados</i> (shirtless ones), or the star-shaped identification mark Dr Ara cut behind Evita's left ear. As a coup leader said, "Dead, that woman is still more dangerous than when alive." Mr Eloy Martinez continually questions his own writing to add further layers of confusion between legend and fact, despite lulls and over-writing. "Everything in the book", he has said, "is true."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An exiled Paraguayan novelist, Augusto Roa Bastos, said much the same ("all the people are real") in the preface to his novel "Madama Sui". After 47 years in exile from his "almost forgotten country", Mr Roa Bastos looked into the story of a half-Japanese girl that he knew at school in Manora nicknamed Sui from the Guarani <i>"suinda", </i>meaning owl. Sui wanted to emulate Eliza Lynch, an Irish mistress of the dictator Solano Lopez, and admired Evita Peron. Picked from a beauty competition by the dictator Stroessner (not dignified with his name in the novel), she became his concubine for two years. From her 20 notebooks, Mr Roa Bastos "compiled" a life in her own words, one that dwelt especially on a love affair with the lesbian ex-Nazi who ran Stroessner's harem.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Much of the novel is in the form of interviews with an Italian architect who was Sui's platonic lover and mentor. The sensual, strangely innocent Sui stayed in love with a school-friend nicknamed El who fought the dictatorship as a guerrilla. She committed suicide, aged 20, when he died. Mr Roa Bastos not only claimed that everything was true, but also that his writing exploited a woman's intuition. Refusing the novelist's usual claim of omniscience, he explores how gossip and legend complicate what may or may not have happened.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While Mr Roa Bastos has manfully tried to write a woman's version of events, an arguably more exciting branch of post-boom writing is women's fiction itself, which is nearly always succinct and short. Laura Esquivel is already well known for a novel-turned-film and for "La Ley del Amor", a novel complete with cartoons and <font size=-1>CD</font>. She has now written a pastiche science-fiction story based on a rape and murder in Tenochtitlan (Mexico city) in 1527, with consequent unhappiness in 23rd-century Mexico. The plot--the term is relative--revolves about Azucena, an astro-analyst aware of her past lives and searching for an ideal love. There are gender changes, mind-reading plants, thought photographs, astro-telephones, spaceships and lots more pastiche sci-fi elements, written in slangy Mexican, and based on the law of love which is to atone for past crimes and hates, so expiating the traumas of the Spanish conquest. Despite dense-sounding detail, the novel is light and exuberant.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lightness of touch is also to be found in Carmen Boullosa's seventh novel, "Duerme", a mock adventure story about Claire, a cross-dressing French whore. She becomes a pirate, is kidnapped, has to pass for a colonial Spanish grandee, the Conde Urquiza, and is later hanged. An Indian saves her, however, by cutting open her breasts and filling her with a magic Aztec water. Claire befriends a poet, becomes a viceroy's bodyguard and witnesses a play, but then flees Mexico city and is paralysed forever in a coma. A fairy-tale tone merges with digressions reminiscent of the tales of Italo Calvino, with dreams and with zany plot-twists, all finely worked in a delicate, humorous Mexican Spanish. The feminist viewpoint is not forced or schematic; Claire simply resents being a woman.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To judge from these recent works, younger Latin American novelists have moved out from the shadow of the "boom" generation. They are questioning omniscient fiction- and history-writing. New writers, often women, feel they can be quirkily good without having to be the voices or interpreters of a continent.


