<html><head><title>Shovelware</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr11.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Pop culture on CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>Shovelware</h2><ul> <li><a href="9ex247.html">V<font size=-1>OODOO</font> L<font size=-1>OUNGE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By the Rolling Stones. <br>
 <li><a href="9ex250.html">H<font size=-1>OME</font> G<font size=-1>ROWN</font> F<font size=-1>ANTASY</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Zion Train. <br>
 <li><a href="9ex248.html">X<font size=-1>PLORA</font> I.</a>&nbsp;  By Peter Gabriel. <br>
 <li>F<font size=-1>REAK</font> S<font size=-1>HOW</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By the Residents.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Voyager</i>. <br>
 <li><a href="9ex251.html">P<font size=-1>UPPET</font> M<font size=-1>OTEL</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Laurie Anderson. <br>
</ul>






<p>BARRY DILLER, of <font size=-1>QVC</font> and Fox Television fame, was one of the first mainstream businessmen to develop a taste for multimedia products. But he said: "We have to resist media imperialism--the tendency to colonise, to define new technologies in terms of the old." His warning has gone unheeded. Too many media companies are producing "shovelware", software that seems designed merely to convince shareholders that the firm's multimedia market share will rise over the next two quarters. This is one of the reasons that some of the pop products are overwrought.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An example of this is Virgin Interactive's "Voodoo Lounge". The Rolling Stones' first foray into the medium is supposed to give us an idea of what it is like to spend time with the band. Its setting is a party where the first person encountered is the bouncer who, after making a few threatening gestures, makes the explorer feel like a <font size=-1>VIP</font>. The idea that this would give anybody a sense of privilege is laughable. In a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> that serves up a group of three-frame animations and the odd bit of second-hand video, the only redeeming feature is the "VoodooRaver", a screen whose psychedelic animations keeps the spectator amused for about two minutes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Zion Train's "Home Grown Fantasy" is just as uninspired, and combines a cheap price (around &#163;8.99) with a cheap result. Its unglossy cardboard cover shows the serene figure of that all-too-familiar five-pronged leaf. The <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> includes much praise for the marijuana plant, "Did-you-know?" statistics and the odd jab at repressive legislation. The rest of the "Seedy-<font size=-1>ROM</font>" program also has a tired feel.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For better value go back to one of the first <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s made by a top rock musician: Peter Gabriel's 1994 piece, "Xplora I". Like "Voodoo Lounge", it has the <font size=-1>VIP</font> angle, though Xplora's visit to a rehearsal (for which the user has to get a pass) gives it an edge. But it, too, has flaws. The session, along with much of the rest of this <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>, is too dependent on video, a medium whose linear nature hinders inter-activity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A good part of "Xplora I" is about the former Genesis singer's global musical taste. On one screen you can click on little coloured balls that represent continents. Each of these balls produces a list of musicians whose music can then be heard. In another part, you have to guess, with the "help" of producer Brian Eno, which performers would sound good with each other. A good guess brings the reward of a little video; a bad guess brings a reprimand from Brian.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At about the same time as "Xplora I", the Residents, a mysterious San Francisco band, teamed up with Voyager and with Jim Ludtke, a <font size=-1>3D</font>-graphic designer, to make the dazzling and humorous "Freak Show". Here the music seems to have been centred around the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> rather than vice versa. The setting resembles a freak show at a Barnum &amp; Bailey circus. It contains all sorts of new life forms. When viewing these (highly impressive) mutants loses its novelty, the explorer can peek into their lives. One freak, the elusive "Herman the Human Mole", has a telephone with ten direct dials, on one of which you hear a husband kill his wife, supposedly because of your call. When you finally find Herman (hiding in a chest of drawers) he reluctantly agrees to tell his life story.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps the best pop artist's <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> to date is Laurie Anderson's "Puppet Motel". The always avant-garde work of Ms Anderson is in a league of its own. Like the Residents she has joined forces with a talented computer graphic designer (Hsin-Chien Huang) and the Voyager company.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On her <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> the sense of reality is utterly suspended. The viewer explores the rooms of the puppet motel, if room is the right word. The different areas are perhaps better described as sensory experiences that are not dissimilar to those evoked in using a telephone for the first time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some of these rooms contain puzzles, though not of the condescending type that buyers have come to expect from many of the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s on the market. Some are simply playthings. There is a Ouija board, for example. Using a flying revolving widget you can ask yes-no questions. When this reviewer asked about money, the answer was positive, proving that computers can have a kindly heart.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
