<html><head><title>Puppet Motel.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl251.jpg"><img src="cs251.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>P<font size=-1>UPPET</font> M<font size=-1>OTEL</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Laurie Anderson. <br>
<i>Voyager</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="9bt251.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Laurie Anderson has always blurred the boundaries--between performer and
audience, techno and tanglible, ephemeral and real. In the dark spaces of her
imagination shadows race, nebulae swirl, words turn to smoke, electrical outlets
whisper for attention, and time travels both ways. Welcome to Puppet Motel, an
intimate and completely original performance piece on CD-ROM.
<p>Designer Hsin-Chien Huang's amazing spaces shift and dissolve around you, offering ways to join, alter, and record the Anderson experience. Leave messages on the answering machine. Watch videos with a ventriloquist's dummy who performs "Puppet Motel," the hit single from Anderson's ablum Bright Red. Connect the dots to create your own constellation. Ply four juiced- up, electronic violins. Watch the set of the 1995 tour assemble itself as Laurie sits on a virtual stage explaining the development of the show. Familiar Anderson images and tools--telephones, fax machines, Tvs, typewriters, and a glowing, howling electrical outlet at the center--connect you to over an hour of music (including "Down in Soho," which premieres on this CD-ROM), excerpts from Stories from the Nerve Bible, and many strange side trips. There are no right or wrong moves in Puppet Motel. Navigate a world saturated with Laurie Anderson's presence and interact directly with her intelligence and art. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
