<html><head><title>What the world is reading</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><br><h2>What the world is reading</h2><p>IN THAT party game where contestants try to dream up the most boring title for a book, ''Canada: Gentle Giant to the North" is always a strong contender. So it is no surprise that Canadian bestsellers flop in the United States. English-speaking Canadians, however, remain fascinated by the elephant next door: more than half of the bestsellers on their list are written by Americans.</p><br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The popularity of American bestsellers, in translation, on the Canadian French list is more surprising. So perhaps is the appearance of only two of the bestsellers in France on the Canadian French list: futurology from Microsoft's Bill Gates and a romp through the virtues with Andr&eacute; Comte-Sponville.</p><br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Francophone nationalists in Quebec should hesitate before citing this as yet another example of Anglo-American domination of their culture. The divide between the French-speakers on the opposite shores of the North Atlantic is wider than usual. Readers in France are absorbed by books about the presidency of Fran&ccedil;ois Mitterrand: attacks, exposures, recollections, conversations and muck-raking. No fewer than five of the ten bestsellers in France are about the Socialist who served two seven-year terms as president and died of cancer in January this year.</p><br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<br><h3>Non-fiction bestsellers<a href="#foot">*</a></h3><ul><li><a href="#usa">United States</a><li><a href="#fra">France</a><li><a href="#cana">Canada (French)</a><li><a href="#canb">Canada (English)</a></ul></td></tr></table><a name="usa"><br></a><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><hr size=5 width=70 align=left><h4>United States</h4><ol><li>Rush Limbaugh is a Big Fat Idiot <i> by Al Franken</i>. &#160; A comedian on current affairs</li><li>Men are from Mars, Women are from Venus <i> by John Gray</i>. &#160; Relationships</li><li>It Takes a Village <i> by Hillary Rodham Clinton</i>. &#160; Bringing up children by the first mother</li><li>The Seven Spiritual Laws of Success <i> by Deepak Chopra</i>. &#160; Serving body and soul</li><li>Emotional Intelligence <i> by Daniel Goleman</i>. &#160; As important as IQ</li><li>The Way of the Wizard <i> by Deepak Chopra</i>. &#160; Spiritual lessons for a happy life</li><li>The Road Ahead <i> by Bill Gates</i>. &#160; Wonder machines</li><li>Time present, Time Past <i> by Bill Bradley</i>. &#160; A political and sporting has-been</li><li>How Could You Do That? <i> by Laura Schlessinger</i>. &#160; A radio therapist writes</li><li>The Beardstown Ladies' Stitch-in-ime Guide <i> by Robin Dellabough</i>. &#160; Folksy guide to money making</li></ol></td></tr></table><a name="fra"><br></a><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><hr size=5 width=70 align=left><h4>France<a href="#foot">**</a></h3><ol><li>L'Honneur Perdu de Fran&ccedil;ois Mitterrand <i> by Jean Edern Hallier</i>. &#160; An anti-Mitterrand polemic</li><li>La Mort Intime <i> by Marie de Hennezel</i>. &#160; Comforting the dying</li><li>Les Oreilles du Pr&eacute;sident <i> by Jean-Marie Pontaut and J&eacute;r&ocirc;me Dupuis</i>. &#160; Mitterrand's telephone taps</li><li