<html><head><title>Red and green all over?</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="7gr14.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>...and Mars</b></p>
<h2>Red and green all over?</h2><ul> <li><a href="7ex183.html">B<font size=-1>LUE</font> M<font size=-1>ARS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Kim Stanley Robinson. <br>
</ul>


<p>IT IS 2127, a bare century after the arrival of the first 100 settlers on Mars. The once inhospitable planet is already a lot more like Earth: pressure at surface level (there being no sea as yet) has risen to around a third of Earth's and plants are taking hold. Administratively, Mars is a post-colonial protectorate under the supervision of the United Nations. But rebellion has flared and Earth cannot respond.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fans of the two earlier books in Kim Stanley Robinson's "Mars" trilogy will rush to read this sequel. And they will not be disappointed. Earth, too, is in turmoil. Global warming has melted ice at the poles, raising sea levels by seven metres and flooding coastlines. Thanks (or no thanks) to an age treatment, human life expectancy is counted in centuries and the population of Earth approaches 15 billion--a thousand times that on Mars. The power of big-business "metanationals" is waning. National identities are returning and local collectives taking root.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Martians exploit these earthly troubles, despite their own abiding fractiousness. They overcome their <font size=-1>UN</font> minders, declare independence and promulgate a constitution, a compromise between preservationist, keep-Mars-rock Reds and progressive Greens who want it "terraformed", that is, wet and lush enough to live without oyxgen bottles and airtight cities. An upper bound for atmospheric pressure is written into the constitution and there is a supreme environmental court.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That all may sound like lightly processed borrowings from academic reports on global competitiveness, Worldwatch papers on population or the environment and "The Debates on the American Constitution, 1787". But the story is told through the characters of some of the "First Hundred"--the unpredictable, clever eccentrics chosen on Earth to colonise Mars. Well past 200 Earth-years old by the novel's end, their age has advantages and drawbacks. They know more than their shallow descendants. But, born into a world where the lifespan was threescore and ten, they are ill at ease with their stretched lives and burdened by over-full memories.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Their ruminations on physics, medicine, ecology, areology (Martian geology), psychology and much else allow the author to show off a wide-ranging curiosity. At times, he sounds a dilettante of the future world. But this is sci-fi (with doses of psy-fi and social-sci-fi) where science does not replace the story, but sets a technical context for bold socio-political speculation. Robots can build just about anything. Venus is being made to rotate so as to make it habitable. To adapt to new atmospheres and gravities, people can alter their genes, taking on traits from other animals. Yet they eat ice-creams at the sea, build houses by hand, commit murder and go fishing. Unlike Ovid's morphed mortals, in sum, they stay human--just.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Read before the two previous books in this trilogy, "Blue Mars" is a bracing, deep plunge into a different past, albeit one set far into the future. Read afterwards, it makes for a gripping continuation.




<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
