<br>


<h2>Trade, taxes and growth</h2> <p><b>Enlightenment should precede reform. These
books help provide it</b></p>

<ul> 
<li><a href="#1">A<font size=-1>GAINST</font>
<font size=-1>THE</font> T<font size=-1>IDE</a>:</font> A<font size=-1>N</font>
I<font size=-1>NTELLECTUAL</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font> <font
size=-1>OF</font> F<font size=-1>REE</font> T<font size=-1>RADE</font>.&nbsp;  By
Douglas Irwin. <br> 

<li><a href="#2">T<font size=-1>AXING</font> O<font
size=-1>URSELVES.</font></A>&nbsp; By Joel Slemrod and Jon Bakija. <BR>


<li><a href="#2">E<font size=-1>CONOMIC</font> E<font
size=-1>FFECTS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> F<font size=-1>UNDAMENTAL</font>
T<font size=-1>AX</font> R<font size=-1>EFORM</font>.</a>&nbsp;  Edited by Henry
Aaron and William Gale.<br> 

<li><a href="#3">E<font size=-1>CONOMIC</font> G<font
size=-1>ROWTH IN</font> E<font size=-1>UROPE</font> S<font size=-1>INCE</font>
1945.</a>&nbsp;  Edited by Nicholas Crafts and Gianni Toniolo.<br>
</ul>

</td></tr></table> <a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0> <tr><td
valign=bottom align=left width=60><img
src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td> <td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>A<font size=-1>GAINST</font> <font
size=-1>THE</font> T<font size=-1>IDE:<br></font> A<font size=-1>N</font> I<font
size=-1>NTELLECTUAL</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font>
F<font size=-1>REE</font> T<font size=-1>RADE</font>.<br> By Douglas Irwin. <br>
<i>Princeton University Press; 265 pages; $29.95 and &#163;22.50</i><br>

<p>EVER since Adam Smith taught that a country could best allocate its resources,
and so maximise its wealth, by trading freely with others, economists have
regarded free trade as superior to protectionism. But, as Douglas Irwin's
historical odyssey shows, discussions of trade did not originate with Smith.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Beginning with the ancient Greeks and
travelling via the early Christian thinkers and natural-law philosophers, such as
Hugo Grotius, to the English mercantilists of the 17th century, Mr Irwin
describes the evolution of thinking on trade that occurred before Adam Smith.
Many ancient thinkers were contemptuous of trade, regarding commerce as an
inferior activity. The mercantilists, in contrast, recognised the importance of
foreign trade but felt it should be regulated by the state, largely to achieve or
maintain a favourable balance of exports over imports.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though proponents of free, rather than
regulated, trade existed before Adam Smith, their analysis was unsystematic.
Smith devised a coherent and rigorous analytical framework. The details were
filled in by later classical economists. David Ricardo, for instance, famously
espoused the principle of comparative advantage. This maintains that a country
can benefit from free trade even if it is less efficient than its trading
partners at making everything (though Mr Irwin argues that Ricardo is credited
with greater clarity and insight that he in fact showed).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With these intellectual origins in place, Mr
Irwin proceeds to document and assess the main challenges to free-trade theory.
These include the terms-of-trade argument, which holds that a country can, under
certain conditions, benefit from a tariff improving the ratio at which it
exchanges its products with the rest of the world. Other challenges are weaker,
including the notion that "infant industries" need protective tariff barriers in
order to flourish. All are analysed, weighed and put into context.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Against the Tide" is an impressive
intellectual achievement. As the history of an economic idea it pays less
attention to the political and economic setting in which different theories were
promoted than to their analytical rigour. This purity makes the history a
delightful as well an educational read. It should be a set text for anybody
interested in trade policy.</td></tr></table> <a name="2"></a><table cellspacing=0
cellpadding=0> <tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img
src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td> <td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>

T<font size=-1>AXING</font> O<font
size=-1>URSELVES</font>.<br>
By Joel Slemrod and Jon Bakija. <BR>
<i>Press</i>;<i> 304 pages</i>;<i> $25 and
&#163;21.50</i><p>
E<font size=-1>CONOMIC</font> E<font
size=-1>FFECTS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> F<font size=-1>UNDAMENTAL</font>
T<font size=-1>AX</font> R<font size=-1>EFORM</font>.<br> Edited by Henry Aaron
and William Gale.<br> <i> Brookings Institution</i>;<i> 521 pages; $52.95 and
&#163;41.25</i><p>

WITH President Clinton back in the White House, fundamental tax reform will not be
at the top of America's economic agenda. It was, after all, Robert Dole who
called for a <i>"</i>fairer, simpler, flatter<i>"</i> American tax system.
Nonetheless, the movement for tax reform has gained such momentum that the issue
will remain alive. And, with the help of <i>"</i>Taxing Ourselves<i>"</i>, the
layman will finally be able to understand it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;American taxpayers complain about the
complexities of their current income-tax-based system; economists believe that a
shift towards taxing consumption rather than income would generate higher saving
and so boost America's growth rate. Both have a point: reducing complexity and
increasing savings are good reasons for tax reform. But a careful examination of
the case for change demands a clear understanding of the principles behind
America's existing tax system, its goals and how different proposals would affect
their attainment. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Taxing Ourselves" provides
just that. It describes America's current tax system with admirable clarity, and
then goes on to examine the criteria for choosing between competing systems: the
"fairness" of a tax system, its simplicity and how much it fosters economic
growth. An analysis of the basic building blocks of reform--such as introducing a
single tax rate, removing exemptions and shifting the tax base from income to
consumption--is followed by a critical evaluation of specific reform proposals.
They include a single "flat tax", a value-added tax and a national sales tax. For
anybody interested in tax reform, yet confused by political polemic, "Taxing
Ourselves" is an invaluable guide to the debate..
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For those whose interest goes further, the book
from the Brookings Institution extends the analysis. It addresses oft-ignored
details about the economic impact of tax reform: the issues raised, for instance,
by the transition from an income-taxed based system to one centred on consumption
taxes. Would employers have less incentive to provide employees with health
insurance if this benefit were no longer tax efficient? What would happen to
charitable contributions if they could no longer be deducted from taxable income?
This will not be the final word on any of these issues, but it sets the standard
for future debate.</td></tr></table> <a name="3"></a><table cellspacing=0
cellpadding=0> <tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img
src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td> <td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>E<font size=-1>CONOMIC</font> G<font
size=-1>ROWTH IN</font> E<font size=-1>UROPE</font> S<font size=-1>INCE</font>
1945.<br> Edited by Nicholas Crafts and Gianni Toniolo.<br> <i> Cambridge
University Press; 624 pages; &#163;55 and $80</i><br>

<p>BETWEEN 1950 and 1972, per capita incomes in Western Europe grew at an average
of 3.8% a year, far faster than at any comparable period in history. In the
subsequent two decades the growth rate more than halved and unemployment
increased sharply. This collection of essays examines both the "Golden Age" and
the less glorious years that followed. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It
stands out from previous analyses of Europe's economic performance for three
reasons. First, it places the post-war experience into a longer historical
context, demonstrating that the "Golden Age" was an exceptional period: later
growth rates are closer to Europe's historical trend. Second, the essays combine
traditional analyses of growth, which emphasise physical capital and increases in
productivity, with newer theoretical insights that place greater importance on
human resources and economic policy. And third, thanks to careful descriptions of
individual countries, the book is richly comparative. The essays are not always
easy, but for those who wish to understand Europe's post-war performance they are
worth the effort.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i>
