<html><head><title>32 into 1 will go</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="3gr12.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Encyclopedias on CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>32 into 1 will go</h2><ul><li>B<font size=-1>RITANNICA</font> 2.0. </a>&nbsp; By Joseph Stiglitz.<br>
<br>
</ul>

<p>OTHERS are more loved. The 1975 Columbia may be the best in one volume. But nobody really disputes that the Britannica is not only the largest but also the greatest of encyclopedias, at least in English. Born of the Scottish Enlightenment, it has carved its course, like a big river, across nations. It has grown in breadth, depth and mass, its tributaries feeding every other encyclopedia in the world. In 1920 the Britannica migrated to Chicago and, despite its name and its distinguished list of contributors from across the world, it is now a wholly American publication. Under American ownership editorial standards remain high, though its editors tend naturally to reflect the preoccupations of their own continent more than those of Europe or elsewhere.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Arguments about the many different editions of the Britannica have always been fierce. The 20th-century ones all have passionate critics and defenders. The 11th (1911), a great assemblage of 19th-century learning and certitude shot through with the first stirrings of modern doubt, still has admirers; the 14th, repeatedly revised from 1929 to 1973, kept to the old format of gathering what was deemed worth knowing in one alphabetical list. But balancing science and humanities, English-speaking and other cultures, got ever harder. In 1974, for the radically changed 15th edition, Britannica was split into a Micro- and a Macropaedia, short entries and longer essays. Now Britannica has taken the next giant step, not of content this time but of form, by going electronic.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Overdue and inevitable as this was, it still has to be asked what advantages Britannica 2.0 has over the 32-volume bound set. Price is one. At &#163;755 the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> version is half as dear as the cheapest print edition and a fifth the price of the "Connoisseur": a misnamed display object bound in leather and stamped with spine lettering in 23-carat gold. Its content, written in clear layperson's language, remains consistently high, offering better value for money than any competitor. The integrity of the publishers cannot be faulted in their decision to keep every one of the 44m words of the print edition, even if this does create visual congestion on a tightly-packed monitor.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As if unsure of their wares, other publishers of encyclopedias on <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> have tended to wrap them in warm colours and soft music. It comes therefore as a bit of a shock to load the Britannica disc and watch the words appear in sombre grey. This denial of tint would, however, have delighted the Society of Gentlemen of Scotland who founded the Britannica in Edinburgh 200 years ago, and is bracing in its way. The disc itself is red, a concession to colour as bold as a bishop's purple socks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A vast extension in search capacity is the single biggest advantage of the electronic Britannica. In Britannica 2.0 the user can call up an article by typing a headword into the search box; by listing a string of key words linked to each other with the logical operators "and", "not", "or" and "adj" (for "adjacent") available to help narrow the search; or by posing a written question on screen and clicking for its answer. The last, though tempting, is also the most likely to waste time, after the initial amusement has worn off. The question, "What are the seven deadly sins?", for example, will come up with anger, lust and so on but will point you, for good measure, to Grumpy, Happy and the other dwarfs. On the other hand, it hits a bull's-eye if asked who coined the term "iron curtain". No, not Churchill; Goebbels.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A weakness of the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> version is that only 2,500 remain out of the print edition's 24,000 photographs, drawings and colour plates. The editorial litmus seems to be whether illustration is essential to literal understanding of the text. So instead of a seductive Tintoretto or an aerial view of the Great Rift Valley, you get not one but hundreds of schematic line drawings of mathematical principles: useful, but not crowd-pleasers. Worse still, their captions are almost too small to read unless you go through an elaborate series of hoops in the options menu in the Netscape tool bar to enlarge the size of the print. Also, statistical tables are so long that they flow off the screen, forcing you to grasp on to hundreds of invisible figures to retain the full picture.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Maps, which in the electronic version show only political boundaries, offer an equally stringent memory-test; their title is given, as in the print edition, at the end. So the user has to scroll down screen after screen to follow the course of an (unnamed) river, to be told at the end that it is the Nile. The few colour reproductions that inform us aesthetically are neither listed nor readily accessible. Why, for example, is there a small, under-exposed snapshot of the interior of Amiens Cathedral tucked under "High Gothic", but not linked to the entry on either Amiens or cathedrals? The sad conclusion is that the compilers of this <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> are out of sympathy with the visual possibilities of the medium.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With the Britannica 2.0 comes an abridged Merriam-Webster Collegiate Dictionary, a lightweight work whose limited entries follow the old-fashioned lexicographic practice of presenting the earliest (and usually obsolete) definition of the word first and the current meaning last.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is easy to cavil over delays and shortcomings. Rival encyclopedias such as Grolier's went electronic ten years ago. Many parents who once might have bought an expensive encyclopedia spend the money instead on a computer. Britannica's revenues are reported to have dropped sharply. Sales of the encyclopedia in North America alone fell from 117,000 sets in 1990 to 51,000 last year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When in April 1995 the parent company in Chicago let it be known that it was seeking an investor or a buyer even, word got out to Microsoft in Seattle that Britannica was, after two centuries of success, near bankruptcy. Bill Gates and his Microsofters were jubilant at what they seem to have believed were a rival's death- throes, convinced that what was bad for Britannica must be good for their "Encarta", even though, by comparison, Microsoft's pathetic encyclopedia is as a box of lego to the Taj Mahal. In fact, Britannica's owners needed money to readjust their sights from the mainstay print edition to a new source of revenue-making, by creating new channels of distribution and product development such as Britannica's Online service on the Internet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another potentially radical change in Britannica's long history began in December, when an American businessman, Jacob Safra, successfully bid for it and won. He soon moved to reassure worriers. "Our goal", he said, "will be global in distribution to all people, all incomes and all ages." And late and under-illustrated as it is, the electronic Britannica looks set for success. Compression technology is moving so fast that with each year more and more elements can be added to the disc. Multi-layered, two-sided discs were developed some time ago. But the equipment needed for them is not yet producible at a market price. But that, too, presumably will change before long.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
