<html><head><title>Gliding on the rings of Saturn</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="7gr11.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Moods</b></p>
<h2>Gliding on the rings of Saturn</h2><ul> <li><a href="7ex211.html">A<font size=-1>N</font> U<font size=-1>NQUIET</font> M<font size=-1>IND</font></a>: A M<font size=-1>EMOIR OF</font> M<font size=-1>OODS AND</font> M<font size=-1>ADNESS</font>.&nbsp;  By Kay Redfield Jamison. <br>
</ul>

<p>MANIC-depressive illness kills tens of thousands every year, many of them young, gifted and imaginative people. Byron, Schumann and Virginia Woolf were among the sufferers. So are many members of the medical profession, who have easy access to the means of suicide. Kay Redfield Jamison's book is a devastatingly candid account of her experience of the disease. But the author is no ordinary victim of the illness. As professor of psychiatry at the Johns Hopkins University school of medicine in Baltimore, she is able to filter her experience through an intellectual understanding of the condition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From childhood, she was always intensely emotional, given to frightening, although often wonderful, extremes of mood. She experienced her first attack of the disease at 17 and from then on her life became caught up in an unrelenting cycle of mania and depression. These worsened in intensity as she moved into adulthood. She could be violent to others, often people she loved, just as others were necessarily brutal towards her when she was in the full grip of psychosis. "I have been physically restrained by terrible, brute force; kicked and pushed to the floor; thrown on my stomach with my hands pinned behind my back; and heavily medicated against my will."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Like so many sufferers, Dr Jamison resisted taking lithium, the elemental salt whose clinical use was discovered by an Australian psychiatrist in the 1940s. The effects of lithium, if used in any quantity, can be overpowering and at times lethal. It killed a number of patients while it was under test although ironically it failed to kill Dr Jamison when she tried to commit suicide by taking a massive dose.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another of lithium's side-effects is that, unless used sparingly (the practice in recent years), it impairs the enjoyment of life. However, the real resistance to lithium comes more from the widespread belief that an effort of will is needed to overcome the illness. This conviction, combined with an addiction to manic "highs", which were like "gliding along the rings of Saturn", is why Dr Jamison resisted taking lithium for many years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;She cites the Chinese belief that to conquer a beast you must first find it beautiful and this she has tried to do with her own manic-depressive illness. The story at times makes harrowing reading but the writer has wit and the soul of a poet. She writes, for instance, an exquisitely moving account of a love affair she had with an Englishman, ended by his sudden early death.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;She is also generous about the many people who helped along the way. Interestingly, the only ones to come out badly are psychoanalysts, portrayed as humourless, jargon-ridden bigots, although she was greatly helped by psychotherapy. She wisely points to the need to treat the dual aspects of any individual suffering from mental illness-- that is, the brain with medication and the mind with psychotherapy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The book ends with a brief discussion of the research by James Watson, a famous geneticist, into the "troubled helix" that is responsible for manic-depressive illness, a quest for the biological equivalents of quarks and leptons. Mr Watson has gathered up a multidisciplinary team to study the genetic pedigree of affected families. Dr Jamison's brilliant father, for instance, was afflicted with the disease as were many others in his family. You finish the last page feeling that you have shared the author's healing experience.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
