<html><head><title>Zero-based terror</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Turn of the millennium</b></p>
<h2>Zero-based terror</h2><ul> <li>T<font size=-1>HE </font>E<font size=-1>ND OF </font>T<font size=-1>IME</a>:</font> F<font size=-1>AITH</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> F<font size=-1>EAR</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> S<font size=-1>HADOW</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>ILLENNIUM</font>.&nbsp;  By Damian Thompson.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Sinclair-Stevenson; 366 pages; &#163;16.99.</i> <br>
 <li>O<font size=-1>MENS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> M<font size=-1>ILLENNIUM</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> G<font size=-1>NOSIS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> A<font size=-1>NGELS</font>, D<font size=-1>REAMS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> R<font size=-1>ESURRECTION</font>.&nbsp;  By Harold Bloom. &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i> Riverhead Books; 255 pages; $25.94. Fourth Estate; &#163;15.99.</i> <br>
 <li><a href="12ex392.html">F<font size=-1>INS</font> <font size=-1>DE</font> S<font size=-1>I&Egrave;CLE</a>:</font> H<font size=-1>OW</font> C<font size=-1>ENTURIES</font> E<font size=-1>ND</font> <font size=-1>1400-2000</font>.&nbsp;  Edited by Asa Briggs and Daniel Snowman. <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

SOME sneering wag has already come up with a phrase for it: "pre-millennial tension". Though meant as a put-down, the jibe pulls its punch. Is there something to millennium fever or not? Well, yes and no. As the millennium ends, people across the world are anxious about all sorts of looming calamity. But only a relative handful of calendar-nuts are worried because the millennium is ending.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Alarm at approaching dates and fear of impending disasters are not the same thing, as Damian Thompson makes clear in an outstanding book on a much-hyped topic. His main interest is apocalyptic prophecy and he takes it as given that, when calling out "the end is nigh", the more successful prophets are vague on timing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The book goes into the cultural roots of doomsaying and then surveys the current "millennial" ferment, whether date-related or not. It is partly reportage, sweeping up things with only a loose connection: loud, money-grubbing churches in Seoul, fiery horror at Waco, nerve-gas on the Tokyo subway. The book's first, historical half is the more interesting and successful.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Thompson explains how calendars grew out of an early awareness of seasons, how <i>anno domini</i> dating was adopted in Christendom and how a modern sense then emerged of historical time as an unbroken progression. He places the eruptions of apocalyptic fervour which he has studied into their historical context, be it the Middle Ages or the 16th century, and finds that such outbreaks come almost invariably in periods of economic or social upheaval. An enlightened sceptic, he accepts the now common view that the so-called "terrors of 1000" are the invention of a later age. He shows sympathy as well as amusement at famous non-events of 19th-century prophecy such as the Great Disappointment of 1844, when 50,000 Millerites in America waited vainly for the end of time on October 22nd.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In his darker reflections on apocalyptic movements, he leans heavily on a book by Norman Cohn, "The Pursuit of the Millennium" (1957), which treated Nazism and Marxism, not to everyone's satisfaction, as secular forms of "eschatological fantasy". Mr Thompson's feel for the tangle of beliefs and resentments in the "the underground river of New Age ideas" is exemplary. But it is not clear that all-purpose categories such as outsider religion or end-of-an-era anxiety shed much extra light here.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Thompson is at his best looking back. His insight that people in troubled times often over-generalise their condition makes sense. It is easy to see the end of your world as the end of everything. There was always a tension between religious or philosophical ideas of man in abstract at the centre of the cosmos, and tribe-, town- or kin-related notions of particular men, a tension that may survive half-consciously to this day. In Kabbalist tradition, for example, when a person dies, so does a universe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Intriguing, too, is what Mr Thompson has to say about Zoroaster, an early Persian prophet with lasting influence whom he identifies as the first known apocalyptic seer. Zoroaster, he recounts, was the main source for Hebrew visions of a time of tribulation and destruction, followed by a new-made perfection--a common pattern, it could be added, for later doomsaying prophecy. It is from Zoroaster, Mr Thompson goes on, that the Manichaean vision of a universe split between warring powers of light and darkness, spirit and matter, descends; and this dualism survives, repressed or absorbed, in Christianity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A sense of alternative traditions resurfacing runs through Harold Bloom's brilliant, idiosyncratic study of millennial omens. Mr Bloom, who is one of America's foremost literary scholars, embarks here on what he calls a "spiritual autobiography", a mutable venture drawing in the Romantics, Shakespeare, Kabbalists, Sufis and Freud among many others. Gnostic visions of a universe from which the creator has absented himself interest Mr Bloom in particular. His view is that <i>gnosis</i>--the conviction of direct contact with God--springs from the repeated failure of promised apocalypse. America, to Mr Bloom, is a nation of prophecy, and of powerful gnostic leanings. He cites a survey showing that more than two-thirds of its inhabitants believe in angels and that almost a third claim direct experience of the divine. Though often hard to follow, Mr Bloom's latest book is full of dazzling insights and unexpected connections.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The title of "Fins de Si&egrave;cle: How Centuries End" is a bit of a cheat. These seven essays, written from a British perspective, examine the turn of each century from 1400 to 2000, only to show that centuries end in no special way. Widespread celebration of centenaries is a modern habit. Appealing to a non-existent tradition and mainly to assert Rome's primacy, an embattled Pope Boniface VIII did call a jubilee in 1300. But the French king had him beaten up and deposed soon after; the papacy was then removed to Avignon and for the next several centuries, even on return to Rome, was in no condition to celebrate much of anything. Until the 19th century, new year was marked at widely different dates even within western Christendom. Before then the approach of double-zero years was rarely taken either as a sign of an era ending or as a cause for general foreboding. The very phrase "fin de si&egrave;cle" came into use little more than 100 years ago, initially to describe a rather local mood of lassitude among a set of refined Parisians. About the zeroes at least, you can relax.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
