<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev12/rv4/12bt392.html 199.173.162.110 19970113191316 text/html 2343
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 19:09:31 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 05-Dec-96 19:25:14 GMT
Content-length: 2158
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Fins de Si&#233;cle</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl392.jpg"><img src="cs392.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>F<font size=-1>INS</font> <font size=-1>DE</font> S<font size=-1>I&Egrave;CLE:<br></font> H<font size=-1>OW</font> C<font size=-1>ENTURIES</font> E<font size=-1>ND</font> <font size=-1>1400-2000</font>.<br></h2>
<p> Edited by Asa Briggs and Daniel Snowman. <br>
<i>Yale; 272 pages; $35 and &#163;19.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="12jb392.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
Asa Briggs is an internationally known historian and President of the English Social History Society. He has been Professor of History at the University of Leeds, Vice-Chancellor of the University of Sussex, Provost of Worcester College, Oxford and Chancellor of the Open University. Among his many books are Vctorian People (1975), The Age of Improvement, 1783-1867 (1979), A Social History of England (1985) and Victorian Things (1988).
<p>Daniel Snowman has written several books on twentieth-century social and cultural history (including a comparative study of British and American values), as well as on such diverse topics as the polar regions and Placido Domingo. For many years he was Chief Producer, Features, at the BBC. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
