<html><head><title>In the mirror of the 1960s</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h1>In the mirror of the 1960s</h1>
<p><b>Today's anti-government liberals have a lot more in common with old-fashioned 1960s radicals than you might think</b></p><ul> <li>R<font size=-1>EASSESSING THE</font> S<font size=-1>IXTIES</font>.</a>&nbsp;  Edited by Stephen Macedo. &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i> Norton; 320 pages; $25.</i> <br>
 <li><a href="10ex292.html">I<font size=-1>N THE</font> S<font size=-1>IXTIES</font>.</a>&nbsp;  Edited by Ray Connolly.<br>
 <li><a href="10ex293.html">A T<font size=-1>ALE OF</font> T<font size=-1>WO</font> U<font size=-1>TOPIAS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Paul Berman.<br>
 <li><a href="10ex294.html">M<font size=-1>AKING</font> P<font size=-1>EACE WITH THE</font> 60s.</a>&nbsp;  By David Burner. <br>
</ul><ul></ul>


<p>"FREEDOM'S just another word for nothing left to lose," rasped Janis Joplin, and all those listening knew her song was about more than a lost lover. For the young radicals of the sixties were not only, or even chiefly, interested in gaining more liberty--or licence, as their critics would have it. They were also committed, often in confused and sentimental ways, to the ideals of equality and fraternity--collaborative values which put limits on individual freedom.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The raggedness of the advances and the retreats on these three fronts--liberty, equality and fraternity--help explain why so many veterans from either camp of the counter-cultural wars in that rebellious decade are convinced that their side lost. In his introduction to "Reassessing the Sixties", George Will, a conservative journalist, sums up the puzzle:
<ul><font size=-1>So, then, who won?...Politically--or, more precisely and narrowly, in the contest for political offices--the right has won. But conservatives are not happy because they sense the primacy of cultural forces and feel that the culture is still shaped by the forces that have lost in electoral politics, by people who believed what the left believed in the sixties.</font></ul>
By and large, he is right. Today's anti-government neo-liberals, who laud personal responsibility and abjure prejudice against gays, blacks or anybody else are, in a sense, the children of 1960s radicals. That, however, is not how most of the leftist veterans see it--at least not in America, if the recent spate of books about the sixties is any guide. The sweet longing for the hedonism of the period (swinging London, the Beatles, Mary Quant and so on) that keeps breaking through in a mainly British collection of pieces edited by Ray Connolly finds no echo in the set of earnest American essays edited by Stephen Macedo.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In America, the sixties is shorthand not for the decade that began in 1960 with the election of President Kennedy, but for the 11 years that began with his assassination in 1963 and ended in 1974 after America's forced withdrawal from Vietnam and President Nixon's resignation to escape impeachment for perjury in the Watergate scandal. Between these dates, Robert Kennedy, Martin Luther King, Malcolm X and several civil-rights activists were shot dead, rioters set city blocks ablaze and colleges were racked by protests against the draft, the Vietnam war and "the military-industrial complex" that sustained it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Young intellectuals, mainly academics or college students, were in the van of the counter-cultural revolution on both sides of the Atlantic, but their efforts at coalition-building were different. In Europe they tried to make common cause with the working class but achieved much greater success in the east than in the west.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;French workers were quickly persuaded by wage increases to end their general strike during the 1968 student rebellion. At its high point some 20,000 students had marched through the Latin Quarter of Paris in "the Night of the Barricades". Danny Cohn-Bendit, an <i>enrag&#233;</i> from the University of Nanterre (now a Green politician in Frankfurt), was speaking less the language of the organised working class than that of libertarian anarchy when he shouted through a bullhorn: "There are no marshals and leaders today! Nobody is responsible for you! You are responsible for yourselves."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The effort to unite intellectuals and workers fared better in Eastern Europe, especially in Alexander Dubcek's Czechoslovakia during the "Prague Spring". There, Paul Berman recalls in "A Tale of Two Utopias", they won broad support when they championed the young, humanistic Marx against the old, iron-laws-of-history Marx, Hegel against Engels, Lenin against Stalin, left-wing humanism against "scientific" leftism, artists and intellectuals against office-clerks and censors, the avant-garde against the party-mandated arts.</p>
<p><b>American exceptionalism</b></b>
<br>In the accounts of the rebellions of the sixties in America, the workers and their unions hardly merit a mention. By then, as David Burner notes in "Making Peace with the 60s", it was almost impossible to discover any visible radicalism within the American social-democratic tradition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was a heritage that had once flourished among western farmers, Kentucky coal miners, and the militants of Little Steel. In the era of the Great Depression of the 1930s, writers, artists and intellectuals had been drawn to sharecroppers, migrant workers and union organisers. But 30 years later they saw white working men mainly as reactionary rednecks keeping blacks out of white schools in the south and as blue-collar workers keeping blacks out of white jobs in the rest of the country.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The intellectual left and the radicalised students, regarded by the average Joe as over-educated and over-privileged, sought instead to make common cause with the civil-rights movement. It was an uneasy alliance. The civil-righters were led by ministers of evangelical churches, charismatic men who almost alone among southern blacks were not beholden to whites for their income and security. It is the break-up of this alliance that Mr Burner views as the great tragedy of the sixties. For, as he sees it, the civil-rights movement "took a wrong turn as it gradually came to emphasise the 'identity politics' of race and ethnicity at the expense of the vastly more important politics of class and distribution of wealth".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first fracture in the loose coalition of what were then called progressive forces came between the Negro civil-rights movement, which welcomed white allies, and the Black Power movement, which despised them. The Black Power folk split in turn over whether the goal was to be black capitalism, African communalism or some kind of Marxist Utopia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Further fragmentation followed on the left. Harvey Mansfield notes in his essay in "Reassessing the Sixties" how feminism began partly as a reaction against the male chauvinism of the sexual revolution. Were women, the feminists asked, to be liberated from the kitchen and the nursery only to be confined to the bedroom? Within a decade, says Jeremy Rabkin in his essay in the same book, some feminists, in attacking pornography as the promotion of violent and degrading attitudes towards women, were campaigning for censorship.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Berman examines the fragmentation of the Gay Liberation Front, a shard of the counter-cultural revolution whose ecumenism once permitted the inclusion of both men and women. First the women split off into a Women's Caucus, then black and Hispanic women split off into their own group, and finally the Hispanic women left this to form Las Buenas Amigas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In their wacky desire to shock, it often seemed as if radicals were afraid that conservatives might be running short of ammunition and were obliging them by keeping up the supply. Yet the labels "radical" and "conservative" here are deceptive. Conservatism is a broad church which includes economic liberals and political or cultural traditionalists. Culturally speaking, yesterday's left-wing radicals and today's right-wing libertarians have much more in common than often supposed. Which, when you think about it, is not all that surprising. They have both been moulded by the same social changes: the weakening of the father-dominated family, and of authority figures generally; the success of education in undermining hierarchies and patterns of deference; the spread of wealth dissolving class barriers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite their excesses and absurdities, and their wholly predictable failure to create a more collaborative society, the rebels of the sixties were a symptom of sweeping social change in the developed world--and mainly for the better. In Eastern Europe, the heirs to Alexander Dubcek are in power in several former communist lands. In Western Europe, deference, if not routed, is in full retreat. In America, it is now unthinkable that any mainstream politician would oppose legislation to desegregate hotels, motels, restaurants and other public accommodations, as Barry Goldwater, Ronald Reagan and George Bush did in denouncing the Civil Rights Act of 1964. Visible integration among characters in television dramas, integrated entertainment and integrated television news teams today appear ordinary and normal. But, Mr Burner notes, this is only because the civil-rights movement challenged the discriminatory practices that were previously regarded as ordinary and normal.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Censorship has all but gone, despite the feminist backlash. It is hard, in the 1990s, to comprehend how D.H. Lawrence's "Lady Chatterley's Lover" was banned in Britain until 1960, and William Burrough's "Naked Lunch" was prevented from being published in full in the United States until 1966. Much discrimination against women and homosexuals has fallen away.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Above all, as Todd Gitlin notes in the concluding essay in "Reassessing the Sixties", on every political and cultural front today, "the question is not whether to question authority but which authority to question". It is not the epitaph that the Woodstock Nation would have wished for the decade, but it is no mean achievement all the same.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
