<html><head><title>Always in vogue</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr14.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>The human figure</b></p>
<h2>Always in vogue</h2><ul> <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>VOLUTION OF</font> A<font size=-1>LLURE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By George Hershey.   &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i> Press; 236 pages; $30 and &#163;19.95</i> <br>
</ul>



<p>SIX foot tall and weighing seven stone is not everybody's ideal of feminine beauty. It nonetheless excited the editors of the British version of <i>Vogue</i>. They filled several pages of a recent issue of their magazine with pictures of a model on this skeletal side of slender. The photographs caused a brief fuss when a watch-making company threatened to pull its advertising in protest. It and other objectors argued that <i>Vogue'</i>s impressionable young readers would starve themselves to achieve the emaciation so elegantly depicted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is the sort of fracas that tickles George Hershey, an art historian at Yale University. In "The Evolution of Allure", he describes how people have been striving for millennia to make their lives imitate what they see depicted in art. His strong thesis goes beyond simple imitation to encompass evolutionary strategy: "Figure art", he writes, "has urged us to breed...for beauty." Artists selected as models people who appealed to their taste. Their depiction of certain features and physiques helped, in turn, to mould people's ideas of beauty and to persuade them to seek partners who conformed to the archetypes. The loop was tightest in the classical period from the fifth century <font size=-1>BC</font>, and again during the Renaissance, when the canon of bodily proportions that was exemplified by the classical sculpture of Polykleitos was rediscovered and further elaborated.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ancient depictions of figures show very varied physiques, from bulbous carved goddesses to willowy hunters in cave paintings. The art of the 20th century has similar variation: Mr Hershey strikingly juxtaposes illustrations of the ancient works with a lolling Lucian Freud nude and some spindly Giacometti walkers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But between about 450<font size=-1>BC</font> and 1900 sculpture and painting in the West kept great regularity. The nipples, navel, groin, knees and heels of Polykleitos's Spear Bearer can be measured off down his body in multiples of head lengths: 2, 3, 4, 5.5, 7; Michelangelo's David is almost the same, except his knees are exactly 5 head-lengths down. Canons of proportion became immensely complicated, ordering the ratios of all sorts of bodily measurements, from chin to nose, and throat to hair-roots in systems that were studied and elaborated by the artist-anatomists of the Renaissance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The obsession with the pattern of the well-formed man became more sinister when it merged in the 19th century with physical anthropology. Ill-formation and other outward signs signalled bad character to such anthropometrists as Cesare Lombroso, a particularly ferocious scrutiniser of his fellow man and woman.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lombroso believed that the human race was under threat of regressing to extinction. "Atavists", whose degeneracy was signalled by such evolutionary throwbacks as "enormous jaws, high cheek bones,...solitary lines in the palms...[and] handle-shaped ears", were, according to Lombroso, in the process of out-breeding the nobler, better-formed people in whom humanity's future hopes lay.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Using statistical methods more feeble than a contemporary of Galton's should have employed, Lambroso claimed to prove in "L'Uomo criminale", a book published in 1876, that men with black hair were more atavistically prone to crime than those with blond hair. He saw in art and life evidence that genetic rot had already set in, that atavism was welling up to overwhelm the good breeding work of original heroic races such as the Greeks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lombroso's ideas influenced much art criticism of the late 19th century, including that of Max Nordau, who railed against decadence in artists such as Rodin and Whistler. Nordau was particularly enraged by their portraits of women, in which he saw feral sensuality tempting the viewer to orgiastic degeneration. He favoured taking a stringent line with artists who dallied with such primitive passions, invoking psychiatric hospitals, criminal trials and restrictions on reproduction, both artistic and sexual.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This approach was exuberantly adopted by the Nazis in their programme of eugenic ennoblement (although they did not acknowledge the influence of Nordau, who was Jewish). Once again, art was supposed to present bodily ideals to which healthy human beings would aspire as they selected mates. Bodily proportion became more extreme: the shoulders of the "Aryan" super-heroes in Nazi art are broader in proportion to head size than those of any Renaissance statue; and the women differ more widely from the men than previously, a boosted sexual dimorphism in the manner of birds and animals which go in for great displays.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Hershey's book trots briskly across a lot of history, picking out some shameful low points in science and some rather better art. The breadth of the book allows him to make bold comparisons. Some of its points are made effectively by well-chosen juxtapositions of illustrations: Arnold Schwarzenegger's hemispherical hypermuscles with the multiple plump breasts of an Ephesian Artemis of the 5th century <font size=-1>BC</font>; or Batman with a photograph of a naked man taken by William Sheldon, an American eugenicist who regarded Dick Tracy as a fine "mesomorphic" man.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since this is a work about art, bigger illustrations would have helped, particularly of the complex diagrams of proportion. At least there are a lot of them, but a little more flesh on this rather bony book would have made for even better reading and looking.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
