Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Backlash against Mc</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="10gr9.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td valign=top><br><p><b>American economy</b></p><h2>Backlash against McJobs</h2><ul> <li><a href="10ex310.html">F<font size=-1>AT</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> M<font size=-1>EAN</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By David Gordon. <br> <li><a href="10ex311.html">A<font size=-1>MERICA</font> N<font size=-1>EEDS</font> <font size=-1>A</font> R<font size=-1>AISE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By John Sweeney. <br> <li><a href="10ex312.html">J<font size=-1>OB</font> C<font size=-1>REATION</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> D<font size=-1>ESTRUCTION</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Steven Davis, John Haltiwanger and Scott Schuh.  <br></ul></i><p>"THE economy is creating tens of thousands of new jobs, that's the good news," says a man looking up from his newspaper. "So what's the bad news?" he is asked. "To support a family you'll need three." The joke, which takes various guises, reflects bitterly on the fact that the real wages of American workers have declined continuously over the past two decades.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Between 1948 and 1966 the real hourly wage of "production and non-supervisory" workers in the private sector rose by more than 2% a year. The rate of wage growth then slowed until 1973, when real wages actually started contracting, as they have done ever since. This has gone along with more job insecurity, loss of benefits and the growth of "McJobs".<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How can this extraordinary phenomenon--which threatens the American assumption that the next generation will always be better off than the last--be explained? In "Fat and Mean", David Gordon clears the usual suspects.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The phenomenon cannot be blamed on a "skills mismatch", he claims, because real wages were beginning to fall before the new computer technology became widespread. Although high-school drop-outs have suffered the greatest relative decline in wages, the hourly pay of computer operators and engineering technicians has also fallen. Even the real wages of college graduates are now shrinking. Increased international trade--the so-called global hiring hall--cannot be blamed either, he says. Hourly wages have fallen steeply for workers shielded from foreign competition, such as shop assistants and builders.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Gordon finds the answer in bosses' changed attitude to workers. (His point is reinforced by the head of the <font size=-1>AFL-CIO</font> union organisation, John Sweeney, in "America Needs a Raise".) In effect, argues Mr Gordon, an assault on labour began in the early 1970s as a growing big-business lobby--typified by the Business Roundtable--worked to reduce union activity and government interference. (The attack gathered pace after President Reagan sacked striking air-traffic controllers in 1981.)<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The business victory has led to a decline in union membership and in the real value of the minimum wage. The fruit of recent economic growth has gone heavily to managers and shareholders. The stick of supervision has replaced the carrot of wage growth. Despite redundancies at companies such as <font size=-1>AT&T</font> and <font size=-1>IBM</font>, America has more managers today than it had in 1989, before downsizing became fashionable.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Gordon deplores all this. Having more managers, consuming ever larger amounts of the national income, does not simply depress workers' pay, it is economically inefficient. If workers receive no incentive, productivity growth will decline even further and returns on capital will be depressed. Moreover, poor pay fosters social discontent. Mr Sweeney says discontent is already exploited by xenophobic politicians. Like Mr Gordon, he thinks the answer lies in a revitalised union movement and a higher minimum wage.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The argument has several weaknesses. It ignores the fact that the recent decline in real wages corrects the imbalance experienced after the second world war, when wages grew 10% faster each year than productivity. Mr Gordon's statistics on the numbers of managers are so dubious that his "stick" thesis stays unproven. If productivity gains from a more co-operative approach to labour were so clear and a huge "corporate bureaucratic dividend" was available, it is hard to see why people would not have realised this. Both authors dismiss the idea of a trade-off between high wages and employment. Recent European experience suggests they are wrong.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In their explanation of net employment in American manufacturing between 1972 and 1988, Messrs Davis, Haltiwanger and Schuh concentrate on its two determinants: job creation and job destruction. Their findings will change the way economists look at the job market. They reveal an extraordinary amount of activity behind small changes in net employment. Roughly 10% of jobs disappear and reappear within an average year. In recessions this disturbance becomes even more pronounced: job turnover (or reallocation) rises to more than one in five workers.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But they find little correlation between job creation and destruction (the number of new jobs increased in the 1982-83 slump). Nor do they find any relationship between exposure to international trade and job volatility--all industries show high levels of job turnover. They expose as a "myth" the belief that small companies produce more jobs than big ones.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Schumpeterian vein, the authors conclude that "large-scale" business failure and job destruction are normal, probably essential, elements in a successful market economy. It is a controversial interpretation of their findings. The current pace of change appears to be more frenetic than dynamic. The American worker, hurt by falling wages and increasing job insecurity, is its chief casualty.<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845679600,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
