<html><head><title>America Needs a Raise.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl311.jpg"><img src="cs311.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>A<font size=-1>MERICA</font> N<font size=-1>EEDS</font> <font size=-1>A</font> R<font size=-1>AISE</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By John Sweeney. <br>
<i>Houghton Mifflin; 167 pages; $18.95.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="10jb311.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
John J. Sweeney was elected president of the AFL-CIO in October 1995.
Previously he led the Service Employees International Union, which, during a
period when the rest of the labor movement was in steep decline, grew from
625,000 to 1.1 million members. Known for his militant championing of the
poorest and least powerful segments of the work force, Sweeney has also
served on the National Committee on Employment Policy and in the
International Labor Organization. He is the coauthor of Solutions for a New
Work Force. He lives in Washington, D.C., with his wife, a former New York
City schoolteacher, and their two children.
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845679600,rev">Search</a>
