<html><head><title>A year in Arcadia</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Literary cannonades</b></p>
<h2>A year in Arcadia</h2><ul> <li>G<font size=-1>REAT</font> B<font size=-1>OOKS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By David Denby.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Simon &amp; Schuster; 492 pages; $30</i> <br>
</ul>


<p>A WINNER of the Nobel prize for chemistry was once asked what courses he had found most valuable at Columbia, New York's elite Ivy League college. "The core", came his answer. It startled the interviewer but would not have surprised many Columbia graduates.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whatever else they are studying, students there have to take two courses: on the literary masterpieces of Europe and on the great works of philosophy and political theory. Each course, held in small classes, takes four hours a week for a year. The reading lists have changed a bit with time and taste but there are plenty of old immoveables such as the "Iliad", the "Inferno" and "King Lear".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The idea behind "the core" was that whatever students go on to do they ought at least to have met the writers who formed the heart of western culture and who spoke most directly to what humans were and could be. For decades that aim seemed so obviously sensible and high-minded as to be beyond question. But times change and "the core" became controversial, political even, as anyone who read even a paragraph or two about the ideological battles on America's campuses in the 1980s will know.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rather than re-fight those familiar "culture wars" head-on, David Denby, who reviews films for <i>New York Magazine</i>, had a genial idea. In middle age many people fantasise about re-enrolling in the university courses they liked most or wished they had done more with. At 48, Mr Denby fulfilled this dream and retook the Columbia "great-books" courses he had done in 1961. Out of his experience has come a captivating book that casts light on many things: on the job of a critic, on what classics are, on the pleasure of sustained reading (as against magazine flipping, hypertext clicking or literary theorising) and on how the best teaching in the humanities can still stretch young minds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How good teachers work with gifted young people has always been something of a mystery: a charged, intimate experience, often written about from either side but seldom recorded by mature, neutral observers. In fascinating detail Mr Denby describes how professors lead their charges in argument without patronising them, let alone trying to indoctrinate. Behind a cloak of pseudonyms the students emerge as distinct and lively personalities. In one striking vignette, a teacher well known for espousing lesbian feminism patiently expounds to a mixed class of men and women, blacks and whites, Aristotle's views on the natural inferiority of women and the need of orderly societies for inequality.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A <i>Leitmotiv</i> of Mr Denby's is the part classics by Dead White Males play in an American university where Asians, Hispanics and African-Americans account for over a third of the students and where <font size=-1>WASP</font> men are a minority. Mr Denby mounts a thoughtful, compelling case against putting together literary canons on the basis of skin-colour and gender. Columbia's two "great-books" courses took hold, he notes, as the university transformed itself from being an almost entirely upper-class Protestant enclave to being a much more open place taking the intellectually gifted children of Jewish, Italian and East European immigrants. The aim then was to assimilate those excluded from the larger culture of the nation. In the 1980s "assimilating" courses came under attack for, it was said, marginalising minorities, such as blacks or women, and later immigrants.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not so long ago Columbia admitted women and, coincidentally or not, some women writers, notably Virginia Woolf, entered the "great-books" course. As a student of the English novel years ago, Mr Denby could not stand her, but now she strikes him as indisputably great and he is accordingly grateful that the canon was forced open. Yet Mr Denby avoids simple-minded conclusions. As an example of honest literary standards, he cites Woolf's "A Room of One's Own". In it she judged many women writers severely, refusing to overlook literary failings just because as members of a "second sex" they led demeaning lives: on the contrary, she thought, a sense of wounded subordination often tends to produce bad writing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the end of the year Mr Denby was not surprised by his love of the western classics but was struck to be reminded what they really are: "less a conquering army", in his vivid phrase, "than a kingdom of untamable beasts, at war with one another and with readers". To explore this wilderness, even with a guide, he believes, is to get a bracing course in tough-mindedness, moral doubt and self-criticism. Far from being a frozen and "hegemonic" celebration of the West, the "great books", Mr Denby found, raise one big question after another. If, as well you might, you envy Mr Denby his year-long reading party, you should read his exuberant book.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845679600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
