Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>The new darkness</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h1>The new darkness</h1><ul> <li>I<font size=-1>CON</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Frederick Forsyth. &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i> Bantam Press; 447 pages; </i>&#163;<i>16.99 and $24.95.</i> <br>
 <li>E<font size=-1>XECUTIVE</font> O<font size=-1>RDERS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Tom Clancy. &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i> Putnams; 875 pages; $27.95. HarperCollins; &#163;17.99.</i> <br>
 <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> T<font size=-1>AILOR OF</font> P<font size=-1>ANAMA</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By John le Carr&eacute;.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Hodder &amp; Stoughton; 410 pages; &#163;16.99.</i> <i>Knopf; $25.</i> <br>
 <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>ASTERLESS</font> M<font size=-1>EN</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By J. K. Mayo. &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i> Pan; 432 pages; </i>&#163;<i>5.99.</i> <br>
 <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>ONKEY</font> H<font size=-1>OUSE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By John Fullerton. &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i> Bantam; 288 pages; &#163;15.99. Crown; $23</i> <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

SHADOWS thrown by floodlights on walls and sentryposts, those gritty traces of old frontiers where ideologies bristled at each other, lurk in the minds of too many writers of political thrillers and spy fiction. Those were good days, you can hear authors yearn in books turned out since the Berlin Wall fell. Before then readers more or less knew who the bad guys were, and writers aping a few well-known models such as John le Carr&eacute; could endlessly permutate bad apples, weak politicians, double-dealing deskmen and unwilling heroes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fresh veins being tricky to find, Frederick Forsyth tries hard to get a line from old ones. "Icon", set in Russia, exploits his nose for big events and his eye for circumstantial detail. In the run-up to a post-Yeltsin presidential election, a clever, charismatic right-winger is accidentally discovered by British intelligence to have a hidden Hitlerian agenda and to be in cahoots with the Russian mafia. Stopping him becomes a matter of principle for the intelligence men, but (echoes of Munich) they get no help from wimpish western leaders.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new-world disorder east of the river Bug ought to crackle with possibilities for good spy fiction, though you would not think so to read Mr Forsyth. He pulls the dreariest old-world spooks out of retirement to take the wheels off the villain's bandwagon. Their <font size=-1>MO</font> is stale and, despite its potential, the whole saga is as dull as watching morons let tyres down.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tom Clancy is at least aware that today's spies need new challenges. In "Executive Orders", he gives his longest-running character, the spy Jack Ryan, two big ones: how, having been flung by a cataclysmic accident into the Oval Office, to run the government of the United States when most of Congress and the Supreme Court are dead; and how to prevent a newly conjoined Iran-Iraq republic from savaging its neighbours and the interests of America in the Middle East.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This enormously long book keeps up a reasonable pace despite its many gratuitous diversions, such as the introduction of two characters whose main purpose seems to be to represent the hate-affair some Americans have with all things federal. The story covers a wide front, including a nasty biological attack on America's cities, which makes new work for the intelligence services (who did it?) and leads to decisive military retaliation overseas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clancy, as ever, entertains with this book, but also leaves an unpleasant aftertaste. He (or his hero) seems to feel that America would be better off if its sleazy, ineffectual politicians were all wiped away and replaced by selfless, ever-competent professionals (spies for foreign affairs, bankers for economic policy) who need not worry about public opinion or special-interest groups. Mr Clancy's books are hugely popular in America: are his (or Jack Ryan's) Platonic opinions popular, too?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the more complex, more tainted world of John le Carr&eacute;, Mr Clancy's simplicities would soon vanish in a swamp as corrupt as the one he wants to drain. Shrewd old pro that he is, Mr le Carr&eacute; has ruthlessly let go his entire cold-war staff and brought in new personnel, each as nicely rendered in "The Tailor of Panama" as in earlier books. Their sweaty awfulness oozes off the page yet they all have their own distinctively dreadful chemistry. These characters alone are a cruel reproof to Mr Forsyth's and Mr Clancy's robots.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As a story, "The Tailor of Panama" is less a thriller than a comic opera. The unfortunate tailor of the title, a British expatriate, is recruited by incompetent spies desperate to find a conspiracy, any conspiracy, which can be embroidered up to convince superiors in London that they should keep signing the expense accounts. If the premise sounds weak, Mr le Carr&eacute; develops the tale with almost farcical verve. He revels in the contortions of British diplomats, aghast at the <i>arriviste </i>spymasters whom they pretend to accept, all the while struggling to extricate themselves from absurd but inevitable catastrophe. Readers who wonder whether Graham Greene was not here 40 years ago are right, and Mr le Carr&eacute; acknowledges his debt to "Our Man in Havana". This tale, told with wit and ingenuity, is a splendid homage from one master of political thrillers to another.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The ennui of a spy world shorn of enemies is exploited with a lot less warmth and humour by J. K. Mayo. No longer locked together in silent war, the "masterless men" of his title need a new common bond and have found one in money-making crime. Their old masters must destroy them, and bloodily. The plot has too many coincidences. But at its best Mr Mayo's prose has a rough sparseness that echoes John Buchan, and his musings about complicity and betrayal are just pointed (and short) enough to be readable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Mayo's night thoughts, however, will sound almost dainty when set against the raw disgust with which John Fullerton writes in "The Monkey House". His setting is Sarajevo under siege and although readers will have seen or read countless reports about the bombing and bullying of the city, few have much clue what it was really like to live in that pit of despair.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Fullerton, a journalist who worked in Bosnia, spares little in this bleak tale of a cop who has to solve a drug addict's murder. He must pick though torn families, shredded loyalties and unfathomable enmities in a town where old obligations seem suddenly without meaning and where the moral vacuum feels far more perilous than the daily rain of mortar-bombs and snipers' bullets. Well-written and tightly plotted, "The Monkey House" is a chilling, angry thriller in which one policeman's search is a small light snuffed out by countless lost souls. If the best political thrillers each have their own vision of hell, Mr Fullerton has certainly found his.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
