</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Gulled pioneers</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="11gr5.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Travels in America</b></p>
<h2>Gulled pioneers</h2><ul> <li>B<font size=-1>AD</font> L<font size=-1>AND</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Jonathan Raban.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Picador; 320 pages; &#163;15.99. Pantheon; $25</i> <br>
</ul>


<p>THIS was the year the American press discovered Montana. First came the 81-day siege by the <font size=-1>FBI</font> of a ranch in Jordan, taken over by the Montana Freemen; then the capture in April of Ted Kaczynski, the man alleged to be the Unabomber, in a cabin in the woods near Lincoln. Suddenly, easterners discovered an authentic badland, glinting with bigotry and violence in almost unimaginable space.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Jonathan Raban, an English-born writer transplanted to Seattle, discovered it a little earlier. His is an engrossing and sympathetic attempt to reconstruct the lives of the homesteaders who, between 1910 and the 1930s (when most gave up), tried to make a living by farming in eastern Montana. They were lured west by government offers of land and by pamphlets, published by the railway companies, which promised enormous harvests from the virgin soil: furrows shining with coins.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, the land was desert. Uncharacteristically wet weather lulled the settlers for a few years; then, in 1917, drought came, along with searing winters and plagues of grasshoppers. The homesteaders hung on as long as they could, determined to try to make a go of it. Then, chastened, they headed further west, where they ended up logging in the north-western forests or apple-picking (so like the lowly piece-work they had left in Europe!) in the orchards of Washington state.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Little remains of their struggles. The 1916 map of the Chicago, Milwaukee and Puget Sound railway line, published as the end-papers to this book, shows a thick procession of towns along the route, confidently named after the daughters and acquaintances of the railway directors. Most of these are now virtual ghost-towns, with collapsed shacks still bearing the names of "Bank" or "General Store", while their few remaining residents live in trailers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The homesteads themselves, always difficult to distinguish in the featureless prairie, sometimes still hold the ruin of a farmhouse; more often, all that remains is the carcass of an old car, a path to a hen-house, or a patent lightning-conductor sticking out of the ground. Travelling salesmen did a brisk trade in these; indeed, the empty plains swarmed with salesmen and loan sharks bent on separating the naive homesteaders from their money.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a tale of almost unbearable folly, disingenuousness and sadness, lifted only by the sheer courage of the immigrants. Its saddest moments come when Mr Raban intrudes on the ruins of the homesteads, finding in one a set of desperate household accounts, in another the remains of a photograph album burned before departure. The ruin of a one-room schoolhouse produces reading books with advice on saving money and mending clothes. He even finds a copy of Campbell's "Soil Culture Manual", the dry-farmer's bible, promising yields of 54 bushels of wheat to the acre. It has been broken at the spine, and bears the print of a muddy boot.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The patient observation in this book is captivating. Less convincing is Mr Raban's argument that the homesteaders, tricked by the federal government, grew naturally into militiamen and survivalists. It was not only the government that lured them west; they wanted to go west themselves. Once they were there, the government enticed them with cheap loans; but it was the homesteaders who fell for the shiny mowers and harvesters on offer from the agricultural companies, stumbling into debts they could not possibly repay.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As far as western anti-government feeling goes, Mr Raban is not much nearer to explaining it at the end of his book than he was at the beginning. And that is only to be expected. His yuppie liberal sympathies continually give him away. He drives a Jeep, rather than a pick-up; he wears a Brooks Brothers tweed jacket, not a plaid shirt; he votes Democratic. At one especially revealing point, when he has crossed the continental divide and reached the Cascade range, he comes across the Skykomish river, "a torrent of boiling cappuccino". Only a rank outsider could describe the badlands of America as perceptively as Mr Raban does; but he is also doomed, this reader feels, never wholly to understand them.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
