<html><head><title>A Right to Die? The Dax Cowart Case.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl222.jpg"><img src="cs222.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>A R<font size=-1>IGHT</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> D<font size=-1>IE?</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> D<font size=-1>AX</font> C<font size=-1>OWART</font> C<font size=-1>ASE</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Robert Cavalier, Preston Covey and David Anderson. <br>
<i>Routledge; &#163;35</i> <i>and $49.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<p><b>Extract</p></b>
Introduction to the Case
<p>Some years ago, Donald (Dax) Cowart, an unmarried 25 year old man, returned from active duty in the Air Force and, while waiting for a job in the airlines industry, worked in real estate development. One summer's day, Dax drove out to look at some unpopulated land that he was considering as an investment. As he was getting ready to leave, his attempt to start his car set off an explosion in a buried but leaking gas pipeline. Dax received second- and third-degree burns over two-thirds of his body.</p>
<p>Dax's injuries left him severely scarred. His hands were badly deformed and the sight in his one remaining eye was at risk. As a patient, he had to undergo daily treatment in an antiseptic tank. This was so painful to him that he asked the doctors to stop his treatment. Dax felt that the length of his projected treatment, and the expected quality of life that he would receive from it, did not warrant the torment that he was experiencing. The doctors knew that if they continued his treatment, he would live; if they stopped his treatment, he would surely die. The question is now raised: Does Dax have a right to die? If so, what exactly does that mean?</p>
<p>This CD-ROM provides you with an interactive multimedia environment in which to explore the case of Dax Cowart. This User Guide gives you set-up instructions and a general overview of the program.</p>
<p>A Teacher's Guide is also available with the multi-user package. This contains further background information and numerous suggestions on how to use the program in various settings.</p>
<p>Final note: This CD-ROM is in a sense a "tool"; an important pedagogical environment that allows a user to "experience" a real-world case in all its emotional detail and moral complexity. It should be used thoughtfully and in the context of specific disciplinary needs. It is intended to be an element in the ongoing discussion about patients' rights and doctors' responsibilities, both from the perspective of individual situations and policy needs. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
