<html><head><title>The geneology of morals</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="12gr3.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Biology and society</b></p>
<h2>The geneology of morals</h2><ul> <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> O<font size=-1>RIGINS OF</font> V<font size=-1>IRTUE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Matt Ridley. &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i> Viking; 295 pages; &#163;20</i> <br>
</ul>

<p>MATT RIDLEY is easily one of the best science writers around. A zoologist by training, he writes with a fresh zeal and has large things to say or report about the biological basis for human motivation and behaviour. He has the range and equipment to be what, in the 17th and 18th centuries, was known as a "natural philosopher", a much-needed species of thinker-scientist that sub-specialisation has all but wiped out. "The Red Queen", an earlier book of his, on the evolution of sex, deserved its good reviews. Against these high standards, "The Origins of Virtue" comes as a disappointment: over-ambitious in scope, frustratingly muddled in argument and showing tell-tale signs of haste.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a hard book to summarise. The ground covered is vast. Taken as a tempting sampler of recent work in evolutionary psychology, it succeeds well enough. Mr Ridley briefly recounts the big shift within biology 20-30 years ago which replaced the species with the individual gene as the basic unit of evolutionary change. Insights that game theory offers into the "blind" but apparently strategic working of natural selection are then fascinatingly reported, as are countless other suggestive analogies of biology or behaviour between human and non-human animals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So far, so good. It is the red thread that Mr Ridley tries to find in all this that gets him, or his uninitiated readers, in a tangle. The argument, roughly, is this. History shows that no society survives without reciprocity and co-operation; evolutionary biology (on a leading current interpretation) shows that humans are but vehicles for "selfish" genes. How then did social values evolve? The gap between nature and society looks too big. Or rather once it did. Now, as Mr Ridley reports with justified excitement, evolutionary biologists think they know at least where to start making bridges: they are beginning to show how, both among humans and lower animals, certain sorts of seemingly unselfish deed might be useful in passing on the doer's genes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That achievement deserves only applause (or will do when powerful early insights can be purged of misleading metaphors and amplified with a lot more detail). But it is important to see these promised advances in biology for what they are--answers to gaps or puzzles in the tale of evolution--and not to push them farther than they will go.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How they will bear on the riotous variety of language and kinship, law and morals, politics and culture found in human societies is hard at this remove to say. Biology will be part of the story, more maybe than dogmatic opponents of "sociobiology" allow. But "biological" is not a synonym for "natural" or "systematic". People's behaviour has many levels. Biology is never likely to tell the whole story of the human animal's conduct.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At times Mr Ridley writes as if he thinks gene-bequeathal did motivate all human behaviour, much as Marxists once thought they had revealed class-interest, Freudians unconscious drives, and religious believers divine election as the hidden motor of people's actions. Explaining others' motives to them is a pleasure, and Mr Ridley records with relish how some human enterprises--the Wars of the Roses, for example, or football riots--mimic animal behaviour.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But he is also keen to show how a gene-based view of human history leaves a conservative-minded westerner's most cherished social values undisturbed. Ingenious examples and experiments are brought in to show how natural selection may have favoured "virtue" (hence the book's title), by which he really means social, as opposed to anti-social, behaviour. This is a welcome corrective to biologically minded thinkers for whom humans threatened to become prisoners of an inherently selfish genetic nature. But to others not tempted by that illusion, it looks more like a theory reversing gracefully out of a cul-de-sac. The book ends with a chapter called "Trust". A better name would be "The biological basis of recent Anglo-American conservatism"; it would have been wiser to leave it out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Two enemies haunt this book: the cruder foes of sociobiology, and moral philosophers. Mr Ridley's impatience with the first is understandable. His mistrust of the second is a pity. Philosophers do in some sense parasitise science, but in ways science can learn from. To put it at its simplest, learning the origin of a moral rule does not tell you if it is a good one or not. Imagine that gene-bequeathal is shown to be humanity's golden rule. People have evolved to a point where they still have to ask, "Yes, but should it be?"


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
