<html><head><title>Newspapers on the Internet still look like interlopers</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Byte-stained wretches</b></p>
<h2>Newspapers on the Internet still look like interlopers</h2><ul></ul>


<p>IN the early 1800s Mary Shelley had only to see a frog's leg twitch under an electric current to dream up Frankenstein. Today Internet surfers see some news flit across their computer screen and they conjure up Frankenpaper, the destroyer of the traditional newspaper.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As they say, newsprint wastes trees, it leaves ink on your hands, it takes a fleet of lorries and an army of children to distribute, and is still often out of date by the time it reaches its readers. Internet newspapers are immediate, global, can be searched in seconds, and customised to a reader's every interest--just Wall Street, Leeds United and jazz, thanks very much.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The digital zealots write off newsprint too soon. Paper is portable, lasting, easy on the eye, and quick and comfortable to read. The chances are, rather, that traditional newspapers will keep producing new and improved digital editions on the basis of their paper versions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most of the world's top newspapers are already moving on-line to try their hand at this new game, if not to take advantage of its efficiencies, then simply to keep up with the competition. The result so far: the same static and dated stories, but etched in electrons and phosphor rather than dead trees and ink.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most newspapers today are simply treating the Internet as another sort of printing press--another place to dump last night's snapshot of the news. But these are still early days. As the Internet market evolves and grows, newspapers will undoubtedly grow with it (as will <i>The Economist</i>'s own experimental site). This is how they are doing so far:</p>
<p><b><i>New York Times</i> (<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/">http://www.nytimes.com</a>)</b><br>The Grey Lady has never been trendy, but when she moves, she usually moves surely. Her Web site is solid, useful and comprehensive. Not much flair, except in the computer section and moderated forums, but the <i>Times</i>'s stories have never needed much embellishment.
<br><font size=-1>CONTENT:</font> Entire issue.
<br><font size=-1>COST:</font> Free in America; $35 a month elsewhere (half that initially).
<br><font size=-1>LOOK:</font> A touch of Grey Lady to set the tone at the top, then straight text.<br><font size=-1>SEARCH:</font> Soon available: all articles in past week, and selected articles back to 1980. Headlines and synopsis free, $1.95 per article for full text.
<br><font size=-1>FUN FEATURE:</font> Thriving forums, chaired by celebrities (such as James Gleick, the author of "Chaos", who handles debates on the future of newspapers, on-line economics and intellectual property); an enjoyable--so far--flood of generally intelligent comment from readers.</p>
<p><b><i>London Times and Sunday Times</i> (<a href="http://www.the-times.co.uk/">http://www.the-times.co.uk</a>)</b>
<br>Despite recent efforts to brighten itself up, today's <i>Times</i> remains rather dull. It seems livelier on the Web. The stories are no better than the print versions, but the on-line design is one of the world's best.
<br><font size=-1>CONTENT:</font> Entire issue.
<br><font size=-1>COST:</font> Free.
<br><font size=-1>LOOK:</font> Colour-coded tabs for each section make navigation easy.
<br><font size=-1>SEARCH:</font> Only current issue.
<br><font size=-1>FUN FEATURE:</font> Working crossword.

<p><b><i>Financial Times</i> (<a href="http://www.ft.com/">http://www.ft.com</a>)</b>
<br>A tentative site from a paper that could do a lot with customised displays and hypertext, but has not yet worked out quite how.
<br><font size=-1>CONTENT:</font> Just top stories, a few market indicators and a news summary.
<br><font size=-1>COST:</font> Free.
<br><font size=-1>LOOK:</font> Pink and boring.
<br><font size=-1>SEARCH:</font> None.
<br><font size=-1>FUN FEATURE:</font> Daily share prices for listed British companies.</p>
<p><b><i>Wall Street Journal</i></b>
<b>(<a href="http://www.wsj.com/">http://www.wsj.com</a>)</b>
<br>This impressive site is devoted mainly to the <i>Journal'</i>s "Money and Investing" section, but has many other articles too. It is a preview of the full-paper service with continual updates that will be introduced later this year.
<br><font size=-1>CONTENT:</font> Main business and financial stories.
<br><font size=-1>COST:</font> Free at the moment.
<br><font size=-1>LOOK:</font> A clean and quick read.
<br><font size=-1>SEARCH:</font> Past month, free.
<br><font size=-1>FUN FEATURE:</font> Company profiles.</p>
<p><b><i>San Jose Mercury News</i></b>
<b>(<a href="http://www.sjmercury.com/">http://www.sjmercury.com</a>)</b>
<br>The newspaper of Silicon Valley should have one of the best Web versions, and indeed the <i>Mercury News</i> does: it is fully interactive, allowing readers to set up quickly a custom paper with just the news they want.
<br><font size=-1>CONTENT:</font> Entire issue.
<br><font size=-1>COST:</font> Some content free; $4.95 a month for full access ($1 a month for current subscribers).
<br><font size=-1>LOOK:</font> A long, scrollable strip of departments in frames--the first newspaper that looks as if it was designed from scratch for a computer screen.
<br><font size=-1>SEARCH:</font> All stories since November 1994.
<br><font size=-1>FUN FEATURE:</font> Resum&eacute; service linked to classified ads.</p>
<p><b><i>USA Today</i></b>
<b>(<a href="http://www.usatoday.com/">http://www.usatoday.com</a>)</b>
<br>The paper that anticipated the fractured and icon-heavy style of the Internet was a natural for Web publishing. Thanks to a fast server, it retains its graphic look without much of a speed penalty.
<br><font size=-1>CONTENT:</font> Entire issue.
<br><font size=-1>COST:</font> Free.
<br><font size=-1>LOOK:</font> Bouncy mix of graphics, icons and text.
<br><font size=-1>SEARCH:</font> Full text for past six days.
<br><font size=-1>FUN FEATURE:</font> Current sports scores.</p>
<p><b><i>Le Monde</i></b>
<b>(<a href="http://www.lemonde.fr">http://www.lemonde.fr</a>)</b>
<br>France is home of the path-breaking, if now dated, Minitel computer network and a foe of English-language cultural imperialism. No surprise, then, that the Internet has been slow to take off there. <i>Le Monde</i> is among the very best newspapers in the world, but its current Net offering is second-rate.
<br><font size=-1>CONTENT:</font> The front page, top stories and a few special features.
<br><font size=-1>COST:</font> Free.
<br><font size=-1>LOOK:</font> An unnecessarily faithful reproduction of the paper <i>Le Monde</i>; it takes minutes to download.
<br><font size=-1>SEARCH</font>: Not yet.
<br><font size=-1>FUN FEATURE</font>: Send e-mail congratulation to the day's newlyweds.</p>
<p><b><i>Die Welt (<a href="http://www.welt.de/">http://www.welt.de</a>)</i></b>
<br>German dailies are not for the faint-hearted: a dozen pages of news, whole sections on culture and engineering, a day's reading on finance and economics. Such weight seems even more daunting on <i>Die Welt</i>'s dry and dated site.
<br><font size=-1>CONTENT:</font> Headlines and a generous sampling of full stories.
<br><font size=-1>COST:</font> Free.
<br><font size=-1>LOOK:</font> Boring, texty.
<br><font size=-1>SEARCH:</font> Daily stories back to May 1985.
<br><font size=-1>FUN FEATURE:</font> Stockmarket index.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
