</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Word-play</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="4gr13.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>
<p><b>Languages on CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>Word-play</h2><ul><li>E<font size=-1>NGLISH</font> <font size=-1>FOR</font> C<font size=-1>OMMUNICATION</font></a>&nbsp; <i>Disk-T, Moscow; $12 (Windows only)<br>
<li></i>G<font size=-1>LOBAL</font> G<font size=-1>ERMAN</font></a>&nbsp; <i>Mindscape, Burgess Hill, UK; PC format 29.99 and $32.95.<br>
<li></i>G<font size=-1>LOBAL</font> F<font size=-1>RENCH</font></a>&nbsp; <i>Mindscape; PC format 29.99 and $32.95.<br>
<li></i>J<font size=-1>APANESE</font> <font size=-1>FOR</font> B<font size=-1>USINESS</font></a>&nbsp; <i>Berlitz; PC and Mac 49.95 and $79.</i><br>
</ul>
<p>QUITE apart from its considerable merits as a tool for a Russian speaker learning English, "English for Communication" is an enthralling work of fiction to the ear of a native English speaker. Its dialogues and routines carry within them a faint echo of dissonance, grammatical or semantic, that raises them from the banal to the inspired. For example:
<ul><font size=-1>She doesn't look her age, does she?</font></ul>
How old is she?
I never ask women about their age.
Or, even better in its way:
<ul><font size=-1>Thank you for the compliment.</font></ul>
It's not a compliment. I meant it.
These and other exchanges form part of a running script between a dozen main characters that breaks down into ten "lessons", each emphasising a group of grammatical points and stock phrases. The plot verges on the surreal: a group of English and American scientists gathers for a conference in Moscow on an unspecified topic that is to be filmed by a famous director and covered by the correspondents of several national newspapers. But at least it is a plot of sorts, and thus enough to give a general coherence and sense of direction to the material--which, set against some rival offerings, is no trivial achievement.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The interface of "English for Communication" is a model of its kind, evidently designed by somebody who knows about the needs of computer users as well as those of language students. It uses menu- and hot-button commands of the type that will be second nature to the user of a word-processing program.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Times-Roman lettering is clear, big and bright. Photographs and short video-clips are embedded into texts. The program window can be scaled up and down. There are buttons for going back and forward, printing, saving and recording, turning off the sound, and for switching vertically and horizontally between sections of the course (ie, from the dialogues of lesson one to the grammar or the routines of lesson one; or from the dialogues of lesson one to the dialogues of lesson two).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mouse-sensitive text is displayed on the screen in English or in English and Russian parallel texts. Click, and it is spoken aloud. Another click is enough to secure a repeat. These may sound obvious points, but they display a measure of common sense that is still all too rarely encountered when booting up a strange <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A further virtue of "English for Communication" is that the facts and lore about English life are true and useful. Don't confuse the English with the Scots, for example. When you hear the English criticising their country, don't join in. When in doubt, talk about cricket or the weather.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Global German" and "Global French" deserve high marks for their ease of loading. They come with neat instruction booklets that tell you precisely what and where to type in order to start the loading process. And as the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> loads, it runs a neat utility program that tests whether <font size=-1>WAV</font> and <font size=-1>MIDI</font> sound systems are working as they should be. But after that it is pretty much downhill. Tinkly music drives out concentration and makes the student wish that his <font size=-1>MIDI</font> player were not working after all. The interface hogs the whole screen, making it impossible to shrink the window and get on with something else, or to fiddle with the computer's settings, without leaving the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> all together.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The student may learn words, phrases or (now and again) sentences, but from lists and tables as though this were at best an intelligent dictionary. Vocabulary is presented in grids of words that change from one language to another when clicked. Grammar is delivered in great slabs of small-font text. At best the student may get to rearrange a sentence, or attempt a test which consists of trying to find the right word buried in a table of wrong ones. There is no sense of direction, and hence no incentive to progress. A much more attractive approach is taken by "Japanese for Business", which is something of a cross between a phrase book and a computer game. It is hard to imagine anyone learning much useful Japanese here, apart from a few phrases. But the cultural tips, business protocol, travel hints, menus, music, games, quizzes, random snippets of information and animated cartoons offer a delightful way of preparing yourself for a first visit to Japan.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Clearly, there are big differences of style and approach between different publishers of <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> language courses. But collectively they are enough to provoke doubts as to whether <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> will ever offer a language-learning medium as effective as book, tape or flesh-and-blood teacher.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For one thing, the main virtue of a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> is its capacity for random access--which makes it the perfect medium for works of reference. But the main quality of any good language course will tend to be its robustness of structure, carrying the student where the student will often not want to go. Learning a language through course-work is rarely "fun", of the kind to which home-computer <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s tend to aspire. More often it is something much closer to a painful struggle against the deficiencies of your intellect.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
