<html><head><title>Bears routed</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="11gr7.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Post-communist Russia</b></p>
<h2>Bears routed</h2><ul> <li><a href="11ex334.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>OMING</font> R<font size=-1>USSIAN</font> B<font size=-1>OOM</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Richard Layard and John Parker. <br>
</ul>


<p>AFTER the fall of Soviet communism in 1991, the pessimists lost little time predicting that post-communist Russia would come to a sticky end. A collapsed economy, hurt pride and rampant nationalism, they said, would soon drive it to neo-communist or neo-fascist imperialism. It has not happened yet, and the great merit of this excellent book is to show why it is unlikely to happen.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It carefully charts post-communist Russia's admittedly unsteady and uneven progress toward creating a market economy, democracy and the rule of law. The authors' first-hand knowledge and insider perspective--Richard Layard has been an economic adviser to successive post-communist reformers, John Parker was Moscow correspondent, and is now special features editor, of <i>The Economist</i>--give their attractively written account the stamp of authority. The decisive repudiation of the communists in the presidential election in July strengthens their upbeat analysis.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sceptics will say that the prediction that Russia will grow by 4% a year "for a decade or more" is far too bullish. But the authors make a powerful case for it. Russia has a highly educated workforce, exceptional natural resources, a potentially huge domestic market. Add to this the fact that the Russian economy has been largely privatised, that much of the financial and legal framework for commercial enterprise is now in place and that Russia, unlike China, has a post-communist constitution, and it is not hard to foresee an investment boom, given moderately competent political management.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Layard and Mr Parker demolish familiar misconceptions. One is that the economy should have been "de-monopolised" before prices were liberated. They point out that President Boris Yeltsin and Yegor Gaidar (his first economics minister) never had this choice. They inherited from Mr Gorbachev a state and an economy which barely functioned. Freeing prices (done at a stroke on January 2nd 1992) was the only way to get food back into the shops, end the queues and start restructuring industry for market demand.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Equally silly is the frequent claim that "tight money" caused the collapse of output. Far from money being tight over the crucial period in 1992-93 when output fell, most of Russia was on the verge of hyperinflation. Output collapsed mainly because the planned economy collapsed. Loose, not tight, money contributed to the output fall by depressing real incomes--a point which deserves more emphasis than it receives here. Unexpectedly, high continuing inflation enabled a "classical" type of industrial restructuring to take place: as the authors put it, workers in declining firms were "pulled" into better jobs by the fall in their relative wages rather than being "pushed" out of old jobs into unemployment as happens in Western Europe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Layard and Mr Parker do not disguise the traumas which the Russians have suffered since the reforms started. Most Russians are still worse off than they were in 1991, especially pensioners, and children from poor families. Doing business in Russia remains tough. It is not the "mafia" which makes it so, but lack of secure legal definition and enforcement of property rights. Agriculture has barely been de-collectivised.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is good to see President Yeltsin acknowledged as the real hero of post-communist Russia. "It is a remarkable testimony to [his] genius that...he should have selected in turn as economic overlords four outstanding men: Gaidar, Fedorov, Shokhin and Chubais." An encomium to the long-suffering Russian people would not have been out of place. Whenever it has really mattered, they have supported their president and the reform policy. They deserve better of their rulers than they have had in the past. For the first time, they may be about to get lucky.<br>
R<font size=-1>OBERT</font> S<font size=-1>KIDELSKY</font>&#3;
<p>
<b>Reminder to readers</b>
Our policy is to identify the reviewer of any book by a member of <i>The Economist</i> staff.



