<html><head><title>No pretence</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="12gr6.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Repression in China</b></p>
<h2>No pretence</h2><ul> <li><a href="12ex363.html">T<font size=-1>ROUBLEMAKER</a>:</font> O<font size=-1>NE</font> M<font size=-1>AN'S</font> C<font size=-1>RUSADE</font> A<font size=-1>GAINST</font> C<font size=-1>HINA'S</font> C<font size=-1>RUELTY</font>.&nbsp;  By Harry Wu with George Vecsey. <br>
 <li>S<font size=-1>CARLET</font> M<font size=-1>EMORIAL</font></a>: T<font size=-1>ALES</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> C<font size=-1>ANNIBALISM</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> M<font size=-1>ODERN</font> C<font size=-1>HINA</font>.&nbsp;  By Zheng Yi; edited and translated by T.P. Sym.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Westview Press; 224 pages; $32 and &#163;23.95</i> <br>
</ul>

</i>
<p>A FEW years ago there was a swiftly banned craze among students in Beijing for <font size=-1>T</font>-shirts with striking designs and vaguely subversive slogans. "I'm depressed; let me alone" was the most popular. Another was more puzzling, but went to the heart of Chinese society. It showed the profile of an evil-eyed eagle, and a slang phrase, roughly translated as "pretend you didn't see." Life in China today relies on collective pretence. People have to feign forgetfulness of outrages they lived through; and they have to blink at continuing arbitrary injustice. The habit is so ingrained that there is genuine bewilderment at those who refuse to pretend.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Harry Wu, who spent 19 years in labour camps, was caught sneaking across the border into China in 1995, his captors seemed nonplussed. Here was a man with an American passport and a wife, a house and two cars in California. Why throw it all away simply to "make trouble" for the Chinese government?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Or take Zheng Yi, a writer who, as a student, was one of Chairman Mao's red guards in the cultural revolution of the late 1960s. He became obsessed with stories that, in one part of China during the period, blood-letting had sunk into mass cannibalism. Even Liu Binyan, China's best and bravest investigative writer, had looked away from this horror.
Harry Wu has been accused of suffering from a "martyr complex" for insisting on returning to China when he was already a marked and hunted man. His defence is straightforward. The prison camps persist; they continue to ruin the lives not just of criminals but of those who simply disagree with the government. And he, Harry Wu, is very good at investigating them. His notoriety stemmed originally from television documentaries showing that goods made with convict labour were being exported to the United States, in contravention of American law. Because this is one area where the link between trade and human rights is undeniable, Mr Wu made plenty of trouble.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1995 he was caught up in another political squall, over Hillary Rodham Clinton's planned visit to the United Nations women's conference in Beijing. He became a hostage. The book is an account of his detention, interrogation, trial and cynically calculated release, interlarded with his life history. He is a hero of our times, and his story deserves to be heard.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Zheng's narrative makes harder reading. It is, in the full sense, disgusting. He tells how, in the Guangxi region of China, purge-victims in the cultural revolution were humiliated, beaten, tortured, killed--and then, in some cases, eaten. He meets unrepentant cannibals, who tell him barbecued human liver is delicious.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Zheng makes a valiant attempt to come to terms with how this could have happened. As a Han Chinese, he has to guard against explaining away the cannibalism as the peculiarity of the local ethnic group, the Zhuang (who, with some 60m people, form China's largest minority). Rather, he shows it to be a pattern of vicious lunacy gripping all of China.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Very few of the most guilty were properly punished. In factories and villages people live and work alongside those who, just a generation ago, persecuted them or their families. As Mr Wu notes, the cultural revolution, it seems, had "only victims". But some workers or peasants who got to university did well out of it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Zheng refers naturally to one of the best-known Chinese stories of the century, "Diary of a Madman", by a pre-revolutionary writer, Lu Xun. The madman is obsessed by China's "4,000-year history of cannibalism". Lu Xun meant it as a metaphor for an inhumane society, where only survival matters. It is the sort of society where, as Mr Wu is being deported to freedom, one of his guards tricks him out of $1,000, "for his air-ticket". Lu Xun's metaphor is all the more powerful for being sickeningly, literally, true.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
