<html><head><title>What the world is reading</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><br><h2>What the world is reading</h2><p>MOST unusually, only a single book is currently a bestseller in more than one of these four countries. Daniel Goldhagen makes an appearance on both the British and German lists with a controversial account of the Holocaust, which finds the German people collectively responsible for the killing of millions of Jews.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The two top sellers in France are also controversial, though in different ways. Jean Montaldo smashes several haloes in alleging corruption in a French charity dedicated to cancer research. ''Clovis'' has provoked still greater rows but you probably have to be French to comprehend them. Ultra-nationalists in France have sought to commandeer Clovis, a 6th-century monarch. This, in turn, has excited anti-clerical leftists to demonise their country's first Christian king.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The British list is serene by comparison, with several highly inoffensive entries. Delia Smith's wholesome meals are so popular that her cookery books routinely outsell pulp fiction. Sister Wendy Beckett lives a contemplative life in a caravan when she is not gushing about pictures by old and new masters on television. Dava Sobel's study of longitude is scientific history at its exhilarating best. Dickie Bird, the subject of Brian Scovell's biography, is the best-loved cricket umpire in Britain.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Readers in Germany, it seems, are currently as enthusiastic about self-improvement as American readers are most of the time. Ute Ehrhardt gives German women emancipation tips; Alfred Biolek, a television personality, tells Germans of both sexes how to prepare stunning meals; an old American proponent of the feel-good factor, Dale Carnegie, tells them how to win friends and influence people; and Daniel Goleman, a new American feel-gooder, reassures them that even thick people can be smart.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The 1996 presidential elections are not yet having much impact on American reading. Both political offerings on the list are fluffy: revelations from inside the White House from Gary Aldrich, an <font size=-1>FBI</font>agent, and reminiscences by Ed Rollins, a political operative, in a book that one reviewer called a ''raincoat-opener".<br><h3>Non-fiction bestsellers<a href="#foot">*</a></h3><ul><li><a href="#1">United States</a><li><a href="#2">Britain</a><li><a href="#3">France</a><li><a href="#4">Germany</a></ul></td></tr></table><a name="1"><br></a><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><hr size=5 width=70 align=left><h4>United States</h4><ol><li> The Dilbert Principle 	<i> by Scott Adams	</i>. &#160; 	Management fads satirised	</li><li> Men are from Mars, Women are from Venus		<i> by John Gray	</i>. &#160; 	Relationships</li><li> Unlimited Access		<i> by Gary Aldrich	</i>. &#160; 	The Clintons behind closed doors</li><li> The Zone  		<i> by Barry Sears	</i>. &#160; 	 Where to take body and mind</li><li> Bare Knuckles and Back Rooms		<i> by Ed Rollins	</i>. &#160; 	The black arts of politics </li><li> Simple Abundance		<i> by Sarah Ban Breathnach	</i>. &#160; 	Comfort and joy for women</li><li> Bad As I Wanna Be		<i> by Dennis Rodman	</i>. &#160; 	Basketball's bad boy tells all</li><li> Outrage		<i> by Vincent Bugliosi	</i>. &#160; 	O.J.'s acquittal explained</li><li