<html><head><title>Church militant</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="11gr2.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Vaticanology</b></p>
<h2>Church militant</h2><ul> <li><a href="11ex333.html">H<font size=-1>IS</font> H<font size=-1>OLINESS</font></a>: J<font size=-1>OHN</font> P<font size=-1>AUL</font> II <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> H<font size=-1>IDDEN</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> O<font size=-1>UR</font> T<font size=-1>IME</font>.&nbsp;  By Carl Bernstein and Marco Politi. <br>
</ul>


<p>HALFWAY through this conspiracy theorists' account of the life and reign of Pope John Paul II, one denizen of the large tribe of shadowy sources who people the book explains why the pope really joined what the authors call a secret "holy alliance" with Ronald Reagan to topple communism. "What this gave him," whispers the source, described as a deputy to an ex-secretary of state, Alexander Haig, "was that he felt he had a high-level intimate relationship with the world's most powerful country. He was a player."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Carl Bernstein, a reporter of Watergate fame, is a creature of Washington. Marco Politi, Vatican correspondent for <i>La Repubblica</i>, has an Italian insider's knowledge (and taste) for church machination. They retell the story of the young, devout Karol Wojtyla, tracing his growth into manhood during the second world war, his studies at a clandestine seminary and his ordination as a priest 50 years ago this month. "His Holiness" engagingly recounts how in 1978 a conclave of cardinals improbably chose a provincial Polish cardinal as the first non-Italian pope in 455 years. Accounts of his first trip to Mexico in 1979 and his triumphant return to Poland later that year are particularly vivid.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Trouble comes when the book lurches into "the hidden history of our time". This is a replay of the thesis Mr Bernstein first broached in <i>Time</i> in 1992, namely that America and the Vatican entered a covert alliance to overthrow communism and that their pact was sealed at a papal-presidential summit in 1982. As a follow-up, Vernon Walters, American ambassador-gadfy-at-large, and the then director of the <font size=-1>CIA</font>, William Casey, also met the pope.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Four years ago, Mr Bernstein's account brought denials from actors and observers alike in Washington, Warsaw and the Vatican. It even drew a papal disclaimer. That Mr Reagan and the pope shared a goal in Poland, or that they were both pleased by the collapse of "the evil empire" is beyond question. That they conspired together to achieve it--did they need to?--is unproven in this book.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More convincing is the authors' picture of the pope in the 1990s as an ill and ageing autocrat, sure in his achievements but beset by a sense of solitude: the passing of the communist devil has not brought the spiritual regeneration that he hoped for in Eastern Europe. Even Poles may now divorce and have abortions. More positively, they remember that he is also "the last of the giants on the global stage...the only international spokesman for universal values."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite its insights, this portrait is marred by hyperventilated writing, by over-reliance on unnamed sources, by reconstructed conversations that do not always ring true and by interpretation applied with a sledgehammer. There are some splendid images of a driven, holy man; some revealing glimpses of John Paul's conviction and his uncompromising character. But on balance, "His Holiness" is a flawed and unsatisfying book.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
