<html><head><title>His Holiness</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl333.jpg"><img src="cs333.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>H<font size=-1>IS</font> H<font size=-1>OLINESS</font>:<br> J<font size=-1>OHN</font> P<font size=-1>AUL</font> II <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> H<font size=-1>IDDEN</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> O<font size=-1>UR</font> T<font size=-1>IME</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Carl Bernstein and Marco Politi. <br>
<i>Doubleday; 582 pages; $27.50 and &#163;20</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="11bt333.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
With the same meticulous reporting skills and narrative excitement that went
into All the President's Men and The Final Days, Carl Bernstein and Marco
Politi provide an astonishing look at the foremost political figure of our time. In
their research, Bernstein and Politi have had unprecedented access to rare
sources of information in Rome, Washington and Moscow, including once top-
secret Soviet files. Through these documents, the reader gets a previously
impossible inside glimpse into the Soviet hierarchy and sees how they
recognized the serious threat John Paul II posed to their survival, even at the
start of his papacy. Startling Politburo minutes show Brezhnev, Andropov, and
other key figures heatedly discussing at length how to handle the Pope - even
within days of the nearly successful assassination attempt. Yet, John Paul
would come to dominate his time, ultimately fashioning an alliance with
Reagan to reverse Yalta and hasten the demise of Communism. Ironically, it
was not for his political instincts that he rose through the Church ranks, rather
he is the first prelate in history to rise to the papacy based on his work in the
field of sex -as writer, researcher and counsellor to young couples.
<p>His Holiness succeeds where other studies have failed at capturing the humanness of John Paul II. What also emerges is the unknown story of a boy who turned to God after losing all of his closest family. members and whose destiny was shaped by growing up in Nazi (and later Communist) Europe. As it examines the controversial man who has sent the Catholic Church on a course that has both divided and uplifted its billion members, His Holiness explains how his iron will and strong convictions have made him the great moral leader of our time. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
