<html><head><title>Turning students into customers</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>The future of universities</b></p>
<h2>Turning students into customers</h2><ul> <li><a href="10ex295.html">C<font size=-1>RISIS</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> A<font size=-1>CADEMY</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Christopher Lucas. <br>
 <li><a href="10ex296.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> U<font size=-1>NIVERSITY</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> R<font size=-1>UINS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Bill Readings. <br>
 <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> F<font size=-1>UTURE OF</font> A<font size=-1>CADEMIC</font> F<font size=-1>REEDOM</font>.</a>&nbsp;  Edited by Louis Menand.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>University of Chicago Press; 256 pages; $24.95 and &#163;19.95</i> <br>
</ul>


</i>


<p>THE titles say it out loud: trouble looms on and off the campus. It was not al ways so. As Christopher Lucas notes, America's universities were for long spared the barrage of outside criticism that its schools have had to put up with for most of this century. Arguments about the aims and content of higher education tended to be confined to the ivory tower itself--though from the 1960s on they became ever angrier. Not till the 1980s did outsiders really look hard at universities as they might at a business or a government department. An argumentative example was Charles Sykes's "Profscam", which accused academics of not teaching, of publishing unreadable waffle as "research" and of sacrificing scholarship to political correctness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Polemics aside, scrutinising the efficiency of universities is only reasonable. America alone has 14.5m students, nearly ten times the number in 1939. Its universities earn, on one estimate, $175 billion a year, making them twice as big a "business" as airlines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lucas traces higher education's tribulations to the late 19th century. Start-up capital came from industrial tycoons keen to create monuments to themselves. The intellectual capital came largely from Germany, especially from the liberal-arts model devised by Wilhelm von Humboldt, the founder of Berlin University. This model stressed the unity of research, scholarship and teaching. And it laid down a broad curriculum, from Latin to mathematics, that all students should follow in order to become cultured citizens.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Charles William Eliot's inauguration as president of Harvard in 1869 marked the start of a long decline for the liberal-arts ethos. To Eliot it was no longer realistic to try to define a single body of knowledge that all educated people should possess. Harvard students were allowed to pick courses that suited their interests and aptitudes. Powerful faculties grew up providing ever more specialised and job-related courses. To Mr Lucas this has gone too far. He cites evidence that today's bosses would rather employ "liberally educated generalists" than narrowly trained specialists, and he suggests ways to update the liberal arts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Bill Readings, such efforts are futile, since the German-inspired "university of culture" is beyond repair. Universities, he argues, are becoming indistinguishable from the transnational firms they do business with. They even issue vacuous "mission statements" that contain platitudes about striving for "excellence". He shares Mr Lucas's disdain for the bean-counting of this new "university of excellence", which treats students as customers, rather than as members of a scholarly community.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In an ever more provocative chain of argument, Mr Readings says that the Humboldtian model aimed to be "producer, protector and inculcator of an idea of national culture"; that the end is nigh for the very concept of national culture; that no "global culture" will emerge to replace it; and so, instead of trying to turn their institutions into the Sony or the Shell of the education industry, academics must learn to live meaningful lives among the ruins of the "university of culture".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Readings seeks to make a virtue of the current campus rows between traditionalists, multiculturalists, postmodernists and other -ists. The traditionalists will not, he says, be able to rebuild a consensus about what constitutes "culture" or even "truth". So he proposes that the new ideal should be the "university of dissensus", where academics accept that "the position of authority cannot be authoritatively occupied" and where questions are thrashed out without any expectation of answers. Unfortunately, that sounds rather like the Monty Python sketch, "Is this the right room for an argument?", where people are paid to argue for the sake of it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Edward Said makes a similar point in his essay in "The Future of Academic Freedom". He does not mourn the university's decline as a storehouse of national culture, because he has seen the damage that that idea has done to academic freedom in Arab universities. Where Mr Readings calls for "dissensus", Mr Said uses the happier image of an intellectual traveller, keen to visit new worlds, to use different idioms and to understand a variety of disguises, masks and "rhetorics".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His is one of nine essays on the future of academic freedom commissioned by the American Association of University Professors. Among the questions debated are: are universities endangered by the argument that there is no fundamental truth, independent of the human mind, or by the competing demands of those who want absolute free speech and those who want to curtail discussion of touchy issues?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Curiously, although the tension between free speech and the rights of ethnic minorities is discussed, these essays on academic freedom hardly touch on the difficulties faced by sociologists who attempt to conduct studies on alleged differences between races. Nor does any essayist tackle an important question posed by Mr Lucas. Tenured employment, he notes, was supposed to be the bulwark of academic freedom. But is it not now, he asks, more a threat to free speech, as junior academics parrot their elders' opinions so as to secure tenure for themselves?


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
