<html><head><title>The big enchiladas</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="11gr6.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h2>The big enchiladas</h2>
<h2>How political biography aids political analysis</h2><ul> <li><a href="#1">T<font size=-1>HE</font> G<font size=-1>ORBACHEV</font> F<font size=-1>ACTOR</font>. By Archie Brown.  <font size=-1>OUP; </font><i>406 pages; &#163;19.99 and $30</i></a><br>
 <li><a href="#2">H<font size=-1>ELMUT</font> K<font size=-1>OHL</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Christian M&#252;ller. <br>
 <li><a href="#3">T<font size=-1>HE</font> G<font size=-1>ERMAN</font> Q<font size=-1>UESTION</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> O<font size=-1>THER</font> G<font size=-1>ERMAN</font> Q<font size=-1>UESTIONS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By David Schoenbaum and Elizabeth Pond. <br>
 <li><a href="#4">S<font size=-1>POKESMEN</font> <font size=-1>FOR</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> D<font size=-1>ESPISED</font>.</a>&nbsp;  Edited by R. Scott Appleby. <br>
</ul>

</td></tr></table>
<a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>T<font size=-1>HE</font> G<font size=-1>ORBACHEV</font> F<font size=-1>ACTOR</font>. By Archie Brown.  <font size=-1>OUP; </font><i>406 pages; &#163;19.99 and $30</i><br>
<i>406 pages; &#163;19.99 and $30</i><br>
<a href="11ex346.html">Extract</a> - <a href="11jb346.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="11bt346.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>FAWNING histories of world statesmen can make bad reading; admiring ones are another matter. Archie Brown, who teaches politics at Oxford, sets out to put the record straight for the essentially tragic figure who freed Eastern Europe from the Soviet yoke and presided over the break-up of the Soviet Union.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mikhail Gorbachev has come in for much criticism since he was elbowed aside by Boris Yeltsin. How distant his <i>glasnost</i> and <i>perestroika</i> now sound; almost as quaint as the "evil empire". The argument that Mr Brown develops is that Mr Gorbachev was unique for a leader of his classic Soviet upbringing in ruling out the harsh use of force. Even when his disintegrating empire did act with some brutality, as it did in Lithuania, he is pictured, almost plausibly, as a victim of this bad behaviour, not its perpetrator.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most intriguing, certainly the murkiest, episode in this lively interpretation of Mr Gorbachev's role in a superpower's fall is the coup in Moscow that failed but nonetheless brought him down. Insinuations that Mr Gorbachev was a participant in the coup against himself or somehow condoned it have never quite been laid to rest. Mr Brown finds such charges "absurd".
</td></tr></table>
<a name="2"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>H<font size=-1>ELMUT</font> K<font size=-1>OHL</font>.<br>
 By Christian M&#252;ller. <br>
<i>Gustav L&#252;bbe Verlag; 119 pages; DM88.</i><br>
<a href="11ex354.html">Extract</a> - <a href="11jb354.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="11bt354.html">Biography</a><br>
</i>
</i></td></tr></table>
<a name="3"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>T<font size=-1>HE</font> G<font size=-1>ERMAN</font> Q<font size=-1>UESTION</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> O<font size=-1>THER</font> G<font size=-1>ERMAN</font> Q<font size=-1>UESTIONS</font>.<br>
 By David Schoenbaum and Elizabeth Pond. <br>
<i>MacMillan; 264 pages; &#163;14.99. St Martin's Press; $39.95</i><br>


<p>THAT Helmut Kohl deserves even more credit than he is commonly given for keeping his re-united Germany on the right (western) track is the theme of this ode to a chancellor who has just eclipsed Konrad Adenauer to become post-war Germany's longest-serving leader. Christian M&#252;ller, the Bonn correspondent of the <i>Neue Z&#252;rcher Zeitung</i>, makes much of how his hero secured Mr Gorbachev's agreement to allow a unified Germany to be a member of <font size=-1>NATO</font>, though in retrospect it is hard to see how the Russian could have prevented it, so weak was the hand he held.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kohl's detractors recall how he was still declaring, just months before the Berlin Wall fell, that he did not expect to see unification in his lifetime. It seems they do not know half the story. Mr M&#252;ller reveals that Mr Kohl had been working on unification since June 1989 (the wall came down in November) and broached the prospect of unification with Mr Gorbachev at a time when there was a real temptation to pave the way for it by making Germany neutral. Mr Kohl stoutly resisted the temptation and three months after the wall fell Mr Gorbachev was obliged to hand him the key to German unity with virtually no political strings attached.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One odd note is apparent in this elegant analysis of what happened in 1989-90 in Germany: the argument that Mr Kohl has always been underestimated jars during a period when he is being lionised--and perhaps getting even more credit than is his due.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In their book, David Schoenbaum, an American political scientist, and Elizabeth Pond, an American journalist, make the sharp-sighted point that during all the years when top Germans were protesting, along with Mr Kohl, that German unity was out of the question, they were really taking part in a national conspiracy not to alarm anybody, including themselves.


</td></tr></table>
<a name="4"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>
J<font size=-1>WAHARLAL</font> N<font size=-1>EHRU</font>. <br>By B.R. Nanda <br><i>OUP; 312 pages; &#163;16.99</i><br>
<a href="11ex356.html">Extract</a> - <a href="11jb356.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="11bt356.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>LIKE Mr Kohl, Jawaharlal Nehru had the chance to build a nation. Considering the size of his task he did rather well, particularly when it came to establishing democracy in post-partition India. Mr Nanda is the founder of India's Nehru Memorial Museum so nobody would expect him to treat his subject harshly, but he certainly raises the big questions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Was Nehru an only half-serious foe of British imperialism who reverted to type (Oxbridge-educated, incurably pukka) before he had got the job done? Could he, with more patience, have prevented the sub-continent's partition when the British left in 1947? And was his determined promotion of non-alignment for India the irritating mistake that the West, and Russia too for that matter, thought it to be? From beneath most of the heavy questions that hang over his memory, Nehru emerges looking all right, heroic even--provided he is judged, as Mr Nanda demands, within the perspective of the ideas, assumptions and standards of his time, not with unforgiving hindsight.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The conflict at the heart of this study is Nehru's perplexing relationship with Mahatma Gandhi. Nehru at first "jumped" at the older visionary's solution of non-violence to redress India's problems, but later he grew impatient with it. Yet Nehru, independent India's first prime minister, never let their differences reach breaking point. His leadership was characterised by the caution which led him to install the new India in the British Commonwealth, so as to heal old wounds.
</td></tr></table>
<a name="4"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>S<font size=-1>POKESMEN</font> <font size=-1>FOR</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> D<font size=-1>ESPISED</font>.<br>
 Edited by R. Scott Appleby. <br>
<i>University of Chicago Press; 416 pages; $22.95 and &#163;15.95</i><br><p>THESE detailed portraits of "fundamentalist leaders of the Middle East" include Zionist zealots from Israel alongside Islamic extremists from countries ranging from Iran and Egypt to Lebanon and Sudan. As a guide to radical (mainly non-government) leaders in the Middle East, it serves its useful purpose all the better for being impartial.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite its weight of academic jargon, this collection edited by a historian at the University of Notre Dame reaches the down-to-earth conclusion that what is most divine about these extremists is their political nous. Fire and charisma are their stock in trade, yet they succeed by constantly weighing the religious inflexibility that their followers expect from them against the shifting demands of the political situation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Apart from the late Ayatollah Khomeini and Sudan's Hassan Turabi, none of the figures portrayed here has had the chance to build a nation. All the same, this objective account deserves a place on the bookshelves at quaking chanceries throughout the Middle East.



