<html><head><title>The Gorbachev Factor. By Archie Brown.  oup; 406 pages; &#163;19.99 and $30</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl346.jpg"><img src="cs346.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> G<font size=-1>ORBACHEV</font> F<font size=-1>ACTOR</font>. By Archie Brown.  <font size=-1>OUP; </font><i>406 pages; &#163;19.99 and $30</i><br></h2>
<p><i>406 pages; &#163;19.99 and $30</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="11bt346.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Mikhail Gorbachev was arguably the most important statesman of the second half of the
twentieth century. He played the decisive role in ending the Cold War and in allowing the
countries of Eastern Europe to regain their independence peacefully. He left Russia a freer
country than it had ever been. Although he failed in his attempts to turn the Soviet Union into
a genuine federation, he refused to resort to the repression that would have been needed to
preserve the USSR intact in the face of opposition from a number of its peoples.
<p>What kind of man made this massive difference to his own country, Europe, and the world? What were his views when he became Soviet leader and how did they evolve? Who and what influenced him? When did he move from being a reformer of the Soviet system to becoming the 'gravedigger' of Communism? How decisive for the dramatic changes of the last decade was the Gorbachev factor? In this masterly account, Archie Brown--a renowned authority on Gorbachev and the first Western scholar to predict his importance answers these questions in fascinating detail. Drawing upon a wide range of sources, including the memories (and memoirs) of those who worked most closely with Gorbachev, he combines acute political analysis with new information as he tells the story of Gorbachev's rise and fall--and of his less than seven years in power which changed the course of history. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848102400,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
