<html><head><title>Just So</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="4gr15.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Classics on CD-ROMS</b></p>
<h2>Just So</h2><ul><li>H<font size=-1>OW</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> L<font size=-1>EOPARD</font> G<font size=-1>OT</font> H<font size=-1>IS</font> S<font size=-1>POTS</font></a>&nbsp; <i>Microsoft; 25.52</i><br>
<li>R<font size=-1>ECESS</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> G<font size=-1>REECE</font></a>&nbsp; <i>Morgan Interactive</i><br>
</ul>

<p>MULTIMEDIA is supposed to be great for children, but can infotainment do the classics? These two ambitious attempts at the art of classic story telling could not be more different. Microsoft's re-telling of Rudyard Kipling's "How the Leopard Got His Spots" is so speckled, sprottled and spottled with success that it will be the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> to beat for some time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Reading classic stories to children is a sublime pleasure of parenthood, made all the more exciting when the little darling in your lap is absorbed in the words and images. How can computers compete? Lesson number one is to stick close to the original poetic prose. Danny Glover's reading of nearly the full text of the "Just So" story is magnificent. Barely a phrase is lost. Mr Glover relishes the "catty-shaped", "jumpsome", "patchy-blatchy", "slippery-slidy" phrases and positively delights in reminding children that "calling names won't catch dinner".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In "Recess in Greece", by contrast, Odysseus from "The Iliad" is a smart-alecky, street-wise American kid. Hermes the messenger god is a Hell's Angel biker, Zeus is a gunslinger from the American west, Apollo is a 1960s rock star and the Spartan war with Troy is depicted as an American football match. No poetry here. Programs are interspersed with games, including a game to match scattered images.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Microsoft, much more imaginatively, presents the challenge of matching snippets of African music. In fact, it is music that holds lesson number two. Microsoft added to the story-telling experience by hiring Ladysmith Black Mambazo, a South African group. Its music provides a sometimes haunting, often funny and always strong thread through "The Leopard". Homer's tale is supposed to be reinforced by cute snippets of modern music or jazzed-up Greek tunes but Microsoft has shown Morgan Interactive what every composer for the ballet knows: the music must enrich and sustain the story.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both programs have the obligatory hot spots. A click of the mouse transforms objects in unexpected ways, but our seven-year-old co-reviewer was already wise to the tricks of transformation. Where Microsoft scores is in its beautiful, vivid drawings by Lori Lohstoeter. Her art is inspired by the marvellous African exhibits in New York's Metropolitan Museum. The supporting pictures and video come from Britain's National Trust, the <font size=-1>BBC</font>, the American National Geographic Society, the Smithsonian Institution and other authoritative sources.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A third lesson, already evident in earlier Microsoft <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s for children, is to make sure there is something for the parents. The subtle anti-racism message of "The Leopard", even its gentle debunking of vegetarian obsessions, have no parallel in "Recess in Greece". Adults do get to brush up on their Greek gods, but the hipness of the characters makes it hard to trust what you are seeing. In humour it is no contest. Kipling and Microsoft win hands down.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
