<html><head><title>My news or yours?</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h2>My news or yours?</h2>
<p><b>Can personalisation save you from drowning in newsprint?</b><p>THINK of your daily newspaper as all the pizzas on your home-delivery menu: you order one, you get them all. Two-dozen boxes arrive with each order. You hate ham, anchovies, mushrooms, artichokes and so on, and you routinely throw them away. You keep the four-cheese and the margarita. Simpler, surely, to place an order. That, in essence, is the idea behind the <i>Daily Me</i>, the stock name for personalised newspapers on the net. You tell the "publisher" what your daily interests are; you get that and only that.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It sounds sensible. But does personalisation work? One problem is delivery. The idea of customising newspapers pre-dates the net. But, with newsprint, cost made it unworkable. Knight-Ridder, a big American newspaper chain, spent years of research on the so-called "tablet", a hand-held screen, which would combine the best features of an electronic newspaper and a conventional, print-based one. The idea proved futuristic. Knight-Ridder cancelled it in August 1995 and has since focused electronically on publishing through the net.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another problem is pre-selection from the mass of raw information hitting newspaper offices. Normally, news editors sort this out. Can their decision-processes be programmed? These involve news-sense, a nose for puffery, knowing when two stories are the same and other quick hunches needed to sort out press releases, trade promotions and wire feeds. These may be programmable one day. They are not programmed yet. Are then editors dispensable? Without them readers get the all-or-nothing pizza-problem back again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And then there is the question of the <i>Daily Me</i> against the <i>Daily Us</i>. A good newspaper is a newspaper readers associate themselves with. It has a character, a personality. It takes people out of their own world. The <i>Daily Me</i> is solipsistic, satisfying the interests of a community of one. Such communities exist only in the imagination. The premise that people's tastes and interests are so different that each would demand unique menus is false. The image of billions of readers with distinct, customised newspapers is techno-fiction. Conformists, by definition, are commoner than eccentrics.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That said, tastes and interests do differ enough to create market chances. The net offers an ease of choice from among the contents of normal papers that big publishers, and some small ones, are trying to exploit--or would be trying if they could figure out more reliably how to charge for them. Here is a selection of <i>Daily Me</i>sites:

<p><i><b>The Times (London)</i></b>&#160;&#160;<a href="http://www.the-times.co.uk/">http://www.the-times.co.uk/</a><p><font size=-1>Name: </font>Personal Times <br><font size=-1>Represented by:</font> Dour-faced butler<br><font size=-1>Sources:</font><i>The Times</i> and <i>Sunday Times</i><br><font size=-1>Cost:</font> Free
<p><i>Personal Times</i> provides a useful snapshot of each day's print edition, saving you from having to buy it.<hr size=5 width=170 align=left><p><i><b>IBM</i></b>&#160;&#160;<a href="http://www.infosage.ibm.com/">http://www.infosage.ibm.com/</a><p><font size=-1>Name:</font><i> InfoSage</i><br><font size=-1>Represented by:</font> Glitzy corporate logo<br><font size=-1>Sources:</font> Wire services<br><font size=-1>Cost:</font> $24.95 a month<p><i>Infosage</i> is not so much a general, personalised electronic newsheet as an all-purpose (or no purpose) trade paper. Instead of filtering junk mail, <i>Infosage</i> generates it, despatching dozens of industry-specific "stories" each day (many of them raw, repetitious news releases).<hr size=5 width=170 align=left><p><i><b>Los Angeles Times</i></b>&#160;&#160;<a href="http://www.latimes.com/">http://www.latimes.com/</a><p><font size=-1>Name: </font><i>Hunter</i><br><font size=-1>Represented by:</font> A cute golden retriever masquerading as a poodle<br><font size=-1>Sources: </font><i>LA Times</i>, Associated Press wire services<br><font size=-1>Cost:</font> Free<p>This retriever is perhaps too good at his job, dragging snippets out of the <i>LA Times</i> and sticking them (clumsily) next to identical ones from the Associated Press.<hr size=5 width=170 align=left><p><i><b>Adaptyx</i></b>&#160;&#160;<a href="http://www.daptyx.com/">http://www.daptyx.com/</a><p><font size=-1>Name: </font><i>Rex</i><br><font size=-1>Represented by:</font> Bespectacled, golden tyrannosaurus rex<br><font size=-1>Sources:</font> General news sources on the Internet<br><font size=-1>Cost:</font> Free
<i><p>Rex </i>uses wire services directly from the net. He tends to avoid trivial stories and once he finds something you like, he brings other reports of the same event. Readers can "train" this predator by telling it what they did or did not like.<hr size=5 width=170 align=left><p><i><b>Pointcast, Inc</i></b>&#160;&#160;<a href="http://www.pointcast.com/">http://www.pointcast.com/</a><p><font size=-1>Name: </font><i>Pointcast Network</i> (<font size=-1>PCN</font>)<br><font size=-1>Look:</font> Slick, <font size=-1>CNN</font> without toothy grins<br><font size=-1>Sources:</font> Wire services, some American daily newspapers<br><font size=-1>Cost:</font> Free<p>A triumph of style over content: <font size=-1>PCN</font> uses a fresh format and looks wonderful. But it shovels out half-filtered stories from news wires and its coverage is weak.<hr size=5 width=170 align=left><p><i><b>Crayon.net</i></b>&#160;&#160;<a href="http://www.crayon.net/">http://www.crayon.net/</a><p><font size=-1>Name: </font><i>CReAte Your Own Newspaper </i>(<i>Crayon</i>)<br><font size=-1>Represented by:</font> A crayon<br><font size=-1>Sources:</font> Web-based newspapers<br><font size=-1>Cost:</font> Free<p>An early personalised newspaper offering readers business news from one paper, sports from another and opinions from a third. Works well and is still in many ways a model of the genre.<hr size=5 width=170 align=left><p><p><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
