<html><head><title>Walking on eggs</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="10gr7.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td valign=top><br><h2>Walking on eggs</h2><p><b>Most of the world's fastest growing economies are in Asia. Despite this, several of the latest books about Asia are remarkably downbeat</b></p><ul> <li><a href="#1">P<font size=-1>ACIFIC</font> D<font size=-1>EFENSE</font></a>: A<font size=-1>RMS</font>, E<font size=-1>NERGY</font> &amp; A<font size=-1>MERICA'S </font>F<font size=-1>UTURE IN</font> A<font size=-1>SIA</font>.&nbsp;  By Kent E. Calder.<br> <li><a href="#2">C<font size=-1>OLLISION </font> C<font size=-1>OURSE</font></a>: A<font size=-1>MERICA</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> E<font size=-1>AST</font> A<font size=-1>SIA</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> P<font size=-1>AST</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> F<font size=-1>UTURE</font>.&nbsp;  By Bryce Harland. <br> <li><a href="#3">T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>EGACY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> T<font size=-1>IANANMEN</font></a>: C<font size=-1>HINA IN</font> D<font size=-1>ISARRAY</font>.&nbsp;  By James Miles. <br> <li><a href="#4">H<font size=-1>UNGRY</font> G<font size=-1>HOSTS</font></a>: C<font size=-1>HINA'S</font> S<font size=-1>ECRET</font> F<font size=-1>AMINE</font>.&nbsp;  By Jasper Becker. <br> <li><a href="#5">D<font size=-1>ICTIONARY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>ODERN</font> P<font size=-1>OLITICS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>OUTHEAST</font> A<font size=-1>SIA</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Michael Leifer. <br> <li><a href="#6">I<font size=-1>NDIA'S</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMIC</font> R<font size=-1>EFORMS</font> 1991-2001.</a>&nbsp;  By Vijay Joshi and I.M.D. Little<br></ul></td></tr></table><a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td valign=top><br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>P<font size=-1>ACIFIC</font> D<font size=-1>EFENSE</font>:<br> A<font size=-1>RMS</font>, E<font size=-1>NERGY</font> &amp; A<font size=-1>MERICA'S </font>F<font size=-1>UTURE IN</font> A<font size=-1>SIA</font>.<br> By Kent E. Calder.<br><i> William Morrow, $25. <br>Published in Britain as </i>A<font size=-1>SIA</font>'<font size=-1>S</font> D<font size=-1>EADLY</font> T<font size=-1>RIANGLE</font>.<br><i> Nicholas Brealey; 253 pages; &#163;16.99</i><p><a href="10ex304.html">Extract</a> - <a href="10jb304.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="10bt304.html">Biography</a></i></br></i></br><p>THIS book is a coherent but pessimistic view of Asia's future. The three sides of the triangle, according to Mr Calder, are rapidly growing economies, leading to shrinking energy resources and an arms race. This he sees as a formula for conflict. Some of Mr Calder's worries may be overdone. It is not obvious that East Asians face an energy crisis. Higher prices will encourage China and Indonesia to use power more efficiently. Japan has been doing so for some time. Asian arms purchases, again, are lower than in the 1980s and military spending is not growing as a percentage of <font size=-1>GDP</font>.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The greater risks in Asia lie in the internal pressures for change that are reshaping priorities among big and middle-sized countries. As befits the holder of the Japan chair at Washington's Centre for Strategic and International Studies, Mr Calder is at his best when explaining why Japan will grow more assertive as Asia becomes less predictable and the United States less involved. His analysis of the domestic roots of instability in China, Korea, Taiwan and several South-East Asian states is astute.</td></tr></table><a name="2"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td valign=top><br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>C<font size=-1>OLLISION </font> C<font size=-1>OURSE</font>:<br> A<font size=-1>MERICA</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> E<font size=-1>AST</font> A<font size=-1>SIA</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> P<font size=-1>AST</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> F<font size=-1>UTURE</font>.<br> By Bryce Harland. <br><i>Institute of Southeast Asian Studies; 230 pages; $29.90</i><p><a href="10ex305.html">Extract</a> - <a href="10jb305.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="10bt305.html">Biography</a><br><p>A FORMER New Zealand ambassador to both Washington and Beijing sees collision looming between Asia and America. Mr Harland seems to place most of the blame on an American attempt to export its values and to force open Asian markets. There is a lot more of the past than the future in this book, which may also underplay the latent conflicts within Asia itself. But it provides a very useful guide to the history of American involvement in Asia by an author with a longer memory than most.</td></tr></table><a name="3"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td valign=top><br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>EGACY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> T<font size=-1>IANANMEN</font>:<br> C<font size=-1>HINA IN</font> D<font size=-1>ISARRAY</font>.<br> By James Miles. <br><i>University of Michigan Press; 379 pages; $29.95 and &#163;19.95</i><p><a href="10ex306.html">Extract</a> - <a href="10jb306.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="10bt306.html">Biography</a><br><p>IF YOU want the pessimistic take on China's future, this is your book. James Miles was the <font size=-1>BBC</font>'s correspondent in Beijing for seven years and reported on the Tiananmen Square massacre. He worries that China is in "disarray" and risks a new revolution because of the social and political forces unleashed by economic reform. He writes with the vigour of the best of the "reportage" school of journalism and his description of rising inequality, weak leadership, deep social crisis and rampant corruption in the modern Chinese system is powerful. Mr Miles argues that China is less stable than it was in the run-up to the events of 1989 and gives warningthat toleration of the status quo is very different from approval.</td></tr></table><a name="4"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td valign=top><br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>H<font size=-1>UNGRY</font> G<font size=-1>HOSTS</font>:<br> C<font size=-1>HINA'S</font> S<font size=-1>ECRET</font> F<font size=-1>AMINE</font>.<br> By Jasper Becker. <br><i>John Murray; 352 pages; &#163;19.99. Free Press; $25</i><br><p>FROM 1958-62 China had a famine that killed 30m people; 35 years later China's leaders still do not talk about it. This was a man-made famine, and the men who made it were the political parents of those now in power in China. Astoundingly, Jasper Becker, another China-based British journalist, is the first to write a full account of one of this century's great horrors. Passionately but precisely, Mr Becker records the tragic results of one of the boldest example of Utopian engineering ever attempted--one that included trying to abolish money and property and promised people's communes instead. The careful academic tones are mixed with horrific eyewitness accounts.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Becker urges readers to understand the roots of depraved policies that, although similar to those carried out in Stalin's Soviet Union, have received far less attention. He also recounts how--as with the Soviet Union's great famine--a great many western "experts" missed what was going on (J.K. Galbraith, Barbara Ward, Joseph Needham, Gunnar Myrdal) and instead showered praise on a Chinese regime that supposedly kept its people from famine.</td></tr></table><a name="5"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td valign=top><br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>D<font size=-1>ICTIONARY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>ODERN</font> P<font size=-1>OLITICS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>OUTHEAST</font> A<font size=-1>SIA</font>.<br> By Michael Leifer. <br><i>Routledge; 304 pages; &#163;16.99</i><br><p>DESPITE a conscious effort to promote a regional identity, each of the ten countries of South-East Asia has a distinctive and complex political structure and recent history. Mr Leifer has updated a guide of enormous use to businessmen, diplomats, students and journalists. The dictionary provides a succinct and reliable source for a quick mugging-up on personalities, parties and policies in the individual countries, as well as on the bewildering and acronym-infested process of regional co-operation. Its concerns range from <i>abangan</i> (the name given to Javanese who practise a syncretic form of Islam) to <font size=-1>ZOPFAN</font> (<i>"</i>the Zone of Peace, Freedom and Neutrality<i>"</i>, announced in 1971).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The dictionary's most obvious home is the briefcase of the visitor to the region, seeking a map through the political minefields. But a bigger market should be South-East Asia itself, where many countries admit they are short of experts in the affairs of their neighbours. It is hard to think, for example, of a South-East Asian scholar who could have produced such a panoramic work. That is also in part a result of timidity. Frank writing about other countries' internal affairs has a price (the first edition of the book, for example, was banned in Malaysia).</td></tr></table><a name="6"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td valign=top><br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>I<font size=-1>NDIA'S</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMIC</font> R<font size=-1>EFORMS</font> 1991-2001.<br> By Vijay Joshi and I.M.D. Little<br><i>Oxford University Press; 296 pages; &#163;25 and $36</i><p>THIS study is probably the most cogent account so far of India's economic reforms since 1991, and of the debates within the country on the changes. It notes that substantial economic progress has been made in five years, but argues that the amount of unfinished business is large and daunting. The authors do not think the necessary changes will come quickly, if at all. India, in their view, will not become another Asian tiger, not in the near future at any rate.<p><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845679600,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
