<html><head><title>Up and away</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="12gr5.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Prophetic bestsellers</b></p>
<h2>Up and away</h2><ul> <li><a href="12ex361.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>ELESTINE</font> P<font size=-1>ROPHECY</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By James Redfield. <br>
 <li><a href="12ex362.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>TORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> B</a>: A<font size=-1>N</font> A<font size=-1>DVENTURE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>IND</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> S<font size=-1>PIRIT</font>.&nbsp;  By Daniel Quinn. <br>
</ul>

</i>
<p>JAMES REDFIELD'S "The Celestine Prophecy" has spent nearly three years on American bestseller lists and 6m copies are in print worldwide. What is the secret? The story is a helter-skelter chase to recover an ancient Mayan manuscript that contains life-enhancing, but establishment-menacing, advice about meditation and self-fulfilment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The New Age American hero, a youth counsellor and no Stallone, must gather the scattered bits of the precious text before the Peruvian (sic) government stops him. Ranged against him, more threateningly, are the Catholic church and the world's scientific establishment, each afraid that the Mayan revelation will destroy their authority.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The nine Mayan insights have a distinctly modern ring. They are a mix of self-help and spiritualist (or surrealist) science: remember that society involves selfish egos; don't ignore coincidences; pay attention to energy fields; if stuck, meditate (it even makes you invisible). The Mayans apparently knew all this before their mysterious disappearance centuries ago. Indeed, they spirited themselves away by meditation to a parallel universe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The Story of B" also uses adventure to push an antinomian outlook. "B" is for blasphemy, here the belief that nature matters as much as man. When not dodging murderous attacks from Catholic friars, the book's tree-hugging heroes preach vivid animist sermons.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Interestingly, these writers differ on the future. Mr Redfield (or his hero) thinks western civilisation must move up to a higher, scientific-spiritual plane. Rejecting progress, Daniel Quinn (or his animists) see a return to pre-scientific belief as the key to human survival. Is the publisher hedging bets, or just segmenting the market?


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
