<a href="cl361.jpg"><img src="cs361.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>ELESTINE</font> P<font size=-1>ROPHECY</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By James Redfield. <br>
<i>Warner; 282 pages; $9.99.</i> <i>Bantam; &#163;7.99.</i><br>
</p><br>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
James Redfield has a B.A. in Sociology, an M.Ed. in Counselling, and for
fifteen years worked as a therapist with emotionally disturbed
adolescents. He has recently completed, with Carol Adrienne, a
psychologist and metaphysical counsellor, The Celestine Prophecy: An
Experiential Guide, which is designed to help readers intensify and
expand the exciting knowledge contained in each of the 9 insights of
The Celestine Prophecy. This companion guide is available in Bantam
paperback. The best-selling sequel to The Celestine Prophecy, The Tenth
Insight, is now available in Bantam Press hardcover.
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
