<html><head><title>The total librarian</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="9gr12.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h2>The total librarian</h2>
<p><b>Traditionalists worry that the Internet will drown knowledge in a sea of random information. Indexing technology has proved them wrong so far</b></p><ul></ul>


<p>"YOU shall seek all day ere you find them; and, when you have them, they are not worth the search." Shakespeare understood the plight of the Internet surfer. The Internet's greatest asset--that it lets anybody "publish" worldwide, practically for nothing--is also its greatest liability. It is as if the world's greatest library were created by inviting millions of people to bring along some books, knickknacks and old snaps, and stack them on a shelf, any shelf.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the beginning the only way to find something on the Internet was to have somebody tell you where it was. Most of the people on the Internet were then academics, who are used to such informal information-sharing, so this approach was good enough. But as universities began to hook up their students, who were then joined by companies and home users, word-of-mouth was not enough. The search services that existed were incomplete, hard to use--and swamped.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The introduction of the World Wide Web in 1993, with its concept of hypertext links between documents, revolutionised the Internet, and the process of finding things on it. With the easy-to-use Web came a flood of information, as readers morphed into publishers, and the Internet's content began to look more and more like Jorge Luis Borges's fictional "Total Library" of all human knowledge.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But along with this mass of data came a way to make sense of it. Hypertext meant that each document on the Web was ultimately linked to all others in a string of associations, much as every person on the planet is said to be only six acquaintances away from every other. Because hypertext links tend to connect related documents along a particular theme, it is theoretically possible to find whatever you want simply by surfing the contours of this "information space", at each intersection taking the route most like the subject you are pursuing. In practice, this works only if you have a good idea of where to start. More often ("Is there a good Japanese restaurant in West Hollywood?") you have no idea where to begin. What you need is an index.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Internet users have assembled plenty of home-grown indexes, each focused on a specific area, but none of them comes close to covering the whole Internet. Companies are now competing to offer fuller Internet guides. Their offerings fall into three main categories: indexes, search services and hybrids.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yahoo! is the best example of the first. With a lead "ontologist" and a staff of 20 full-time classifiers, it races to sort the Web's new pages into sensible categories. Bringing order to all human knowledge is a long-standing Sisyphean folly, but Yahoo! comes remarkably close. It has some 20,000 categories, listing more than 200,000 Web sites. Users can search by keyword or can follow subject links.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yahoo! does a tremendous job, but it is fighting a losing battle. As fast as the Yahoos find sites and classify them, the Web grows faster. It already has more than 80m pages, and is doubling in size every four or five months. And each classifier adds his own private bias: is Scientology a cult or a religion? Too many classifiers and the predictability of the system erodes; too few and it becomes incomplete. Yahoo! has chosen to lean towards the second approach: rather than claiming to be the complete guide to the Web, it sees itself more as a "Best Of" service.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Search "engines" are the opposite: an "All Of" service. The leading ones--Lycos, InfoSeek and Digital Equipment Corporation's AltaVista--send software "spiders" out into the Web to follow every link on every page, returning details of each new one they find. By having such robots constantly trolling the Internet, these services end up with what amounts to a copy of the entire Web in their own computers. Visitors can then type in a few keywords and these search engines will return every Web page that includes those words.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The advantage of this is that it can ignore classification. Are rumours of "black helicopters" conspiracy theory, military aviation or politics? Who cares? Find them all, and then sort it out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is amazing stuff, and more useful than just finding sites. You can find people, measure your own Web stature (a few hundred hits on your own name is worth bragging about), even use it as a sort of zeitgeist spell-checker, to see which form of a new word is most commonly used. But ultimately, it is not enough. Users who do not know exactly what they want and are not expert in "Boolean searching" (the use of commands such as <font size=-1>AND</font> or <font size=-1>NOT</font> to direct a search) are likely to find themselves scrolling through hundreds or thousands of possibly pertinent sites.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What the Web needs is something in between: a service that is both "All" and "Best". This is the dream of the hybrids, which attempt to harness the computers themselves to bring some order to the information chaos. Excite, for example, uses a statistical technique to lump together pages that have many words in common.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This and related automated classification techniques can keep up with the Web's growth. But they still suffer from the naivet&eacute; of machines. They are undiscriminating, likely to rank a press release as highly as an investigative news report, and to include everything on a subject, no matter how dim or deluded.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The best hybrid, InfoSeek's "Ultra" engine ( <a href="http://ultra.infoseek.com">http://ultra.infoseek.com</a> ), knows enough about English to recognise short phrases, names and word variants ("mice" will also find "mouse"), which filters out much of the clutter. The result is a site that, when it works, makes the Internet feel like an oracle. But, if the predictions of Oren Etzioni, a computer scientist at the University of Washington, prove right, searches in the future will be better in at least three ways. Software on your own <font size=-1>PC</font> will learn your interests, which will help it pick the most relevant search services. It will also know more about the resources available, directing a search for a person to the best names database, and a search for medical information to a health database. And, eventually, the software will know more about English, allowing more "natural language" querying.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Etzioni's "SoftBot" project provides hints to what this future might look like. But the one thing that it cannot do much about is the quality of the pages it returns: it will find wrong answers as cheerfully as right ones. Which is why there will probably always be a role for both man and robot in this game.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
