<html><head><title>Picking blind</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>United Nations</b></p>
<h2>Picking blind</h2><ul> <li><a href="10ex327.html">A W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> N<font size=-1>EED</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> L<font size=-1>EADERSHIP</font></a>: T<font size=-1>OMORROW'S</font> U<font size=-1>NITED</font> N<font size=-1>ATIONS</font>.&nbsp;  By Brian Urquhart and Erskine Childers. <br>
</ul>



<p>MEMBERS of the United Nations have always been sloppy about choosing their club's top officials; when good men or (very rarely) women happen to get the jobs, it tends to be by luck rather than judgment. Never before, however, has the <font size=-1>UN</font> got itself in quite such a tangle over appointing its secretary-general. Boutros Boutros-Ghali, whose term runs out at the end of this year, wants a second go (which has never before been denied an incumbent); the Americans for political reasons have said that they will veto his reappointment. Neither Mr Boutros-Ghali, who on the whole has done fairly well, nor the Americans are prepared to give way.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A splendid time, therefore, for two distinguished <font size=-1>UN</font> veterans, Brian Urquhart and Erskine Childers (who sadly died recently), to present an up-to-date version of their advice, first proffered and ignored in 1990, on how a secretary-general and other <font size=-1>UN</font> notables should more sensibly be chosen. Is it being ignored again? In essence, yes. The current method is absurdly lackadaisical: somebody puts himself forward and the five veto-wielding members of the Security Council decide, for political reasons, whether he is acceptable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The authors' recommendations are brisk. All the <font size=-1>UN</font>'s executive heads, including the secretary-general, should have a single seven-year term. A search body would be set up to track down talent, to scrutinise prospective candidates and present a short list for further examination. And, most radically, they want the <font size=-1>UN</font> to think about the qualities its top men should have. Some incumbents have been dreadful.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These days, it seems that the only thought in American minds is that the world's top officials should be cost-cutters. Senator Jesse Helms, who leads the charge against the <font size=-1>UN</font>, suggests in the current issue of <i>Foreign Affairs </i>that America (the <font size=-1>UN</font>'s largest debtor) should leave the club unless the next secretary-general can prove that it is being "downsized".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The dotty American view of Mr Boutros-Ghali--that he seeks world government--makes it electorally convenient for President Clinton to oppose him, despite the views of other governments. An obvious compromise is to allow him two more years, or seven in all, letting everyone off the hook with a term the authors of this sensible study recommended in the first place.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
