<html><head><title>A World in Need of Leadership</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl327.jpg"><img src="cs327.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>A W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> N<font size=-1>EED</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> L<font size=-1>EADERSHIP</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>OMORROW'S</font> U<font size=-1>NITED</font> N<font size=-1>ATIONS</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Brian Urquhart and Erskine Childers. <br>
<i>Ford Foundation; 103 pages; free</i><br>
</p><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
A WORLD IN NEED OF LEADERSHIP: TOMORROW'S UNITED
NATIONS
<p>A FRESH APPRAISAL</p>
<p>By Brian Urquhart and Erskine Childers</p>
<p><ul> 'The selection of the leaders of the principal international organizations, including the Secretary-General of the United Nations... continued to be haphazard, far less searching or systematic than any small university's procedures for choosing a new president'</ul></p>
<p>In this book the authors renew their frank examination of how governments choose the executive heads of the UN System. They have substantially expanded their 1990 study with more detailed analyses, and recommendations for uniform leadership policies in the UN System.</p>
<p>The authors demonstrate that the selection of a UN Secretary-General has not to date been a search for a superlative candidate, but 'almost literally an "old- boy network" affair'. They also analyse elections among the Specialized Agencies, pointing out that the lack of any common policy for the system by its member governments 'denies them and the international community any possibility of a UN-System team integrally planned for any future period'. Up to date statistics on all leadership posts refute 'the widespread canard that the UN System is dominated by the Third World'.</p>
<p>The study concludes with 15 detailed recommendations that do not require constitutional change. The authors urge that the General Assembly should adopt a comprehensive new approach based on positive searching for the best possible person as Secretary-General, and a single term of seven years. The five Permanent Members should relinquish their veto over candidates. All governments, and civil society and the public at large, should be able to contribute suggestions at the outset and review a short list of candidates at mid- point. 'It would be healthy for the international community if the next Secretary-General were a woman.'</p>
<p>'Only statesmanship and leadership of the highest order can guide the international community through the current period of anger and upheaval and rebuild a more peaceable and just world. This is a matter of vital importance for 211 the peoples of this earth.' </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845679600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
