<html><head><title>History writ large</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="11gr1.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<b>
BY INVITATION</b><br>


<h1>History writ large</h1>
<p><b>The writing of history becomes ever more specialised. Yet bold, sweeping histories still appear. Do they work? We asked Sir Raymond Carr, who is famous for his histories of Spain and Latin America, and was for many years warden of St Antony's College, Oxford, to give his view</b></p><ul> <li><a href="11ex345.html">E<font size=-1>UROPE</font></a>: A H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font>.&nbsp;  By Norman Davies. <br>
 <li><a href="11ex339.html">A H<font size=-1>ISTORY OF</font> E<font size=-1>UROPE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By J.M. Roberts. <br>
 <li><a href="11ex335.html">W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Hugh Thomas. <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

<p>

<p>IN 1920 H.G. Wells published his "Outline of History". It was meant to awaken people to the realisation that only a rationally ordered world-state would save humanity from destroying itself. The "Outline" sold 3m copies. Yet if an undergraduate today were to present its chapters as essays they would be tossed back with a red line through them. Hopelessly amateurish, the "Outline" breaks almost every craft rule of the history profession, or as Norman Davies would now put it, the history industry.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a polemical introduction to his own survey of European history, Mr Davies sees the industry as suffering from a crisis of over-production. Historians engaged in professional debates<i> intra muros</i> write more and more about less and less, he believes. And there are, on top of that, the enemies without: the deconstructionists who denounce the "tyranny of facts" and profess to see no difference between history-writing and story-telling. Nor is it any easier for the old-fashioned historians who still try to explain "what really happened" but who reach also for a non-professional readership. Writing for generations brought up on television, they too are tempted to present history as a succession of images. All of which, in Mr Davies's view, denies "educated adults" the general work they deserve on the origins of contemporary problems, without which they "cannot hope to function efficiently".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Davies's introduction is more than a catalogue of the pits in which professional historians have buried themselves. They are guilty men, he thinks, in that by neglect they have cut off Western Europe from the Europe to the east, excising Poland, Bohemia and Hungary from the history of the Renaissance. By their manipulation of the ambiguous concept of western civilisation to exclude the barbarian Slavs, they have accepted a frontier frozen by the cold war. With its end, Mr Davies implies, the breach can be healed and the excised nations brought into an enlarged Europe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite his polemical agenda, Mr Davies accepts in practice that, as with a camel, it is easier to describe Europe than to define it. And he describes Europe in all its diversity with immense learning and panache in a book weighing almost two kilos that sweeps from Hellas to the collapse of the Soviet empire. There are doses of shock treatment. Thirty years before Auschwitz, D.H. Lawrence suggested the building of a "lethal chamber as big as the Crystal Palace" for the disposal of "the sick, the halt and the maimed". This was not racism but eugenic cleansing. It was H.G. Wells who speculated on how his New Republic would "treat the inferior races".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Davies has to confront the problem of every historian who sets out to write "total history" over a long space of time. The difficulty is to combine the hawk's vision from above with the view at ground level. His solution is "capsules", some 300 mini-essays framed in distinctive type. A capsule on German nationalism, as celebrated by the colossal Hermann monument (1875), leaps backward to a monument to Prince Llewelyn's dog (1790) as "the ultimate in political aesthetics of national sentiment". Although the capsules are helpful in removing, say, the technical achievements of musicians from the narrative text, they sometimes bear so little relationship to the text that they are self-indulgent, even quirky. A capsule on corn dollies serves to explain the importance of wheat as a European crop; but a capsule on the last words of the famous, from Nero's mother to H.G. Wells, distracts rather than illuminates.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Davies's other device is the "snapshot" which freezes in time a moment of symbolic importance. These are small masterpieces in which history comes to life as individuals wrestle with insoluble problems on imperfect information, often to be overwhelmed by accident. A vivid description of the siege of Syracuse (212 <font size=-1>BC</font>) illustrates the balance of power in the Mediterranean. A day-by-day account of how Europe blundered into war in 1914 contains superb portraits of the British foreign secretary, Edward Grey, the country gentleman who warmed to Theodore Roosevelt when he recognised the song of the "gold crested wren"; and of his German opposite number, Theobald von Bethmann Hollweg, a polite and earnest bureaucrat.</p>
<p><b>Self-confidence and its loss</b>
<br>John Roberts's approach to the problems of writing a "total" history of Europe is different, and more convincing. His gifts of compression and clear exposition are outstanding. Within a narrative framework he ranges from the role of cattle in Minoan society to the influence of Freud as questioning "the very foundations of liberal civilisation". His cardinal virtue is his constant awareness that events in the past were once in the future. Luther could not foresee that the Latin theses he nailed to a door in 1517 would finally destroy the unity of Christendom. Nobody in 1914 foresaw the horrors of a war that would undermine the self-confidence of Europe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Mr Roberts, Europe is an imperfectly defined geographical area in which various peoples have shared certain experiences at certain times, but this casts no light on "any on-going persistent civilisation we can identify as Europe". His key point is that by the 19th century these people had achieved a commercial, political and cultural hegemony in the world based on a shared conviction of racial, Christian or technical superiority.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Traditional societies might attempt to resist the dissolvent impact of a superior civilisation without success, as in the Indian Mutiny and the Boxer Rebellion in China. But the solvent of Europe's overseas empires was to be its most successful cultural export: nationalism turned a conservative reaction into a revolutionary anti-Europe anti-imperialist creed, first in India and then throughout Asia. One Asian nation "modernised" on European lines so as to resist European influence: in 1905, Japan inflicted on Russia the first defeat of a major European power by Asians since the Middle Ages. Its victory was an inspiration to other Asians, "the greatest single reason for them to ponder whether European rule was bound to be their lot".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By 1914 Europe's hegemony was showing signs of strain. Its collapse came as a disunited Europe of competing nations committed collective suicide in what Mr Roberts calls Europe's two civil wars. By 1945, the old imperial powers--the Dutch, French and British--were bankrupt and dependent on America in a world split between two superpowers. Mr Roberts argues that had Russia been among the victors of 1919 at Versailles, it might have achieved the supremacy given it, not by the attractions of Soviet communism but by the might of the Soviet armies, in 1945.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a global economy, in which decisions in Tokyo affected unemployment in Wales, Europe could no longer be considered as an autonomous unit with a distinct history. "Europe's work", in Mr Roberts's view, "is done": its innovations and ideologies have been internalised by non-European societies and turned against it. Its world historical role has been eroded. Hitler's declaration of war against America changed the destiny of the world. No modern European statesman could take a decision of such magnitude. Any claim to be the residuary legatee of Christendom, created in the Middle Ages by the advances of the alternative civilisation of Islam, makes no sense, he believes, in a Europe that is now a "neo-pagan and post-Christian society".</p>
<p><b>Examining the clockwork</b>
<br>Hugh Thomas's solution to writing total history is more radical. He jettisons narrative history for thematic history. A brilliant writer, if sometimes perverse in his judgments, his <i>Leitmotiv</i> is the influence on societies of technology, conceived in the widest sense. The cultivation of new crops provides the key to the ancient, settled empires. He notes the "rice driven" hydraulic Empire of China. The stirrup brings the "horse-powered autocracy" of William the Conqueror. The Reformation could not have succeeded without the "real revolution" of moveable type: Protestantism is a book religion; Luther was a bestseller.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With the Industrial Revolution and its consequences he positively delights in detail: barbed wire, invented to keep cattle from straying, contributed to the horrors of trench warfare. In the end, the result of technological and scientific advance is paradoxical. Not only has the optimism of the 19th century, inspired by its material successes, been eroded. In the 1930s people thought they understood the scientific triumphs that shaped our world. Today they are less sure.</p>
<p><b>The pitfalls of grand history</b></b>
<br>Like Mr Roberts, Lord Thomas argues that good history is necessary because bad history brings disaster on those who peddle it and seek to impose their distorted visions on whole societies. Hitler, for whom all history was the history of race, might have won the war had he not expelled Jewish scientists. More convincingly it was his misreading of Russian history and of the need of Germany for <i>Lebensraum</i> to the east that led him to Stalingrad and defeat. Communist tyrannies professed to believe that the class struggle was the motor of history, when according to Lord Thomas, "it is utterly false to suppose that all history is the history of class struggle". Like their mentor Marx, they were, in his view, blind to the force of nationalism, suppressing what they did not understand.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But history, to Lord Thomas, is not without lessons. History properly understood puts people on guard against "the growth and grossness of the modern state". Like his admired de Tocqueville, he sees centralising regimes crushing those intermediate bodies that sustain liberty and give colour to our lives. The success of America is, he thinks, a result of an optimistic view of the capacities of human beings; most things are better done by individuals than by the overgrown state.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How secure are such conclusions? Wells drew a different message: we can be saved only by a Platonic world republic. World history from the Stone Age to the Gulf war is fascinating in its own right as a record of the sufferings and triumphs of mankind. But given the immense diversity of human experience over time, attempts to discover a pattern yields "laws" of dubious validity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Oswald Spengler, in "The Decline of the West" (1918), the most ambitious, misleading and, in its time, most influential essay in world history (Arnold Toynbee and Hitler were among his victims), drew the conclusion that civilisations and empires must, like living organisms, suffer a process of decline and decay. True enough, empires and civilisations do collapse. But so general a proposition tells you little. They decline for a complex variety of reasons. They can collapse suddenly as did the European empires after 1945; they can soldier on for centuries as did Byzantium. "Imperial overstretch" may be a convincing explanation of Spain's decline, but it is less convincing when employed to portend the imminent collapse of America's hegemony.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even so final and seemingly decisive an event as the "implosion" of the Soviet empire is open to widely different interpretation. To Lord Thomas, it leaves the world with a single superpower capable of global management provided it does not suffer from spasms of self-doubt and a lack of restraint in intervening to suppress "brutal wrongdoing". He suggests that it offers "the prospect of a better world than any other which can reasonably be imagined" even if that world is compelled to copy "its style of government, its music, its fashion, even its food". For Mr Davies, the mindless materialism of a transatlantic, homogenised culture may be the most insidious consequence of America's triumph. Both views are sweeping but can both be right?



