<html><head><title>World History.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
</tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Hugh Thomas. <br>
<i>HarperCollins; 764 pages; $35</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="11bt335.html">Biography</a>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
Those early years of the Earth belong to chemists, not to historians. For a historian, it is
enough to know that a metallic core, 3,750 miles wide, came into being within the Earth--
mostly liquid iron and nickel, though solid in the centre. Between that core and the Earth's
crust, a 'mantle' of iron and magnesium 1,875 miles deep took shape. The crust, of diverse
composition, varies between twelve to thirty miles in depth on land, and only four miles
under the sea.
<p>One of the foremost historians of our time surveys the story of mankind. Beginning with prehistory, when the age of hunters slowly turned into an era when agriculture dominated change, through the intellectual transformations of the Renaissance and the Enlightenment, to the industrial era and the modern world, Hugh Thomas stresses themes of particular interest and significance in human history and details the influence of advances in technology.</p>
<p>Within certain obvious chronological divisions this world history is organized thematically into six major sections: The Foundations of History, The Age of Agriculture, The World Transformed (after the Renaissance), Industrial Triumphs, Absolutism and Democracy, and Wars of Our Time. Subjects covered include climate, food and drink, dress, housing, population, energy, disease and medicine, religion and laws, invention, wars, agricultural and industrial development, class and race, cities and communications. Brilliantly written, original in concept and execution, this is a classic work of history by a major historian.</p>
<p>Originally published in 1980 under the title History of the World and unavailable for some years, this revised edition includes additions, deletions and corrections made since the original publication and changes in the final chapters. There is also a new epilogue and new maps. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848102400,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.europe.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
