<html><head><title>What the world is reading</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><br><h2>What the world is reading</h2><p>NOWHERE are bestseller lists compiled on oath, although in some places the rules of this approximate science are more stringent than elsewhere. In Latin America, <i>Veja</i>, <ro>a widely read Brazilian magazine, publishes a weekly list. In Mexico, nobody puts out a similarly respected list, so our correspondent in Mexico city constructed a listing based on inquiries at two of the capital's leading bookshops. The two Mexican lists are offered here with a consumer warning to all that they should be taken as broad indicators of reading trends, not strict or conventional bestseller rankings.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One striking difference between these lists and those in Europe, say, or North America is how much more mixed they are. On the fiction lists, literary novels--for instance, Carlos Fuentes's new novel--jostle with potboilers. On the non-fiction side, books touting self-help or odd beliefs sit next to serious works of analysis or reportage on Mexico's current economic and political ills. Old is there as well as new. ''Jonathan Livingston Seagull'' is not stuffed in an ornithological museum: it has gone to Mexico. There are lots of translations but also plenty of home-written entries. ''Mal de Amores'' is a passionate historical novel by one of Mexico's most popular woman novelists. And in Mexico, Christian self-help, interestingly, takes fictional form (note the three books by Carlos Cuauhtemoc Sanchez).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Brazil, ''global authors'' also compete with local ones. There is the standard international fare of Ken Follet, Sidney Sheldon and Jostein Gaarder. But Brazilians are also reading books that throw oblique light on their own country. ''O Xango de Baker Street'' by Jo Soares transplants Sherlock Holmes to fin-de-si&egrave;cle Rio de Janeiro in a comic detective tale. ''Comedia da Vida Privada'' is a collection of gobbets of ironic reflection served up each Sunday in a Sao Paulo newspaper by Luis Fernando Verissimo. ''Rapina'' is by a first-time thriller writer and set in Brazil's financial markets. The non-fiction list is dominated by how-to and self-help books, by works involving mysticism and by Christian literature, particularly of the evangelical kind. ''Paula" is a chronicle of the last days of a bestselling Chilean author's daughter, who died of a crippling disease.<br><h3>Fiction bestsellers<a href="#foot">*</a></h3><ul><li><a href="#1">Mexico fiction</a><li><a href="#2">Mexico non-fiction</a><li><a href="#3">Brazil fiction</a><li><a href="#4">Brazil non-fiction</a></ul></td></tr></table><a name="1"><br></a><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><hr size=5 width=70 align=left><h4>Mexico fiction</h4><ol><li>	La Frontera de Cristal 	<i> by Carlos Fuentes	</i>. &#160; 	The latest from one of Mexico's best-known novelists	</li><li>	Mal de Amores 	<i> by Angeles Mastreta	</i>. &#160; 	A personal and passionate historical novel	</li><li>	Volar Sobre el Pantano	<i> by Carlos Cuauhtemoc Sanchez	</i>. &#160; 	Self-help novel for people in hardship	</li><li>	El Mundo de Sofia	<i> by Jostein Gaarder	</i>. &#160; 	Teenager discovers western philosophy	</li><li>	Cartero de Neruda	<i> by Antonio Skarmeta	</i>. &#160; 	Inspiration for the film "Il Postino"	</li><li>	Juan Salvador Gaviota 	<i> by Richard Bach	</