<html><head><title>A blood sport</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Political advertising on CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>A blood sport</h2><ul> <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> A<font size=-1>RT</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> C<font size=-1>AMPAIGN</font> A<font size=-1>DVERTISING</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By G.R. Boynton.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Chatham House;</i> <i>$19.95 and &#163;12.99</i><i> </i> <br>
</ul>


A PEERAGE was recently awarded by John Major to Maurice Saatchi, the British advertising man responsible for the slogan "Labour Isn't Working" and a series of other low-blow campaign posters for the Conservative Party. Mr Saatchi's first salvo for the Tories' advertising offensive this summer proved even more controversial. His posters seemed inspired by a Monty Python collage. They showed Tony Blair, the Labour leader, with demonic bloodshot eyes, and so offended the Advertising Standards Authority that it told the Conservative Party to stop using them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet they are tame compared with some of the more egregious examples from past American presidential campaigns which appear on G.R. Boynton's <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>. A television advertisement in support of President Lyndon Johnson's bid for re-election in 1964 is an infamous example. As a little girl in a meadow counts aloud the petals on a flower, she is gradually drowned out by a harsh male voice counting down from ten to zero. The climax is a nuclear explosion, the implied likely consequence of the defeat of Mr Johnson by the Republican Party's candidate, Barry Goldwater. More recently, Ann Richards depicted her rival in an election for governor of Texas as a little cartoon catapult that perpetually whirled mud at Ms Richards.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Boynton's <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> devotes one of its six chapters to negative advertising, illustrating with these and other video clips some of the techniques available to the would-be political bull-terrier: horror-movie sound effects, mocking caricatures, ponderous lists of the opponent's deficiencies compared with the candidate's glowing merits. Other chapters cover the use of biography by candidates, the chair as a symbol of power, and treatment of domestic and of foreign policy. But none is long enough to give more than an overview of these subjects and the disc does not tell you where to go for further information.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is a pity, because playing through "The Art of Campaign Advertising" is unlikely to satisfy anybody. Those well-versed in politics will find nothing they did not already know; people who are intrigued by something they see will soon be frustrated by the disc's deficiencies of design as well as its lack of bibliography. It contains little that could not be done better on a video tape, which would have the advantage of better-quality reproduction on television.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other than allowing the viewer to choose which of the six sections to watch, the disc is not interactive at all; each section plays through in order, without scope for interrogating images or text. Even hurrying forward to look for a particular film clip is more laborious than it would be on tape. There are unnecessary repetitions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Boynton has chosen some absorbing film clips, including several that had more influence on subsequent advertising techniques than on the political campaigns themselves. But fascination soon gives way to tedium as you watch them halt along on a computer screen, while his narrating voice blips and falters. This is a shame; the subject promised more.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
