<html><head><title>Impressionistic</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>



<p><b>Statistics on CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>Impressionistic</h2><ul> <li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>C</font>G<font size=-1>RAW-</font>H<font size=-1>ILL</font> I<font size=-1>NTERACTIVE</font> G<font size=-1>UIDE</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> B<font size=-1>USINESS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMICS</font>.</a>&nbsp;   &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>McGraw Hill; &#163;99.88</i> <br>
</ul>



<p>TAKING a walk through an interactive "Guide to World Business and Economics" does not sound as enjoyable as a walk in the country but this McGraw-Hill <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> tries to make it as easy and enjoyable as possible. You can walk across the world (if you are in any doubt as to where you are you can cheat, as the mouse scuttles from Kirgizstan to Kazakhstan, and look at the bottom left-hand corner of the screen where the country names magically appear). A similar technique is used for charts--when you put the cursor on a bar on a chart, the actual value is shown, this time in the bottom right-hand corner.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Interactive features offer you the chance of creating your own portfolio of countries and/or subjects, although the task is complicated by the rather mysterious icons. Gathering statistics for over 226 countries on a wide variety of subjects on a reasonably comparable basis is, of course, hard to do--as <i>The Economist'</i>s own research department can attest. However bang-up-to-the-minute the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> is when it comes out, it is bound quickly to get out of date--not least because last month's <font size=-1>GDP</font>, trade inflation and sales figures are routinely revised later.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The "World of Information" sections for 1994 and 1995 are, by definition, less time-sensitive, and so more durable, than more recent facts and figures. And they reinforce the impression that this <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> serves better as a reasonably current electronic encyclopedia/almanac than as a tool for assessing business opportunities or making strategic investment decisions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The price tag makes the guide an affordable purchase for home use, which is more than can be said for the updated version that is promised for December. On current plans it will cost &#163;229.13.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
