<html><head><title>Facts of death</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="8gr14.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Medical ethics on CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>Facts of death</h2><ul> <li><a href="8ex222.html">A R<font size=-1>IGHT</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> D<font size=-1>IE?</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> D<font size=-1>AX</font> C<font size=-1>OWART</font> C<font size=-1>ASE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Robert Cavalier, Preston Covey and David Anderson. <br>
</ul>


<p>A YOUNG man is charred over two-thirds of his body in a freak accident when a leaking natural-gas pipeline engulfs him in fire. After a year of treatment, including excruciating daily baths to keep his wounds from infection, he is blind, cannot use his hands and is horribly scarred. He asks his physicians to stop treatment. If they do so, he will die. Should the doctors agree to his wishes?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The difficult real-life case of Dax Cowart is the topic of this <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>. The viewer reads the facts of the case; video clips show a disfigured Dax as well as his mother, lawyer, nurse and doctors discussing the issue. Texans all, they speak in a slow-paced twang well suited to the seriousness of the topic; they seem like decent, thoughtful people anxious to do what is right.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Suicide is "not a reasonable solution to the problem" of Mr Cowart's pain during treatment, his burn physician argues. Mr Cowart wonders why a doctor should have decision-making authority over a competent patient. "I don't see how anyone else could possibly have the right," he complains. His mother insists she could never willingly give up her son.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At different points in the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> journey, the viewer is asked questions about what should and should not be allowed to happen to Dax and why. Every once in a while, there is a chance to comment on participants' remarks or to make a decision on the case and defend it. The hope is that this semi-Socratic method could be a useful tool for schooling medical professionals in these awful dilemmas. As a whole, it succeeds, but as with so many <font size=-1>CD-ROMS</font>, the publishers have not fully tapped the technology's potential.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unless one is dogmatically libertarian (patients have all the rights) or dogmatically pro-treatment (any and all medical treatment must always be offered), it is hardly possible to negotiate the grey areas of end-of-life issues with consistency. Compassion, intellect and religious belief seldom converge. A better <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> would have let the viewer confront this moral truth by questioning the consistency of their responses. Related cases might have been given more mention. The evolving ethics of near-death decisions are part of a robust debate that does not get as much emphasis as it should. A bibliography would have helped.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And Dax Cowart? Treatment continued against his wishes, though techniques were developed that lessened his pain. He went home. Two suicide attempts failed. He is blind and cannot really use his hands (but he presses calculator buttons, for example, with his tongue). He bought a house and went to law school. He walks with ease, has married (twice) and practices--what else?--personal injury law. Mr Cowart, his face an immobile, scarred mask of flesh, says he is glad to be alive. But he thinks the decision on whether or not to end his life ought to have been his.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/"index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
