http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev12/rv14/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113124137 text/html 7614
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 12:37:53 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 03-Dec-96 18:24:35 GMT
Content-length: 7430
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Wild, heroic ride</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="12gr14.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Musical lives</b></p>
<h2>Wild, heroic ride</h2><ul> <li>C<font size=-1>HARLES </font>I<font size=-1>VES</a>: </font>A L<font size=-1>IFE WITH </font>M<font size=-1>USIC</font>.&nbsp;  By Jan Swafford.  &nbsp;  &nbsp; <i>Norton; 450 pages; $30 and &#163;22.50</i> <br>
</ul>

<p>WRITING music is an introverted, solitary business, and a composer's life can be outwardly uneventful, which is why many composers' biographies are so dull. Music is harder to refer to than a picture or a poem; it is also more discrete from life. You may experience a satisfying spine-tingle when Isolde begins her "Liebestod", but care little about what Wagner had for breakfast, and do your best to forget about his ghastly opinions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whatever the reasons, writing a composer's biography is a tough number, and it is a rare treat when a biographer gets inside a composer's skin. Jan Swafford does so magnificently in this new Ives biography. He also illuminates Ives's background, and the period which produced him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ives was born in Danbury, Connecticut, in 1874. In 1898 he graduated from Yale (not very brilliantly, except on the football field), moved to New York and embarked on a Wall Street career in life insurance. "If [a man] has a nice wife and...children," he wrote later, "how can he let [them] starve on his dissonances?" He was a multi-millionaire before he was 40; but the strain took its toll. By 1917 he was almost written out; by 1926 he was a sick man and had stopped composing altogether. At the end of 1929 he retired from business. The rest of his life (and much of his money) was spent working to get his music heard.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is an extraordinary story, and Mr Swafford tells it brilliantly. Ives was born in the aftermath of the Civil War, when America, still rural, was healing its self-inflicted wounds with the twin medicines of God and Mammon. He came of age in turn-of-the-century New York, where optimism and boom were the order of the day: America was becoming a world power, science promised a glittering future in the new, improved 20th century and 1% of the country's population owned seven-eighths of the nation's wealth. His later years witnessed a sadder, wiser New Deal America, chastened by the first world war and the Depression.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ives was a progressive in politics, an optimist by temperament. He believed in man's perfectibility, and saw music as a means for achieving it--by happy accident, the woman he spent his life with was called Harmony. He was a New England transcendentalist, a musical successor to Emerson and Thoreau--both of whom he celebrated in his music.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He was also the man on whose shoulders fell the task of inventing American music and dragging it into the 20th century. When he was born, Brahms and Wagner were in business, and music meant European music. Dvorak shocked Americans in the 1890s by suggesting that they build a national music on the foundations of black and indigenous American music. The response of one composer, Edward Macdowell, was typical: "Masquerading in the so-called nationalism of negro clothes cut in Bohemia will not help us."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Oddly enough, Ives would have agreed with this: he had no time for nationalism, seeing it as the root of all war. He despised the genteel musical culture of 19th-century America as "cissy" and exclusive. To him, music was a tree whose branches reached for the universal, but which needed roots in the particular. Ives's particular was not America, but Danbury, marching-bands and revivalist hymns. These were inclusive, democratic contexts which served him as musical icons. Once he settled in New York, his memories acquired a patina of nostalgia, and the Danbury he celebrated in his music was a place which no longer existed--and probably never had, outside his imagination. In this, as in many things, Ives foreshadows a rootless age.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More than any other composer except Mozart, he was primed for creative mastery by his father. George Ives, town bandmaster and eccentric, was a radical thinker--witness this advice (in 1894) to Charles, who was having trouble with his Yale supervisor, a genteel, German-trained composer, Horatio Parker: "Tell Parker that every dissonance doesn't have to resolve, if it doesn't happen to feel like it, any more than every horse should have to have its tail bobbed just because it's the prevailing fashion." And this: "Don't pay too much attention to the sounds...If you do, you may miss the music. You won't get a wild, heroic ride to heaven on pretty little sounds."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He was, also, a heroic figure. For years openly ridiculed by the musical establishment as a bumbling amateur (worse still, a <i>rich</i> amateur) Ives continued to compose and push his work regardless. Nor was he in the least an amateur: as Swafford shows, he had a thorough grounding, was a capable church organist, and remained an excellent pianist throughout his life.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some of Ives's music does suffer from the isolation which he suffered--and which, to an extent, he inflicted on himself by his orneriness. But at its best--in "The Unanswered Question", "Central Park in the Dark", the "Concord Sonata", "Three Places in New England", the Fourth Symphony, and many of the songs--it blazes with originality and intensity. It is an astonishing legacy, which should be even more widely honoured than it is today.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite eventual recognition, Ives's last years make sad reading. The periods of overwork, neglect and disappointment had exhausted and embittered him. His manic New England optimism, which had carried him through so much, and which infuses all his music, had an inevitable depressive downside. His constitution gave way and he became a cranky recluse.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a splendid book, finely researched and couched in lucid, jargon-free language. Jan Swafford has produced a rich portrait of a great, lovable man who still has many lessons to teach. This is much more than a narrowly musical biography: it should be on the shelves of anyone interested in the history of the past century.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
