<html><head><title>Oil quack</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="12gr10.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Business lives</b></p>
<h2>Oil quack</h2><ul> <li><a href="12ex372.html">D<font size=-1>OSSIER</a>:</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>ECRET</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> A<font size=-1>RMAND</font> H<font size=-1>AMMER</font>.&nbsp;  By Edward Jay Epstein. <br>
</ul>

<br>Hammer engaged in an aggressive campaign of self-promotion--a campaign capped by the publication of several self-serving autobiographies that inspired admiring stories in a willing business press. He used secret Swiss slush funds to support Prince Charles's philanthropic causes in the daft hope that the Windsors would grease his way to a Nobel prize. His strategically recruited aides included James Roosevelt, a skint son of Franklin Roosevelt, Senator Albert Gore, the father of the vice-president of the United States, Marvin Watson, a crony of Lyndon Johnson's, and Howard Baker, a Republican bigwig who persuaded President Bush to pardon Hammer for the illegal gift of cash he gave to Richard Nixon in 1972.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Edward Jay Epstein, an experienced investigator in the fields of high finance and espionage, strips Hammer clean of his deceptions. With the help of newly accessible Comintern records and other material from Russian archives, voluminous <font size=-1>FBI</font> files and many interviews with Hammer's former lovers and with members of his family, he paints a vivid, compelling portrait of a thorough scoundrel.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At times Mr Epstein's dossier reads like a le Carr&eacute; novel. In 1920 Armand Hammer let his father, Julius, a New York doctor, go to prison for an illegal abortion he himself had performed. Then, going to the Soviet Union in his father's place, he masqueraded as an enlightened capitalist in order to cover up his role as money launderer for the Communists. Through the rest of his life, he continually revised his identity, covered up his business frauds, shuffled his women, betrayed his family and dipped into his companies' funds to pay bribes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Little attention is paid by Mr Epstein to Hammer's career as a conglomerator, and tothe way he pushed up the value of Occidental Petroleum shares as he acquired companies and cashed in on Libyan oil. But he does reveal how Hammer put fame before profits in, for instance, sinking $2.5 billion of Occidental Petroleum's money into fertiliser operations in the Soviet Union and coal mining in China.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is hard to believe now that Hammer was able to pass himself off for so long as peace-making agent between the United States and the Soviet Union. The confidence successive Soviet leaders invested in him as a go-between and a fixer was misplaced. Hammer had little influence within the White House during either the Carter or the Reagan administrations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After his death, it was apparent that Hammer had reneged on promises to support members of his family, a former lover and his illegitimate daughter. More than 100 claims were soon lodged against his estate, including a demands for $640,000 from the Reagan Presidential Foundation, for $250,000 from the Danielle Mitterrand Foundation and for $1.4m from the Salk Institute. All were charitable pledges on which Hammer had welshed.


