<html><head><title>Moulding history</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Industrial symbols</b></p>
<h2>Moulding history</h2><ul> <li><a href="10ex315.html">P<font size=-1>LASTIC</a>:</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>AKING OF A</font> S<font size=-1>YNTHETIC</font> C<font size=-1>ENTURY</font>.&nbsp;  By Stephen Fenichell. <br>
</ul>


<p>ELEPHANTS suffered greatly during the billiards craze that swept America in the 1860s. Hunters had to gather as many as 50 tusks to find one with a grain even enough to supply the ivory from which the balls used for the game were crafted. Ivory prices rose sharply as a result, prompting Phelan &amp; Collender, the largest supplier of billiards equipment in America at the time, to offer $10,000 in gold to whoever could invent a substitute. The reward sent countless amateur scientists to their garden sheds to tinker with wood chips, glues, shellac and strips of muslin.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among them was John Hyatt of Illinois, a printer. He never won the Phelan &amp; Collender prize, despite filing two patents for variously composed billiard balls, but an accident in the course of his research led him to wealth as the head of the Celluloid Manufacturing Company. This firm produced products ranging from false teeth to shirt cuffs from a material that Hyatt had discovered after knocking over a jar of collodion, a solution of plant fibre in ether and alcohol. Printers used to paint collodion on to their fingertips to form a thin film to protect them while handling hot metal type. But the slick which Hyatt discovered in his cupboard in 1868 had formed a stiff, transparent lacquer that struck him as a potential coating for his elusive billiard balls. Further experiments led him to add camphor to the mixture; this created celluloid, the first thermoplastic, or material which could be repeatedly softened by heating and then moulded into a shape it would hold when cooled.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The early history of plastic and its predecessors, as recounted in Stephen Fenichell's entertaining book, is full of such lucky spills. Christian Sch&#246;nbein, a chemist at the University of Basle, discovered guncotton in 1846 when he mopped up a spill from a flask in which he had been distilling a mixture of nitric and sulphuric acids. A few years earlier Charles Goodyear, a chaotic amateur experimenter, stumbled on a process for curing rubber, soon to be known as "vulcanisation" (a name thought up by a British rival in the raincoat business) by spilling raw latex and sulphur together on to a hot stove. And the synthetic mauve dye which started to pour from the vats of W.H. Perkin &amp; Sons' factory in Harrow in the 1850s, laying the foundations for much of the modern pharmaceutical industry, was another mop-up job, discovered when the firm's founder examined the rag with which he had cleaned up the spilt remains of a failed attempt to synthesise quinine. The story of plastic even includes a pair of human Spills, Daniel and George, two brothers who supplied the British army with 340,000 yards of rubberized cloth to keep it dry during the Crimean war, and later bankrupted themselves in patent battles with Goodyear.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From haphazard beginnings, plastics have grown in variety and sophistication to find ever more applications during what the author calls a "synthetic century". He tells the many strands of their story breezily, although with too many mixed metaphors: a critic of nylon is said to have "hit the nail right where it hurt". Plastic's image has fluctuated widely during that time: sophisticated bakelite was perfect for a streamlined, modern look in the 1920s; glamorous sheeny nylon was preferred to silk for stockings in the second world war; flexible Tupperware, made from plastic that no longer pretended to be anything other than artificial, fitted the forward-looking 1950s; styrofoam became a symbol of 1980s environmental carelessness. Inventors, hucksters, philanthropists and lunatics have all played their part. Their presence enlivens the tale of what Mr Fenichell rightly identifies as an emblematic material of the modern world.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
