<html><head><title>Plastic</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl315.jpg"><img src="cs315.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>P<font size=-1>LASTIC:<br></font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>AKING OF A</font> S<font size=-1>YNTHETIC</font> C<font size=-1>ENTURY</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Stephen Fenichell. <br>
<i>HarperBusiness; 356 pages; $25 and &#163;16</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="10jb315.html">Jacket Copy</a>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
STEPHEN FENICHELL is a freelance writer who has written extensively on
popular culture, business, and travel for New York, Men's Journal, Forbes/FYI,
Conde Nast Traveler, Lear's, and American Photo. He is the author of Other
People's Money and coauthor (with Lawrence Charfoos) of Daughters at Risk:
A Personal DES History. He lives with his wife and daughter in New York
City.
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
