<html><head><title>Art at bedtime</title></head> <body
background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0> <tr><td valign=bottom
align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top> <br>


<p><b>Holiday gift books</b></p> <h2>Art at bedtime</h2>

<!--<ul> 

<li><a
href="12ex376.html"><font size=-1>AN</font> A<font size=-1>TLAS</font> <font
size=-1>OF</font> L<font size=-1>ITERATURE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  Edited by Malcolm
Bradbury. <br> <li><a href="12ex377.html">P<font size=-1>ARADISE T</font><font
size=-1>RANSFORMED</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Guy Cooper and Gordon Taylor. <br>
<li><a href="12ex378.html">I<font size=-1>'LL</font> <font size=-1>BE</font>
Y<font size=-1>OUR</font> M<font size=-1>IRROR</font>.</a>&nbsp;  <br> <li><a
href="12ex379.html">H<font size=-1>ENRI</font> C<font
size=-1>ARTIER-BRESSON</font> A<font size=-1>ND</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font>
A<font size=-1>RTLESS</font> A<font size=-1>RT</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Jean-Pierre
Montier. <br> <li><a href="12ex380.html">I<font size=-1>INSTALLATION</font>
A<font size=-1>RT</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Nicolas de Oliveira, Nicola Oxley and
Michael Petry. <br> <li><a href="12ex381.html">R<font size=-1>ED</font> H<font
size=-1>OT</font> A<font size=-1>ND</font> B<font size=-1>LUE</font>.</a>&nbsp; 
By Amy Henderson and Dwight Blocker Bowers. <br> <li><a
href="12ex382.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> U<font size=-1>LTIMATE</font> E<font
size=-1>NSYSLOPEDIA</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> E<font size=-1>XTREME</font>
S<font size=-1>PORTS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Joe Tomlinson. <br> </ul>-->


<p>THE best coffee-table books are not the ones you leave out for display but
those you take to bed to browse through. As a tip for presents you may want to
give (or get), here is a selection of the season's best.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For literary tourists, or readers momentarily
bored by the novel they are reading, nothing could be better than <a
href="12ex376.html">An Atlas of
Literature</a> (Edited by Malcolm Bradbury. De Agostini; &#163;25 and $35).This
extraordinary compilation of 80 essays, complete with detailed city maps, is a
guide to the places where classics, old and new, western and non-western, were
written. It lists authors' homes (from Dante's to Isabel Allende's), publishing
houses where their books were accepted, refused and rewritten, and caf&eacute;s
and other hang-outs where they were endlessly and eloquentxly talked about.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<a href="12ex377.html">Paradise Transformed</a> (By Guy Cooper and
Gordon Taylor. Monacelli; &#163;35) is a gorgeous book illustrating the works of
more than two dozen modern landscape gardeners. It includes all sorts of styles:
traditionalists like Dan Kiley, "abstract" designers like George Hargreaves,
playful experimenters like Maggie Keswick and Charles Jencks, as well as a
Japanese master of rocks and water, Motoo Yoshimura.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nan Goldin is one of New York's best-known
art-photographers. Her work is shown in art museums across the world. <a href="12ex378.html">I'll be
your Mirror</a> (Scalo; $70) is the title of an exhibition of hers at New York's
Whitney Museum (ending January 5th). Her greeny-yellow pictures are mainly of
friends on the New York "scene", shot in bed, in the bath, playing Monopoly. Her
unsentimental eye owes something to a powerful early 20th-century German
photographer, August Sander; her feel for oddity and illness to the more recent
work of Diane Arbus. But she is warmer than either. Henri Cartier-Bresson
represents a more serene tradition in which art and reportage mix. <a href="12ex379.html">Henri
Cartier-Bresson and the Artless Art</a> (By Jean-Pierre Montier. Thames and
Hudson; &#163;50. Bulfinch; $75) is a beautifully illustrated study of his
60-year career. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If photography is one thing
painting has made room for in art museums, installation art is another. An object
of mystification or mockery on its first appearance, it is now so widely accepted
and taught that some painters fear for their future. <a href="12ex380.html">Installation Art</a> (By
Nicolas de Oliveira, Nicola Oxley and Michael Petry. Thames and Hudson;
&#163;17.95. Smithsonian Institution; $34.95) is a useful survey of a
fast-expanding genre, tracing its forebears in the early 20th-century
avant-garde. The photographs are good, though with "site-specific art" there is
no substitute for the site. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <a href="12ex381.html">Red Hot and
Blue</a> (By Amy Henderson and Dwight Blocker Bowers. Smithsonian Institution
Press; $39.95 and &#163;29.95) is schmaltzy, smiling and full of irresistible
pep, just like the American musical it celebrates. (The book accompanies an
exhibition at the Smithsonian in Washington.) It tells the story of musicals from
vaudeville to Stephen Sondheim and beyond, treating Broadway and Hollywood as
equals in the creation of an all-American art.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For browsers and lounge-potatoes, the ultimate
coffee-table book this season, however, may well be <a
href="12ex382.html">The Ultimate Encyclopedia
of Extreme Sports</a> (By Joe Tomlinson. Carlton; &#163;14.99). It lists 41
popular ways to get your adrenalin pumping, and perhaps kill yourself, by land,
air or sea. It starts with <font size=-1>BASE</font> jumping ("buildings,
antenna-tower, span, earth"), and includes ski-flying, sky-surfing, aggressive
in-line skating, extreme motocross, street luge, barefoot water-skiing,
unassisted deep diving, wake-boarding, as well as older challenges such as
mountaineering, high-wire acts and solo round-the-world yachting. The book
contains a handy list of addresses (postal and electronic) for people who want to
get in touch with groups that do these sports. But it is a fair guess that the
publishers of this entertaining guide are counting also on a vicarious, bedside
browsership.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i>
Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a
href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849916800,rev">Search</a>
